<html><head><title>The Geekicon</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: manar hussain, 19-Dec-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="language.gif" alt="LANGUAGE AND ELECTRONICS">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The Geekicon</h1>

UNLIKE the reference monoliths that respond to changes in English the way an elephant flinches from gnats, the "Hacker's Dictionary" or "Jargon File" is an electronic compendium as fluid and variable as the language it records. It has many authors and sits in many editions on different Internet sites. The latest issue contains over 2,000 entries.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many are computer-geek slang from the 1970s or earlier, and many are rarely used logical puns, of which geeks are fond, on the illogicality of English. (The plural of "mongoose", states the dictionary, is widely agreed to be "polygoose".) A few, though, are terms that have made their way to the wider Net community and even the outside world.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netlish is an ad hoc sort of tongue, creating words and spellings as the need arises (<i>adhockery</i> itself, now used for all sorts of arbitrariness, may have originated as a programmer's term for random problem-fixing attempts).<i> Software </i> is familiar even beyond Net-users--but, on the Net, much software is freely distributed in forms such as <i>freeware </i>(no cost), <i>shareware </i>(appeals to your conscience to send a fee), <i>careware </i>(the fee is a donation to charity), <i>postcardware </i>(send a postcard to the programmer), and others. People, in contrast to computers (<i>hardware</i>), may pejoratively be referred to as <i>wetware</i>. Another Netlish effect is to cross-breed languages: Italian hackers, says the dictionary, have invented <i>scrollare </i>and <i>deletare </i>in place of the Italian words for "scroll" and "delete".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Abbreviations in e-mail (no one now says "electronic" mail) are also a favourite. Their original purpose, speed, has been supplanted: it is the convention that matters. A contentious statement may be prefixed by <font size=-1>IMHO</font>, <i>in my humble opinion</i>. Often this is ironic, since no humility is intended; some users dispense with the irony, preferring <font size=-1>IMAO</font>--<i>in my arrogant opinion</i>. Jeering or wistful references may be made to <font size=-1>IRL</font>--<i>in real life</i>, ie, not in cyberspace. Another well-known <font size=-1>TLA</font> (<i>three-letter acronym</i>--also sometimes used <font size=-1>IRL</font>) is <font size=-1>URL</font>, of which it can safely be said that more people know what it is (an Internet address) than what it stands for (<i>uniform resource locator</i>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a while the <i>smiley</i>, <b>:-)</b> (like a face on its side), seemed to be a metalinguistic breakthrough for expressing emotion on the cold face of a computer screen. An industry in <i>emoticons </i>was briefly spawned, including <b>:-(</b> (sad), <b>:-O</b> (shocked) and <b>%)</b> (punched in the face). Few, though, are used. Over-use now is the mark not of the true geek but of the <i>newbie</i>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Oddly, the Hacker's Dictionary does not give the origin of <i>geek</i>. A couple of mouse-clicks, however, lead to the online site of a more traditional source: Webster's, which has "a carnival performer often billed as a wild man whose act usually includes biting the head off a live chicken or snake."<br>
<br>

