<html><head><title>Fog on the Tyne, Newcastle cut off</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>North-east politics</b></p>
<h1>Fog on the Tyne, Newcastle cut off</h1>

<font size=1>NEWCASTLE</font><p>
THE great iron lattice-work bridges arching across the River Tyne are Newcastle's most famous landmarks. Though outsiders do not much notice it, they also span the frontier between the city and its smaller and poorer cousin on the south bank-- Gateshead. And, lately, more than just commuters have been flowing across the bridges. Gateshead has been winning prestige projects in the north-east of England that in previous years would have gone to Newcastle as the regional capital. The divided Labour group that runs Newcastle seems incapable of putting up a united front to stop this drain.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The latest bout of irritation on the north bank has emerged with the realisation that Gateshead is inching ever closer to achieving what seemed a distant dream a few years back--creating the biggest exhibition and performance space for the contemporary arts outside London. If this happens, it will be because Gateshead Metropolitan Borough Council has stepped in while Newcastle City Council dithers. Last month, Northern Arts struck a deal with the Gateshead council to build a &#163;35m music centre to house a music school, two concert halls, and the Northern Sinfonia orchestra.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Newcastle had turned down Northern Arts, balking at the prospect of having to cough up &#163;200,000 a year for the running costs of the centre. "We didn't get a formal business plan, and without one you could run into long-term revenue problems," explains Tony Flynn, leader of Newcastle City Council. Gateshead was not given a business plan either, but nevertheless reckoned it was worth the gamble.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The money to build the centre has yet to be awarded by the National Lottery, but the signs are that it will be handed out. It also looks likely to be forthcoming for a &#163;46m scheme to convert the disused Baltic Flour Mill, next door to the music centre site, into a contemporary-art gallery. The Arts Council has already spent &#163;480,000 on a study which suggests the plan is workable.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But far from applauding these Gateshead initiatives which Newcastle's people will be able to use without paying any extra council tax, Newcastle councillors seem decidedly surly about them. Colin Gray, chairman of the finance committee, snorted in a letter to a local paper, the <i>Journal</i>, that the music centre was "the new sex symbol of the chattering classes" and that matters of "true regional significance", such as improvements to the <font size=-1>A</font>1, were being sacrificed. Other councillors have sniffed at Gateshead's plans for a footbridge to make it easier for Newcastle citizens to get to the arts centres as unnecessary and liable to damage the view of the Tyne Bridge.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Flynn protests that these comments caricature Newcastle council's official position, which supports the arts centres and the footbridge. It is simply, he says, that the council is worried about adding more burdens to its revenue budget, which had to be cut by &#163;8m this year.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other councillors, however, tell a different story, of how the ruling Labour group has split into different factions since Sir Jeremy Beecham quit in 1994 after 17 years as leader. East-end and west-end groups are fighting for more cash for their respective parts of the city, an old guard does not see eye-to-eye with new councillors, and all seem unable to unite over common interests. "There is still a power vacuum. Flynn cannot get things through the group," says one councillor. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The indecision is making life difficult for Sir John Hall, who is looking for a site to build a new stadium for Newcastle United Football Club. After various clandestine meetings between the club and different council factions, the council eventually agreed to ask Sir John to submit a plan for a stadium on part of the Town Moor, open ground to the north of the city centre.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has been vigorously criticised by people who live nearby. Sir John, aware that council politics might scupper this scheme, has let it be known that it is looking at other sites, including one in Gateshead. George Gill, leader of Gateshead council who has known Sir John since the football-club owner made his fortune out of the Metrocentre shopping complex in Gateshead, says the two have had only an informal chat. But, he adds, "We have got the facilities for them."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sir John may only be using the threat of Gateshead to goad Newcastle into making a decision. Building arts centres is bad enough, but the mere thought of having to cross the Tyne to watch Newcastle United is enough to make any city Magpie fan sick into his brown ale.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
