<html><head><title>Her Majesty's Shambles</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Privatisation</b></p>
<h1>Her Majesty's Shambles</h1>

THE National Audit Office, the watchdog of the nation's accounts, is about to announce that it will conduct an inquiry into the sale of Her Majesty's Stationery Office (<font size=-1>HMSO</font>), the government's 200-year-old publisher. Charges that its privatisation was a political fix are now being tossed around the City and Westminster.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These suspicions are fuelled by the eventual sale price--&#163;54m, which was at least &#163;10m lower than other final offers, and a third of the original forecast. Labour's civil-service spokesman, Derek Foster, describes the sale as "a sweetheart deal for their [the Tory government's] friends". Some disappointed bidders agree. The head of one of the consortia claims that he offered and is still prepared to pay more than double what the company was eventually sold for. "None of us felt this sale was evenly handled," he says.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The winning bid was put together by Electra, an investment trust, and Robert Fleming, an investment bank, and chaired by a former editor of <i>The Economist</i>, Rupert Pennant-Rea. It was not short of political friends. Lord King, a former cabinet minister, is on Electra's board. The investment company's deputy chairman, Lord Vinson, is a founding director of the Centre for Policy Studies, a Thatcherite think-tank. Robert Fleming employs a former Tory chief whip, Tim Renton, as a parliamentary consultant. The two companies have together donated nearly &#163;600,000 to the Conservatives in recent years.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But proof of a political fix requires more than friends in high places. The evidence suggests not so much a conspiracy as an expensive cock-up.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the government put the company up for sale a year ago at the insistence of the deputy prime minister, Michael Heseltine, the prospectus boasted that <font size=-1>HMSO</font> was "a modern business with a prestigious history" with sales in excess of &#163;375m, employing 2,900 staff in a network of offices, warehouses, print factories and bookshops. There were 14 indicative bids ranging up to &#163;175m. Four consortia were eventually shortlisted led by Mercury Asset Management, Hambros, Electra Fleming and NatWest Ventures.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then things started to go wrong. A six-week round of site visits by the short-listed bidders revealed over-staffed offices and impenetrable accounts. The company had been divided into 14 separate business units, but its accounting systems had not kept pace. A &#163;19m hole was discovered in intra-company trading accounts. Despite the efforts of several teams of accountants, nobody could find the money. One of the bidders described the company's finances as "a bloody dog's dinner".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The disclosure in April that <font size=-1>HMSO</font> had lost &#163;3m on a contract with Uzbekistan because it had shipped goods without securing a letter of credit provided an early warning of problems. But the bidders were astonished at the scale of the chaos. A warehouse in Manchester was stuffed with 100m tax forms printed without changes that the Inland Revenue required. Personal computers were being stockpiled because too many had been ordered. Four properties turned up which were not even on the books. "The business was as badly run as any I have ever seen," said one of the bidders.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not surprisingly, the final offers were lower than the original ones. The eventual winner, Electra Fleming, is understood to have bid around &#163;70m, about &#163;5m-8m more than the consortia led by Mercury Asset Management and NatWest Ventures. But after Electra was declared the preferred bidder, a further round of negotiations led to another 20% being shaved off the price before a deal was finally struck on September 10th. This last-minute haggling has given rise to grumbles of preferential treatment. But given the state of <font size=-1>HMSO</font>'s accounts, it is likely that all of the bidders would have sought to renegotiate. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more serious charge is that the company should not have been sold in such an unsatisfactory condition. The minister handling the sale, Roger Freeman, defends the timing, pointing out that the company's financial position was deteriorating. <font size=-1>HMSO</font>, he says, urgently needed a massive change which only privatisation could provide. But the government could undoubtedly have got a lot more money if it had not allowed <font size=-1>HMSO</font> to get into such a shambles in the first place.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
