<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><p align=center>
<table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</p></center>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width="231" height="24" alt="Britain in Brief" border=0></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>Gulf war reverse</b> &nbsp; The armed forces minister, Nicholas Soames, admitted that the Commons had been misled about troops' exposure to pesticides during the Gulf war. He announced an inquiry into civil servants' conduct in the episode and an investigation into whether there is a "Gulf war syndrome" afflicting veterans of the conflict.<br>
<p><b>Tiffs on talks</b> &nbsp; John Major and John Bruton, the Irish prime minister, met but could not agree to a timetable for Sinn Fein's inclusion in talks on Northern Ireland.<br>
<p><b>Women's rule</b> &nbsp; The Lords took the unprecedented step of voting on Lord Archer's address to the queen, which proposes a bill to give women the same status as men in the order of succession to the throne. The bill must still pass both houses of Parliament.<br>
<p><b>Hearing complaints</b> &nbsp; The Conservative Party faced a rebellion in its ranks as Tory <font size=-1>MPs</font> objected to budget-cutting measures which would have ruled out future claims for increased war pensions due to loss of hearing.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Pleading police</b> &nbsp; London's Metropolitan Police asked the Court of Appeal to reduce damages awarded against it in two different cases from nearly &#163;300,000 to &#163;25,000, and to establish guidelines for future cases.<br>
<p><b>Switched off</b> &nbsp; At the behest of Virginia Bottomley, the national heritage secretary, Britain's three television watchdogs pledged to draw up and enforce stricter codes on screen violence.<br>
<p><b>Soaring</b> &nbsp; Airtours, one of Britain's biggest tour operators, declared a near-50% jump in pre-tax profits to over &#163;86m. The company now plans to expand through new acquisitions, according to its chairman.<br>
<p><b>Santa Claws</b> &nbsp; A mob of 22 men all dressed as Father Christmas attacked a taxi driver in Market Harborough, Leicestershire. The driver has decided to stick to his profession despite a broken nose, since he considers another such attack unlikely.<br>
<p><br>

</td></tr></table></center>

