<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Serbia represses</h2>
Crowds remained on the streets in Serbia after the government closed down the country's last two independent radio stations. They had been broadcasting reports on 16 days of widespread protest against the annulment of municipal elections won by opposition parties.<p>
A <b>bomb</b> on a Paris commuter train killed two people and injured more than 160, many seriously. Suspicion fell on extreme Islamists from Algeria.<p>
<b>Greek farmers</b> demanding cheaper fuel and better price supports blockaded roads and railways. A crippling 12-day strike by French <b>lorry drivers</b> ended after concessions by their employers and the government.<p>
Russia's defence minister, <b>Igor Rodionov</b>, tried to sack the army's commander, Vladimir Semyonov. President Yeltsin approved the dismissal order, which accused the general of dishonourable conduct, but then withheld<p>
a presidential decree needed to put the order into effect. The general denied the accusation.<p>
<b>Russian miners</b> declared a national strike to protest at non-payment of wages. Unions said 80% of the 400,000 miners had joined the strike.<p>
Petru Lucinschi was elected <b>Moldova's president</b>, defeating the incumbent, Mircea Snagur. He had campaigned on a platform of closer ties with Russia.<p>
European Union finance ministers could not agree on a <b>stability pact</b> to curb budget deficits after the start of economic and monetary union. Although they neared agreement on the size of fines to be imposed on countries with excessive deficits, most resisted German demands that exceptions be made only for countries whose economies shrink by 2% in a year.<p>
Swiss voters rejected a liberalisation of the country's <b>labour laws </b>in a referendum. In another vote they narrowly rejected proposals to make it more difficult for asylum-seekers to enter the country.<p>
<h2>Vetoes and votes</h2>
The Organisation of African Unity, accepting America's veto, dropped its exclusive support for the reappointment of <b>Boutros Boutros- Ghali</b> as <font size=-1>UN</font> secretary-general. Mr Boutros-Ghali himself "suspended" his candidacy. On the understanding that it is still Africa's "turn", other African candidates were encouraged to come forward. The president of the <font size=-1>UN</font> General Assembly has set December 17th as the deadline for a decision. <p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Some 85% of Algerian voters, said the country's rulers, approved changes to their constitution that banned<b> Islamist parties</b> and extended the president's powers. The regime's claim of a 79% turnout was considered implausible.<p>
Tutsi rebels in eastern <b>Zaire</b> pushed deeper into the country. They claimed to have seized Kisangani (formerly known as Stanleyville), an important town controlling the Zaire river. Hutu-Tutsi clashes increased in <b>Burundi</b>.<p>
<b>South Africa</b>'s Constitutional Court approved the final changes to the constitution.<p>
In <b>Sierra Leone</b>, government and rebels signed an agreement to end five years of savagery.<p>
<b>Israel's attorney-general</b>, Michael Ben-Yair, resigned. He had earlier questioned the use by police of physical force during interrogations of Palestinian suspects. The <b>Palestinian police</b> were accused in a report by Amnesty International of brutality to their own people.<p>
<h2>New faces</h2>
Madeleine Albright, America's ambassador to the United Nations, was set to be named as the next <b>secretary of state</b>, according to reports in Washington. The other members of Bill Clinton's new foreign-policy team were said to be William Cohen (a former senator from Maine) as secretary of defence, Tony Lake (at present national security adviser) as head of the <font size=-1>CIA</font>, and Sandy Berger as head of the National Security Council, where he is now number two.<p>
Hawaii became the first state in America to recognise <b>homosexual marriages </b>when a state judge found that its government had failed to establish "a compelling state interest" to justify its prohibition of same-sex marriages.<p>
In <b>Ecuador</b>, President Abdala Bucaram, elected as a populist, announced a plan of sober economic reform: fiscal balance, privatisation, easier labour laws, even a local version of Argentina's monetary straitjacket. <p>
<h2>Troops out</h2>
The United States agreed to close some of its <b>military bases in Okinawa </b>and return the land to the local people. A new base for American helicopters will be built on an artificial island to be constructed offshore.<p>
About 1,000 students took part in a protest in Yangon, the capital of <b>Myanmar</b>, demanding an independent union and other rights. It was the biggest demonstration of its type for eight years.<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
