<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <p align=center><img
src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"
border=0></p> <p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business
this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%> <center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top
width=30%> <h2>Keep it French</h2> The French government suspended the sale of <b>Thomson </b> after
an independent commission said it could not approve an offer from the Lagard&egrave;re Groupe because of
its plans to sell one part of the conglomerate, Thomson Multimedia, to Daewoo Electronics. With thousands
of workers at Thomson Multimedia in revolt at the prospect of a South Korean owner, and other labour
disputes flaring, the French government gave in.<p> Another South Korean firm, <b>Samsung
Electronics</b>, had better luck. In March the world's biggest supplier of personal-computer screens will
supply the first of 5m monitors to <b>IBM</b>, the American computer giant, in a three-year deal worth
$2 billion.<p> Two of America's biggest airlines, <b>Delta</b> and <b>Continental</b>, are discussing a
merger that would create America's biggest carrier--and probably prompt other takeovers in their
industry. If the deal goes ahead, one beneficiary could be Air France which has marketing alliances with
both carriers.<p> America's <b>Dow Corning</b>, a breast-implants maker which went bankrupt in 1995 to
limit its exposure to lawsuits claiming the implants were unsafe, produced a new settlement plan. A $600m
fund would be set up for women who settle out of court; a further $1.4 billion would be contingent on proof
that the implants are hazardous; and $1 billion would go to banks and other creditors.<p> Argentina's
growing supermarket sector attracted another outside investor. Exxel, a global investment fund, bought
<b>Supermercados Norte</b>, Argentina's second-largest supermarket chain by sales (of $1.2 billion), for
$440m and said it planned a public share offering.<p> <h2>Drink up</h2> <b>Bass</b>, a British
beer'n'leisure group, is to spend &#163;670m ($1.1 billion) creating 7,000 new jobs next year, much of it
in its pubs and restaurants, after declaring pre-tax profits up 12% to &#163;671m for 1996, a year in
which it spent another &#163;568m creating 6,000 jobs.<p> The Antique Wine Company in London sold 127
bottles of <b>Chateau d'Yquem</b>, a French dessert wine, which included every vintage produced from
1855 to 1990, to a Las Vegas hotel and casino for $1m.<p> Prince Alwaleed bin Talal, a Saudi Arabian
investor whose eclectic portfolio includes both Canary Wharf, London's biggest property development, and
Euro Disney, a French theme park, announced he was buying the <b>George V</b> hotel in Paris. He is
paying Granada, a British leisure group, $172m for what he describes as "the best hotel in the world".<p>
Six officials at Japan's <b>Ministry of Trade and Industry</b> were reprimanded for failing to supervise
staff properly and accepting excessive favours from an oil broker.<p> </td><td
width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%> <h2>Skidding</h2> <b>Volkswagen</b>'s seemingly conciliatory gesture towards
<b>General Motors </b>in sacking Jose Ignacio Lopez turned into more of a two-fingered salute when it
replaced him with another <font size=-1>GM</font> defector, Javier Garcia Sanz, and said that Mr Lopez
would remain as a consultant. <font size=-1>VW</font>'s share price dropped 5.7% on concerns that the
two car makers, at war since the defection of eight <font size=-1>GM</font> executives to <font
size=-1>VW</font> in 1993, would fail to reach an out-of-court settlement.<p> In what could be the first
step towards a broader alliance, on-off talks between America's two aerospace giants brought an
agreement to collaborate on a super-jumbo. Hundreds of underworked engineers from <b>McDonnell
Douglas</b>, which recently abandoned its own plans for such an aircraft, will move from Long Beach to
Seattle to help <b>Boeing</b>, snowed under with orders, develop two new versions of the Boeing 747.<p>
<b>Aeroflot</b>, Russia's state-controlled international airline, said it would buy 20 Russian-made
Ilyushin-96 long-range aircraft equipped with American jet-engines and avionics, in a deal worth $1.5
billion. The move appeased Russia's aircraft makers, which reacted angrily to Aeroflot's purchase of ten
Boeing 737 mid-range aircraft earlier this year. <p> Bowing to government pressure, <b>Avtovaz</b>,
Russia's biggest car maker, said it would double its share capital and offer the new shares to one or more
outside investors. Any proceeds would help the stricken firm meet its so-far-unpaid $500m tax bill.<p>
<b>Eurotunnel</b> won permission from health-and-safety officials to restore most passenger and car
services through the Channel tunnel. But a decision on resuming freight shuttles--one of which was the
source of a large fire which raged in the tunnel last month--will not be made until official inquiries are
completed.<p> <h2>Top dollar</h2> (See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The ebullient Dow Jones went
into reverse; the index fell 79 points on December 3rd. Most European <b>bourses </b> carried on rising
buoyed by a strong dollar. The dollar's strength, plus the British government's talk-down of the pound, put
the damper on sterling's extended rally.<p> Three former executives at <b>Archer Daniels Midland</b>
were indicted by a Chicago grand jury for conspiring to fix prices in the $600m market for lysine, an
animal-feed additive. Also indicted was an executive at Ajinomoto of Japan, one of <font
size=-1>ADM</font>'s leading competitors. A South Korean company, Cheil Jedang, agreed to plead guilty
to fixing prices and to pay a $1.25m fine.<p> <b>Alan Bond</b>, currently serving a three-year sentence
for fraud relating to an Impressionist painting, pleaded guilty in an Australian court to two charges of
dishonesty relating to a A$1 billion ($800m) corporate fraud, Australia's biggest ever.<p>

</td></tr></table></center> <p align=center><a href="ww0232.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p> <p
