<html><head><title>All quiet on the eastern front</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table
width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26"
alt="Asia" border=0> <td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif"
width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>All quiet on the eastern front</h1>

<font size=1>DELHI</font><p> SOME called it weak-kneed, most said it was pragmatic statesmanship. India
has many complaints about China-- that it has occupied Indian territory, given missiles and nuclear
technology to Pakistan, and supported the Pakistani position on Kashmir.
Yet the Indian government rolled out the red carpet for Jiang Zemin, the president of China, when he visited
Delhi on November 28th and signed an agreement for confidence-building measures which could lead to the
partial demilitarisation of their disputed border.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two
countries agreed not to attack one another; to limit or reduce troops and weapons in a zone to be worked out
on both sides of the "line of actual control" (<font size=-1>LAC</font>); and to ban combat aircraft within
ten kilometres (six miles) of the <font size=-1>LAC</font> except with prior notice.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Below the surface, this is an agreement to disagree. Both sides
have territorial claims on the other. China has offered to make the <font size=-1>LAC</font> the official
border, which means it would give up its claims in the eastern sector in return for India giving up its claims
in the western sector. But no Indian government could agree to a deal like that; it would be accused of
treason by all opposition parties. So demilitarising the <font size=-1>LAC</font> is an interim measure to
reduce tension, the chances of a military clash, and defence spending, without any surrender of
territory.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two sides disagree even on where the <font
size=-1>LAC</font> runs, though they have not pursued their disagreement violently since an ugly military
clash in 1987. The current aim is to avoid any further fighting till the <font size=-1>LAC</font> is
formally demarcated, a task that has so far proved elusive. Troop reductions have also been discussed in
the past, but without success. The Chinese side of the border is a plateau on which troops can be quickly
moved, whereas the Indian side is steep, landslide-prone mountainside. China would like both sides to
withdraw an equal distance, but India says that would enable the Chinese to reach the border faster. The
issue is unlikely to be resolved quickly.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some Indians argued
that their government should have refused to receive the head of a country it accuses of supplying <font
size=-1>M-11</font> missiles and nuclear-weapons technology to Pakistan. But the government, though it
stridently accuses Pakistan of threatening Indian security, has chosen not to make an issue of China's role.
It has decided to live with China's weapons sales, which it thinks are motivated by commercial rather than
strategic considerations.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though some Indians worry that
China may be trying to "contain" India by fostering ties with Pakistan, Myanmar and Bangladesh, the Indian
government is less suspicious. The Chinese attack of 1962 is now a distant memory in India. Deng Xiaoping's
China looks less threatening than Mao's. Indeed, an invasion by Chinese businessmen now seems more likely
than an invasion by Chinese troops. Trade between the two countries is a mere $1 billion, but growing at
30% each year. India will back China's entry into the World Trade Organisation, and China will back India's
entry into the Asia-Pacific Economic Co-operation forum. Modest beginnings, but not to be sneered at in a
region where international tensions still run high.<br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
