<html><head><title>Working miracles</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table width=100%><tr><td
valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0> <p><font
size=-1> These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published
here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions. </font></p></td><td></td> <td align=right
valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The
Economist" border=0> </td></tr></table>

<h1>Working miracles</h1>

BRITAIN'S "flexible" labour markets are increasingly held up as a model for the inflexible rest of Europe to
follow. Research published in December's issue of <i>Labour Market Trends</i> was claimed in support of
this conclusion by Tory ministers. But on closer inspection it raised as many questions as it answered.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Certainly, unemployment has fallen more quickly during the
economic recovery of the 1990s than it did in that of the 1980s. Nor has this triggered a rise in
wage-inflation. This suggests that Tory reforms to weaken employment rights such as job protection and to
curb trade-union power, thus encouraging employers to hire new workers sooner as demand increases,
have paid off.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, says the new research, that is not the
whole story. Several other factors contributed to the change. In the 1990s more people opted out of the
workforce--into higher education, early retirement, or invalidity--than in the 1980s. Job growth was
spread more evenly across the country, so it took longer for shortages to occur in any one area, making it
easier to contain wage pressures.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As our <a
href="br1.gif">chart</a> shows, Britain's job creation record was better in the 1990s than in the 1980s, both in
absolute terms and in comparison with America and Germany. Of all the Group of Seven rich countries, only
France had a similar improvement. Yet Britain's record still only matched Germany's. That was better than
in the 1980s, but hardly justifies Tory boasts about Britain's superior labour-market policies. For
American-style jobs-growth, Britain, and the rest of Europe, need more than flexibility: they need better
education and a social-security system that does not actually discourage working, for a start.<br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
&nbsp; - &nbsp; <a
href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849920400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; -
