<html><head><title>New rail barons</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Rail privatisation</b></p>
<h1>New rail barons</h1>

THREE more passenger rail franchises were awarded to private companies this week--Great Eastern to FirstBus, Anglia to <font size=-1>GB</font> Railways, and West Anglia and Great Northern to Prism Rail. Only a third of the original 25 franchises remain unsold. Unless an election intervenes, they will be sold within the next four months.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet already the government's blueprint for the industry is in the bin. The government had hoped that by splitting British Rail into more than 100 different companies it would promote competition. But the lesson of other utility privatisations--that what ministers split, the market reassembles--is being repeated.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;John Seurat of Symonds Travers Morgan, a transport consultancy, says that rail is likely to follow the pattern of the bus industry. Deregulation of buses led to the appearance, and then the disappearance, of 500 separate companies. The industry is now dominated by a handful of operators--three of which (Stagecoach, National Express and FirstBus) are among the leading contenders for rail franchises.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Stagecoach has already got two franchises, South West Trains and the Island Line, and is one of three preferred bidders for the Inter City West Coast line. It is now bidding to take over Porterbrook, one of three leasing companies. This move, if approved, will be the first step towards the vertical integration of the rail industry.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Monopolies and Mergers Commission is worried about whether to allow bus companies to dominate the rail industry. It is therefore looking attentively at bids by Stagecoach for ScotRail and by National Express for Midland Main Line; but both are likely to be approved.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other key players in the franchise race are Connex, owned by the Compagnie G&eacute;n&eacute;rale des Eaux, Sea Containers, a ferry and container operator, and Virgin, part of the consortium which runs the Eurostar passenger trains. Between them, the five companies already control nearly half of all rail passenger revenues, a proportion likely to increase in coming months. Industry sources also expect that the three franchises awarded to management buy-outs-- <font size=-1>M</font>40 Trains, Victory Railways and Great Western--will also attract bids.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The City, not surprisingly, has contracted rail fever. Porterbrook was privatised for &#163;527m and bought from its managers by Stagecoach for &#163;825m seven months later. Shares in Prism Rail, a small train operating company which has the London-Tilbury-Southend franchise, have quintupled in six months from the &#163;1 offering price. Railtrack's shares, which were floated earlier this year at 190p, have also nearly doubled in value. Its first pre-tax statement after the flotation reported that profits had leapt by 77%, to &#163;173m.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The expectation of big profits lies behind this stockmarket performance. The new operators are promising new rolling stock, smaller subsidies and even lower fares. Their confidence is based partly on the belief that increasing road congestion will drive people on to trains.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are some signs that their optimism may be justified. Most franchisees are reporting a sharp rise in passenger volumes, maybe because even travellers seem to be benefiting. According to the first performance figures from eight privatised routes, seven were more punctual than they had been before privatisation, and all eight were more reliable in running scheduled services.<br>
<br>

