<html><head><title>Bigger, faster, better ears</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table
width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26"
alt="Business" border=0> <td align=right valign=top><img
src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"
border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The other technopolists</b></p> <h1>Bigger, faster, better ears</h1>

<p><b>Internet folk are famously opposed to the proprietary standards that made Microsoft and Intel so
dominant. So how did Cisco Systems win 85% of the Internet's richest market--and become worth the same
as General Motors?</b></p><br> ALL this year the computer industry has been hotly debating which
company, Microsoft or Netscape, will win the Internet software market. But there has been no such debate
on the hardware side, because there is no contest. The undisputed leader in this market is Cisco Systems, a
maker of network equipment. Thanks to its soaring share price, Cisco has a market capitalisation of over
$40 billion (much the same as General Motors), yet the firm has barely attracted the notice of the average
computer user, much less the antitrust authorities. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Part of
the reason is that the Californian firm's market is as obscure as it is fast-growing. Cisco makes computer
networking equipment of all sorts, but most of its profits come from selling specialised computers called
"routers" that direct traffic at the intersections of the Internet's many routes. These are machines that the
ordinary user never sees, nor much cares about. Like the switches of a telephone network, these devices,
provided they are doing their job properly, are in effect invisible. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Each e-mail message or transmitted Web <dest="makes"
ref="page"> its way from sender to receiver by being automatically bounced, pinball-like, from one router
to the next. The wires that connect the Internet's routers are just dumb pipes; all the magic of the network
lies in the routers. It is they that enable the Internet to weave together seamlessly thousands of smaller
networks, or send a message around the world without specifying anything more than a few characters. As
the Internet doubles in size each year, so does the demand for ever more, ever faster routers. And 85% of
these are made by Cisco.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This dominance of one of the hottest
high-tech markets has lifted Cisco into the ranks of the computer industry's most successful firms. The
company is big (sales in the past financial year exceeded $4 billion, and this year are expected to pass $6
billion) and highly profitable (net profits were nearly $1 billion last year), and it has been almost doubling
in size each year for most of this decade (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). Yet while Cisco may share
with Microsoft and Intel some of the financial rewards of market domination, it got there in a very
different way.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most quasi-monopolies in technology markets
owe their position to their ownership of a standard. Because so much of technology is about one gizmo
connecting to or working with another gizmo, they usually need a common language for talking to each
other. Sometimes that language is open and free for all to use; but often such standards were created and
are owned by one company which, either through might or luck, has managed to persuade the rest of the
industry to do things its way.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Owning such a de facto standard
is the surest way to become a technopolist, as Microsoft proved with its <font size=-1>PC</font> system
software, and Intel with its <font size=-1>PC</font> processor chips. But the Internet has, since its start,
been a creature of open, non-proprietary standards. Part of the reason for this is that communications
technologies need ubiquity for maximum impact; the more people you can communicate with, the more
useful the technology becomes. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No company owns an accepted
Internet standard. Cisco can use every trick and secret in the book to make its routers faster than the
competition or easier to use, but where they connect with the rest of the Internet they must stick largely
to open Internet standards. Even when Cisco invents a way to improve upon those standards, it must submit
it to an independent standards committee and make it available to other firms before customers will accept
it. Networking companies expect equipment to be "interoperable", so they can unplug a Cisco router and plug
in one from a competing firm, such as Bay Networks or Ascend Communications, in its place. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The consequence of this devotion to open standards is that network
operators enjoy what economists call low switching costs: changing suppliers is relatively easy. It is this
that makes Cisco's dominance so surprising. Much of Microsoft's hold on the software market is due to high
switching costs. If you abandon Microsoft's Windows for another company's system, many of your other
programs, which cost a packet and took weeks to learn, may well stop working, or you may be cut off from
the next hot software innovation. Likewise, Intel dominates the microprocessor market because it sets the
standard and enjoys a monopoly on its newest chips for years before competitors figure out how to clone
them.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike them, Cisco keeps its dominance the
old-fashioned way: it simply makes routers that are better than the competition's. It created the router
market in 1984, when Sandy Lerner and Leonard Bosack, a husband-and-wife team of Stanford academics,
set up the firm to market machines they had cobbled together at their university. And it has managed to
stay ahead of its competition ever since by running faster.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From the beginning, Cisco distinguished itself from bigger
companies by retaining its local connections and listening to its customers. Firms such as <font
size=-1>IBM</font>, <font size=-1>AT&T</font> and Proteon were already in the network-equipment
business, but missed the significance of routers--and router-based networks such as the Internet. "The
number of companies that gave away this business is remarkable," says Mike O'Dell, head of technical
operations for <font size=-1>UUN</font>et, which uses Cisco routers to run much of its global Internet
network. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With its close ties to the universities and companies
developing the Internet, Cisco could evolve along with it. But, as the company grew, it found that it
sometimes had to choose between its own technical goals and the wish-lists of its customers. On one side
was Ms Lerner, who put herself in charge of a "customer advocacy" group. On the other were the
professional managers the firm had brought in. In 1990, after the firm went public, its two founders
left.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite that clash, and despite its tremendous growth
since then, Cisco has managed to keep its reputation for knowing its customers better than the competition.
That allowed Cisco to foresee how the market would develop, because the staid corporate networking
market tends to trail Internet trend-setters by a few years. And its customer focus helped Cisco to sell a
lot of boxes without much promotion. It did not buy its first advertisement until 1992, when it already had
more than $300m in annual revenues. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Internet service
companies have a close interest in telling Cisco what they need, because the very fabric of the Internet
depends on the company being able to come up with faster routers quickly enough to keep up with the
network's soaring traffic-demands. This information flow helps the firm to stay a technology hop ahead of
its competition. The Internet is, in effect, Cisco's research and development laboratory.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Only as good as your last byte</b></b><br> What could go wrong? In fact, Cisco's
quasi-monopoly may be more fragile than its admirers on Wall Street believe. The company's position rests
on little more than its ability to listen better, innovate faster and employ better people than its competition.
If another rival starts to do all of these things a little bit better, or too many brainy people leave Cisco, the
advantage could disappear overnight. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And, naturally, Cisco is
facing the usual risks of domination: complacency, conservatism and excessive concentration on the most
profitable markets. Already some customers are mumbling that other firms seem to have more compelling
technologies for the next generation of even faster routers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Cisco's usual reaction to having missed a beat in this fast-moving
market is to buy a company with the necessary technology-- since 1994, it has spent more than $5 billion
on such acquisitions. But such takeovers have their administrative costs. Other hardware firms have often
got into trouble because they have bitten off something bigger than they could chew. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the Internet's booming market, where service providers are
constantly upgrading to better routers to stay ahead of demand, Cisco cannot count on customer loyalty
alone to sustain its lead. Switching suppliers is never easy, but it is certainly easier for Cisco's customers
than, say, Microsoft's. A dominance based simply on being better at guessing the way forward than other
firms and getting there faster is never as safe as one built on owning an industry standard. Even the best
legs eventually get tired, and the best hearing grows faint.<br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
