<html><head><title>Hail to the mighty pound</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"> <table
width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26"
alt="Finance and Economics" border=0> <td align=right valign=top><img
src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist"
border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Hail to the mighty pound</h1>

<p><b>Sterling was the strongest of the world's major currencies until it dipped this week. Is this the end
of its rise, or just the beginning?</b></p><br> THESE are halcyon days for the British pound. Between
August and early December, sterling soared from $1.54 to $1.68, &#165;164 to &#165;193, and DM2.28
to DM2.64. Its trade-weighted value (which reflects the pattern of Britain's trade with different countries)
was over 14% up on a year earlier (see <a href="fn1.gif">chart</a>). This is heady stuff indeed for a
currency which has been falling in value for most of the past 50 years. And it is only four years since
sterling was pushed into a withdrawal from Europe's exchange-rate mechanism (<font size=-1>ERM</font>)
that deeply embarrassed the government. But what happens next to the pound--and with it, the British
economy-- is now in the balance. Is the strong pound back for good? <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To many Britons, the pound's long-term fall from global reserve
currency to small change symbolised their country's broader decline from industrial superpower to an
also-ran struggling to keep up with the likes of Singapore and Italy. That is why some British nationalists
oppose joining the planned single European currency, the "abolition of the pound" being, for them, a final
admission of economic defeat. Yet sterling's recent revival has not led the average Briton to walk taller. It
seems to have been greeted with a mixture of indifference and ambivalence.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Soon after winning the 1992 British general election, John Major,
the prime minister, said that his goal was for sterling to replace the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark as
Europe's strong, stable currency. But now, with sterling still some way beneath the exchange rate it had
with the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark then, Mr Major's government seems uncertain about what to make
of the pound's new-found strength. Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, has argued that the
rising pound will dampen inflationary pressures, so reducing the need for him to raise interest rates before
next year's general election. But, more recently, he has echoed the fears of "large numbers of British
industries" that sterling is getting too strong.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sterling's exit
from the <font size=-1>ERM</font> soon after Mr Major pledged to out-muscle the <font
size=-1>D</font>-mark sharply changed British attitudes towards a strong pound. Instead of pushing up
inflation and thus prolonging recession, as was predicted, the weaker pound boosted the international
competitiveness of British firms, helping exports to soar. Britain became a cheap place to visit and to do
business. Huge amounts of foreign investment poured in, reviving bits of the economy as moribund as the
film industry, which has been inundated with work from Hollywood studios attracted by its low production
costs. And all this coincided with huge problems in the big continental economies, especially France, whose
politicians complained endlessly about Britain's "unfair advantage" of cheap sterling.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The stronger pound seems to threaten all this. Will
<i>Newsweek</i> still call London the "world's coolest city" if its high prices, in dollars, scare off
American tourists? Might foreign investors divert their cash elsewhere? According to the British Screen
Advisory Council, Britain is now less expensive than America in only two of the seven main elements of
film-making, compared with five in August. And who will buy British? The Confederation of British Industry
claims that the strong pound is hurting exports. Some analysts in the City of London recently cut their 1996
profit forecasts for leading British exporters by two percentage points.<br> </p><p><b><b>Revaluation or
aberration?</b></b><br> For now, such fears are overdone. It is easy to exaggerate how important cheap
sterling has been to the economy since 1992. The recession of the early 1990s was already over when the
pound left the <font size=-1>ERM</font>. Foreign investors come to Britain as much for its access to
Europe's single market, its flexible labour laws and its English-speaking workers as its weak currency.
Also, although cheap sterling helped exporters, many took the opportunity to pad their profit margins
rather than increase the volume of export sales; their sales need not suffer now if they trim margins again.
Britain's main export markets are likely to grow faster during the next few years than in the recent past,
and this extra demand should make up for any sales lost because of a strong pound.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even after this year's surge the pound seems pretty fairly valued.
Economists disagree greatly about what a "right" exchange rate is. But most estimates suggest that the
pound's trade-weighted value is roughly right. Britain's current account is almost in balance: a far cry
from 1988, when sterling was too strong, hitting exports and boosting imports. The pound's real exchange
rate (the nominal rate adjusted for differences in inflation between countries) is still below its average
over the past 15 years.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Britain's economy, the central
question is whether the pound's rise is a short-term aberration or a fundamental revaluation. Predicting the
foreign-exchange markets is hazardous. Economic theory sheds some light on long-term exchange-rate
movements, but is useless in forecasting either the direction or timing of short-term changes. No one is
absolutely sure why the pound has been so strong this year, which makes it hard to say whether it is still
rising, on a plateau or riding for a fall.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is Britain's growing
inflationary pressures that most probably explain the rise of sterling, reckons David Mackie, an economist
at J.P. Morgan, an investment bank. Investors, including the notorious hedge-fund speculators, have been
buying the pound like hot cakes because Britain is one of the few countries where interest rates are
expected to go up reasonably soon. The currency markets seem to be pricing in a rise of one percentage
point. Meanwhile, rates in America and Japan look stable, and continental Europe's may be ready to fall.
That greater-than-expected differential in interest rates means greater returns for investors who own
pounds. <br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One alternative explanation pins the pound's rise on
expectations that Britain will, after all, join in the single European currency that may start in 1998. That
interpretation looks misguided, since both Britain's main political parties are increasingly lukewarm about
abandoning sterling-- and British voters overwhelmingly oppose doing so. Yet another story in the markets
has sterling in much demand, along with the Swiss franc, as a haven for investors who think the new single
currency will prove inflation-prone. That explanation also strains belief: the money markets expect
inflation to be higher in Britain than in most of the countries likely to join monetary union, so investors
would be more likely to dump sterling than to hold it.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of
this technical stuff will trouble ordinary Britons, few of whom have yet noticed that the pound in their
pocket is for once going up. They will soon catch on to the pleasures of cheap imports and affordable foreign
travel. But those who puff that the pound's recent strength is a long-term "reward" for Britain's improved
economic fundamentals may end up disappointed.<br> &#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main
reason for long-term changes in exchange rates is differences in inflation rates. British inflation is at its
lowest in decades, but is still higher than in America, Japan and much of continental Europe. There are signs
it will soon rise--particularly if the British government repeats the errors of the late 1980s by using a
strong pound to excuse lax monetary policy. Keeping the pound mighty may take more hard work than
Britain is willing to put in.<br> <br>

<p align=center> <a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
