<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>A single step</h2>
The <b>Italian lira</b> re-entered Europe's exchange-rate mechanism. Finance ministers insisted on a strongish central rate of 990 lire to the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark; in subsequent trading the lira strengthened. Keen to adopt the single currency at the first stage, Italy must keep the lira in the <font size=-1>ERM</font> for two years.<p>
(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>The pound </b>rose to its highest level in four years against the dollar, driven by hopes that British interest rates would rise. This week's pre-election budget reinforced these expectations.<p>
The Russian government showed its confidence in maintaining the value of <b>the  rouble </b>by setting an annual range for the currency against the dollar instead of the usual six-monthly band. The rouble will start 1997 in a range of 5,500-6,100 roubles to the dollar and decline to 5,750-6,350 roubles.<p>
<h2>Taking stock</h2>
<b>Union Bank of Switzer land</b>, beset by bad loans, will report its first full-year loss since the second world war and take a one-off charge of SFr3 billion ($2.3 billion), leaving it with a loss for 1996 of about SFr500m. Standard & Poor's, an American credit-rating agency, put a watch on its <font size=-1>AAA</font> rating. Like other banks hurt by Switzerland's prolonged recession, <font size=-1>UBS</font> will also restructure its domestic operations.<p>
A Detroit judge ruled that <b>General Motors </b>could pursue racketeering charges against Jose Ignacio Lopez, who is accused of taking secret documents with him when he left <font size=-1>GM</font> to join <b>Volkswagen</b>. Opel, <font size=-1>GM</font>'s subsidiary in Germany, denied reports that it was in talks with <font size=-1>VW</font> over an out-of-court settlement. Any deal, it said, would require the firing of Mr Lopez, payment for damages, and a public apology.<p>
American shares soared, taking the <b>Dow Jones </b>above 6,500 for the first time and helping seven European markets to reach new records before dropping back. Bond prices rose.<p>
<b>ABN Amro</b>, the Netherlands' largest bank, bolstered its position as the biggest foreign bank in America with a $1.95 billion purchase of Standard Federal, the mid-west's biggest savings bank.<p>
Germany unveiled a bill to improve <b>shareholders'  rights</b>. Among the proposals: companies will be allowed to buy back up to 10% of their shares; supervisory boards will be limited to 12 members; and schemes limiting shareholders' voting rights will be banned.<p>
Malaysia's overcrowded banking sector is being shaken up by a complex deal to form a huge Malaysian financial-services company. <b>Rashid Hussain</b>, a big stockbroking firm and property developer, paid M$2.16 billion ($855m) for a 75% share of Kwong Yik Bank, which will later merge with <font size=-1>DCB</font> Holdings, Rashid Hussain's banking operations.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Skandia</b>, a Swedish insurance company, and <b>Stadshypotek</b>, Sweden's biggest mortgage bank, are to merge, creating a financial-services group with a market value of SKr45 billion ($6.7 billion). An angry government, whose proposed sale of its 34% stake in Stadshypotek triggered the talks (of which it was not aware), insisted its stake would go to auction.<p>
Following the lead of Japan's biggest stockbroker, Nomura Securities, which recently bailed out its lending unit, <b>Daiwa Securities</b>, the second biggest, will inject &#165;120 billion ($1.1 billion) of capital into Daiwa Finance to write off bad property loans. Other Japanese stockbrokers are likely to follow suit.<p>
Russia raised $1 billion from a debut Eurobond--twice as much as originally planned. It also agreed with the French government to pay $400m to French holders of <b>Imperial  Russian bonds</b> in default since 1917--a deal derided by the bondholders, who had claimed $30 billion.<p>
<h2>Smoke damage</h2>
<b>Eurotunnel</b> shares dived on news that the damage caused by a fire in the Channel tunnel could delay the resumption of a full rail service for months. They recovered when the company said that this would not affect its restructuring.<p>
In America's biggest gas-and-utility merger, <b>Duke Power</b>, a North Carolina electricity utility, agreed to buy <b>PanEnergy</b>, a Texan natural-gas concern, for $7.7 billion.<p>
<b>Olivetti</b>'s new boss said that his struggling company's plan to sell assets might be delayed. He gave a warning that a proposed investigation by parliament could precipitate Olivetti's closure.<p>
The <b>Suez Canal</b> will give some ships discounts ranging from 5% to 35% to combat competition from oil and gas pipelines and from other shipping routes.<p>
The Russian government dismissed a consortium of western banks that was to have led a $1 billion initial public offering of <b>Russia's telecoms  holdings</b>; it also combined its stakes in the country's two largest telecoms operators. A group led by two domestic banks, with close connections to Boris Yeltsin's presidential campaign, are likely to become not only the new advisers but big shareholders too. The government threatened a large car maker, Avtovaz, with bankruptcy. <p>
France said it would sell at least another 5% of <b>Groupe  Bull</b> in the next few weeks to take its stake in the computer maker below 50%. The government also fired the boss of Groupe des Assurances Nationales two weeks after opposition from within the state-owned firm had forced the postponement of its banking subsidiary.<p>
Representatives from America's television and computer industries reached agreement on technical standards for transmitting <b>digital-televi sion signals</b>.<p>
<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
