</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The great O.J. replay</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The great O.J. replay</h1>

<font size=1>LOS ANGELES</font><p>
TWO and a half years after the murder, and 13 months after an extraordinarily protracted criminal trial had found him not guilty, O.J. Simpson finally took the witness stand on November 22nd. His testimony was the central act in a civil case brought against Mr Simpson by the victims' families for the "wrongful deaths" of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman outside Nicole's house. Deeply familiar as the story is, the case has lost none of its power to transfix, divide and unite Americans. Even though the judge has barred cameras from the courtroom, Mr Simpson is once again the talk of every bar-room and dinner-table in the country. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Simpson case touches on three great American obsessions: celebrity, crime and, above all, race. Johnnie Cochran, Mr Simpson's leading lawyer in the criminal case, deliberately made race, rather than murder, the subject of that trial. He made sure that the majority of jurors were black women, since it had been suggested that black women were even more likely than black men to believe that Mr Simpson was innocent. And he painted Mr Simpson, who had hitherto moved almost exclusively in white society, as a victim of racial oppression.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Cochran's tactics even included redecorating Mr Simpson's house before a visit by the jury, substituting pictures of his relatives for those of his white girlfriends and hanging a copy of Norman Rockwell's painting, "The Problem We All Live With", in which a black girl walks to school surrounded by federal marshals, outside his bedroom. And he accused the Los Angeles Police Department of a large-scale conspiracy to frame a black hero. The result was that, when the verdict came, the nation was sharply divided on racial grounds, with blacks regarding the outcome as a vindication and whites seeing it as a travesty of justice.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The civil trial differs from the criminal trial in four important ways. Mr Simpson will lose his fortune rather than his freedom if he is found guilty. The proceedings are less skewed towards the defendant: the burden of proof is not quite so heavy, and the judge does not have to bend quite so far to protect his rights. The majority of the jury are white rather than black women. And Mr Simpson (who exercised his constitutional right not to testify in the previous trial) has no choice but to take the stand.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His appearance there sent the media into a frenzy. The big news networks employed teams of tame academics and lawyers and produced regular updates throughout the day. The E! channel (which specialises in celebrity trivia) tried to make up for the ban on cameras in court by putting on nightly dramatisations of the proceedings. On talk radio, the talk is of little else; newspapers and magazines are once again filling up with details about Ford Broncos, bloodied gloves and Italian shoes. The media have virtually mounted an assault on the Santa Monica courthouse, masterminded from a mass of news-trucks nicknamed "Camp O.J.", and would-be spectators arrive at four in the morning to compete in a lottery for courtroom seats. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the three days he had him on the stand, Daniel Petrocelli, the plaintiffs' leading lawyer, subjected Mr Simpson to a blitz of scornful, rapid-fire questions, intended as much to rile him into losing his temper as to expose weaknesses in his argument. Addressing him as "sir", but in a voice tinged with contempt, he once got so close to Mr Simpson that he had to be asked to step back. Mr Simpson stood up well to this barrage, keeping his temper under control, speaking in a clear, emphatic voice and, after a shifty start, making eye-contact with the jury. Yet after three days of questioning his position was weakened.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Simpson admitted he had no idea how the victims' blood ended up in his car and house, or how his own blood turned up at the crime scene. (His lawyers will no doubt offer some explanation as the trial progresses.) He also admitted that he had no idea how he got a deep gouge on his hand on the day of the murders. He swore that he had never hit, struck or slapped his ex-wife. But Mr Petrocelli placed an enlarged photograph of Nicole's bruised and beaten face on the wall behind Mr Simpson, and reminded him that he had entered a plea of no contest to a charge of battering her in 1989. Mr Simpson denied retrieving a "Dear John" telephone message from a girlfriend on the night of the murder. But Mr Petrocelli produced telephone bills proving that he had listened to the message.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Petrocelli's aim is, first, to persuade the jury that if Mr Simpson can lie about hitting his wife or receiving telephone calls from his mistress, he can also lie about murder; and, second, to provide an explanation of why he acted as he did. He is trying to present him as a jealous and abusive husband who finally cracked in May 1994, when Nicole made it clear that she no longer wanted to see him and returned a $6,000 birthday present.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Petrocelli succeeded in introducing three new pieces of evidence. The first was the fact that, shortly after his arrest, Mr Simpson's defence team had given him a polygraph test and produced a score so dismal as to suggest "extreme deception". The second was a telephone conversation with the police during the famous slow-motion car chase in 1994. Mr Simpson told the police (whom he later accused of framing him) that "I know you're doing a good job" and said that "No one's going to be hurt. I'm the only one that deserves it." The third was a photograph of Mr Simpson wearing Bruno Magli shoes--the type of rare, expensive shoes that left footprints at the scene of the crime. Mr Simpson has always denied owning such "ugly-ass shoes" and maintains that the photograph is a fake.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dynamics of the civil trial are turning out to be very different from those of its predecessor. The plaintiffs have learned the importance of keeping things concise and focused: they are likely to make their case in six weeks, compared with the six months the prosecution took in the criminal trial. The judge, Hiroshi Fujisaki, has added to this businesslike atmosphere. Nicknamed the "anti-Ito" because he is as intolerant of rambling as his predecessor was indulgent of it, he dismissed a juror on November 26th because she passed a favourable comment on a tie worn by a member of the prosecution team.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More important still, he has done his best to keep the race card out of the trial. He has forbidden the defence to harp on about the testimony of Mark Fuhrman, a former detective whose unrelated remarks about "niggers" did much to scupper the criminal trial, or to indulge in "far-fetched hypothesising" about racist conspiracies. This will make it hard for the defence to argue, as it did in the criminal case, that Mr Simpson is the victim of an anti-black plot. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The biggest worry about the trial is not that the judge is ruling out important evidence, but that Mr Simpson is being subjected to double jeopardy. Critics argue that, after two and a half years of non-stop commentary on the subject, no jury will be able to come to a fair verdict on Mr Simpson, particularly as so many of the leading commentators have proclaimed that the criminal trial was a travesty of justice. But against the fear of double jeopardy should be set the fact that a growing number of high-profile cases are now going to a second trial, simply because the first trials were ruined by a mixture of racial politics, media pressure and courtroom charisma.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the Rodney King case, four police officers were acquitted of beating up a black motorist because the case was tried before an all-white jury, and because one of the accused policemen, Stacey Koon, put up a compelling performance. A jury failed to convict the Menendez twins of murdering their parents--despite the fact that they admitted to killing them--because their lawyer selected the jurors carefully and played on their emotions like a master. But charismatic performances are difficult to repeat, and moving a trial to another district can make it harder to play the race card. In a legal system that is being distorted by race and celebrity, perhaps it takes a little double jeopardy to remind Americans that judicial procedure is a serious thing.<br>

<p align=center>
