<html><head><title>The ghosts at the EMU feast</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The ghosts at the EMU feast</h1>

<font size=1>BRUSSELS</font><p>
<p><b>The lira's re-entry into the exchange-rate mechanism has increased the  chances that most of the European Union's countries may join a single cur rency on January 1st 1999. But pitfalls still strew the path</b></p><br>
IT WAS just like old times. A Saturday summons of monetary officials to Brussels, a row, then a tortured finance ministers' negotiation that ran almost until the markets reopened on Monday. It could have been any of the myriad realignments of Europe's exchange-rate mechanism in the 1980s and 1990s. This time, however, it was a case of readmitting, not devaluing, a currency: the Italian lira, which was ejected by the system, along with the British pound, in September 1992. Surely this should have been a matter for celebration. So why the row?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the answers to that question are to be found some hard truths, not about the <font size=-1>ERM</font>, but about Europe's prospective passage towards its single currency, the euro. The ostensible argument over the weekend of November 23rd-24th concerned the lira's parity. Italy, whose economy has flourished since its currency fell from its old <font size=-1>ERM</font> central rate of 802 lire to the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark, wanted the new parity to be fixed no stronger than 1,000. It expected the French, who say they have suffered badly from what they call Italy's earlier "competitive devaluation", to fight for a stronger lira. In the event, it was the Germans who fought harder--but settled for a central rate of 990.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since <font size=-1>ERM</font> currencies can now fluctuate by as much as 15% either side of their central rates, this will make little practical difference--which is why the French were quite relaxed. The Germans, however, had a different agenda. They wanted to stress publicly how strict they would be, not just about the <font size=-1>ERM</font> but, more importantly, about the single currency. After the deal was done, the president of Germany's Bundesbank, Hans Tietmeyer, swiftly made plain that although Italy had now rejoined the <font size=-1>ERM</font>, its qualification for the single currency was far from assured.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Tietmeyer has reasons to worry. When the Maastricht treaty was negotiated in 1991, the Germans insisted on tough criteria to ensure that countries seeking to join the new currency should have low inflation rates, low long-term interest rates, stable exchange rates within the <font size=-1>ERM</font>, and low public-sector deficits and debt. For a while, it seemed that such rules would narrow the starting cluster to the Benelux countries, Austria, Germany, France and perhaps Ireland--and even that would have required a flexible interpretation of the debt criterion for the Irish and the Belgians.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More recently the picture has changed. Earlier this month the European Commission forecast that no fewer than 12 of the Union's 15 countries--that is, all except Britain, Italy and Greece--might, broadly, meet the Maastricht criteria in 1997 (see <a href="eu1.gif">chart</a>), including the toughest one of all, the ceiling for budget deficits at 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>. Since then both Italy and, this week, Britain have put forward budgets that they claim will bring them below the 3% ceiling. With Finland and Italy both now inside the <font size=-1>ERM</font>, only Sweden, Britain and Greece could be said not to comply with the exchange-rate criterion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such a rapid change has seemed incredible to many, notably the Germans, who dismissed the commission's forecasts as over-optimistic and complained that the 1997 budgets of several countries included a host of one-off measures and dodgy accounting fiddles. Most striking are: France's plan to count a one-time transfer of cash from France T&eacute;l&eacute;com to the government, which in turn will take on the company's pension liabilities; Spain's tactic of using privatisation receipts to pay for losses in other state-owned industries; and Italy's planned "euro tax", which is to be partially refunded in future years.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The sums involved are significant: the France T&eacute;l&eacute;com ploy is worth 0.5% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> and the euro tax 0.6%. Sceptics also point to a report of the European Monetary Institute, the precursor of a European central bank, which was published the same day as the commission forecasts and asserted that "progress in fiscal consolidation has generally been too slow." The <font size=-1>EMI</font>, much less bullish than the commission, noted that in 1996 only four countries' budget deficits were below the 3% limit.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yves-Thibault de Silguy, the commissioner for monetary affairs, shrugs off such criticisms. The reason that so many countries' figures cluster conveniently close to the 3% ceiling, he says, is that governments have made heroic efforts to get them there. As for the one-off measures, controversial ones have to be approved by the independent European statistical office (run by a Frenchman). In any case, when it comes to its evaluation early in 1998, the commission will, he promises, look not just at actual figures for 1997 but also at forecasts for 1998 before opining on which countries have "durably converged" and should thus qualify for the currency.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All the same, the process of choosing, in early 1998, which countries should join the new currency will be fraught. The Maastricht treaty provides that a European Council of heads of government must decide, country by country. The council may be guided by the treaty criteria, by the commission's recommendations or even by the opinions of the European Parliament; but in the end each decision will be taken by qualified majority vote. With Britain, which may well opt out of the single currency, in the chair, the task of assembling the necessary majorities will be delicate. The whole exercise could degenerate into ugly political horse-trading, with a risk of court challenges to follow. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given the uncertainties of all this, and in particular the risk (as they see it) that Italy and Spain might be let in, it is not surprising that the Germans are insisting so fiercely on a "stability pact" that would, they hope, prevent participants in the single currency from borrowing excessively. They want the pact to provide for sanctions, including fines of up to 0.5% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>, to be applied automatically; and they want "exceptional circumstances" that could justify a temporary deficit of more than 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> to be tightly defined in advance.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The commission and most other member states, though they accept the principle of a stability pact, want it to be less rigorous. This argument looks unlikely to be resolved before next month's European Council meeting in Dublin, and maybe not even then. It has been complicated by a row in Britain over parliamentary scrutiny of pact documents--even though the pact will apply only to members of the new currency, and the council has agreed that countries not in the single currency do not have to rejoin a revamped <font size=-1>ERM</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But other ghosts loom. Many people in many <font size=-1>EU</font> countries are still queasy about the whole project. A recent opinion poll in Germany found only 21% favouring a single currency as soon as 1999. The French are a bit keener than the Germans, but worries linger and the franc is under pessure again. <br>
</p><p><b><b>Watch that franc</b></b><br>
Recently Val&eacute;ry Giscard d'Estaing, a former president, called for a weaker franc to help fight unemployment. In fact, the franc is probably not overvalued. Over the past eight years, French unit labour costs have risen more slowly than those in the rest of Europe. French unemployment, as elsewhere in Europe, owes more to excessive labour-market regulation than to a strong franc. More arguable are fears that the euro itself could become overvalued against the dollar, especially if central banks around the world switch some of their reserves out of dollars and into euros.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet, as Mr de Silguy observes, the strength of the euro will depend largely on financial markets, not government intervention. Indeed, there may yet be concerns about the confidence of the markets in the single currency--and in the untried European central bank. This week the European Parliament endorsed the choice of Wim Duisenberg, who has won a good name as boss of the Dutch central bank, as the new bank's prospective head. But even he may find it hard to cope with the long transition from 1999 to 2002, when the euro will exist alongside national currencies--giving the markets plenty of time to test the commitment of governments, especially Germany's, to the single currency.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a speech in Dublin this week, Jacques Santer, the commission's president, declared that the single currency was now an irreversible project and that the euro would definitely begin on January 1st 1999. He denounced scares about the euro--such as claims that some countries in the single currency might be forced to pay for others' unfunded pension liabilities--as so many "ghosts" that should not be believed in.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The betting is getting stronger that the euro will be born on time, little more than two years from now. But, despite Italy's <font size=-1>ERM</font> move this week, it is still questionable whether the new currency will manage to embrace the lira or the peseta in the first round. And enough genuine spectres still lurk that might spoil the currency feast.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
