<html><head><title>Squeeze, gently</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Intel and microchips</b></p>
<h1>Squeeze, gently</h1>

<p><b>Nobody needs reminding that Microsoft dominates its markets. But it is far  from unique in that. In the first of a series on other firms that dominate differ ent parts of the high-technology business, we look at Intel</b></p><br>
INTEL, the world's largest semiconductor company, and Microsoft, the world's largest software firm, each have an extraordinary grip on the market for personal computers. Microsoft's Windows accounts for some 90% of the market for operating-system software. Thanks to the Pentium chip and its siblings, Intel accounts for about the same share of <font size=-1>PC</font> microprocessors. The two firms' core products account for the single largest chunk of the cost of most <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Combined, they sell some $25 billion-worth of their wares a year, making nearly $6 billion profit in the process.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some people lump the two companies together, dubbing them the "Wintel monopoly" (see <a href="wb1.gif">table</a>). Yet, in one crucial respect, the firms are different. For most of this decade Microsoft has been under investigation by trustbusters in America and Europe. In 1994 it settled one complaint by America's Justice Department, only to find the agency weighing in again the following year to stop it from buying Intuit, a financial-software firm. Hardly a day goes by without new calls from competitors to stop the firm's march to global domination.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intel, on the other hand, was briefly investigated by America's Federal Trade Commission in 1992 and given a clean bill of health the next year. The trustbusters still watch it, but show no sign of intervening. Its two main competitors, Advanced Micro Devices (<font size=-1>AMD</font>) and Cyrix, dropped some lawsuits against the firm (in the face of huge legal bills) nearly two years ago, and now seem content to live on scraps from the giant's table. "We've made our peace with Intel," says an <font size=-1>AMD</font> spokesman. Most of the "Wintel" grousing is aimed at Microsoft, which is feared and loathed by many in Silicon Valley. Intel, on the other hand, is more admired than despised.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why? Intel claims that it is careful to, for example, train salesmen not to tie the sale of one generation of chip to a promise of preferred treatment with the next. But such practices are only the most obvious form of monopolistic abuse.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more subtle concern arises when a firm with a dominant position in one market uses it to "leverage" its way into adjacent markets. Microsoft has expanded greatly from making operating systems into more general software, from its word processors and spreadsheets to entertainment and education programs. Its critics claim its success in such markets is largely due to the advantages in technology, marketing and financial clout that it gains from its dominance of operating-systems. Their constant griping is one reason why America's antitrust investigators continue to hover over the firm. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intel, too, has spread its tentacles from its core market. Improving technology means that each new generation of chips includes many more transistors (the building blocks of digital electronics) than the previous one. To put them usefully to work, Intel has gradually folded the work of other chips into the processor. In its next-generation chips, it is building in 57 "multimedia extension" functions, which will let the processor take on other jobs, from video processing to the communications work of a modem. This will inevitably take some business away from firms that sell stand-alone chips that do the same thing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the same time as Intel has been expanding the definition of a processor, it has also been reaching outside the chip. Three years ago it started selling its processor as part of an entire "motherboard", the guts of a <font size=-1>PC</font> (and something that <font size=-1>PC</font> makers used to produce themselves). Intel now leads the market in such boards, and even makes some complete <font size=-1>PC</font>s for other firms.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Just a chip shop</b></b><br>
So why, if Intel mimics some of Microsoft's tactics, is it not seen as such a threat to its rivals? One answer is simply that it has fewer rivals to make complaints. Software is a much easier business to enter than semiconductors. All it takes is a <font size=-1>PC</font> and a few programming skills. In contrast, making a microprocessor to rival Intel's can be a billion-dollar proposition; its competitors in this market number fewer than a dozen. Nevertheless, higher barriers to entry is normally a reason for worrying more about market dominance, not less.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So a better explanation of why competitors seem less concerned about Intel than about Microsoft boils down to ambition and motivation. Microsoft's ambitions are boundless: it has a finger in everything from office software to joysticks and keyboards, and from financial programs to games. Recently it has started a cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> news channel, a network of regional news and entertainment sites on the Internet, a virtual travel agency, and even an on-line magazine that will be printed out and distributed in coffee shops (the company, after all, is based near Seattle).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intel, on the other hand, is still content to stick to chips, and mostly to the relatively costly processors used in <font size=-1>PC</font>s rather than the cheaper components used in video-players or other consumer-electronics devices. One reason for this caution, reckons Alex Balkansky, head of C-Cube, another semiconductor firm, is that Intel has stumbled badly before, whereas Microsoft has not. Intel started out making commodity memory chips, but was driven out of the market in the 1980s by Japanese competitors. By 1986, it was losing money. Since then, it has concentrated on top-of-the-range processors, where margins are fatter. Such other chips as it makes are used more to find work for its older manufacturing plants than to find new markets.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second difference is that Intel has largely chosen to grow not by fighting its rivals for a bigger chunk of the <font size=-1>PC</font> pie, but by expanding the pie itself. It reckons that anything it can do to help the industry sell more <font size=-1>PC</font>s will be of greater benefit to it than conquering that last sliver of the microprocessor market it does not already control. And if rivals gain more than it does from the growth, then so be it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft, in contrast, is frequently perceived as more domineering. In a recent interview in <i>Red Herring</i>, a technology magazine, Marc Andreessen, co-founder of Netscape, a software firm locked in a bitter battle with Microsoft, claimed that its giant rival "would rather eliminate a 10% market share competitor than grow the market by 50%". <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At first glance, Intel's foray into motherboards invites the same sort of complaints. In 1993, the firm was worried that <font size=-1>PC</font> makers were dragging their heels in adopting its new Pentium chips, which were by far its most profitable ones. So it started shipping them on cheap motherboards it designed to exploit every speed advantage the Pentium had over its competition. <font size=-1>PC</font> makers had little choice but to use them; if they waited to design their own boards, someone else would beat them to market with Intel's. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Initially, this infuriated <font size=-1>PC</font> makers. They feared that Intel was trying to steal the last bit part of their business that did not involve simply assembling other firms' parts. But most of those complaints have now died down, in part because Intel has scaled back production of motherboards between new generations of processors, returning more of that market to other firms. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Intel can afford such restraint because it makes so much money from its core processor business. While other parts get cheaper, Intel's processors are getting more expensive: from $50 for an average 286 chip in 1985 to $200 for today's much more powerful Pentium. Given that the price of memory chips--the other expensive part of a <font size=-1>PC</font>--has plummeted, Intel can now push up its processor prices again without raising the overall cost of a computer. Goldman Sachs, an investment bank, reckons that the average price of Intel's processors will rise to $300 over the next two years: with 80m <font size=-1>PC</font>s expected to be sold a year by 1998, that extra $100 per chip could add $8 billion to the firm's sales. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may seem like unimaginable wealth, but it pales beside the potential riches of the media and services markets Microsoft has in its sights. Intel's decision to stick to its knitting keeps it out of trouble with regulators, but also limits its ambitions. Microsoft is willing to risk antitrust suits (and $1 billion in investments) in its quest for domination of more markets. But with that risk comes the chance for greater returns--one reason why the software firm's price-to-earnings ratio is almost twice Intel's. In the rapacious computer industry, "finite greed" (a term Microsoft's boss, Bill Gates, once used to explain a competitor's hesitation) has its price.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?849315600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="fn6502.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

