<html><head><title>Alger Hiss</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ob.gif" width="138" height="26" alt="Obituary" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Alger Hiss</h1>

WITHOUT Alger Hiss, would there have been a Joe McCarthy? It is a fair question. The investigation, trial and conviction of Alger Hiss--and surely there was never a better name for a spy--provoked Senator McCarthy's charge a month later that the American State Department was "infested" with communists. After all, where there was one commie rascal, there were bound to be more-- say, 205. That accusation launched the red scare that deadened American cultural life for a decade and turned the perfectly defensible goal of prosecuting communist spies into a national disgrace. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the process, anti-communism became seen as mean-spirited and tacky--a reputation that lingered until the Berlin wall fell. To a degree, it deserved this reputation. Cool intellectuals such as Mr Hiss drove rougher sorts like McCarthy to distraction, a distrust that later found memorable expression in George Wallace's contempt for "pointy-headed intellectuals". In effect, the trial of Mr Hiss drew the line between anti-communism and anti-anti-communism that became so strong a feature of American life.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This divide was, from the beginning, as much aesthetic as ideological. Take a look at Whittaker Chambers, who in 1948 told Congress that Mr Hiss had spied for the Soviet Union in the 1930s. Chambers had terrible teeth, bad suits and a paunch; radio listeners could almost hear the gravy stains on his tie. Lean and sauve, Mr Hiss carried himself like an aristocrat. He wasn't, at least not by birth. But through diligence and a capacity to impress the great and the good, he had led a gilded life. After a brilliant academic career, he became a clerk at the Supreme Court. At the State Department, he was an adviser at the Yalta conference that in 1945 divided Europe between the Soviet Union and the West, and organiser of the conferences that sculpted the United Nations.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Enter Richard Nixon</b></b><br>
Alger Hiss cut so impressive a figure that when he first testified to deny Chambers's charges, Congress gave him a standing ovation. Unfortunately for him, an ambitious new congressman, Richard Nixon, insisted that the claims be investigated. The tide turned. In 1950, Mr Hiss was convicted of perjury (under the statute of limitations he was not tried for spying). After 44 months in prison, he was freed to begin his lifelong effort at vindication.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In this, he had many sympathisers; the Hiss trial became an ideological litmus test (liberals for him, conservatives against). Again, the judgment seemed partly aesthetic. Defenders of the British spy Kim Philby felt disbelief, until he took up residence in Moscow, that "one of us" could be "one of them". So it was with defenders of Mr Hiss. Add the fact that Nixon had a key role in the investigation: clearly, Alger Hiss must be innocent. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two men loathed each other, but their destinies were entwined. Mr Hiss's confrontation with Chambers was the first televised congressional hearing. This was the same forum later used to force Nixon out of the presidency--an office he admitted he never could have won without the Hiss investigation to launch his career. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Hiss used Nixon's downfall in 1974 to attempt his rehabilitation, with some success. The Massachusetts bar re-admitted him to practice in 1975. On the lecture circuit he offered himself as a modern Dreyfus, a French army officer wrongly convicted of treason. Then came the publication in 1978 of "Perjury", which concluded that Mr Hiss was guilty. The author, Allen Weinstein, was so clearly "one of us"--a liberal academic who had set out to prove that Mr Hiss was framed--that the 700-page book made a great impact. Mr Hiss lost the support of much of liberal America; his defenders are a dwindling band.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the evidence has never been quite conclusive enough to clinch the case in the public mind. The end of the cold war has not lessened the ambiguity of Alger Hiss. In 1992, General Dmitri Volkogonov, chairman of the Soviet archives, said he had found nothing to indicate that Mr Hiss had been a spy. But he later back-pedalled, noting that many files were destroyed after Stalin's death, that he had not searched very hard, and that he did not have access to military intelligence archives. The case for the prosecution was bolstered by the release this year of Russian cables intercepted by the National Security Agency that seemed to refer to Mr Hiss; scraps from Hungarian archives suggested that he was a spy well into the 1940s. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now that he is dead and communism has lost, the question of Mr Hiss's guilt or innocence is of less importance. What is still remembered is the stunning effect his trial had on America, bringing the cold war into the home. In an irony he would hate, Mr Hiss can take much of the credit for bringing Joe McCarthy and Richard Nixon to prominence. And in an irony he might appreciate, the excesses in the pursuit of communist spies that his trial launched did much to make anti-communism anathema in the West. In this sense, at least, Alger Hiss surely served the interests of the Soviet Union.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
