<html><head><title>A foreign policy for America</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>A foreign policy for America</h1>


ONCE upon a time, the world viewed from Washington seemed a simple place: there were good guys, and bad guys, and the rest. The good guys were America's friends, the bad guys were communists, and the rest were unimportant. Then, after the Berlin Wall came down, the world looked even simpler. Suddenly, there was only one superpower, which, freed of all constraints, was now able to set about creating a "new world order", swatting flies like Iraq as it did so. The illusion lasted only a moment, but it was replaced neither by a new, more complex view of the world nor by any sense of urgency about the need to find one. For the past four years, America has juggled a variety of different (and sometimes inconsistent) foreign policies, each reflecting a different (and sometimes inconsistent) view of the world. Fortunately, the price paid has not been great. But in his second term, Bill Clinton may not be so lucky.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fortune has smiled on Mr Clinton partly because the world remains relatively quiet. The American troops now preparing for a stint in Bosnia or central Africa may question that. Yet relatively quiet it is, despite the ethnic squabbles that afflict the Balkans and many parts of Africa besides Rwanda, Burundi and Zaire. Some of these disputes, and others from Chechnya to Sri Lanka, are a consequence of the triumph of democracy. Where communists once sat on national aspirations, people now feel free to burst forth. Where tribes and nations long resented colonial borders or dominance by other groups, they can now assert their independence, invoking as they do so the tenets of self-determination.<b><br>
</p><p><b>Attend and co-operate</b></b><br>
These rows will not go away for a while. They will need to be managed, and managed better than Yugoslavia was during Mr Clinton's first 1,000 days. But the record of the past year in Bosnia shows that, when the administration gives its full attention to a foreign-policy question, and works with its allies, not against them, it can produce results.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That has been apparent from the outset with the most immediate set of issues arising out of communism's collapse: how to ease the transition to democracy and market economics in Eastern Europe and, most importantly, in Russia. Here the policy has been coherent: offer conditional financial help to governments anxious to reform their economies, and security help--at first through <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s Partnerships for Peace--to those who fear their neighbours; meanwhile, cajole and subsidise to control arms, especially nuclear arms. The administration has done this well. But note that luck, too, has played a part: Russia today might well look frightening had Boris Yeltsin not managed, against most expectations six months earlier, to win re-election last July.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's policy towards Asia has shown less coherence: the administration sees the region variously as trading opportunity, trading threat, security worry and human-rights abuser. At the Asia-Pacific Economic Co-operation forum in the Philippines next week, Mr Clinton will, if he is wise, be publicly talking trade and privately reassuring nervous Asians that America will stay around in their region--so long as they are welcoming. Meanwhile, in Beijing this week, his outgoing secretary of state, Warren Christopher, has been trying to tell China that America wishes to engage it economically, without uncritically backing its bid to join the World Trade Organisation. The Chinese, however, well know that at the start of his term Mr Clinton wanted to link China's most-favoured-nation trade status to human rights. Though the link was eventually abandoned, they remain mistrustful, all the more so in the light of America's subsequent friendliness towards Taiwan: first the granting of a visa to its president, then the show of naval force in March during China's attempts to force Taiwan to toe the one-China line.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other problems inevitably absorb the energies of America's policymakers. The Middle East still soaks up a lot of diplomatic effort. Iran and international terror remain a worry. So does North Korea, Iraq and other states that may be acquiring weapons of mass destruction. Haiti and Cuba, thanks to proximity and electoral pressure, loom large in the view from Capitol Hill, if not from Foggy Bottom. Still, most of these places remain low on the list of Washington priorities until a crisis--a threat, a bomb, an invasion--puts them on the front pages. Then, panic past, they are allowed to slip away again.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<b></b>This approach to foreign policy is unlikely to be adequate for long. The world is still in an unnatural post-cold-war condition. America remains the only superpower but, despite the boys in Bosnia and the battleships in the Taiwan Strait, suspicions remain that it is gun-shy. Soon the challenges will come not from Somali warlords but from full-fledged countries, growing in economic might and maybe military bravado.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is safe to assume, for instance, that Russia's external ambitions are not satisfied, merely temporarily suppressed. Other countries will surely try to secure the gamut of weapons Saddam Hussein had failed to acquire when he snatched Kuwait. In many places, Islam seems to offer the only ideology to challenge the new orthodoxies of liberal politics and economics. And it is far from clear whether an ever-richer China will be a benign or a belligerent actor on the world stage.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the new foreign-policy team in Washington--and it had better be a team, not a group of rivals--needs to keep Russia, proliferation, Islam and China constantly in mind. On none of these issues does it need a radical change of policy. On Russia, the elements are all in place, so long as <font size=-1>NATO</font> enlargement goes ahead sensitively but firmly. On proliferation, the problem is to keep up the pressure on would-be renegades and others tempted to help them. Islam requires coolness, not panic, a readiness to see that the religion in itself poses no threat and that different Islamists therefore need to be treated discriminatingly. And on China, perhaps the most difficult issue, America at last seems to have discovered the right mix of engagement and containment. But the Chinese should be left in no doubt that America will not tolerate aggression.<b><br>
</p><p><b>Invest in allies</b></b><br>
Rather than design new policies, America needs now to apply its existing ones consistently and in concert with others. Consistency is needed because oscillations suggest weakness (China) and undermine allies (Bosnia). Co-operation is needed because America cannot always act alone, even if it sometimes thinks it wants to, and it certainly does not want to pay alone. In fact, though allies can be awkward, it is very much in America's interests to put alliances in place to deal with difficulties when they crop up, as they will. That is why Mr Clinton is foolish to waste so much goodwill by pursuing a vendetta against the current <font size=-1>UN</font> secretary-general and by persisting with the Helms-Burton law on trade with Cuba.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where is America to find its allies? Where it can, of course, among democracies old and new, especially in Asia, where Chinese expansionism is already being felt. But the friendship likeliest to prove useful is the old one with Europe, often tested but always liable to be taken for granted. Four times this century--in two world wars, Korea and the Gulf--America has fought alongside Europeans. They know that undeterred aggression means war and, if they stop to think, that deterred aggression means peace: the big war they did not fight was the nuclear one with Russia. If the next 50 years are to be as relatively unbloody as the past 50, America will have to be just as resolute as it was with Soviet communism. And it will need every bit as much help from its friends.<br>

<p align=center>
