<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Going home</h2>
At least 500,000 <b>Rwandan refugees </b>in eastern Zaire went home after their camps were attacked by rebels. But former Rwandan soldiers and Hutu militiamen fled further into Zaire. Plans for outside military intervention were thrown into confusion when Rwanda said none was needed and America scaled back its commitment.<p>
At the <b>United Nations</b>, 14 Security Council members backed a second term as secretary-general for Boutros Boutros-Ghali. The United States vetoed him.<p>
President Frederick Chiluba of <b>Zambia</b> easily won re-election. A leading rival, ex-president Kenneth Kaunda, had been banned from standing. His party and some others boycotted the poll.<p>
<b>Israeli </b>television showed an amateur video of border police beating Palestinians. Binyamin Netanyahu, the prime minister, called the beatings "unpardonable". Palestinians talked of "racism".<p>
<h2>Tough customers</h2>
Opposition members of Belarus's parliament threatened to impeach the country's president, <b>Alexander Lukashenka</b>, if he went ahead with a referendum that would lengthen his term and extend his powers. But both sides hinted that compromise was possible.<p>
Romania's president, Ion Iliescu, a former communist, lost his bid for a third term, marking the country's first peaceful democratic shift of power. The new president will be <b>Emil Constantinescu</b>, a centrist academic.<p>
Six ministers from the junior partner in <b>Estonia's</b> governing coalition quit to protest a co-operation agreement signed by the prime minister, Tiit Vaehi, and the leading opposition party.<p>
An alliance opposed to Serbia's government won the mayorality of the country's capital, <b>Belgrade</b>. It accused the government of suppressing the results of elections in other municipalities.<p>
In <b>Moldova</b>, the incumbent, Mircea Snegur, took the lead in the first round of voting for president. But he faces a tough fight in the second round against Petru Lucinschi, the speaker of parliament.<p>
At least 68 people were killed by an <b>explosion</b> in a block of flats in the southern Russian republic of Dagestan. Most were border guards and their families, prompting speculation that local gangs might have taken revenge for a crackdown on arms-and caviar-smuggling.<p>
A parliamentary commission recommended that Belgium's highest court investigate allegations that a deputy prime minister, Elio di Rupo, has engaged in <b>paedophile activities</b>. Mr di Rupo denies the allegations.<p>
Italy's public-works minister, <b>Antonio Di Pietro</b>, the driving force behind the "clean hands" anti-corruption campaign, resigned. He complained of being victimised after becoming a target of investigation himself.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Italy and Greece approved measures designed to help them qualify for Europe's <b>single currency</b>. Italy's parliament passed a tight budget and the government spelled out details of a "tax for Europe". Greece's cabinet approved a series of new taxes, including levies on banks and state securities.<p>
An unmanned Russian space vehicle, intended to reach <b>Mars</b>, fell into the South Pacific after a booster rocket failed to carry it clear of its Earth orbit. The rocket was carrying scientific equipment for 20 other countries. <p>
A fire in the <b>Channel tunnel</b> between Britain and France sent eight people to hospital and disrupted service.<p>
<h2>Old blood</h2>
Thailand's general election produced a <b>new prime minister</b>,<b> </b>Chavalit Yongchaiyudh, a former general, but the coalition government he is putting together looks a lot like the failed previous one.<p>
The <font size=-1>IMF</font> cancelled a $20m loan to Cambodia because of the country's failure to control <b>loggers </b>who are destroying forests.<p>
A fire in an office block in <b>Hong Kong</b> killed about 40 people and injured about 80.<p>
The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees suspended most of the agency's activities in <b>Kabul </b>because four of its staff had been arrested by the Taliban, which captured the Afghan capital in September.<p>
<h2>Close encounters</h2>
Two <b>unlikely visits </b>were announced for 1997. The pope met Fidel Castro in Rome and is to visit Cuba. Bill Clinton is to go to Brazil, his first presidential visit to Latin America.<p>
In <b>Mexico's </b>Congress, the <font size=-1>PRI</font>, President Ernesto Zedillo's party, rammed through legislation on electoral reform--shorn of key points that had been accepted in all-party talks inspired by Mr Zedillo. <p>
In <b>Colombia</b>, despite pressure from President Ernesto Samper, congressional committees yet again dawdled over legislation rendering drug-traffickers' profits liable to forfeiture.<p>
A former <font size=-1>CIA</font> station chief, Harold Nicholson, was charged with selling <b>secrets</b> <b>to Russia</b> for the past two years. He is the highest-ranking <font size=-1>CIA </font> officer to be charged with spying. His lawyer says he will plead not guilty.<p>
<b>John Huang</b>, the Democratic Party fund-raiser at the heart of the controversy over solicitation of foreign funds, lost his job at the Democratic National Committee. A spokesman said he was simply one of 105 people who were laid off after the election.<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
