<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Well-connected</h2>
(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Shares in <b>Deutsche Telekom</b> were floated in the second-largest initial public offering ever. The price of the shares, which attracted 2m German investors, leapt from DM28.5 ($19) to over DM33 in the first few hours of hectic trading. Germany's government confirmed plans to sell its 35.7% stake in<b> </b>the national airline, <b>Lufthansa</b>, worth nearly DM3 billion.<p>
American banking regulations were eased further, increasing the <b>powers of commercial banks </b>to expand into selling insurance and underwriting securities.<p>
<b>Unocal</b> agreed to sell its petroleum-refining and marketing business to Tosco, another American oil firm, in a deal worth around $2 billion. Unocal will use the proceeds to pay debts and expand exploration and production, particularly in Asia.<p>
Yasuo Hamanaka, the trader who lost $2.6 billion for Japan's<b> Sumitomo Corporation</b> through unauthorised copper dealing, claimed through his lawyer that his former boss had been involved in dodgy trading. Sumitomo posted a net loss of &#165;212.1 billion ($2 billion) for the half-year to September.<p>
The French government fired the head of<b> Groupe des Assurances Nationales </b>(<font size=-1>GAN</font>), a big state-controlled insurance group. The sacking of Jean-Jacques Bonnaud came less than a week after the privatisation of <font size=-1>GAN</font>'s banking subsidiary, <font size=-1>CIC</font>, had been halted after meeting resistance from within. Mr Bonnaud refused to go.<p>
<b>Russia</b> made ready for its long-planned debut Eurobond issue. It also confirmed plans to merge two state-run telecoms firms, Rostelecom and Svyazinvest, possibly in preparation for privatisation.<p>
As the Bank for International Settlements warned that the introduction of electronic money could shave billions of dollars off central banks' note-and-coin-issuing revenues, MasterCard, a payment-card group, said it had agreed to take control of<b> Mondex</b>, an electronic-cash firm.<p>
<h2>Pipes and drums</h2>
A group of ten international oil companies and the governments of Russia, Kazakhstan and Oman settled their remaining differences over the construction of a $1.5 billion <b>pipeline</b> that will help western oil ventures in Kazakhstan to export their crude. An agreement should be signed early next month.<p>
Russia's largest company is to shake itself up.<b> Gazprom</b> said it will sell peripheral activities (eg, farms) to focus on gas, moving further into distribution and appointing a new finance director.<p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
America's Pentagon picked Lockheed Martin and Boeing to design and build prototypes for the <b>Joint Strike Fighter</b>, the biggest-ever military-aircraft contract. The two will together get $2.2 billion and four years to produce the final design. The decision dealt a blow to McDonnell Douglas, which had teamed up with British Aerospace and Northrop Grumman.<p>
Despite its good news,<b> Lockheed Martin</b> said it will close eight American plants and lay off 1,600 workers. The move was prompted by a reduction in American defence spending and Lockheed's recent purchase of Loral, a defence-electronics firm.<p>
The committee overseeing the investigation into<b> </b>Swiss banks' holdings of <b>assets deposited by holocaust victims</b> picked three accountancy firms--Arthur Andersen, <font size=-1>KPMG</font> and Price Waterhouse--to conduct the search. Swiss bankers and politicians said they might create a fund for victims of Nazism.<p>
American Airlines was poised to announce an order for several hundred<b> Boeing</b> jets worth around $6 billion. Boeing confirmed an order for ten 777 aircraft from Air France.<p>
The World Trade Organisation agreed to the European Union's request to set up a panel that will decide whether America's<b> Helms-Burton law</b> (which penalises foreign firms that invest in Cuba) violates trade rules.<p>
Sources within Sony said that the Japanese group's president, Nobuyuki Idei, plans to float its troubled American film studio, <b>Sony Pictures</b>, which owns Columbia and TriStar Pictures.<p>
<h2>Black gold</h2>
Oil giant Texaco ended a 2.5-year-long <b>racial discrimination case </b>by agreeing to pay $175m to 1,400 black employees, some of whom had complained of being passed over for promotion and pay rises. The company still faces a federal investigation. A Texaco official was charged with obstruction of justice.<p>
Chiroscience, one of Britain's largest <b>biotechnology</b> firms, announced a $200m takeover of Darwin Molecular, a Seattle-based firm of which Bill Gates owned 14%. <p>
Thousands of savers flocked to withdraw their money from <b>Bulgaria</b>'s State Savings Bank after it emerged that the bank had been using deposits to finance the government's hefty debts.<p>
Japan's ministry of finance shut down <b>Hanwa Bank</b>, a small regional bank--the first government-ordered bank closure in post-war Japan.<p>
There were smiling faces at <b>Euro Disney</b>. The Paris-based theme-park operator made net profits of FFr202m ($40m) in the year to September 30th. Reduced entry prices helped produce a 9% rise in visitors, to 11.7m.<p>

</td></tr></table></center>
