<html><head><title>Good intentions</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" width="256" height="26" alt="Special feature">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Good intentions</h1>

<p><b>Bill Clinton has another four years to set the world to rights--if only he can keep his concentration</b></p><br>
"IN AN increasingly interdependent world Americans have a growing stake in how other countries govern, or misgovern, themselves. The larger and more close-knit the community of nations that choose democratic forms of government, the safer and more prosperous Americans will be, since democracies are demonstrably more likely to maintain their international commitments, less likely to engage in terrorism or wreak environmental damage, and less likely to make war on each other." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those fine, even provocative, words come from Strobe Talbott, deputy secretary of state (and President Clinton's chief adviser on Russia), in the latest issue of <i>Foreign Affairs</i>. But will they define a "Clinton doctrine" by which the rest of the world will temper its behaviour over the next few years? Or will they be soon forgotten, as a second-term presidency continues the ad hoc habits ("photo-op foreign policy" and "foreign policy as social work" are among the biting, if facile, criticisms) of the past four years?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The questions matter because America is so obviously the world's leader--its biggest economy, its most powerful warrior and, thanks to the demise of the Soviet Union (President Reagan's "evil empire")--its only remaining superpower. Whatever the crisis, America, it seems, must play the decisive role. In the past year it has brokered a sort of peace in the Balkans; kept Arabs talking with Israelis; and sent its navy to support Taiwan against the bluster of China (see <a href="sf1.gif">map</a>). Even France, whose Gaullist tradition presumes more than a <i>soup</i><i>&ccedil;on</i> of anti-Americanism, acknowledges if not America's leadership at least the need for its help: this month's offer of French troops for Zaire was contingent on the presence of Americans, too. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The difficulty is to be sure of the answer. Just as foreigners are ambivalent about America, often relying on its power while also resenting it, so is America about the rest of the world.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, historically, America's attitude has always been one of deliberate distance. It should, said Thomas Jefferson, seek honest friendship with all nations, but "entangling alliances with none". Hence, before the second world war, America's every entrance on the the global stage was followed, sooner or later, by its withdrawal. For all the 1960s' talk of American imperialism, fostered by covert action round the world and overt war in Vietnam, the truth is that America has had no territorial ambitions since the end of the 19th century. Only Latin America, "Uncle Sam's backyard", has real cause to see the United States as a menacing quasi-imperialist, meddling either to protect its trade or to repel the alleged threat of communism.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Seen against that background America's role in Bosnia conforms to a pattern begun in the French Revolution and continued in the first and second world wars: Europe in a crisis looks to the United States for help--and has to wait. The difference is that the pattern is now interwoven with so many others. Count the value of America's proliferating foreign investment, or the ethnic links of its citizens to other countries, or its obligations under various international treaties: the truth, <i>pace </i>Jefferson, is that America's isolationist instincts must henceforth be limited; for better or worse, the country is permanently entangled. In which case, can non-Americans hope for the better from a second-term Bill Clinton?<br>
</p><p><b><b>Backyard blues</b></b><br>
Start with America's backyard. For decades its complaint was that the United States interfered too much in affairs south of the border (witness the downfall of Salvador Allende in Chile or Manuel Noriega in Panama). Now the grouse is the opposite: not only do Latin Americans feel misunderstood, they also feel ignored.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They have a point. Two years ago in Miami, Mr Clinton, still reasonably fresh from winning approval of the North American Free Trade Agreement (<font size=-1>NAFTA</font>), played host to the first "hemispheric" summit with all the region's leaders bar Cuba's Fidel Castro (a perennial pariah). They set the goal of a hemispheric free trade agreement by 2005; and Mr Clinton agreed to support a broader <font size=-1>NAFTA</font>, together with the spread of similar accords to the Caribbean and Central America. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So much for good intentions. The first disappointment stemmed from the Mexican currency crash of 1994. Though Mr Clinton braved domestic opposition to put together a financial rescue package, he was unable to win approval from a protectionist-inclined Congress for more trade deals.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second setback was the hijacking of the administration's Latin American policy (such as it was) by Mr Clinton's need to get re-elected. He approved the Helms-Burton law, which imposes sanctions against foreign companies "trafficking" (ie, investing) in Cuban assets seized by Castro from American citizens, in order to win votes in Florida, and sought to neutralise criticism that he was "soft" on drugs by hounding Colombia's President Ernesto Samper, who was alleged to have received election money from the Cali cocaine cartel. Mr Samper's American visa was cancelled and the administration refused the certification, necessary to qualify for American aid, that Colombia was co-operating in the war against narcotics. How sad for Colombia. All America's vendetta has really achieved is to destabilise Colombia's central authority to the benefit of narcotics-linked guerrillas.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, putting their complaints aside, what do the Latin Americans really want from Uncle Sam? The less-than-simple answer is some positive understanding: let America adopt a policy of "constructive engagement" towards Cuba, encouraging the foreign investment that would ensure economic liberalisation, and with it political reform. Similarly, in terms of the drugs war, let America recognise that the problem is a shared one, with the consumers as guilty as the suppliers. Most of all, let Mr Clinton seek "fast track" approval from Congress to extend <font size=-1>NAFTA</font><t--mode> </t--mode>to Chile and to negotiate a Free Trade Agreement of the Americas for 34 countries in the hemisphere. Not everyone in the region wants such a deal; but "fast track" would signal America's involvement, and help stop the inclination of Mercosur, the trade-group led by Brazil, to go down a protectionist route.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the Latin wish-list will come true. But the optimists are few. After all, in his first term of office Mr Clinton travelled the globe--and never once set foot in Latin America (belatedly, a visit to the region is now scheduled for next year).<br>
</p><p><b><b>Misleading Asia</b></b><br>
To neglect Asia, with three-fifths of the world's people and several of its potential nuclear flashpoints (think of North and South Korea, India and Pakistan, China and India or Russia and China), would clearly be a mistake of a much greater order. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Couple security concerns with America's trading relationships with both Japan and China, and it is hardly surprising that Mr Clinton began his presidency by emphasising Asia with a fervour that alarmed America's hitherto complacent allies in Europe. The Seattle meeting of the Asia-Pacific Economic Co-operation forum (<font size=-1>APEC</font>) in November 1993 was upgraded, at Mr Clinton's prompting, into a summit of heads of state; and the following May China was informed that its most-favoured-nation trade status would no longer be held hostage to its human-rights record. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But where, Asia wonders, was the follow-up? America's secretary of state, Warren Christopher, quickly became obsessed with the Middle East (critics note his visit to Beijing this week was his first for two years), and the crucial relationships with Japan and China were soon soured by trade rows, with America aggressively insisting on greater market access. The low point came in November last year, when Mr Clinton cancelled his trip to the <font size=-1>APEC</font> summit in Osaka. Admittedly Mr Clinton had a good excuse--a budget crisis had shut down his government--but Asia's leaders were beginning to ask how much they could rely on an apparently inconsistent America.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton, of course, says their reliance can be absolute. This week, while visiting Australia, he used his first big foreign-policy speech since the election to promise the continued presence of American troops in the region. Moreover, he had reassuring words for China: "The United States has no interest in containing China. That is a negative strategy. What the United States wants is to sustain an engagement with China . . . in a way that will increase the chances that there will be more liberty and more prosperity."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Clinton's latest message to China only serves to highlight the problems of his Asia policy. Earlier this year, mixed messages from America about wanting to engage, not contain, China played their part in the China-Taiwan crisis. Miffed by Taiwan's determination to hold its first fully democratic presidential election, and led to believe, from all the talk of engagement, that America would turn a blind eye, China set out to intimidate Taiwan, even firing missiles close to its busy shipping lanes. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To its credit, America's response, orchestrated from the Pentagon, not the State Department, was swift: two aircraft-carrier battle groups sent to "observe" China's actions and to ensure that Taiwan came to no harm. Shortly thereafter, America and Japan agreed to reinforce their bilateral security treaty.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though neither America nor Japan says it publicly, one of the future "risks" facing East Asia is precisely that a more muscular China will continue to refuse to play by the rules. Like it or not, America's role in constraining China will be crucial. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In which case, the administration might consider a change of tone. The Clinton team came to power saying America's economic interests would be at the centre of its foreign policy. The result was to advance the Commerce Department at the expense of the State Department--and to allow trade-dispute brinkmanship to endanger carefully balanced security relations. When he goes to Manila for next week's <font size=-1>APEC</font> summit, Mr Clinton will need to promise consistency as well as friendship if he is to reassure his Asian counterparts.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Old faithfuls</b></b><br>
Ironically, given Mr Clinton's initial preference for the transpacific rather than the transatlantic, Europe now needs little reassurance. In part this is a "better the devil you know" reaction; in part it is because most European governments reckon Mr Clinton has improved over time. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it is also because Europeans have had to recognise their own failings: the Dayton accords on Bosnia, for example, would not have happened without Mr Clinton's special envoy, the bullying Richard Holbrooke. It was the same Mr Holbrooke, bluntly accusing the Europeans of literally sleeping through the night at a time of crisis, who this summer defused a dispute over some rocks in the Aegean that threatened to propel Greece and Turkey-- <font size=-1>NATO</font> "allies"--into armed conflict. Whatever the European Union's ambitions for a common foreign and security policy, in the meantime it clearly benefits from having America on hand--and an America that supports the idea of European integration.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That idea means different things to different people, and affects the way they view America's support. France has always tended to think of an integrated Europe as a counterweight to America. Indeed, its government spokesman, Alain Lamassoure, greeted Mr Clinton's victory with the comment: "It makes progress toward European unity more necessary than ever, so as not to leave American power alone like some kind of gendarme or judge over the affairs of the world." Hence France's determination to secure a European role in the Middle East peace process, or in the reordering of Africa. Yet at the same time France is deeply nervous at the idea of an American withdrawal from the world. President Chirac was not simply flattering his audience when he told Congress in February: "Today, as yesterday, the world needs the United States."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Germany has no such contradictory feelings: European integration and the transatlantic alliance are mutually reinforcing in Chancellor Kohl's mind. Indeed, he puts Germany's rapport with America almost on a par with the Franco-German alliance.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By contrast, feelings in Britain, obsessed by its internal debate over Europe, are confused: Eurosceptics, hankering hopelessly for the old "special relationship", see the <font size=-1>EU</font> as the enemy of transatlantic friendship-- to which the Europhiles reply by pointing out that Britain alone, without Europe, is no longer worthy of America's attention.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Designing the architecture</b></b><br>
In the end, be it in trade or security, America and Europe are mutually dependent, and the task is to ensure the relationship has as few irritations as possible. At the moment there are several: the Helms-Burton legislation; the squabble over Boutros Boutros-Ghali's tenure as <font size=-1>UN</font> secretary-general; differing views on how to deal with Iraq; the flagging momentum of the Middle East peace process; and so on.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The true challenge will be to manage two much bigger, and interconnected, issues: the expansion of <font size=-1>NATO</font> and the relationship of the West with Russia. In many ways America has handled <font size=-1>NATO</font> with diplomatic deftness, ensuring its survival after the end of the cold war had removed its original <i>raison d'&ecirc;tre</i> and agreeing with the Europeans on the "combined joint task force" concept to allow Europe to use <font size=-1>NATO</font> assets without America's involvement. One litmus test for the future, however, certainly for France, will be America's willingness to cede <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s southern command, with its headquarters in Naples, to a European.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Americans have been similarly deft in ensuring approval for the notion that <font size=-1>NATO</font> must expand its membership both to promote Europe's security (not least by giving Germany a buffer between it and the old enemy, Russia) and to reward Central and Eastern Europeans for their rejection of communism. Putting notion into practice, however, will not be easy--and the European Union is not impressed by the idea that difficult cases such as the Baltic states (militarily indefensible) could find an alternative home in the <font size=-1>EU</font>. Why, mutter some southern Europeans, provoke Russia with ill-judged measures, be they for <font size=-1>NATO</font> or the <font size=-1>EU</font>?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One plausible answer is that Russia, at least for the time being an incapacitated country, no longer needs to be handled with kid gloves. Indeed, cynics say that all Russia really wants from America is large amounts of money with no strings attached. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That may be true, but America's agenda with a Russia that has nuclear arms and unstable borders can hardly be dismissed so lightly. The original agreement after the collapse of the Soviet Union was that all its nuclear warheads should be repatriated to Russia. So far Kazakhstan has obliged, as has Ukraine. By contrast, Belarus has not-- and its present political unrest could end with it rejoining Russia. That would not be a tragedy unless Russia used it as a precedent for recovering Ukraine, a country which if threatened should definitely receive America's support.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton's real priority in Russian policy, fortified by last year's extension of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty and the near-global agreement this year on the Comprehensive Test-Ban Treaty, is to push on with arms control.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The American-funded programme for the dismantling and safe storage of Russia's nuclear weapons needs to be accelerated-- possibly by a president-to-president prod. So, too, the effort to eliminate Russia's chemical warfare stocks and its (illegal) biological weapons programme. To show good faith, however, America's Senate had first better approve the Chemical Weapons Convention. Meanwhile, to encourage the Russian Duma finally to ratify the <font size=-1>START II</font> agreement on reducing strategic weapons, perhaps America might dangle the carrot of a <font size=-1>START III</font>--one in which the Americans humour the Russians by scrapping good weapons while the Russians junk bad ones.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Towards engagement</b></b><br>
Assume all of the above happens, from Latin America to the Far East; assume, too, an American-inspired breakthrough in the Middle East; imagine, improbably, that America will allow its trade rows to be solved through the World Trade Organisation rather than by threats of unilateral retaliation. That will still, for some critics, not add up to a consistent and comprehensive foreign policy.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps they are right. But they should remember that America's foreign-affairs budget has halved in real terms since 1984, and is unlikely to increase with the penny-pinching and jingoistic Mr Helms back in his place as head of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. Maybe that is why some Clintonites like to stress "transnational" issues, where America has a role because no other country will take the lead: not just arms control but also the environment; or terrorism; or international crime, from drugs to computer-fraud.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, the most important quality America brings to the world scene is its sheer capacity to get things done. Americans might often wish to be respected for moral fervour in foreign policy; but recent history has shown that, as in Somalia, moral impulses are dangerous if not accompanied by a sense of pragmatic self-interest. Besides, a capacity to make things happen--to bang heads together, convene summits, apply pressure, provide a forum for enemies to shake hands--should not be underestimated. If America only engages, there is no limit to what it might get done. Engagement is all.<br>

