<html><head><title>Brothers in arms</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>India and Russia</b></p>
<h1>Brothers in arms</h1>

<font size=1>DELHI</font><p>
THE old Delhi-Moscow defence relationship has been revived after a gap of five years. Last weekend, India decided to buy 40 <font size=-1>SU-30</font> fighter aircraft for $1.8 billion. More could follow. Russia has also offered to sell India jet trainers, an aircraft carrier, submarines, tanks and howitzers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For some 30 years, India depended on the Soviet Union for most of its arms. Both countries had a common foe in China, and the men in Moscow offered India arms at low prices, as well as cheap credits. They also took payment in rupees. When the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991, so did the defence relationship. The new Russian state was hard up and insisted on payment in dollars. Moreover, deliveries were delayed, and India concluded that Russia could not be relied on as a supplier.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russia now seems more settled, and it has completed deliveries of an old order for ten <font size=-1>M</font>i<font size=-1>G-29</font>s. Its prices have gone up, but are still lower than those of comparable western arms. Last year the two countries started negotiations, and India chose the <font size=-1>SU-30</font> as the aircraft for its air force in the coming decade. The Rao government made an advance payment in dollars and now the United Front government has confirmed the order. After initial purchases of the <font size=-1>SU-30</font>, India is likely to produce under licence another five to six squadrons, each with 20 aircraft, with Russian technical assistance. And it is likely to buy 70 to 100 <font size=-1>M</font>i<font size=-1>G-AT</font> jet trainers, which have many features in common with the <font size=-1>SU-30</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since its financial crisis of 1991, India has slashed defence spending. Expensive defence purchases in the 1980s were one reason for the 1991 crunch. Pakistan was getting military aid from America, and India wanted the capability to take on both Pakistan and China. But the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan ended American arms aid to Pakistan. At the same time the collapse of the Soviet Union hit supplies to India, and the two armies rusted in unison.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;India's senior officers have complained for years that they need to modernise ageing equipment. Besides, the air force has lost 82 aircraft in crashes since April 1993, mainly because of pilot errors and birds (birds sucked into engines have brought down more aircraft than India has lost in warfare). Now that India's budget deficit has come down from 8.3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> in 1991 to 5.5%, the defence chiefs believe their chances are better.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The cheapest option is to upgrade the avionics and weaponry of India's old <font size=-1>M</font>i<font size=-1>G-21</font> squadrons (mostly made domestically). At first, India approached America for this, but was turned down. Indian defence chiefs believe this proves that America is biased towards Pakistan, and reckon therefore that Russia, with all its limitations, is a more reliable partner. Besides, the Russians have agreed that India will maintain and repair Russian aircraft being supplied to Malaysia. This helps.<br>

<p align=center>
