<html><head><title>Russia eyes the world</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Russia eyes the world</h1>

<font size=1>MOSCOW</font><p>
<p><b>Under the guidance of its foreign minister, Yevgeny Primakov, Russia has been carving out a tougher yet more pragmatic foreign policy</b></p><br>
THE main surprise about Russian foreign policy is that Russia seems at last to be arriving at one. After years in which anything seemed possible, two main principles are beginning to emerge. First, expect no more concessions that further diminish Russia's assets and influence, such as they are. Second, expect Russia to be warier of embarking on fresh adventures.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the West, the first of those principles--"no concessions"--is clearly the less attractive. It means Russia will stand by dangerous or dubious friends such as Iraq, Iran and Serbia. It promises a harshness towards countries of the former Soviet Union in which Russia feels its interests are not being recognised or fully protected. It implies a willingness to court public friction with America, still the only power against which Russia likes to measure itself. Russia's widespread hostility to <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s planned expansion is but one expression of such friction-courting. It has been evident, too, in the refusal so far of Russia's Duma, its lower house of parliament, to ratify the <font size=-1>START-2</font> arms-reduction treaty with America.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Russia's resurgent nationalism that has fostered this renewed readiness to say <i>Nyet</i> has been enhanced both by a year of election campaigning and by the illness of President Boris Yeltsin. For until and unless he recovers fully from his recent heart operation, an early presidential election will seem possible and would-be successors will go on outbidding each other in jingoism.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The latest and biggest victim of this crude Russian mood has been Ukraine. This month, hope for an end to the long-running argument over the division of the Soviet Black Sea Fleet was yet again dashed when the Duma decided that Ukraine must cede sovereignty of the Crimean port of Sebastopol to Russia rather than agree to lease it. At the last minute Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's prime minister, called off a visit to Kiev, Ukraine's capital, for fear of being branded "the man who lost Sebastopol".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second principle Russia seems to have adopted--"no adventures"--is better news for the rest of the world. It was tested last month when General Alexander Lebed, briefly Russia's national security adviser, pressed for Russia to stoke up resistance in northern Afghanistan to the new Taliban government in Kabul. But he was talked down by Yevgeny Primakov, a former spymaster who became Russia's foreign minister in January. In the combustible Caucasus, where Russia has already "persuaded" governments to let it keep military bases (in Georgia and Armenia), Mr Primakov is treading warily. As for Chechnya, though still technically a domestic matter as it is constitutionally part of the Russian Federation, most Russian ministers probably accept--not publicly, of course--that the rebel republic will slide away into independence.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new sense of coherence--and of limitation--in Russia's diplomacy is largely Mr Primakov's work. Not that he thinks Russia should do less abroad. Rather, he is taking a more realistic view of the slimmer means at its disposal. His main aim is to persuade the world that Russia is a great power that is passing through a mere phase of weakness--from which other countries would try to profit at their peril.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To help sustain that illusion it is essential for Russia to avoid the sort of sabre-rattling and even sabre-drawing that serve more to advertise its weakness. Whereas Russia's generals, including this week the defence minister, Igor Rodionov, have blown hot and cold on <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s expansion, Mr Primakov has opposed it consistently and relentlessly, but without threatening any specific retaliation should it occur, as it probably will.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Primakov's command of this delicate issue--the main focus of Russia's diplomatic engagement this year with America and the West--has reflected his authority within the Russian government. The foreign ministry is back in charge. Its revived professionalism has won Mr Primakov steadily improving reviews abroad, even from western sceptics horrified at first by his previous job as boss of the Russian foreign intelligence service, and by his 25-year friendship with Saddam Hussein. At home, too, Mr Primakov has a surprisingly wide range of admirers. His background gave him credibility from the outset with communists and nationalists. His pragmatism has since given liberals little to carp at. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Mr Yeltsin's failing heart put him in hospital at the start of his second term in July, Mr Primakov's globe-trotting barely faltered. That signalled a huge change from the days of Andrei Kozyrev, his less wily predecessor, who, lacking friends in government and Duma alike, ended up as little more than a presidential messenger. When even Mr Yeltsin disowned him, as he did from time to time, foreign governments were left thoroughly confused about Russian foreign policy and who was making it.Where Russia can get away with it, its policy in the "near abroad"--the bits of the former Soviet Union that Russia lost--can be pretty rough, with the foreign ministry often content to see the Duma do the bullying. Ukraine is not the only former Soviet state still feeling the heat. Moldova, which does not even share a frontier with Russia, is another. This month the Duma declared the Russian-occupied Transdniestria, sandwiched between Moldova's main body and its border with western Ukraine, a "zone of special strategic interest"--and demanded that Russia's 14th Army should stay there permanently. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over Belarus, too, Russia's empire rebuilders have been smirking. Not that Russia can afford to draw this troubled republic fully back into its orbit. But Mr Yeltsin has been happy to play cat-and-mouse with President Alexander Lukashenka, politely noting his ambition to unite the country with Russia without actually helping him to achieve his aim. All the same, Russia, and especially its raucous Duma, sees virtue in Mr Lukashenka: the more unstable and oppressive Belarus becomes, the less it will attract the West as a strategic partner.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In some places, Russia's harsh diplomacy has actually lowered tension--by grinding down other countries into settling on Russia's terms. This month, for instance, Mr Primakov gave his nod to a border treaty with Estonia, which, chilled by the thought of dealing with a President Lebed or a President Zyuganov, withdrew its main demands. Latvia seems ready to follow suit--though Russia's Duma may yet make trouble. Stubbornness is also winning Russia ground in the struggle for control of the Caspian and its oil pipelines.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This week Mr Primakov turned his attention to Russia's Pacific neighbours. On a visit to Japan, he proposed that the two countries should set aside their dispute over ownership of the southern Kurile islands (the Northern Territories, as Japan calls them) and jointly promote investment there. Japan said it would think about it--and freed $500m in soft loans to Russia that had been frozen for five years.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Next stop for Mr Primakov was China, a still trickier conundrum for Russia, which cannot decide whether to view its teeming neighbour as its greatest prospective ally or as its enemy. Russia even half-fears the Chinese investment it is publicly courting, lest China gain too much of an interest in the sparsely populated and mineral-rich Russian Far East. For all Mr Primakov's talk earlier this year of seeking a foreign policy that is more "balanced" between east and west, Russia so far seems merely to be temporising.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such jostling at Russia's Siberian end does not much alarm Western Europe or America. Russia, for sure, is a power in Asia. The sooner it and Japan come to an accommodation, the better for both. And it may be no bad thing if a would-be expansionist China has an ungainly but equally big neighbour breathing heavily down its northern neck.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The more ticklish area is still Russia's western flank. But there most of the old Warsaw Pact satellites are growing stronger by the day; there is little that Russia can do about it. So long as Russia does not threaten the independence of the Baltic states or Ukraine, and does not too flagrantly fan the flames under the Caucasus cauldron, western governments are not likely to complain much about what Russia does elsewhere in its former empire.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, a big worry is that, even under Mr Primakov's relatively sophisticated tutelage, Russia seems unable to break free of its view of the world as a sort of zero-sum game in which countries become strong only by making other countries weak. In the near abroad, where it counts for something, Russia pursues that logic with hard cynicism. Presumably, it would do the same in the more distant abroad if it only had the chance. Mr Primakov is calm, he is calculating, he can be amusing. But there is something chilling in his Lubyanka-tinted eyes.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
