<html><head><title>Poverty in the treasure-house</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>British Museum</b></p>
<h1>Poverty in the treasure-house</h1>

"A SENSATIONAL piece of marketing" is how Lindsay Stainton, former curator of the British Museum's prints and drawings, describes the decision 243 years ago to open a collection of artefacts to the public and call it "the British Museum". And it works. While Londoners regard the <font size=-1>BM</font> rather as an ancient and charming relation, to be visited only occasionally, the tourists flock in. The <font size=-1>BM</font> gets 20% more visitors than New York's Metropolian Museum; in the league of the world's most popular museums and galleries, it is second only to the National Air and Space Museum in Washington.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Attracting people is not the <font size=-1>BM</font>'s problem. The <font size=-1>BM</font>'s problem is attracting money. The government is cutting its grant, and at the same time the museum is losing the rent it used to get from the British Library, which is moving to new premises. The effect, by 2000, will be a cut in revenue of 24% after allowing for inflation. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After two-and-a-half peaceful centuries, the <font size=-1>BM</font> is poorly equipped for dealing with financial crises. The curators who run its departments tend to be individualists, chosen not for their management skills but for their scholarship. "The place is full of primadonnas," according to an insider. Finance is frowned upon. The top financial officer has the status of a keeper, which is lower in the hierarchy than a curator. And the place lacks a clear mission: it is part-university, producing fine research on art and archaeology, and part-gallery, catering to its visitors.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>BM</font> hopes to persuade the government to make up the money it is losing from the British Library. But even then, it would still be left with a large gap. There are two ways to fill it: cut costs or make money.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Certainly, costs can be cut. Research could be slashed without affecting the service provided to visitors. But does the <font size=-1>BM</font>'s scholarship matter less than providing a warm resort for tour groups?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It could make more money. Thanks to Britain's 19th-century adventurers, who plundered some of the world's most wonderful ancient treasures--the Elgin marbles, King Ashurbanipal's carved lion-hunt from Assyria, the head of Rameses II from Egypt, turquoise-inlaid skulls from the Aztecs--the <font size=-1>BM</font>'s collection is a valuable resource. In the past, its curators sniffed at commerce, as is evident from its cramped little shop. However, the <font size=-1>BM</font> is waking up to its potential: it has opened a shop at Heathrow, which is doing well, and when the British Library moves out, shops and restaurants will be part of the Great Court development being designed by Sir Norman Foster, an outstanding British architect.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The big question, though, is whether to charge for admission. That is the solution favoured by Andrew Edwards, a former Treasury deputy secretary, who was commissioned by the <font size=-1>BM</font>'s trustees to report on the current crisis. The museum's director, Robert Anderson, disagrees. Charges, he says, would change the public's relationship with the <font size=-1>BM</font>. It would become less like public property, and more like visiting a country house. And charging would cut numbers. When the Victoria & Albert Museum introduced a "voluntary" charge in 1985, attendance fell from 1.7m to 1.02m in the following year (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One option short of a general admission fee would be to charge foreign tourists, who make up around 60% of the visitor numbers. That is the practice in some Spanish and Russian museums. But, practicalities aside, there is a difficulty in principle in charging Greeks, Iraqis or Egyptians to see the treasures which Britons lifted from their civilisations in the first place. "This is a very international museum," says Mr Anderson delicately.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the root of the problem is a nonsense for which the government is responsible. Museums have always faced the conundrum that people are willing to give them chunks of money for the Bloggs Wing or the Himmelfarb Gallery, but nobody wants to finance the security guards or the building maintenance. The government is now exacerbating that problem. Lottery money, like private donations, is for capital projects. And while the government promised that lottery money would not replace Treasury money, that is evidently what is happening. The British Museum has got two chunks of lottery money for capital projects--&#163;30m for the Great Court scheme, which will make use of the space vacated by the British Library, and &#163;8m for a "study centre"--at the same time as its revenue for current expenditure is being slashed. If the old thing is in a tizz, it is not surprising.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848710800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
