<html><head><title>Debt and taxes</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Debt and taxes</h1>

"STUNNINGLY good" was how economists at Goldman Sachs, an investment bank, described the news on November 18th that the government repaid &#163;4.4 billion of debt in October. This view was echoed by many other City of London economists, who on average had expected a paltry &#163;2 billion repayment.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If October's figure sets the trend for the rest of 1996-97, the public-sector borrowing-requirement (<font size=-1>PSBR</font>) will total around &#163;23 billion for the financial year, &#163;4 billion less than the Treasury forecast in July (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>). Many economists reckon that this frees Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, to cut taxes by more than anyone had thought possible in the budget on November 26th--without even seeming reckless.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is a danger in all this of a solitary swallow being mistaken for summer. Chris Giles, an economist at the Institute for Fiscal Studies, an independent research group, points out that much of October's repayment was the making-up of ground lost earlier in the year. The big surprise was the strength of corporate-tax revenues. But these are notoriously lumpy and unpredictable. Moreover, firms paying taxes in October come disproportionately from the booming financial sector; a truer test of whether the corporate-tax take is rising comes in January, a big tax-paying month for firms from less-buoyant bits of the economy. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Richard Jeffrey, an economist at Charterhouse, an investment bank, says that even if October's good news did reflect an improved trend for the <font size=-1>PSBR</font>, that would not be a green light for bigger tax cuts. The likeliest reason for any such fall in borrowing is not a smaller structural deficit (borrowing unrelated to the economic cycle)--which might give grounds for tax cuts--but faster-than-expected economic growth. More evidence of this came on November 20th, with data showing retail sales up by 4.1% in the year to October, and broad money expanding at an annual rate of 10.3%. Rather than justifying tax cuts, warns Mr Jeffrey, a shrinking <font size=-1>PSBR</font> should be regarded as a sign of excessively fast growth, and a warning of the urgent need to raise interest rates, or taxes, to prevent inflation rising.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848710800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7599.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

