<html><head><title>Citizen Gates</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Citizen Gates</h1>

<p><b>Microsoft has made a fortune from software. Why is it so keen to risk much of it in the media business?</b></p><br>
EVERY few years, the titans of technology seem to fall under a strange spell. No matter how successful their own businesses may be, they begin to lust after the media market, driven by the vague notion that "content is king". In the late 1980s the spell lured Japanese consumer-electronics firms to Hollywood. In the mid 1990s America's telephone firms were bewitched into investing in television. All emerged poorer and wiser. Now it is the turn of Microsoft, the giant of the software industry.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This year Microsoft will spend some $400m on media projects, ranging from Web sites on the Internet to a cable-television news channel and a film studio. Its founder and boss, Bill Gates, has said he is prepared to lose $1 billion on such investments in the next few years. Microsoft will remain a software firm but with a big media sideline. As he often remarks, media firms, such as Disney, have built themselves into some of the greatest brands in modern history.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it, this ambition seems strange. Last year Microsoft made profits of $2.2 billion on revenues of $8.6 billion. That dwarfs the profits of even the best media companies. The biggest of them, the Disney empire, earned $1.4 billion last year, while Rupert Murdoch's fearsome News Corp made just under $1 billion. Even the richest newpaper empires make less than half that. At best, media firms achieve margins of less than 12% and enjoy 15% annual growth; most live with single digits for both. By comparison, Microsoft has been growing by over 30% a year, and consistently enjoys net margins of over 25%. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why would Microsoft taint its balance sheet with something as sluggish as media? The simplest answer: because it can. Microsoft has an astounding $7 billion in cash looking for a home. Rather than return the money to its shareholders, the company is entrusting it to the vision of Mr Gates. He reckons that one way or another software and content will merge: Microsoft's best bet is to hurry it along.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anyway, he argues, the sort of media Microsoft is investing in are, for the most part, not the stodgy stuff of paper and film. Mr Gates is investing in "interactive content": as he puts it, <font size=-1>CD</font>-<font size=-1>ROM</font>s, Web sites, Internet services and the like. Such things are booming, at least in terms of the number of on-line readers and offerings, both of which are doubling each year (though no big Web publishing venture is making money yet and even <i>Wired</i>, the cybernaut's bible, is losing a fortune). Moreover, Microsoft knows a bit about this market, having executed a remarkable turnaround in the past year to become one of the leaders in Internet software.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gates reckons that there are more similarities than differences between the software business his firm is good at and the new media it is developing. Both are driven by technology in which Microsoft excels. Both are brand-name businesses. And both share the economies of scale of digital reproduction and distribution. All sound familiar? Exactly: Japanese electronics firms said much the same things when they were throwing money around Hollywood. <br>
</p><p><b><b>Subscriptions, not synergies</b></b><br>
In fact, Microsoft's real financial justification for diving into media is not to search for synergies. Instead, it wants to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities the Internet opens up. And there it sees a chance to gain the main economic advantage that the media business has over software: subscriptions. Microsoft makes its money when consumers buy a new <font size=-1>PC</font> (which comes with a Microsoft operating system already installed); when they buy a box containing Microsoft programs (be it a word processor or an educational <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font>); or when they upgrade a program with a newer version. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This limits Microsoft in two ways. First, it is hard--and getting harder--to win repeat sales. Computer programs are like tools: bought once and used many times. Microsoft has to persuade customers to keep throwing old tools away. But customers are becoming fed up with what they call "bloatware"--unnecessary features added to encourage them to upgrade. Increasingly, they are sticking with the tools they already have.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, traditional software ties Microsoft's growth to the fortunes of the <font size=-1>PC</font> industry. Since the company already dominates most of the biggest software markets, growth will tend to come not from new markets but new <font size=-1>PC</font> owners. Their numbers will rise by only 16% or so this year. To keep its shareholders happy, Microsoft needs to grow twice as fast.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Subscriptions--or "recurring revenues"--are one way to do that, by continuously milking existing <font size=-1>PC</font> users for more money, rather than simply waiting for new customers to come along. Microsoft is already selling some of its office software on subscription, with an annual fee guaranteeing support and upgrades. It offers subscriptions to some of its <font size=-1>CD-ROM</font> titles. But most software buyers, who are not used to working this way, have been unimpressed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So Microsoft is looking for more subscription businesses, and the natural choice is media. News changes constantly, and entertainment usually has a shelf life of days. This sort of business can generate a steady flow of cash. Microsoft is prepared to blanket the market with offerings in its search for gold. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Its efforts range from <i>Slate</i>, a political magazine available in both on-line and paper versions, to <i>UnderWire</i>, a Web site aimed at women. With <font size=-1>NBC</font>, an American television network, it runs <font size=-1>MSNBC</font>, a 24-hour news service, available both as a cable <font size=-1>TV</font> station and as a Web site (see <a href="wb1.gif">table</a>). The Web sites and on-line services are aimed at Microsoft's existing market of <font size=-1>PC</font> owners. But the hope is that <font size=-1>MSNBC</font> and Microsoft's investment in DreamWorks <font size=-1>SKG</font>, a new film studio, will reach a new--and potentially bigger--audience. And Microsoft reckons that the more compelling the media products it can put on the Web, the more people will want to buy <font size=-1>PC</font>s to get them, boosting all its businesses. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Seen as a loss-leader, new media may look a reasonable bet. But as a business in its own right, it is far riskier. Like most other new-media pioneers, Microsoft has no idea where, or when, it might make money from its on-line ventures. Take <font size=-1>MSNBC</font>: its cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> part works just like a normal cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> station, taking subscriptions and advertising. Its Web site, however, has a harder task: viewers on-line are reluctant to pay for subscriptions when so many other sites are free, and paying advertisers are still sceptical about the Web.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At least <font size=-1>MSNBC</font> can tap into traditional media markets. <i>Slate</i> has a harder task. It too has many rivals on the Web, most of which are free. For <i>Slate </i>to earn enough advertising revenue to pay its way, Microsoft insiders reckon that the cerebral weekly will need a regular readership of 400,000. That is about ten times as many as the <i>Wall Street Journal</i> has managed to draw with its massive daily on-line offerings. And charging for <i>Slate</i> (which Microsoft intends to do next February) is liable to chase away most of its readers. That, at any rate, has been the the experience of other Web magazines.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, unlike its rivals, Microsoft has two big advantages in this new market. The first is its $7-billion war chest--and the fact that its boss is prepared to put a great deal of this on the line. <i>Slate</i>, <font size=-1>MSNBC</font> and their siblings can afford to lose money for years. No rival can claim as much.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second is that Microsoft can market its services through its ubiquitous Windows operating system. An icon on new computer screens already puts most users a single click away from <font size=-1>MSN</font>. In its next version of Windows, Microsoft plans to make the link even tighter, weaving Web content--anything from news to advertising-- into the <font size=-1>PC</font> "desktop". Already it has divided <font size=-1>MSN</font> into "channels" along such themes as entertainment, cars and travel. Ultimately, it hopes to take the broadcast analogy further, delivering a television-like stream of Microsoft content to <font size=-1>PC</font> screens.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Plenty of other firms aim to dazzle consumers the same way, although they may not have the same technological edge. Firms such as Pointcast created a market for such Internet "broadcasting" and are sure to adopt Microsoft's new technologies nearly as fast as it does. Others, such as <font size=-1>C/NET</font> and HotWired, are creating channels of their own, and even sometimes producing cable-television programmes to show on them. Microsoft is launching Web sites for local information (starting with listings of entertainment)--but so are two competitors called CitySearch and Yahoo, while local newspapers are moving in too.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ultimately, the new media market will not be won by technology. Just as magazines distinguish themselves by the quality of writing rather than the speed of their printing presses, so the media victors will be those with the most creativity and talent. If these are qualities that can be bought, then Microsoft's greatest advantage will be its bank account. If not, Mr Gates's media ambitions may eventually join yesterday's newspapers in the bin.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848710800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
