<html><head><title>Japan's Lou Gerstner</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Japan's Lou Gerstner</h1>

<p><b>Tadashi Sekizawa runs Fujitsu, Japan's biggest manufacturer of mainframe computers. Can he cope with the PC revolution?</b></p><br>
WALK into any Japanese office these days and you fall over empty boxes at every step. The reason is <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Nearly 6m of them were bought in Japan last year, up an awesome 70% from the year before. Two-thirds of them were bound for offices rather than homes. When offices in the United States went through the transition from mainframes to networked personal computers in the early 1990s, it created havoc at <font size=-1>IBM</font>, the world's largest computer maker. Now Fujitsu, the second largest, has begun to face much the same pressures. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>IBM</font> has been resuscitated over the past three years by Lou Gerstner, in one of the more dramatic corporate turnarounds of recent years. Tadashi Sekizawa, the dour 64-year-old telecommunications engineer who has run Fujitsu for the past six years, is altogether a different proposition: neither a marketing wizard nor a management guru. But he has been showing some equally impressive surgical skills. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sekizawa has had some advantages denied to Mr Gerstner. For one thing, he had longer to prepare for the crunch. The domestic market has traditionally accounted for more than 80% of Fujitsu's business. Its large customers were locked into Fujitsu software running on Fujitsu mainframes. In addition, Japan's protracted recession discouraged Japanese companies from replacing their ageing mainframes with <font size=-1>PC</font>s. Even if they had wanted to do so, it would have been hard to find the <font size=-1>PC</font> software. Only lately has software such as Windows 95, Netscape Navigator and Microsoft Office become truly Japanised.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Luckily for Fujitsu, Mr Sekizawa saw what lay ahead. He has forced through a change in corporate culture almost as dramatic as Mr Gerstner's revolution at <font size=-1>IBM</font>. By Japanese standards, he has axed jobs brutally, cutting 10% of Fujitsu's 40,000 employees in the past three years. He has also moved vigorously into the cut-throat <font size=-1>PC</font> business. That has meant overcoming Fujitsu's snobbish dislike of manufacturing abroad. Fujitsu's new range of <font size=-1>PC</font>s is made in Taiwan, and up to 90% of the parts for its <font size=-1>PC</font>s are bought from suppliers in South-East Asia. That has cut manufacturing costs by 20-30%. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sekizawa's other advantage over Mr Gerstner is that Fujitsu is broader than <font size=-1>IBM</font> was at its nadir. Last year, a third of its &#165;3.8 trillion ($39 billion) of consolidated sales and a similar share of its &#165;63 billion in net profit came from telecoms and microchips (Fujitsu is Japan's second largest supplier of telecoms equipment and fourth biggest microchip maker). It is thus a big beneficiary of Japan's new passion for cellular telephones. While overall profits may slide 40% or more this year, Fujitsu may well double its operating profit from cellular telephones and telecoms gear (see <a href="wb2.gif">chart</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, the key to Mr Sekizawa's vision of <font size=-1>PC</font>s is his background as a telephone engineer. He thinks <font size=-1>PC</font>s are becoming appliances like telephones. What he really wants to sell his customers is not so much the "handset", but the infrastructure that connects <font size=-1>PC</font>s together; services and software to make the tedious technology easier to use; and content that will coax subscribers to stay on line. He is enthralled by the Internet, and wants Fujitsu to be getting 30% of its revenue from Internet-related activities within two years. He has allocated almost half of Fujitsu's &#165;385-billion budget for research and development to ensure that it does.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Flights of fancy</b></b><br>
All this may turn out to be an expensive distraction from the task ahead. No one yet has found a way to deliver a reliable flow of revenue from surfing the Internet. Mr Gerstner understood that, and built his success at <font size=-1>IBM</font> on tackling problems in the most pedestrian of ways--ruthlessly cutting costs, rationalising the business and building on what he had.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sekizawa may yet reach the same conclusion. Fujitsu's earnings are likely to be down sharply this year (from &#165;63 billion to perhaps a mere &#165;35 billion--though the company is forecasting &#165;50 billion) as the semiconductor slump continues. Last year Fujitsu invested massively in new chip-making factories in a bid to catch up on its rivals. The market promptly fell apart.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In addition, the company's mainframe sales abroad are making heavy losses. After losing $580m in 1993 and making a small profit in 1994, Fujitsu's American mainframe subsidiary, Amdahl, lost a further $288m in the first half of this year alone. <font size=-1>ICL</font>, the British mainframe maker that Fujitsu bought in 1990 for &#163;700m ($1.2 billion), made a &#163;194m loss last year and a further unspecified loss in the first half of this year. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Sekizawa's riskiest decision so far has been to dump <font size=-1>PC</font>s on Japan's domestic market at prices that have left rivals squealing with outrage. Industry watchers believe Fujitsu is losing up to 15% on every personal computer it sells in Japan (at a cost of more than &#165;100m a day). As an effort to retain its share of the market, the ploy is succeeding. Last year, Fujitsu leapfrogged from fourth to second place in the domestic <font size=-1>PC</font> market, more than doubling its share to 18.4%. That is still well behind <font size=-1>NEC</font>'s 40%, although Fujitsu is gaining so fast that the two companies could be neck and neck within a couple of years. But few believe it can go on losing money on its <font size=-1>PC</font> sales at the current rate. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fujitsu is now where <font size=-1>IBM</font> was three or four years ago. The restructuring has begun. The agony lies ahead.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
