<html><head><title>Into Zaire</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>Into Zaire</h1>


AT LAST help seems to be on its way. Despite their early reservations, the United States and Britain are lending their support to the proposed intervention force for Zaire. With luck, this Canadian-led force will enable aid agencies to go into eastern Zaire and help more than 1m refugees and thousands of local people facing starvation. For many it is already too late. The world has wilfully stood by as a disaster has unfolded. Now that it is belatedly stirring, it had better not repeat the mistakes it committed when, two years ago, it first watched a genocide in this part of Africa and then tried to mop up after it. The trouble is that, this time, everything will be even harder than before.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No one can say this crisis came unheralded. For months many voices have been warning of catastrophe and calling for the United Nations to act. This week in New York the Americans and the British delayed sending a <font size=-1>UN</font> force, first by saying intervention was unnecessary, then by blithely requesting more information. Their nervousness is understandable, though not their tardiness in overcoming it. The difficulties involved in trying to give help are huge, but it is cynical to pretend that they have not been apparent for months. The Americans in particular know that without their logistical--and financial--support, fast and effective intervention would be impossible. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even with American help, this cannot be a straightforward humanitarian operation (see <a href="ir6038.html">page</a>). Delivering food and medicine among rebels and refugees, some innocents, some guilty of genocide, has tortuous political and military implications. The only route for aid is through Rwanda. Understandably, but unforgivably, the Rwandan government is trying to dictate who joins the force and which aid agencies should be allowed to cross its borders. It does not want the removal of the new buffer zone created by its allies in eastern Zaire. Nor does it want the occupants of the Zairean refugee camps, among whom are Hutus who helped carry out the slaughters in Rwanda two years ago, to reassemble elsewhere in Zaire. Were they to do so, the new camps would become bases for attacks across the border.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These Hutus are not the only armed groups with an interest in controlling events. Some Zaireans are trying to get a slice of the action by demanding that all aid should go through the capital Kinshasa. Fortunately, they can be ignored: their army in the distant east of the country has virtually dissolved and, with the two main airports in rebel hands and no roads to send in reinforcements, central authority in the region is nil.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The rebels in Zaire are more serious. They want food for themselves and--to help them gain political support--for displaced local Zaireans. But they do not want food to reach the mass of refugees or soldiers of the former Rwandan army and Hutu militiamen who hide among them. As for the militiamen, they want food for themselves and their families, and control over the distribution of aid so as to maintain their power over the other refugees. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The problem of the former Rwandan soldiers and Hutu militiamen arises largely because they were not disarmed, still less arrested and brought to trial, when the camps were set up two years ago. Separating them from the other refugees is one of two essential tasks for the intervention force--beyond the provision of security, shelter, food and medicine. Ideally, it should arrest the ringleaders and send them for trial at the international genocide tribunal in Tanzania. But, in the circumstances, keeping armed men out of the refugee camps may be as much as it is reasonable to expect.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second task is, in due course, to return the refugees to Rwanda. Had this been done before, the current troubles would be much simpler to deal with. One difficulty is that the better the camps are run, the more refugees will want to remain inside them. Another is that, even if the camps are dreadful, they may seem safer to frightened Hutus than returning to their villages. Separated from the extremist militiamen bent on revenge, the ordinary Hutu peasants may be more easily persuaded to go home. But, to persuade anyone to go back to such a turbulent country, it will be necessary to show them that a close watch will be kept on the Tutsi-dominated Rwandan government lest it sanction persecution.<br>
</p><p><b>Havens, not Utopias</b><br>
Outsiders, however well intentioned, cannot solve all, or maybe even any, of the political disputes in this part of Africa. The people of Rwanda and Burundi--85% of them Hutus and nearly all the others Tutsis--are likely to be quite literally at each others' throats for years to come. For that reason, Rwanda's Tutsi-led government cannot be considered stable in the long term. Zaire's government is already largely a fiction: the president is in France, stricken with cancer, and large areas of the country have long been running themselves with minimal interference from Kinshasa. It is little wonder that the rebels in the east have proved so successful.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Against this background, outsiders can hope only to alleviate the suffering, and avoid making political problems worse. If this intervention force is not to be followed by another in a couple of years' time, it should at least do its utmost to ensure that the camps it creates are short-term havens of peace, not long-term training grounds for killers.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848106000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="am3126.html">Next article</a>
</p>
