HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 02:15:27 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 14-Nov-96 17:59:59 GMT
Content-length: 6572
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>No survivors</h2>
<p>A Saudi Airlines Boeing 747 with 312 people aboard was in collision near Delhi with an Ilyushin freighter from Kazakhstan carrying 37 people. There were no survivors in the world's <b>worst mid-air crash</b>. </p>
<p>A car containing Myanmar's opposition leader, <b>Aung San Suu Kyi</b>,<b> </b>and her aides was stoned by youths, apparently on the orders of the military government. The United States said it was "outraged".</p>
<p>Bangladesh's opposition Nationalist Party began an indefinite <b>boycott </b>of parliament, claiming that its members were being prevented from speaking on national problems.</p>
<p>China said it was opening, for "education in patriotism", eight sites where Japanese soldiers committed <b>atrocities </b>in the second world war.</p>
<h2>New team </h2>
<p>Bill Clinton made his first <b>new cabinet</b> appointment, choosing Erskine Bowles, a North Carolina banker, to be White House chief of staff. Despite his vigorous defence of entitlements in the campaign, Mr Clinton told the leaders of the new Congress that he was keen on a balanced budget. </p>
<p>Riots broke out in St Petersburg, Florida, after a grand jury refused to bring criminal charges against a white policeman who had killed a black motorist.</p>
<p>The American army announced an investigation of <b>sexual harassment</b> at training bases after a survey revealed that 61% of army women said they had encountered it. </p>
<p>Official results confirmed conservative Arnoldo Aleman, with 51%, as winner of <b>Nicaragua's </b>presidential election, far ahead of Daniel Ortega, with 37.7%. But the Sandinist former president still refused to concede.</p>
<p>Meeting in Chile, Latin American and Iberian leaders agreed that free speech and free elections were essential to democracy. <b>Fidel Castro</b> signed up.</p>
<p><b>Guatemala's</b> government and rebels agreed to sign a peace deal, after 36 years of civil war, on December 29th.</p>
<p>Riots shook <b>French Guiana</b>, in theory part of France.</p>
<h2>Talking hunger</h2>
<p>Some 80 heads of state and government attended a five-day <b>World Food Summit</b> in Rome, sponsored by the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation. They promised to halve the 840m people facing chronic malnutrition--15% of the world's population--by 2015.</p>
<p>A <b>bomb</b> killed 14 people at a memorial service for the head of an Afghan veterans' group in Moscow. The attack was linked to tax privileges for the group, which is controlled by organised crime. </p>
<p>Turkey's interior minister, Mehmet Agar, resigned after a gangster, a police chief and a former beauty queen were killed together in a car crash. </p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Silvio Berlusconi, leader of Italy's right-wing opposition, led more than 500,000 protesters in a <b>demonstration</b> against a government plan to raise taxes to help Italy qualify for Europe's single currency. Italy said it wanted to bring the lira back into Europe's exchange-rate mechanism, which limits currency fluctuations, by December. </p>
<p>Germany approved DM3 billion ($2 billion) of <b>emergency spending cuts</b> to hold the budget deficit in 1997 below 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>, the ceiling for countries that take part in Europe's planned economic and monetary union. The Christian Democrats and Free Democrats, partners in the ruling coalition, agreed to put off resolving a dispute over taxes that had threatened to wreck the coalition.</p>
<p>The European Union's auditor criticised the <font size=-1>EU</font> and its member governments for <b>lax financial management</b>. The Court of Auditors said in its annual report that fraud and other errors had amounted to $5.1 billion of the $95.8 billion budget.</p>
<p><b>Slovenia</b>'s Liberal Democracy party, led by Janez Drnovsek, the country's ex-communist prime minister, won the biggest block of seats in parliamentary elections. But an alliance of right-wing parties may unseat him. </p>
<p>Bulgaria's prime minister, <b>Zhan Videnov</b>, won a vote of confidence from leaders of his Socialist Party after its defeat in presidential elections. But Foreign Minister Georgi Pirinski quit, saying the government did not have enough support to remain in power.</p>
<p>Biljana Plavsic, president of the <b>Bosnian Serb Republic</b>, sacked the army chief, Ratko Mladic, an alleged war criminal. Military police opposed to Mr Mladic's removal detained the defence minister, Milan Ninkovic.</p>
<h2>Zaire mission</h2>
<p>America agreed "in principle" to send troops for a Canadian-led multinational force to protect humanitarian aid for more than 1m refugees in <b>eastern Zaire</b>. Britain has also offered troops. The <font size=-1>UN</font> said that thousands were already dying of starvation and thirst. After two days of negotiation with rebels in Goma, relief workers began distributing food on Wednesday but came under shell fire from one of the camps of Rwandan Hutu refugees. </p>
<p>With a <b>Palestinian-Israeli</b> deal on Hebron seemingly only hours away, Binyamin Netanyahu postponed a visit to Washington. The deal was not made. Earlier, Israeli troops fired on Palestinians demonstrating against a land seizure, killing one and wounding 11.</p>
<p>For the first time since the cold war, the United States government is to give allies military aid to help overthrow a hostile neighbour. Almost $20m worth of equipment is to be sent to Uganda, Ethiopia and Eritrea for use against the Islamist government of Sudan.</p>

</td></tr></table></center>
