<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Time and motion</h2>
<p>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The European Court of Justice ruled that Britain must obey European Union rules imposing a <b>48-hour week</b> on member states. John Major, Britain's prime minister, argued that such rules would aggravate Europe's unemployment problem. He said that Britain would disrupt <font size=-1>EU</font> business in other areas unless the rules were overturned.</p>
<p>Zhu Jiazhen, China's labour vice-minister, predicted that <b>China's loss-making state firms</b> will sack some 14m workers over the next five years in order to cut their costs, and that roughly 130m peasants will stop farming and drift to the cities. Chinese newspapers warned him that the country's urban unemployment rate could leap from 2.9% to 7.4% by the year 2000.</p>
<p>Albert Dunlap, the boss of <b>Sunbeam</b>, an American household-appliances firm, lived up to his reputation as "Chainsaw Al". Mr Dunlap promised to halve the firm's 12,000-strong workforce, to shut 39 of its 53 factories and offices, and to discontinue 87% of its products.</p>
<p>Once one of America's most diversified conglomerates, <b>Westinghouse Electric</b>, said it would spin off the rest of its industrial businesses and move into cable-<font size=-1>TV</font>. The company is already America's biggest broadcast television and radio group.</p>
<h2>A new tone</h2>
<p>America and Europe inched closer to a deal that would liberalise their <b>telecoms</b> and <b>information-technology</b> markets. At a meeting of American and <font size=-1>EU</font> delegates, America promised to liberalise underwater cable services to the United States and both Europe and America agreed to abolish tariffs on many high-tech products by the second half of 1997. </p>
<p>Carlo Ciampi, Italy's treasury minister, is ringing the changes in the country's telecoms market. He announced that <b>Stet</b>, a state-controlled telecoms holding company, is to merge with Telecom Italia, its main operating unit. The government plans belatedly to privatise the new firm next autumn.</p>
<p>Yet another British regional electricity company (<font size=-1>REC</font>) is likely to end up in American hands. East Midlands Electricity accepted a &#163;1.3 billion ($2.2 billion) bid from <b>Dominion Resources</b>. Several other American utilities have bid for <font size=-1>REC</font>s. </p>
<p><b>Deutsche Telekom</b> decided to increase the number of shares to be issued in its forthcoming initial public offering from 500m to 600m.</p>
<h2>A new policy</h2>
(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>AXA</b> and <b>Union des Assurances de Paris</b>, two French insurers, announced a $7.8 billion merger, which will create the world's second-largest insurer ranked by premiums. <font size=-1>AXA</font>'s chairman, Claude B&eacute;b&eacute;ar, who will run the merged group, promised to share his firm's "profit-minded" culture with <font size=-1>UAP</font>, whose shares have fallen 47% since the beginning of 1994.</p>
<p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>The Austrian government's six-year struggle to find a buyer for its 70% stake in <b>Creditanstalt</b>, the country's best-known bank, may soon be over. First Austrian, a savings bank, has rejoined a foreign consortium that would like to buy the stake. This should reassure those who want Creditanstalt to remain in Austrian hands. </p>
<h2>Digging deep</h2>
<p>British investigators joined a French probe into suspected <b>insider dealing</b> in the shares of Eurotunnel, which runs the Channel tunnel. An earlier investigation by the London Stock Exchange reportedly failed to uncover any evidence of wrongdoing.</p>
<p>A scandal temporarily shut down the <b>Athens stock exchange</b>. Most of Greece's 65 stockbroking firms said they would boycott the bourse until its clearing house settles outstanding trades left by Delta Securities, a small broker that collapsed after allegedly manipulating share prices and bouncing 2.6 billion drachma ($11m) of cheques. Arrest warrants were issued for three Delta executives.</p>
<p>A Swiss banking ombudsman said a nine-month search for dormant accounts belonging to <b>Holocaust victims</b>, which relatives of the dead claim contain billions of dollars, had unearthed a mere $8,750. The World Jewish Congress called his efforts "pathetic".</p>
<p>Ron Baker, the former head of derivatives trading at <b>Barings</b>, a British merchant bank that collapsed last year, was cleared of most of the charges brought against him by the Securities and Futures Authority, the securities industry's regulator. Mr Baker had been accused by the regulator of failing to show "due skill, care and diligence" in supervising his employees.</p>
<h2>Tokyo's bang</h2>
<p>The Japanese government unveiled an ambitious plan to <b>liberalise Japan's financial sector</b> by 2001. Barriers between the country's banks and securities firms are to be swept away, as are fixed stockbroking commissions and controls on insurance premiums. The finance ministry hopes that this will help Tokyo's capital markets to catch up with those in London and New York. </p>
<p>The Tokyo prosecutor's office charged <b>Yasuo Hamanaka</b>, the copper trader who lost Sumitomo Corp $2.6 billion this year, with forgery. Mr Hamanaka, who faces up to five years in jail if he is convicted, is also threatened with a civil suit from his former employer.</p>

</td></tr></table></center>
