<html><head><title>Polls apart</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Politics</b></p>
<h1>Polls apart</h1>

IF YOU read the <i>Sunday Times</i>, you recently learnt that Labour's lead over the Tories had "fallen to its lowest for nearly three years". If you read the <i>Guardian</i>, the Tories received "a powerful boost" with a five-point cut in Labour's poll lead. If you read <i>The Times</i> you were first told that "Blair surges ahead" but then that "Tory support has jumped". If, however, you read the <i>Daily Telegraph</i>, an "ominous black cloud" still hangs over the Tories.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Divergent findings are not good for polling firms' credibility--and after their failure to predict the Tory win in the 1992 general election the polls do not have credibility to spare. The pollsters are therefore worried. <font size=-1>MORI</font> reacted to criticism of its first <i>Times</i> poll, which showed an unlikely-sounding 28-point Labour lead, by putting out a table of recent polls, published and unpublished, claiming most were in line with its<i> </i>finding. However, it also conducted a second poll for <i>The Times</i>, published on November 14th, which showed Labour's lead down from 28% to 17%.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The problem is compounded because different firms publish results compiled on different bases. Some pollsters believe that crude results exaggerate Labour's lead. They argue that those who refuse to answer their questions include a disproportionate percentage of Tories, reluctant to admit the fact in today's hostile climate. They also point out that, when you ask people how they voted in 1992, more say "Labour" than "Tory", although the Tories won the election. This suggests that their samples may be biased towards Labour. They try to correct for these factors.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such adjustments are not yet proven to produce more accurate figures. So other pollsters prefer not to make them. Of the controversial recent polls, two (by <font size=-1>ICM</font> and <font size=-1>NOP</font>) which show the Tories doing well headlined their adjusted figures. The other three (the two <i>Times</i> polls by <font size=-1>MORI</font> and one by Gallup) did not. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, adjustment does not fully explain the differences. Even when you compare like with like, the results are all over the place. The adjusted Tory vote is put at between 30% (<font size=-1>MORI</font> 1) and 34% (<font size=-1>ICM</font> and <font size=-1>MORI</font> 2); Labour at between 47% (<font size=-1>NOP</font>) and 53% (<font size=-1>MORI</font> 1); the Labour lead at between 13% (<font size=-1>ICM</font>) and 23% (<font size=-1>MORI</font> 1). Two polls had Labour sharply up on the month and three had it down.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may be a run of bad luck. Over time, most samples will more or less accurately reflect the whole population, but individual samples may not. Internal evidence casts doubt on some of this month's samples. <font size=-1>ICM</font>'s, for example, showed that an unusually high proportion of those questioned said that they had voted Tory in 1992, while <font size=-1>MORI</font> 1's had an unusually high proportion saying they had voted Labour then. <font size=-1>ICM</font> scaled down its usual adjustments to allow for this, but it may be that they just happened on an unusually pro-Tory sample and <font size=-1>MORI</font> 1 a pro-Labour sample in the month.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the moment, all polls agree on one finding: Labour is miles ahead. As the election approaches, however, the margin seems sure to narrow. Pollsters will secretly pray that the margin between their findings narrows too. Otherwise voters may start to switch off polls just at the stage in the political cycle when they ought to be of greatest interest.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
