<html><head><title>Mission impossible</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Civil service</b></p>
<h1>Mission impossible</h1>

SIR ROBIN BUTLER, the cabinet secretary, has a mission to resist the politicisation of Britain's non-partisan civil service. His latest target is Michael Heseltine, the deputy prime minister.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This summer, Mr Heseltine instructed Whitehall civil servants to identify "cheerleaders" among providers of government services to speak up for the government's public-service reforms--ie, defend the Tories. One cabinet minister who learnt of the instruction ordered officials to bin it. Then, at Sir Robin's behest, Mr Heseltine withdrew. "A blatant abuse of government power," said John Prescott, Labour's deputy leader, when news of the incident emerged this week. "No minister will tolerate the politicisation of the civil service in this country," Mr Heseltine retorted.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Allegations of politicisation keep popping up all the same. This summer the First Division Association, the mandarins' union, reported more than 20 complaints from members who had been asked to do work which might compromise their political neutrality. Examples included preparing material for election manifestos, altering official reports to provide a party political slant, and briefing for public-relations events during party conferences.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In theory, mandarins are better protected against this kind of thing than they have ever been. The rules set out in "Questions of Procedure for Ministers" say that ministers must not use public resources for party-political purposes. A new civil-service code protects civil-service ethics, and gives civil servants the right of appeal to Sir Michael Bett, the independent First Civil service commissioner, if they feel they have been asked to act improperly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Detailed instructions govern their relations with journalists. Yet more instructions lay down what civil servants may and may not do to cost Labour proposals. Roger Freeman, Mr Heseltine's deputy, on November 11th proposed further protection for them, offering to co-operate with Labour to put a new Civil Service Act on the statute book. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why do allegations of impropriety keep surfacing? The immediate cause is the approach of the general election. Ministers are more and more desperate to win the propaganda war with Labour, and want Whitehall to provide the ammunition. Whitehall knows it may soon be serving new masters, and does not want to prejudice its acceptability to them. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But there is a longer-term trend at work too. Thirty or forty years ago, the line between government and party matters was clearer. Politics intruded less into ministerial lives. They governed largely according to the advice of their civil servants, only rarely taking to the platform or the airwaves to score political points. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All that has changed. In their new book, "The State under Stress" (Open University Press, &#163;16.99), Sir Christopher Foster and Francis Plowden chart the increased politicisation of government. Ministers often take decisions without civil service advice. The system of cabinet committees has atrophied in favour of government by <i>ad hoc </i>cabals of ministers. Ministers allow themselves to be directly lobbied by <font size=-1>MP</font>s who are themselves often directly in the pay of commercial organisations. Moreover, a successful minister is a minister who is on <font size=-1>TV</font>--and when he is, his party expects him to score partisan points.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We thus have a world where the "government of the day", headed by ministers, is far more political than it used to be, and where partisan politics becomes ever more intense. No wonder civil servants find it harder and harder to draw lines between their duty to serve the government loyally and their equal duty to be non-partisan. Acts, appeals and codes cannot resolve such tensions--which may mean that Sir Robin's mission turns out to be impossible.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848106000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
