<html><head><title>A flat market</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Complementary medicine</b></p><h1>The new-age NHS</h1><br><p><b>Unorthodox remedies such as aromatherapy and healing are becoming available on the NHS as doctors find they can do miracles for their budgets</b></p><p>AN ELDERLY woman goes to her doctor complaining of arthritis in her knees. He gives her some tablets but the next week she is back in the surgery complaining that the pills give her an upset stomach. She is given more tablets to treat this side-effect but is soon back again saying that the second set of pills made her ankles swell. She is in turn given tablets to treat this, which cause muscle cramps, requiring a fourth set of pills, and so on. By now, the woman feels sicker than when she started.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This sort of case, not uncommon, is one reason why the medical profession is abandoning its customary conservatism and becoming less dismissive of "new-age remedies", from osteopathy (which is on the verge of becoming orthodox) to faith healing (which is not). Even though most doctors still doubt the scientific validity of such treatments, they are increasingly prepared to use them, because they seem to work better on some types of patient than stuffing them with pills--and often at a lower cost.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The medical authorities have gradually adopted a softer line on their use, and many such treatments are now available on the National Health Service (<font size=-1>NHS</font>). Since doctors are prescribing them alongside the orthodox ones they learnt at medical school, they are now officially described as "complementary medicine". Until quite recently doctors could be struck off if they prescribed unconventional treatments. As recently as 1986 the British Medical Association (<font size=-1>BMA</font>) dismissed them as a "passing fashion". However, an exception has long been made for homoeopathy: this has been available on the <font size=-1>NHS</font> since its foundation in 1948, partly because of the royal family's patronage.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The increasing use of complementary therapies has mostly been the result of individual doctors acting on their own initiative. In order to study the implications for the <font size=-1>NHS</font> as a whole, the National Association of Health Authorities and Trusts recently launched a detailed study of why doctors are prescribing complementary therapies, how much they are spending on them, and what they are doing to measure their effectiveness. A preliminary survey, in 1993, found that the <font size=-1>NHS</font> was spending at least &#163;1m a year on complementary medicine, but the new study is expected to show that the actual figure is far higher.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last year, a survey by Sheffield University of 760 general practicioners found that 40% were offering some form of complementary therapy on the <font size=-1>NHS</font>, especially acupuncture (an ancient Chinese method which aims to cure patients by sticking needles into them), homoeopathy (the use of extremely dilute extracts of natural substances which cause symptoms similar to those being treated), osteopathy and chiropractic (which both involve manipulation of the joints). One doctor's surgery, in Cullompton, Devon, employs a healer who believes her powers come from God. The Royal Liverpool University Hospital offers aromatherapy (massage with plant oils) and reflexology (massaging points on the feet and hands which are supposedly linked to other parts of the body) to treat kidney, bowel and ear complaints.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Edzard Ernst, professor of complementary medicine at Exeter University, says that, apart from osteopathy and chiropractic, there is little convincing evidence that there is anything to most complementary therapies other than the placebo effect, a phenomenon long recognised by doctors: patients can get better simply because they believe their treatment will work, even if they are given pills without any active ingredients. Studies of some treatments have been done, but often the methods used in such studies are flawed and open to bias. It may be that most, perhaps all, of the effectiveness of complementary therapies is attributable to the placebo effect.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet doctors have come to realise that the placebo effect itself can be a valuable therapeutic tool. Dr Vivienne Nathanson, head of ethics at the <font size=-1>BMA</font>, says conventional western medicine has not been much help in treating chronic conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis. So doctors are taking the pragmatic view that if a treatment seems to work, and has no harmful effects, then it is worth a try.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is the approach of Michael Dixon, the doctor whose surgery in Cullompton employs a healer. Dr Dixon says that, although the healer believes she is passing some form of divine energy to the patients, he carefully avoids expressing an opinion on the matter. As well as helping patients for whom no other treatment has worked, Dr Dixon has found that the healer has a soothing effect on his budget: in a rough survey of 50 patients who visited the healer, about a third needed fewer drugs, saving the <font size=-1>NHS</font> up to &#163;1,500 a year between them. The government's <font size=-1>NHS</font> reforms, which allow general practitioners to take over the funding of their patients' treatments, have given doctors a little more freedom over which treatments to choose. More importantly, the reforms have made doctors think harder about the costs and benefits of rival courses of treatment.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While softening its stance on unorthodox therapies, the <font size=-1>BMA</font> has also been pressing for the compulsory registration of those practising them. So far it has succeeded only with osteopathy. In February the government set up the General Osteopathic Council. When it is granted its full powers (probably some time next year), practising osteopathy without a licence from the council will become illegal. Until registration is extended to the other complementary therapies, it is unclear how far doctors and other medical staff can go: a health authority in south London recently found that tarot cards were being used at one of its drug-dependency clinics--it quickly put a stop to this. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Clearly a line has to be drawn somewhere. The medical profession should certainly not get involved in pretending there are mystical forces at work in complementary therapies. And if, in future, rigorous studies find that a particular treatment has no scientific basis, patients should be told this. Human nature being what it is, many will probably be happy to give it a try nevertheless.
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<br>

