<html><head><title>Time for a change</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Time for a change</h1>

<font size=1>NEW YORK AND ATLANTA</font><p>
WHILE all cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> companies are battered by competition from satellite channels, Time Warner, the second-largest, has a further big headache of its own: its corporate structure. Roughly half its 12m cable subscribers belong to networks that are owned by Time Warner Entertainment (<font size=-1>TWE</font>), a company in which Time Warner has a 75%<b> </b>stake and <font size=-1>US</font>West, a local telephone company, the remainder. One side effect of this is that Time Warner does not have direct access to some of the cash flow that is the main attraction of owning cable firms. Its Warner Brothers studio and Home Box Office, a profitable pay-television business, are also tied up in <font size=-1>TWE</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The stockmarket hates this messy structure almost as much as it dislikes Time Warner's involvement in cable. Could both problems be solved in one go? Only if Gerald Levin, the company's chief executive, can overcome his emotional attachment to cable. Mr Levin comes from the cable business and has long invested heavily in cable-TV assets. However, others within the company do not share his enthusiasm. "At the core, Time Warner is a content business," says Richard Parsons, the firm's president. "Cable is an enormous consumer of capital, and the capital it is consuming is not necessarily related to our content business." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Parsons is not a lone voice. The managers brought into the company from Turner Broadcasting, Ted Turner's television empire, which Mr Levin has just bought for $7.5 billion, also seem dismissive about cable's long-term future. John Malone, the boss of <font size=-1>TCI</font>, an even larger cable network that now holds a non-voting 9% stake in Time Warner, argues that the firm's shares "would do miraculously better if they spun off the cable business to their shareholders. So instead of owning a programming company that owns a cable company, I would own a programming company <i>and</i> a cable company." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the cable side of <font size=-1>TWE</font> were to be spun off, it could probably take with it roughly half of Time Warner's current debt mountain of $17.5 billion. But such a solution requires the agreement of <font size=-1>US</font>West. That relationship has been soured by Time Warner's acquisition-- without consulting the telephone company--of Turner Broadcasting.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it, <font size=-1>US</font>West can demand a high price for agreeing to a solution. Mr Parsons, who is supposed to charm the telecoms company into a deal, claims that if <font size=-1>US</font>West will not co-operate, Time Warner could simply sell off "a big chunk" of its other cable holdings to pay off its debt. But this would not unscramble the relationship with <font size=-1>US</font>West. And there is an even bigger drawback to jettisoning cable. "To be a major programmer with no distribution isn't the greatest thing in the world," observes Mr Malone dryly.<br>
</td></tr></table>


