<html><head><title>A Big Bang for Japan</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26" alt="Finance and Economics" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>A Big Bang for Japan</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font><p>
<p><b>The Japanese government has announced its intention to reform the financial system. Should its proposals be taken seriously?></b></p><br>
WHEN Japan's voters returned the Liberal Democratic Party to power in October after a three-year interregnum, most people assumed that the victors would quickly forget their election promises of "administrative reform"--shorthand for taking power over the economy out of the hands of Japanese bureaucrats. For once, the sceptics may be wrong. On November 11th Ryutaro Hashimoto, Japan's prime minister, promised that his government would undertake a sweeping deregulation of the country's financial system by 2001. Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, the new finance minister, called the proposals "the equivalent of London's Big Bang".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In search of a good, if hackneyed image (earlier this year South Korea used the same phrase to describe its own financial-reform package), Mr Mitsuzuka may have been overstating his case. Few of these proposals are new; many were proposed by a government committee in August. Detail is lacking. Some important areas for reform have been ignored. And there will be opposition from vested interests, especially Japan's big securities firms, to those reforms that the government has proposed. But for all that, the prime minister has set a deadline and given his pledge. This time, at least, there seems to be the political will for serious reform. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;About time too. Bureaucrats and politicians alike appear to have realised at last that the glacial pace of Japan's previous financial reforms has strangled the country's economic recovery and thwarted Tokyo's pretensions to be an international financial centre. While it has been mired in red tape, the world's two other big financial centres, London and New York, have roared ahead. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tokyo also faces a growing challenge from Hong Kong and Singapore, which would both like to become Asia's main financial hub. Fed up with Japanese bureaucracy, some financial folk are already moving to Singapore and other centres with a lighter regulatory touch. They are not the only ones leaving town: over the past three years, 54 companies have delisted from the Tokyo Stock Exchange. "Shock therapy is necessary. The alternative is for Tokyo to become a local market," a senior bureaucrat at the finance ministry told foreign journalists this week.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Japan's over-regulated and compartmentalised financial system is a product of both accident and design. After the second world war, the Americans imposed a version of their own Glass-Steagall act, which separates commercial and investment banking, in the shape of Article 65 of the Securities and Exchange Law. But bureaucrats also designed the financial system to make it easier to channel savings into favoured industries: the more segregated the various parts of the financial sector were, the easier it was to control the institutions through which savings were channelled. For example, long-term credit banks made long-term loans to industry. In addition, they were given a monopoly on issuing fixed-rate debt. Commercial banks took deposits and lent at floating rates. All interest rates were set by the finance ministry.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much of this apparatus is still intact. Banks face fierce competition for corporate business, especially now that big companies can tap the capital markets themselves. But the regulations prevent bankers from meeting this challenge by underwriting equities. They are also barred from selling insurance. Other sorts of financial firms also have their hands tied: securities firms cannot offer banking or insurance services, and insurance firms cannot go into banking or securities.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Still too tight</b></b><br>
The sharp divisions between businesses have been relaxed a bit, but only gradually. Interest rates began to be liberalised in 1984. At the end of 1993, banks were finally allowed to underwrite corporate bonds (though not equities) through subsidiaries. And from the beginning of October, life and non-life insurers have been free to enter each other's business, again via subsidiaries. In spite of all this, the boundaries that remain between businesses are still substantial.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such tight control has become not just redundant, but positively harmful. To enable financial firms to earn a crust, bureaucrats have allowed the cost of many financial products and services to remain high by approving cartels and discouraging aggressive competition. Insurance premiums are fixed by bureaucratic fiat. Two decades after they were scrapped in America, and a decade after they disappeared in Britain, fixed commissions on all but the biggest share trades still raise the cost of buying equities in Japan.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Hashimoto now says that he wants to do away with this rigid financial system. Insurers, banks and securities firms, he promises, will be allowed to enter one another's business. Legal barriers separating the different sorts of banks are to be scrapped. Stock commissions and insurance premiums will be deregulated. The asset-management business will be opened up and the detailed rules that govern how pension funds allocate their money will be abandoned for a more general prudential requirement.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Light the fuse. . .</b></b><br>
That is not all. The quality of financial information disclosed by companies will be improved by the adoption of accounts "consistent" with those of other developed countries. In short, assets will be valued at their proper market price, not the price at which they were bought. Pension funds will have to do this from next April. (Given the precarious state of many Japanese banks, however, the government will surely give them much longer to make a change that will make their financial situation appear far gloomier.) <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With a list of reforms this long, it would seem churlish to quibble that the government is not planning to do enough. Yet conspicuously absent from its "to do" list is any mention of the privatisation of the banking operations of the post office. Japan's post office is the world's biggest bank. Since it does not have to worry about shareholders, it can offer higher rates than the banks. And its deposits are fully guaranteed by the government. Small wonder, given fears about the health of private banks, that its deposits have grown by over 11% since 1994. Banks claim, justifiably, that a publicly-owned post office distorts competition. On November 11th Shunsaku Hashimoto, the chairman of Japan's bankers' association, chastised the government for not tackling this question. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such carping aside, the government's deregulatory proposals are generally excellent in intent. Does it have the stomach to push them through? The finance ministry claims that it has. As evidence, it says that a bill to scrap the law that allows only licensed banks to deal in foreign exchange will be introduced in the next session of the Diet (parliament). This, however, is fairly uncontroversial. Few, if any, institutions will be put out of business. Other steps will be implemented only if the government is prepared to put up with the squeals of pain from those whose profits are threatened by deregulation. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chief squealers will be Japan's 230 securities firms. Their income comes from commissions on share-trading and from selling mutual funds. They are already suffering from a sluggish Japanese stockmarket: turnover has fallen 75% since the late 1980s. Deregulation of stockbrokers' commissions, and the entry of big banks and insurers with lots of branches into the equity and mutual-fund business, will put many brokers out of business. The prime minister says that he will tolerate such bankruptcies. Perhaps he will. But a fear of letting firms fail probably means that the government will shy away from scrapping the Article 65 restrictions altogether. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead, the authorities are likely to go for a more convoluted solution. To "moderate" competition throughout the financial industry, it seems likely that firms will be allowed to enter markets from which they have hitherto been excluded only by setting up a new business under the umbrella of a holding company. First, however, holding companies, which were banned after the second world war, will have to be legalised. Even then they will prove attractive to financial firms only if the government introduces a consolidated tax system, so that profits in one part of a company's operations can be offset by losses in another. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Implementing all of this in five years and making sure that vested interests do not neuter the proposals will be a Herculean task. A lot of people think that the government is not up to it. There have been many deregulatory promises unkept in the past. And when change has occurred, it has been frustratingly slow. But there now seems to be a consensus among politicians and bureaucrats that the Japanese financial system needs root-and-branch reform. It is surely telling that a top official at the finance ministry, the country's most powerful bureaucracy, says that, in effect, Japan should have a more freewheeling financial system before its current one makes the country an also-ran. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
