<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Yes, he won</h2>
<p><b>Bill Clinton </b>won the American presidential election with 49% of the popular vote against Bob Dole's 41%, and 31 states against his 19. He becomes the first Democrat to be elected twice since Franklin Roosevelt. But the Republicans held on to both the Senate and the House of Representatives. Ross Perot won 8% of the vote. Less than half of the eligible voters cast their ballots, a record low.</p>
<p><b>Warren Christopher</b> resigned as secretary of state, but will stay on until Mr Clinton's inauguration in January. Several other team members, including William Perry, the defence secretary, Mickey Kantor, the commerce secretary, and Leon Panetta, the White House chief of staff, are also to go. </p>
<p>Voters in California approved by a large margin a proposition to end <b>racial quotas </b>in state contracting and employment.</p>
<p>In <b>Nicaragua</b>, expecting official (but still provisional) results of its October 20th elections on November 7th, the Sandinists accused the seemingly victorious Liberal Alliance of fraud. They demanded a fresh vote in two big provinces, and called a day of "civic protest"--peaceful, apparently--on November 8th. </p>
<h2>Hell in Zaire</h2>
<p>All parties in the war in eastern <b>Zaire </b>have agreed to accept a multinational force to save refugees, but few countries have offered troops. France wants military intervention; European Union aid ministers met to discuss proposals. More than a million people, mostly Hutu refugees, have been left without food or shelter after aid agencies were driven out of the region by fighting. Having seized part of eastern Zaire, rebels offered a three-week ceasefire. </p>
<p>Leaders of big <b>third-world countries</b>, meeting in Zimbabwe, accused rich countries of trying to dictate rules of world trade. One big gripe: rules on labour conditions, seen by the poor as a way of negating their lower wages. But Bangladesh, which supplies half of Europe's <font size=-1>T</font>-shirts, said it no longer used child labour in its textile factories. </p>
<p>Israel's infrastructure minister, Ariel Sharon, unveiled a plan to settle 100,000 more colonists in the occupied <b>West Bank</b>. Not a government plan, said a spokesman.</p>
<p>In <b>Algeria</b>, Islamist guerrillas seized ten women and three children at a village and slit their throats. Later, in another village, 31 more people were murdered the same way.</p>
<h2>Interregnum</h2>
<p>Russia's president, <b>Boris Yeltsin</b>, took back presidential powers less than 24 hours after handing them over to his prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, to undergo a heart operation. Doctors said the seven-hour quintuple bypass went well.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Robert Tatum, an American businessman, was<b> murdered in Moscow</b>. He had been seeking control of the city's Radisson-Slavyanskaya hotel. In Ukraine Evheny Sherban, a prominent businessman and member of parliament, was also murdered.</p>
<p><b>Russia's trade unions </b>said that up to 2m workers went on strike to demand payment of $7 billion in unpaid wages by federal and local governments. Some parts of Russia are running short of food and fuel as winter approaches.</p>
<p>The European Commission said 12 of the 15 <font size=-1>EU</font> countries would meet the Maastricht treaty's requirement for <b>budget deficits </b>of no more than 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> in 1997 if they are to join <font size=-1>EMU</font>. Britain, Italy and Greece were the exceptions. But the European Monetary Institute, precursor to a central bank, felt that progress towards deficit reduction has been too slow.</p>
<p>Voters in <b>Romania and Bulgaria</b> rebuffed ex-communists and supported reformists. Romanians made the Democratic Convention the largest party, and in his race for re-election President Ion Iliescu holds a slim lead over Emil Constantinescu, the Democratic Convention candidate, before a run-off on November 17th. In Bulgaria's presidential election, Petar Stoyanov, a pro-reform lawyer, defeated the Socialist candidate, Ivan Marazov.</p>
<p>Allies of Serbia's president, <b>Slobodan Milosevic</b>, easily won elections for the federal Yugoslav parliament and the parliament of Montenegro, the second republic in the Yugoslav federation.</p>
<p>The European Bank of Reconstruction and Development predicted that growth in<b> former communist economies</b> would accelerate next year from a projected 4% rate in 1996. But all of them, it said, must do more to reform their financial systems and improve infrastructure.</p>
<h2>Bhutto out</h2>
<p>Benazir Bhutto was dismissed as prime minister of <b>Pakistan </b>by the country's president. The president said her government was incompetent and corrupt; it, and parliament, were also dismissed. Miss Bhutto was put under house arrest, but later freed. A general election is to be held in February.</p>
<p>Japan's Liberal Democratic Party won over enough defectors to form a government. <b>Ryutaro Hashimoto </b>was formally reappointed prime minister.</p>
<p>A <b>Khmer Rouge commander </b>and 300 fighters became the latest rebel group to defect to the Cambodian government. But Pol Pot, the rebel leader, was reported to be preparing to renew his attacks on government forces.</p>
<p>A senior official in Washington said America had revised its view, and saw no prospect of <b>Afghanistan's civil war </b> coming to an early end.</p>
<p></p>

</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="bw0759.html">BUSINESS THIS WEEK</a></p>
