<html><head><title>The last best campaign</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The last best campaign</h1>

<font size=1>LITTLE ROCK</font><p>
LONG before the voting finished on November 5th, street vendors in Little Rock were doing a brisk business in <font size=-1>T</font>-shirts with a spoof front-page story from the <i>Arkansas Democrat Gazette</i>. It declared a resounding victory for Bill Clinton. The <font size=-1>T</font>-shirt sellers, like everyone else, had been reading the polls. And the actual results brought no surprise. The only real tension was over the size of Mr Clinton's victory (big, but no landslide) and whether it would help the Democrats recapture at least one of the houses of Congress (it didn't). Shamefully, early estimates suggest that only 49% of eligible voters bothered to vote, the lowest turnout since 1924. (See <a href="am1.gif">chart</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, the final days of the presidential campaign managed a sense of sleepless drama worthy of this great exercise in democracy. Recalling that the first time he had fought round the clock for his country was on the battlefields of Italy in 1945, Mr Dole took off on a 96-hour dash across 20 states with barely a pause for rest, before arriving to vote in his native Russell, Kansas. "I couldn't think of anything else," he explained. "It's my last option." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The "Marathon Man", as he called himself, travelled day and night from diner to parking lot, from airport tarmac to truck stop. To preserve his fading voice, he kept his speeches short and drank "Throat Coat" herbal tea. The valiant effort restored some of the respect that Mr Dole had been in danger of losing in his generally hapless campaign. It was a reminder of the story of his life: an endurance test, and one that he survived.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He might even have dared believe his own brave predictions of victory. For once, he was capturing the imagination, and his opponent was on the defensive over foreign campaign contributions. The race seemed to be narrowing as undecided voters made up their minds, and one tracking poll briefly suggested Mr Dole might just win. The wee hours of Tuesday morning found him in Independence, Missouri, paying homage to Harry Truman, the model for come-from-behind triumph.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it was not to be. Valiant as Mr Dole's final effort was, it also smacked of desperation, and drew attention to one of his main vulnerabilities: his age. Mr Clinton, on a sleepless marathon of his own, looked relentlessly vigorous as he moved from the sunshine of California to the first snows of New England and on to the autumnal colours of the mid-west.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This, as Mr Clinton repeatedly pointed out, was the final campaign of a man who has been running for some office or other for the past 23 years. The last day of the last campaign began with a nostalgic visit to New Hampshire, birthplace of his 1992 comeback. The president moved on to Ohio, Kentucky and Iowa before holding his final rally in Sioux Falls, South Dakota. There, about to leave after his speech and the handshakes along the rope line, he suddenly turned and went back to the podium, waving and striding the stage, hanging on to the last minutes of the campaigning life. Then he was off to Arkansas for his triumphant homecoming.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His triumph is the sweeter because it had looked so improbable after the Republican surge in 1994. The Republicans looked forward to 1996 as the "confirming" election, the year that would give them control of the White House as well as of Congress. Instead, Mr Clinton not only won, but he won with nearly 50% of the popular vote to Mr Dole's 41%. Ross Perot, who took 19% of the vote four years ago, managed only 8% this time as the candidate of his new Reform Party. It could be argued that in 1992 Mr Clinton owed his victory to Mr Perot; not so in 1996. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet even as the voters rewarded the president, they also restrained him. If this election "confirmed" anything, it was the status quo. Republicans held on to the House of Representatives for the first time in 68 years, and increased their majority slightly in the Senate. So much for theories about presidential "coat-tails". Eleven governors' races left the split between the parties unchanged (32 Republican governors, 17 Democrats, one independent). Across the country, it was a good day for incumbents.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With a healthy economy and, of late, a government getting down to business, a reasonably contented electorate decided to keep things much as they were. Neither party can make extravagant claims for a "mandate". Both have to reckon with a political era that is neither of the right nor of the left, but one of extreme competitiveness, notably over what might be called the three "<font size=-1>G</font>s": geography, gender, and the role of government.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Take geography first. On the face of it, the electoral map looks straightforward. Mr Dole carried a swathe of loyally Republican states in the West and the South; Mr Clinton took most of the rest, including bellwether states such as Ohio. Look closer, and the picture is more complicated. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By winning Arizona, which last voted for a Democratic presidential candidate in 1948, and the huge prize of Florida, which voted for Jimmy Carter in 1976 but has been Republican ever since, Mr Clinton showed that the Republicans cannot take their traditional strongholds for granted. The president's defence of Medicare played well with retired folk in both those states. In the north-east, Mr Clinton swept 11 states that had all voted for Ronald Reagan in 1984. Much as conservative southern Democrats turned against liberal Democratic presidential candidates from the 1960s, so the social conservatism of the Republican Party's ascendant southerners now alienates the voters of the north-east. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, the "gender gap" was as wide as it has ever been. Among men, according to the Voter News Service exit polls, the contest was a tie, 44% for each of the main candidates. Among women, Mr Clinton romped home by 55% to 37%. He did so by talking engagingly about issues that women care most about, such as education and family leave. Henceforth, the competition for women's votes will intensify.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Women also tend to look more favourably than men on government activism, the third big area of competition between the parties. It is true that Mr Clinton won by running as a conservative, reforming welfare, promising to balance the budget and proclaiming the era of big government to be over. But it is also true that he won by insisting that government action can help people in their ordinary lives, in contrast to the harsh anti-government message of Republican revolutionaries. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How much action will actually happen? On a balmy election night in Little Rock, the president spoke of the need to put country ahead of party. The election, he emphasised, had shown the strength of the "vital centre" in America. Americans could achieve so much if only they could work together as one big happy family.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But any sense of togetherness will be hard to maintain. Mr Clinton's cabinet is already being shaken out, with four members--including the secretary of state, Warren Christopher, and the secretary of defence, William Perry--offering their resignations. The Democrats generally, remarkably united behind their president for this election, are likely to be a less orderly bunch from now on. For their part, the Republicans are already arguing over whether their failure to recapture the White House was due to an excess of ideology or of moderation. And the continuing Republican control of Congress guarantees yet more hearings into alleged Clintonian scandals.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps the prospect of the subpoenas hitting the fan explained the less-than-ecstatic mood of the thousands gathered for the victory celebration at the Old State House. Perhaps, too, like the rest of the country, everyone was glad it was over. Or almost everyone. Mr Clinton would, if he could, go on campaigning for ever.<br>

<p align=center>
