</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Consolation</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The Senate</b></p>
<h1>Consolation</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
THE prize for the most entertaining Senate race goes to Louisiana, and particularly to a shocking fax entitled "Convicts for Landrieu". "Louisiana's felons, convicts and the like formally endorse Mary Landrieu," it proclaimed. Her candidacy represented a "once-in-a-life-sentence opportunity" for convicts to be let out of prison early. A retired archbishop of New Orleans thought voting for Ms Landrieu, a Democrat who believes women should judge the morality of abortion for themselves, was tantamount to sin. Asked in a television debate to say something nice about this lady, all her Republican opponent could manage was, "I love New Orleans. She's from New Orleans and that's good."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In its vitriol, its ideological charge and indeed its sheer closeness, the Louisiana race combined many of the themes that dominated the 34 Senate fights around the country. The resignation of 14 senators, more than in any year since popular elections to the Senate were first held in 1914, created many hot contests, Louisiana's among them. On the eve of the election, half of the 34 races looked very close. And, although Ms Landrieu won her race (by a margin of less than 1%), Republicans came off better overall. As <i>The Economist </i>went to press, the outcome in Oregon was still in doubt. But the Republicans had won 20 of the remaining 33 seats, having held 19 before. Of the Senate's 100 seats, they will hold 54, or 55 if they win Oregon. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Across the country, it had been assumed that Senate victories would be won in the political middle. This proved true only in the South. Ms Landrieu squeaked home because she posed as a centrist, and because her opponent, Woody Jenkins, was unabashedly right-wing. (He led Louisiana's anti-abortionists; he had promised to scrap the Internal Revenue Service; and he spoke warmly of law-breaking Oliver North.) In Georgia's tight race, Max Cleland fought as a Democratic centrist, too. Despite unattractive episodes from his past (he had asked for the early release of a murderer who killed again, and had fired an employee without due process), he won because his opponent was so far to the right.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Leftish southern Democrats, in contrast, fared less well. Harvey Gantt in North Carolina and Victor Morales in Texas both failed to upset entrenched Republicans. In Alabama, Roger Bedford also lost, even though a Democrat had easily won the seat six years ago, and even though his opponent had once said he thought Ku Klux Klan members "were okay guys until I found out they smoked dope". Mr Bedford went down because he came from the party's left, having beaten a more centrist candidate in the primary.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Outside the South, Democratic centrists were in trouble. In Wyoming, Colorado and Nebraska--all open seats--the Democrats nominated moderates who sought to label their opponents as extreme. All were defeated. In Kansas, Democrats had hoped that their stockbroker-candidate, Jill Docking, could win the seat vacated by the retiring Bob Dole, especially since her views were arguably closer to Mr Dole's than those of her right-wing opponent, Sam Brownback. In New Hampshire, Democrats had big hopes for Dick Swett, a candidate more anxiously centrist even than Bill Clinton. But, though New Hampshire leaned Democrat this year (electing a Democratic governor), Mr Swett lost.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These setbacks are a disappointment for Bob Kerrey, organiser of the Democrats' Senate strategy. He went out of his way to recruit moderates, preferably wealthy ones with cash to spend on advertisements. Had the Democrats recaptured the Senate, Mr Kerrey's stock might have risen enough for him to contemplate the presidency again. As it was, Republicans fought off the Kerrey moderates by linking them to immoderate colleagues. Mr Brownback, for example, warned Kansans that a vote for his opponent was a vote for Edward Kennedy, a liberal Democrat from Massachusetts. Meanwhile old-style Democrats, such as Paul Wellstone in Minnesota and Dick Durbin in Illinois, won with little difficulty.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was a good year for incumbents. Several had been at risk, but only South Dakota's Larry Pressler, a Republican, tumbled. In Massachusetts, John Kerry won with surprising ease (see <a href="am3109.html">page</a>). In North Carolina, Jesse Helms won despite his frailty. South Carolina's Strom Thurmond, who turns 94 next month, won with a campaign stressing his experience.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In all, the Republicans won three seats previously in Democratic hands: in Alabama, Nebraska and Arkansas. Of these, Arkansas was sweetest, partly because Tim Hutchinson will be the first Republican senator from the state in more than 100 years, but more because this is the president's home turf. Before the election, there was talk that Republican-instigated investigations into Whitewater, which have already led to the imprisonment of some of Mr Clinton's old friends, would produce a backlash against the Republicans. The Hutchinson victory killed that theory.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was fortunate for the Republicans, as they gathered at their election-night party in Washington to mourn Mr Dole's defeat, that they had Congress to smile about. Above the tables of tortilla chips and broccoli, huge screens displayed the results as they came in. There were boos when Mr Clinton took one state after another, and cheers when the Republicans notched up a Senate victory. But, from the flow of data on the screen, one number may soon assume particular significance. Of the voters in Arkansas, this poll said, 56% believed that Mr Clinton had not told the truth about Whitewater. Their House and Senate majority assured, the Republicans now have ample opportunity to demand the truth from the administration.<br>

<p align=center>
