<html><head><title>Month by month</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<html><head><title>Month by month</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><p align=center>
<img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
</p></center>
<p align=center><img src="../images/eb.gif" width="360" height="22" alt="Month by month" border=0></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
</font></p></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><img src="ameb.gif" width="227" height="181" alt="Election graph"><br><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Month by month</h2>
<p><b>November 1995: </b>Explaining that he does not yet feel the "calling" for political life, Colin Powell, the most exciting prospect, declares himself a non-candidate. <br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>December:</b> A special election in the San Jose district of California gives the first indication that Democrats will aim at bogeyman Newt Gingrich, health-care-cutter and government-shutter. Bill Clinton sends American troops to Bosnia, disposing of the argument that he is a feeble commander-in-chief. <br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>January1996:</b> Mr Clinton wins the battle of the budget. In his state-of-the-union message, sounding like a Republican, Mr Clinton proclaims that the era of big government is over.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>February: </b>Pat ("Pitchfork") Buchanan wins the New Hampshire primary. Steve ("Flat Tax") Forbes spends lavishly on advertisements attacking Mr Dole, and wins in Arizona.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>March: </b>Other Republican primaries follow thick and fast. With the big money and the party grandees behind him, Mr Dole surges to victory. <br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>April: </b>Prominent Republicans start to despair in public about their nominee. He is "likely to lose badly" in November, writes Bill Kristol, a conservative pundit-editor later dubbed the "First Rat" by the Dole campaign. <br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>May: </b>Mr Dole announces that he will quit the Senate to campaign as Citizen Bob. Mr Clinton, wary of his gays-in-the-military stigma, says he supports legislation banning same-sex marriage.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>June: </b>Mr Clinton, having avoided a costly primary challenge, enjoys "air-wars" supremacy over Mr Dole, who is constrained by federal spending limits. <br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>July: </b>Ross Perot enters the race, Mr Dole enters his 74th year, and the term "soccer moms" enters the political vocabulary.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>August:</b> Mr Dole unveils his tax-cut plan, and tells the Republican convention in San Diego that he can be a "bridge" to the "better" America of his youth. Mr Clinton celebrates his 50th birthday, signs a bill reforming welfare and tells the Democratic convention in Chicago that he can be a "bridge to the 21st century". His master-strategist, Dick Morris, resigns in a sex scandal.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>September: </b>Mr Dole responds to his persistent weakness in the polls: he replaces his media team. In California, he falls off a podium. <br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>October: </b>Mr Clinton gets the better of both presidential debates. Mr Dole makes a late dash for California's 54 electoral votes, tries a desperate plea to Mr Perot to drop out, and starts to attack the ethics of the Clinton administration. <br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>November:</b> The candidates go without sleep in their final bids for victory. They fail to wake up millions of Americans, who do not bother to vote.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

<p align=center>
