<html><head><title>Meanwhile, in Athens . . . </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Meanwhile, in Athens . . . </h1>

<font size=1>BOSTON</font><p>
GLOWING under the klieg lights in Boston's magnificent old Faneuil Hall, John Forbes Kerry, the junior Democratic senator from Massachusetts, stood in front of a white marble bust of John Quincy Adams. William Floyd Weld, the Republican governor who was unsuccessfully trying to snatch Mr Kerry's job, stood in front of a bust of Daniel Webster. No one watching the two men in debate on October 28th thought Messrs Kerry and Weld quite that grand. But there was no hooting at this implicit comparison either, as one might expect if, say, Alfonse D'Amato had been held up against Alexander Hamilton.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Massachusetts Senate race has not been perfect, but it was highbrow enough for the good folk of Massachusetts--always prone to compare themselves to Athenians--to be proud of the example they set for the rest of the country. Both candidates showed experience and brains. They argued fiercely, intelligently and even (more or less) fairly. They debated a staggering eight times, often in head-to-head Lincoln-Douglas format. The outcome changed exactly nothing: Mr Kerry will return to Capitol Hill with a bit more stature, and Mr Weld to Beacon Hill with a lot less. But now the election is finally over, the state is positively soggy with nostalgia.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The race was cracklingly fierce to the last minute. In the home stretch, the <i>Boston Globe </i>revealed that Mr Kerry had once lived for nothing in a fancy Washington apartment owned by a lobbyist, and that Mr Weld's state agency for workers' compensation was shot through with corruption. On October 30th Ross Perot whizzed into Boston to bless Mr Weld's candidacy in weird terms: "If John Kerry is a veterans' advocate, I'm a Chinese aviator." On November 1st, Vice-President Al Gore stumped on Mr Kerry's behalf, and on the 3rd Mr Clinton himself--up a mere 32 points over Bob Dole in Massachusetts--rode to Mr Kerry's rescue at a joint appearance in Springfield.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the real joy of the Massachusetts race was that the candidates were not cynical. There was no doubting Mr Weld's seriousness about cutting taxes and shrinking government, or Mr Kerry's on fighting Republican excesses and improving education. The Clinton and Dole campaigns treated the electorate with contempt, and the electorate reciprocated. The Weld and Kerry campaigns treated the electorate with some respect, and the electorate repaid them.<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
