<html><head><title>A new Newt</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>A new Newt</h1>

"I'M GOING to write several books . . . the founding of the New York Zoological Society was a key moment in our history . . . you know, we could save $14 billion a year by reforming what we do on diabetes . . . " With that, Newt Gingrich bounces up from his seat on top of his roofless double-decker bus, turns his back to the cold wind, and surveys the campaign cavalcade that is following him. Each vehicle is filled with clean-cut supporters decked out in Newt shirts, dedicated to boosting the Republican vote in Mr Gingrich's Georgia district. Mr Gingrich seems thrilled. "Isn't this great?" he exclaims. "Five buses!"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This was the Newt Gingrich on display in the last days of the campaign, in his home district outside Atlanta. It is also the Newt Gingrich whom Americans are soon going to meet, a very different figure from the grim ogre vilified by Democrats since the summer. Having defied predictions that his Republican troops would lose control of the House, Mr Gingrich has every reason to bubble with good cheer. He can now look forward to at least another two years as speaker of the House-- and probably to more than that, since the president's party tends to lose seats in mid-term elections. Bob Dole's retirement makes him the Republicans' pre-eminent leader, as well as their most dynamic one. "I think Newt is in the early-middle phase of his career as a national leader," says one of the speaker's henchmen.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The old Newt--the one attacked in 75,000 Democratic campaign ads--wanted to impose radical budget cuts on a country unprepared for such stern measures. This backfired, so the new Newt on the double-decker bus mixes big ideas with tactical humility. He acknowledges the danger of pushing legislation without building public support first. He even sees the advantage in not pushing anything at all, and leaving the risks of leadership to others. When Mr Clinton proposed an ambitious solution to the inadequacies of American health care, he was butchered for his pains; when Mr Gingrich promoted necessary budgetary reform, he was similarly demonised. If you lead you bleed, is the conclusion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Old Newt (gleefully caricatured by Democrats these past months) was prepared to shut down the government to get his way. New Newt is a magician of compromise and coalition-building. His aides now boast that, rather than resist Democratic calls for a higher minimum wage earlier this year, Mr Gingrich brilliantly caved in, persuading fellow Republicans that so popular a measure could not be buried. He even went so far as to allow Phil English, a Republican from a Democratic-leaning district in Pennsylvania, to sponsor the minimum-wage bill. Mr English duly stressed this feat in his re-election campaign. His victory this week was a triumph of New-Newt tactics. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Old Newt demanded nothing less than revolutionary cuts in government. New Newt is adept at settling for small reforms and making the most of them. On the stump this autumn, Mr Gingrich liked to wave an ice-bucket before his audiences and regale them with the news that, by eliminating free ice deliveries to congressmen, he saved taxpayers the princely sum of $500,000 a year. Never mind that the speaker's plans to control the vast cost of retired Americans' health benefits crashed and burned. Mr Gingrich has privatised a congressional shoeshine stand, a post office and a beauty parlour.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is a rich irony in this. In his celebration of micro-policies, as in his newly pragmatic pose, Mr Gingrich looks uncannily like Mr Clinton, his fellow-victor of the week. This has not been lost on anti-government purists, who hiss with contempt for the speaker these days, as David Brooks has pointed out in the <i>Weekly Standard</i>. "He's randomly conservative," says one Republican. "He has no conservative instincts," says another. Old Newt was the hero of such folk. New Newt is accused of parroting fuzzy lines fed to him by focus groups.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet this seeming Gingrich-Clinton equivalence masks a big difference. Over the past two years, Mr Clinton has essentially conceded ideological victory to the Republicans, promising that the era of big government is over, ending guaranteed welfare payments and embracing the Republican drive to balance the budget. Mr Gingrich, in contrast, has conceded that his style was too abrupt, but his ideas are winning. He can afford to become a pragmatic compromiser now, because his grand ideological battles have mostly been won. "In just two years, Newt Gingrich has accomplished more than most leaders do in a lifetime," proclaim the leaflets in the speaker's campaign headquarters. The hyperbole is hard to digest, yet there is something to be said for the thought.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At some point in the next two years, Mr Clinton will probably appoint a commission to curb the cost of retired people's health care, even though the Democrats lashed Mr Gingrich for saying that this was necessary. The commission will no doubt look at ways to cut costs without compromising the quality of service to old folk, and so Mr Gingrich's excited talk about diabetes on the campaign bus (you can save money and improve health by moving to preventive care) may well turn into solid policy. Equally, the next two years are likely to see a debate about encouraging volunteers to work as a complement to the bureaucratic welfare state. Mr Gingrich's recalling of the volunteer heroism of America's past (as in the founding of the Zoological Society in New York) will doubtless become fashionable. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of which points to the difficulty in interpreting this week's elections. Mr Clinton won by running against Gingrichite cuts in government, or at least a cartoon version of them. On the other hand, Mr Clinton stole many of Mr Gingrich's ideas; and Mr Gingrich survived a congressional election that was, to a large extent, a referendum on his speakership. The lessons of this mixed verdict will be debated for years. Among the many books that will offer an infallible interpretation, count on at least one from Mr Gingrich.<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
