<html><head><title>Goh slow</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Singapore</b></p>
<h1>Goh slow</h1>

JUST as races are not always to the swift, nor battles to the strong, so elections are not always to ruling parties. But in Singapore, that is certainly the way to bet. The People's Action Party is assured of a big victory in the general election that has to be held by next April. Even the <font size=-1>PAP</font>, however, is subject to the ravages of time and chance, which Goh Chok Tong, the prime minister, is doing his best to mitigate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the approach to an election, incumbents like their voters to be basking in the glow of rosy economic statistics. Unfortunately for Mr Goh, his government had on November 5th to reveal figures which showed that in the third quarter of this year, <font size=-1>GDP</font> was only 3.2% higher than in the same period in 1995--the lowest quarterly increase for ten years (see <a href="as1.gif">chart</a>). The growth forecast for the year as a whole was cut for the third time, to 6%.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is hardly the stuff of recession as commonly understood (although, compared with the immediately preceding period rather than with last year, the economy had contracted for the second successive quarter, meeting the technical definition of the term used in America). Singaporean officials also point out, rightly, that the problems facing the economy are cyclical rather than fundamental. It has been hit by a regional slowdown and, in particular, by a global slump in sales and prices of some electronics products (see <a href="wb8439.html">page</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the less than usually hectic growth rate may be one reason why Mr Goh has said that this parliament will serve out its full term, until January 5th. Like British prime ministers, he has the tactical advantage of being able to choose the election date and, unusually for Singapore, has opted to wait almost as long as he can.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if the electorate does react badly to a hint of harder times, recent changes to the election laws will make it more difficult for the small opposition to increase its representation in parliament from the four out of 81 seats it currently holds. Last month Parliament passed bills that would allow an increase in the number of candidates elected in each "group representation constituency" or <font size=-1>GRC</font>. At present, there are 15 <font size=-1>GRC</font>s, each of which elects four members of Parliament from a single party slate. The other 21 come from single-member constituencies. Now the size of a <font size=-1>GRC</font> slate can be up to six candidates.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>GRC</font>s were introduced in 1988, to ensure that Singapore's minority races were represented in parliament, despite a public-housing policy that prevents ethnic enclaves from forming. Each party must field a candidate from a minority group, such as ethnic Indians or Malays, on its slate. However, because it has difficulty in finding enough credible candidates, the opposition has always seen the <font size=-1>GRC</font> system as evidence of the <font size=-1>PAP</font>'s determination to entrench its power. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The opposition has other troubles, too. Chee Soon Juan, leader of the Singapore Democratic Party, and one of the government's most prominent critics, got some figures wrong in a debate in August over health care. Last month, as a consequence, he was grilled for seven hours by parliament's privileges committee, and faces the threat of criminal charges and jail. The local pro-government newspaper, the <i>Straits Times</i>, reported that Mr Chee's evidence had been "confused" and "careless". An editorial on the parlous state of the opposition lamented that "Singapore deserves better". But given the fate of Dr Chee, it is hardly surprising if there are few volunteers to stand against the <font size=-1>PAP</font>.<br>

