<html><head><title>Out of control</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Public spending</b></p>
<h1>Out of control</h1>

TO READ November 6th's newspapers, you would think that the previous day's cabinet had decided to spend its way out of the government's political difficulties. Ministers had agreed, they reported, to spend more next year on health (&#163;600m on top of &#163;34.2 billion); more on education (a "generous settlement"); more on police and prisons (with Michael Howard, the home secretary, "delighted"); and more on defence. Even Scotland and Wales seem to have fought off Treasury efforts to scrap the formulas which give them an anomalously big share of public spending.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;William Waldegrave, the chief secretary to the Treasury, who supervised this process, maintained a dignified silence. But he was far from pleased by the reports. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Five of the six "wise men", the Treasury's outside advisers, recommended on October 31st that Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, should not cut taxes in his November 26th budget. He will cut them all the same. It would therefore have suited the Treasury to have appeared tough on spending. Otherwise, markets may interpret the tax cuts as inflation-provoking election bribes, adding to the pressure for higher interest rates. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, the collective interests of the cabinet as a whole took second place to the departmental interests of its individual members. Out of control in their eagerness to proclaim victory in the spending round, they have undermined the Chancellor's efforts to seem prudent.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, the settlement represents an honourable draw between spenders and controllers. Inflation has turned out rather lower than was expected at the time of the 1995 budget. To hold state spending next year to the real level planned then, Mr Waldegrave would have had to cut cash spending plans by some &#163;3.5 billion. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that could only have been achieved at the cost of disagreeable political consequences--for example, rising hospital waiting lists. In the event, Mr Clarke, whose political antennae are second to none, seems to have settled for around half that amount. Public spending next year will be higher in real terms than this year. But according to Chris Giles, of the independent Institute for Fiscal Studies, the increase will only be around 0.3%. Compared with the 1991 Budget, when Norman Lamont planned a real spending rise of 4%, Mr Clarke's pre-election bribery so far is small beer.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
