<html><head><title>Big bad Rupert</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Broadcasting</b></p>
<h1>Big bad Rupert</h1>

A KIND of hysteria has gripped some of the British press at the sight of <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, that notorious but successful satellite-television broadcaster, preparing to order the first set-top boxes to receive and decode digital signals. <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> is 40% owned by Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Within a few years the whole of British broadcasting will be under his control," yelped the <i>Independent</i>. Mr Murdoch is not quite that close to a monopoly--whatever happens to the airwaves, cable television will still provide competition--but this is a crucial time for other broadcasters.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Digital television requires special receiving equipment. Signals sent from a satellite, through cable or over the air all require different devices, and most of the channels will be encrypted, so that they can be watched only by subscribers. Because <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> seems certain to be ready to launch digital satellite television in Britain before anybody else, rival broadcasters worry that people will buy its set-top-box decoders. When their own channels are launched, people will not want to buy a second set-top box.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This prospect especially alarms the <font size=-1>BBC</font>, which cannot afford to underwrite its own set-top boxes. Even so, it still hopes to produce a package of digital subscription channels. The public broadcaster has been lobbying furiously for guaranteed access to the <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> decoder box.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, for its part, grumbles that the <font size=-1>BBC</font> wants a free ride. It is afraid of the cable industry, which is increasing its share of the market in areas where the two compete head-on, and is also likely to go digital next year. For now, <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>'s main problem is to find partners to help it subsidise the set-top boxes, which will otherwise cost viewers an unattractive &#163;500 or so apiece. It has been talking to <font size=-1>BT</font> and Barclays Bank about the possibility of sharing the bill, in exchange for using the boxes for home shopping and banking. But a deal with <font size=-1>BT</font>, the richest potential partner, will have to get past Oftel, the telephone industry's regulator. Last month Oftel stopped a joint promotion between <font size=-1>BT</font> and <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, offering cheap calls to <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> subscribers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government, harried on one side by the <font size=-1>BBC</font> and on the other by <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, has failed to satisfy either. A new set of regulations, about to be published, will oblige anybody offering a set-top-box gateway to allow access to other broadcasters on fair, reasonable and non-discriminatory terms. The <font size=-1>BBC</font> fears that <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> is so far ahead that these regulations will mean nothing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is probably too bleak. Oftel will police the rules, which is appropriate, for the problem is much the same as the interconnection arguments that arise endlessly in the telephone network, when one telephone company wants to send calls across a rival company's network. There, the argument is usually not about access, but about price.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile, the bones of a possible compromise are emerging. <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> has decided that its set-top boxes should have a plug to allow the attachment of an inexpensive receiver for digital terrestrial television. Because digital terrestrial television will be available in many more homes than satellite services, it is likely to have a much bigger market than satellite alone would provide. In exchange for a terrestrial slot on good terms, <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> might just consider a common interface, to allow its set-top boxes to be used by other broadcasters. This would encourage customers to buy the boxes and could help <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> defray the costs and win more viewers. Would that be a victory for the <font size=-1>BBC</font>? As the telephone business proves, having access to a rival's network is no guarantee of a bigger market.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?847501200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7569.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT09-B16-103</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001031-B029-192</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/09-11-96/br7569.html 199.173.162.110 19970215022716 text/html 4938
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 02:23:12 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Nov-96 17:45:18 GMT
Content-length: 4751
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Big brother</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Government</b></p>
<h1>Big brother</h1>

FREQUENT visitors to America can by-pass immigration queues at <font size=-1>JFK</font> airport in New York by using a smart card and a machine-read handprint. In Australia, job-seekers can call up vacancies on touch screens at 320 Job Centres. About 7m Spaniards in Andalucia can access their own state-benefit records, their privacy protected by an electronic check of their finger prints. And Britain?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Belatedly, it is catching up. On November 6th Roger Freeman, the public-services minister, published a consultative green paper--on <font size=-1>CD</font>-<font size=-1>ROM</font>, naturally--on the electronic delivery of state services. Three pilot schemes to pave the way to one-stop electronic access to government data were launched, including terminals at a branch of the NatWest bank in London. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Making it easier to extract information from government will be phase one. Phase two will allow proper two-way communication. People will be able to get into the system using home personal computers, digital television or terminals in public places such as libraries. The provision of access might even be contracted out to building societies and banks which already have a network to serve their own customers. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In time, people will be able to submit their income-tax returns electronically. Biometric identification (for example, a nifty device that recognises people by studying their iris) may take the place of a written signature on the return.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government claims that services will be available where you want them, when you want them. Responses will often be instant. But those who want to go on using paper and stamps will be able to do so.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The programme could cost an average of &#163;200m a year over ten years, but savings will be higher. Moreover, the cash to pay for it will come from the private sector. Before private firms get paid for what they have installed, they will have to make it work. Deals will be structured so that the more the public uses the system, the higher the return to providers, so they will have an incentive to make their systems user-friendly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This being Britain, there are plenty of sceptics. Civil-service trade unions worry that the new technology will cost clerical jobs. Some civil servants are concerned that too much is being handed over to private firms, which may fail to respond quickly and sensitively to the demands of democratic politicians. Civil libertarians conjure up nightmare scenarios whereby police, tax and benefit data are linked up, giving bureaucrats total knowledge of every citizen. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Peter Lilley, the social-security secretary, is about to lend credibility to this charge. He wants to change the law so that he can get access to tax records to check claims for benefits. This will be tough on fraud but also tough on law-abiding people who don't want any old <i>apparatchik </i>crawling over their tax affairs.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The green paper tries to soothe these fears. It suggests that a single database of names and addresses held by government would be useful, so people who move house would have to send the state only one change-of-address card. But otherwise, it floats proposals for data-sharing only cautiously. Each department will be allowed to use information only for the intended purpose. Data-protection safeguards will not be changed. Big brother? A friendly one, maybe, but keep watching.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
