<DOCNO>WT09-B16-107</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001031-B029-307</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/09-11-96/wb8436.html 199.173.162.110 19970215022812 text/html 10183
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 02:24:05 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Nov-96 18:31:03 GMT
Content-length: 9996
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>A marriage of convenience</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>A marriage of convenience</h1>

<font size=1>LONDON AND NEW YORK</font><p>
<p><b>BT's takeover of MCI is the biggest transatlantic deal ever, but the merger is still surprisingly light on substance</b></p><br>
AS WEDDINGS go, it lacked romance. The bride and groom had been living together for years, and already had a child. They got along pretty well, but he had been worried that her head might be turned by another man. Better, he reckoned, to wed her now and avoid the prospect of fighting for her heart later. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That, with a little lacy licence, is the reality behind the biggest transatlantic merger in history, which was announced on November 3rd: the $21 billion takeover of <font size=-1>MCI</font>, an American telecoms firm, by Britain's <font size=-1>BT</font> (See <a href="wb1.gif">table</a>). The wedding invitations--full of breathless talk of global logic and synergy--were echoed by starstruck analysts, who hailed the deal as a harbinger of a coming revolution in the global telecoms industry. But a closer look reveals a largely defensive move that, at least internally, will mean few real changes at all.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is not to say that the deal is a mistake; indeed, it may have been unavoidable. <font size=-1>BT</font> and <font size=-1>MCI</font> have been linked since 1993, when the British ex-monopoly bought 20% of the nimble long-distance carrier. Together, the two set up Concert, a joint venture to provide global telecoms services for multinational firms. Arguably, because they had already cemented their link with cash, their partnership was more cohesive than a loose web of global alliances offered by <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, a big American rival.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>BT</font>'s worry was that <font size=-1>MCI</font> might be bought by another firm. The American company carries one-fifth of the country's long-distance calls and two-fifths of its overseas calls. But after its early success in grabbing market share from <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, it has been struggling. It would have been a tempting target for one of the regional "Baby Bells", spun off when the original <font size=-1>AT&T</font> was broken up in 1984. They expect to be allowed into the long-distance market soon, under the terms of the Telecommunications Act passed earlier this year. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>BT</font>'s 20% stake entitled it to match any offer for <font size=-1>MCI</font>. But, with several potential suitors, some even bigger than <font size=-1>BT</font>, it seemed safer to slip the ring on <font size=-1>MCI</font>'s finger now, even if doing so meant paying a 44% premium over its current share value. Sealing the deal should take another year or so, a delay due mainly to the need for the union to be blessed by America's regulators. With some tweaking, they are likely to clear it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the past, <font size=-1>MCI</font> has been promiscuous in its search of a strategy, flitting from liaison to liaison. In 1994 it invested $1.3 billion in Nextel Communications, a wireless-telecoms company--a deal that was subsequently broken off. Then it took a stake in Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation, an alliance that is now looking cool. It has also formed alliances with everyone from Microsoft down.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now both <font size=-1>BT</font> and <font size=-1>MCI</font> claim that, simply by combining their operations--the new company, like the existing global partnership, will be called Concert--they will increase their annual pre-tax profit by nearly $850m by the fifth year after the merger. Set against a combined pre-tax profit of nearly $6 billion today, that is hardly a reason to merge. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bigger gains might come from using <font size=-1>BT</font>'s financial muscle and expertise learnt in Britain's local market to launch an assault on America's $100-billion-a-year local telephone market. Gross profit margins on long-distance calls in the United States are well over 40%; profits on international calls are even higher. But at present each long-distance call starts and finishes in a Baby Bell's local territory--and for that privilege long-distance carriers such as <font size=-1>MCI</font> pay the Bells 45 cents out of every dollar of long-distance revenues.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One way <font size=-1>MCI</font> could have sidestepped this tariff would have been to hook up with a Baby Bell, which is why it had in recent months been holding exploratory talks with two previously merged pairs--Bell Atlantic and Nynex, and <font size=-1>SBC</font> Communications and Pacific Telesis--as well as <font size=-1>GTE</font>. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It has also been trying to crack the local market itself with a venture called <font size=-1>MCI</font> Metro, which is building networks to connect corporate clients in 34 American cities. This has had limited success. By the end of this year <font size=-1>MCI</font> will have spent $1 billion on such networks; yet in the third quarter of the year, <font size=-1>MCI</font> Metro generated a paltry $45m in revenues, out of <font size=-1>MCI</font>'s total quarterly revenues of $4.7 billion. And most of its sales were to <font size=-1>MCI</font>'s other businesses.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Making money in the local market will grow harder as competition cuts prices. Many analysts expect local-call revenues to grow only slowly during the next few years. Worse, the new rules for opening local telephone markets are delayed in the courts. Until <font size=-1>MCI</font> is sure what those rules will be-- and it may be another year before they are clear--it cannot decide whether it is wiser to buy or lease network capacity from the incumbent Bells, or to build more of its own network, as it has done so far. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That leaves the global strategy. The theory behind the original Concert joint venture was that multinational clients could avoid having to deal with lots of different carriers. <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s WorldPartners and the GlobalOne trio of Deutsche Telekom, France T&eacute;l&eacute;com and America's Sprint offer something similar (see <a href="wb8442.html">page</a>). Of the three, Concert has been the most successful, winning more than $1.5 billion-worth of contracts and claiming more than 3,000 corporate customers. But its revenues are tiny--in its most recent quarter, <font size=-1>MCI</font> reported $160m in overall sales for the venture--and it is unprofitable. <br>
</p><p><b><b>Concertina</b></b><br>
It is hard to see what Concert gains from a merger. <font size=-1>BT</font> and <font size=-1>MCI</font> have already integrated their global networks more successfully than their competitors have. And <font size=-1>MCI</font>'s marketing skills have already been applied to the venture. <font size=-1>BT</font>'s chief executive, Sir Peter Bonfield, suggests that gains will mostly be made by doing more of the same: merging the sales and marketing forces a bit further, and sharing more technology. In fact, an even bigger benefit may come from winning the confidence of customers, who tend to view loose global alliances with suspicion because they are prone to acrimonious collapse.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best thing that could now happen to the deal would be for a regional Bell to buy into it. Such an addition would, in a single move, bring more local customers than <font size=-1>MCI</font> could hope to assemble by itself in a decade. The Nynex and Bell Atlantic duo seems the best match--they have the most customers making calls across the Atlantic--but <font size=-1>GTE</font> would be available to do a deal earlier. It is the only regional giant already allowed into the long-distance market.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"<font size=-1>BT</font> has reinforced its western front," says Joseph Kraemer, a telecoms analyst with <font size=-1>A.T.</font> Kearney, a consultancy. From there, Asia and Europe beckon. Continental Europe's biggest telecoms markets will open in 1998, and Sir Peter says that <font size=-1>BT</font> will bid for licences where it can. It already has joint ventures in a number of other big European countries, notably France and Germany. Asia is trickier. Had <font size=-1>BT</font> been able to buy Cable & Wireless, as it had hoped earlier this year, it would have won Hong Kong Telecom to boot--and a chance to break into the Chinese market.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead, Concert is now hoping for some arrangement with Japan's <font size=-1>NTT</font>, with which <font size=-1>BT</font> already has long-standing links. <font size=-1>BT</font>'s bosses said this week that a deal would have to wait until next year at the earliest, when Japan's regulators are expected to rule on the company's own future. Transforming a transatlantic tryst into a global <i>m&eacute;nage &agrave; trois</i> will not be easy.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?847501200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
