<html><head><title>Marriage guidance for would-be brides</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Marriage guidance for would-be brides</h1>

THREE alliances offer global telecoms services. Concert, progeny of the liaison between <font size=-1>BT</font> and <font size=-1>MCI</font>, is one; the others are WorldPartners, led by <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, and GlobalOne, combining Deutsche Telekom, France T&eacute;l&eacute;com, and America's Sprint. Both the American carriers may sometimes wish that they had found a beau with such a liberal upbringing as <font size=-1>BT</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All three alliances are oddities. They offer the largest customers of the big telephone companies that own them a one-stop shop for telephone services and rates on international calls that sometimes undercut those charged by local monopolies. Often, local laws allow such discounting providing the ventures limit their reach to big companies.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a relatively new business, but one that is growing quickly--together the three global alliances claim about $3.3 billion in contracts. Yet their ultimate ambitions lie far beyond catering for rich corporate clients. Eventually, they hope to use their global networks to destroy the telecoms rules and rate conventions that have kept standard international calls so expensive for so long.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most such calls are charged according to rates set by each country, in most cases by a monopoly national carrier, as part of a process called "settlement". These rates are usually much higher than the firms' true costs and vary wildly: a call from France to the United States costs twice as much as one in the opposite direction. Because the three main global networks send calls along their own wires, and do not have to hand them off to another carrier at either end, they are able to bypass the settlement system altogether. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today, these networks carry only a small percentage of global telecoms traffic. But as national markets start to open over the next decade, they hope to carry ordinary calls from individuals the same way. In a report to be published later this month, Analysys, a British consultancy, predicts that this could lead to the erosion and eventual collapse of the cosy settlement system. As more traffic bypasses it through global networks, call-back services, and routing through telecoms hubs in low-cost countries, the settlement rates will be eroded.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This will mean not just cheaper calls for all. Most telephone companies will find international business suddenly becomes a lot less profitable. Concert's two rivals consist mainly of telephone companies from countries where markets are still closed--France T&eacute;l&eacute;com and Deutsche Telekom for GlobalOne; 16 companies covering 31 countries for WorldPartners. These companies may be reluctant to cut their prices too fiercely, lest they cannibalise their owners' profits. As a result, they may be least aggressive in the very markets where they have the greatest technical advantages--those of their parents. This weakness is something that Concert, made up of two firms from competitive markets, is sure to exploit.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
