<html><head><title>What a choice</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>What a choice</h1>


THE presidential election campaign has been a strange affair, and not just because it has afflicted voters and onlookers alike with many months of torture-by-tedium. It has been strange because the two candidates have spent so much of the time wearing each other's clothes. Bill Clinton, a man who normally cannot let a bandwagon pass without leaping on to it, has cast himself as the solid, reliable, unflinching incumbent, looking to the future rather than to the past, of course, but doing so sober of mien and straight of spine. Meanwhile, Bob Dole, who for 36 years in Congress stood for prudence and for the non-existence of fairies, has run as a tax-cutting radical, declaring (against all available evidence) that the economy is doing miserably and that he has a magic formula to make everyone richer. Since both these poses test credulity to the limit, it is no surprise that many voters snoozed off as the contest went on.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, on November 5th a choice must be made. Or must it? The fact that the opinion polls suggest that Bill Clinton will win easily, and perhaps even by a landslide, may be enough to persuade even more people not to bother to vote than is usual in America, or at least to focus their attention instead on the battle between Democrats and Republicans for control of Congress. That likelihood even makes it tempting for <i>The Economist</i> to suspend its four-yearly habit of endorsing a candidate for the presidency, for making a choice feels less poignant when the outcome seems so clear.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet such apathy would be wrong for us, and it would be wrong for the voter. Although the congressional vote is the more exciting one, because it is more finely balanced, many of the important issues concern both these races. Both races will help determine--in Congress by the outcome, for the presidency if only by the size of Bill Clinton's victory-- whether the broadly Republican ideas of trimmer government and fiscal austerity that have held sway during the past two years will continue to do so during the coming four. And choosing a president ought never to be a casual, shoulder-shrugging affair: getting the right man to lead the world's superpower may be a trying business, but it is also vital.<b><p>A flawed challenger</b><br>
That point holds true even when the men on offer are far from appealing. In the spring of this year Bob Dole looked the sounder of the two even if not the likeliest winner in November. The tragedy of his inept campaign is that he has looked less sound as each week has passed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reputation that made him the Republicans' senior figure, and clear front-runner throughout 1995 for that party's nomination, was that he stood for what nostalgics see as old-fashioned values and what others see as merely high standards. In Congress, most recently as Senate majority leader, he had been a deal-maker; after all, that was his job. But he stood up for his beliefs, supporting free trade against many of his own party's protectionists and attacking Ronald Reagan's supply-side tax cuts in the early 1980s. His speeches rambled, his wit was sometimes mean, his campaigning dire. But what marked him out was character. Whereas most politicians look good on the surface but rather shabbier beneath, Bob Dole was an exception: apparently too honest to try hard to look good, but rather admirable once you got to know him.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such a character would be well suited for the presidency, if combined with a steely determination in foreign affairs and a willingness to appoint (and listen to) top-notch advisers. Mr Dole's terrible error this year has been to drop that character and try another one: at best, that of the tax-cutting radical; at worst, that of a man willing to discard his principles to get himself elected. His economic plan contains many good ideas, including tax reform and reductions in federal regulation. But its biggest supposed vote-winner, a 15% cut in personal income tax, would be a disaster. Like the Reagan cuts that Mr Dole opposed, it would widen the budget deficit; with unemployment low and the economy growing strongly, it would stoke up inflation. With that plan, and that character change, he made himself an unappealing choice.<b><p>
A flawed incumbent</b><br>
Until, that is, you compare him with the alternative. Mr Dole has thrown his principles away for four months. Bill Clinton has been doing that for four years. That may be a little unfair. But not much, for the difficulty with Mr Clinton is that he changes so often that it is hard to know what you are supporting, or opposing. In 1992, <i>The Economist</i> endorsed this relatively unknown but energetic governor, arguing that President Bush had run out of steam. Four years of hindsight later, that choice looks like a mistake.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under Second-Term Bush the economy would have been just as healthy as under Mr Clinton, and Alan Greenspan would have done exactly the job at the Federal Reserve that he has anyway been doing. There would have been no distracting fiasco over health-care reform, and the task of reforming welfare might (thanks more to Congress than Mr Bush) have begun sooner. Even more important, there would have been some constancy in foreign policy, built on the foundation of the Gulf war victory. Errors would doubtless have been made. But America and the world would have been spared Mr Clinton's first two years of foreign policy made on the hoof; generally getting it right in the end, but taking several wrong turns along the way.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton has not been a bad president; just a mediocre one. He may have been helped by the fact that he has not had to deal with any huge international crises (he nearly helped to cause one, over China and Taiwan), though he would argue that this has hindered him, by not allowing him to show his mettle. His great achievement was the North American Free-Trade Agreement, a deal begun by Mr Bush but in the end well marketed by President Clinton. His worst error came also on trade, however: taking Japan, supposedly one of America's closest allies, to the brink of a trade war over cars.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He has, to be sure, learned from his mistakes. His foreign-policy touch has grown sharper. Brought to his knees by the 1994 mid-term congressional elections, he recast himself as a moderate Republican, keen to balance the budget by 2002, to declare that the "era of big government was over" and, at last, to begin reforming welfare. It is on that ticket that he has run this year, making many small pledges but no new big ones. If he sticks to that position, his second term might not be at all bad. Such a president would be a good balance to a Republican Congress, if (as is to be hoped) that party retains its control of it. Many of the ideas that such a Congress would stand for, including tax reform and further reform of the government safety net, are good ones; President Clinton could usefully restrain the Republicans' social-policy extremists. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But will he stick to that position? That is the question that will always surround him. If he does, this newspaper will congratulate him in 2000 when he retires. But the risk is that he will not. He will face financial constraints imposed by the bond markets, but none of the constraints of re-election. He may be beset by ethical problems, whether over campaign finance or Whitewater indictments, even conceivably of his wife. These might lead him in all sorts of new directions, especially if he has been re-elected on a landslide, and if the Democrats were to regain control of one or both of the houses of Congress. No one can be sure what he would do in such circumstances. And that is why <i>The Economist</i> feels unable to endorse him. We would not know what we were backing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Would we know with Bob Dole? It is hard to be sure. We choose him on the assumption that the real Bob Dole is the one who spent three decades on Capitol Hill, not this year's dubious character; that he would be more prudent than his economic plan implies. That is an awkward basis for an endorsement. But the choice is a lousy one.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846896400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="sf0783.html">Next article</a>
</p>
