<html><head><title>Election Billboard</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><p align=center>
<img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
</p></center><p align=center><img src="../images/eb.gif" width="360" height="22" alt="Election Billboard" border=0></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
</font></p></center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center>
<img src="ameb.gif" width="222" height="153" alt="Election graph"><br><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Trends of the week</h2><p><b>Word: </b>"Outrage". Bob Dole wonders why Americans don't feel more of it about Clintonian ethics. Ross Perot challenges Bill Clinton to a one-hour debate on the subject, and sees his poll-ratings rise as he attacks the Asian-money scandals.<br><br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>Quote:</b> Mr Dole in Texas: "I wonder what people are thinking about, or if people are thinking at all . . . Wake up America, you're about to do yourself an injustice if you vote for Bill Clinton."<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>T-shirt: </b>"Soccer Moms for Dole/Kemp", worn at a Dole rally in Denver. As the shirts are distributed, a little boy asks, "What are soccer moms, Daddy?"<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>Sign: </b>At Mr Dole's rally in Anaheim, California: "Annoy the Media. Vote Dole."<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>Beast: </b>Mr Dole singles out the <i>New York Times </i>as the most notable example of the supposedly hostile liberal media.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>Endorsements: </b>The <i>New York Times </i> backs Mr Clinton. More surprisingly, Mr Perot says he thinks "every American" would pick Mr Dole over Mr Clinton if that were the only choice (thanks to Mr Perot, it isn't). And singer Bruce Springsteen calls California's anti-affirmative-action Proposition 209 a bad idea (unlike Mr Dole, who calls racial quotas a "blind alley in the search for equal justice").<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>

<b>Bimbo eruption:</b> Many expected one, but few expected it to involve Mr Dole rather than Mr Clinton. From 1968, nearly four years before the end of his first marriage, Mr Dole had a long-term relationship with a Washington woman, according to the tabloid <i>National Enquirer</i>. The <i>Washington Post </i>had previously confirmed the story, but deemed it unfit to print.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>Sauve qui peut: </b>The Republican Party launches a $6m ad blitz calling on voters to support Republican House candidates to avoid giving Democratic interests a "blank cheque". Implicit message: Mr Clinton is going to win, so at least try to keep a Republican Congress.<br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>Omen: </b>The New York Yankees win baseball's World Series. In the past, this has heralded a Republican presidential win. <br>
<p align=center><center>***</center></p>
<b>Counter-omen: </b>"The presidential candidate with the greatest number of royal genes has always been the victor since George Washington," says Harold Brooks-Baker of Burke's Peerage. Both Messrs Clinton and Dole can trace their ancestry to King Henry III; Mr Clinton can also trace his directly to Simon de Montfort and Robert I of France. This makes his blood marginally bluer. However, says Mr Brooks-Baker, "President Clinton's descent from Henry III is illegitimate." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<br>

