<html><head><title>A long day's journey</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The campaign</b></p>
<h1>A long day's journey</h1>

<font size=1>UNIVERSITY CITY, MISSOURI, AND DENVER, COLORADO</font><p>
YOU do not need to have spent months on the campaign trail to get a pretty good sense of the way things have gone. Just a day will do. Take last Monday, October 28th, eight days before the election.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bill Clinton was in University City, Missouri, where his own polls tell him he is some 12 points ahead. Bob Dole was in Anaheim, California, where he trails by up to 20 points. In front of Mr Dole was a podium with the word "Trust"; behind him and in every camera shot, thanks to amazing stage-management, stood the eccentric congressman, Bob Dornan, who makes Newt Gingrich look like a moderate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Having prolonged the visit to California, the Dole camp needed to decide where to travel next. The first plan--an overnight stop in Denver on Monday, then on to Ohio before returning to Washington--was abandoned. Maybe Mr Dole would go to Denver on Tuesday, then on to Louisiana. Or maybe not. Throughout Monday, planners waited for the candidate to "sign off" on a schedule; but on Monday evening, with time running out to organise the next day's events, staff were still unsure where their candidate would be going.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was a telling illustration of a campaign plagued by indecision. Mr Dole had lurched from one tactic to another, from economics to ethics, from optimism to anger. Towards the end, he had turned his anger against the "liberal" media (always a bad sign) and against the supposedly sleepy electorate (even worse). He had sent his campaign manager on a bizarre and ultimately humiliating mission to try to persuade Ross Perot to drop out of the race. Now, with barely a week to go, he had apparently lost all sense of direction.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Back in Missouri, Mr Clinton was, as usual, basking in bright sunlight and-- voice slightly hoarse, body reaching towards the crowd, hands resting intimately on the front of the podium--showing off to the "Show-Me" state the latest piece of good economic news. The budget deficit for 1996, the president revealed, was a smaller-than-forecast $107 billion, 63% lower than when he took office. In the distance, a few demonstrators were shouting and holding signs such as "Cattle Futures" and "Paula Jones". But Mr Clinton carried on constructing his metaphorical bridge to the 21st century, before departing to squeeze in stops in Minneapolis and Chicago.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even the mishaps at Clinton events play to his advantage. The president was supposed to be joined at the rally by the best-known local politician, Dick Gephardt, the House minority leader who hopes to replace Mr Gingrich as speaker if the Democrats recapture Congress. But Mr Gephardt missed his flight from Washington. Republicans were thus deprived of perfect images to illustrate their end-of-campaign warnings of a Clinton-Gephardt nightmare (that is, a return to unchecked Democratic power).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the end, Mr Dole opted for a quick stop in Denver on Tuesday before returning to Washington. His campaign cobbled together an event at the Colorado Convention Centre, inviting geologists in town for their annual meeting in an effort to boost turnout. A few geologists turned up, despite the fact that Mr Dole was competing with sessions such as "The Godzilla Syndrome: scientific inaccuracies of pre-historic animals in the movies." Uncharacteristically, it was an animated evening in a packed hall, but Mr Dole was clearly desperate to get back to Washington. Perhaps he should have headed for University City, too. There, in a restaurant called Blueberry Hill, he would have seen Chuck Berry's guitar on display. A famous Berry refrain would make an apt theme for the Dole campaign: "No Particular Place To Go."<br>

<p align=center>
