<html><head><title>China's grassroots democracy</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>China's grassroots democracy</h1>

<font size=1>BEIJING</font><p>
<p><b>Is political change taking root in the Chinese countryside?</b></p><br>
THE crushing of the democracy movement in 1989 seemed to freeze China's political development. Seven years on, repression continues. This week Wang Dan, a leading dissident, was sentenced to 11 years in prison, for "plotting to overthrow the government". But, behind this depressing picture, some observers claim to see signs of incipient political liberalisation in China. One minor sign of this is said to be the occasional assertiveness of the National People's Congress, China's parliament (see <a href="as4425.html">page</a>). But the most important development is an experiment with democracy now under way in the Chinese countryside. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The advent of village democracy in China certainly sounds impressive. There are around 900,000 villages in China, housing perhaps three-quarters of the country's 1.3 billion people. Since 1988, over 80% of these villages have elected, through universal suffrage and secret ballots, their own chiefs and village committees, who serve for terms of three years. By next year, 95% of villages will have held elections-- some will be staging their third election in a row. Although many of the village heads who are elected are Communist Party members, the majority are not. For China as a whole, it marks the party's most sweeping abdication of power since the People's Republic was founded in 1949.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is going on and why? The answer seems to be that village democratisation has flowed from the economic reforms set in train by Deng Xiaoping. Until these reforms were launched in 1978, the party ran a command economy in China's countryside and created a horrible mess. Farm production stagnated, and rural incomes fell. By the mid-1970s the average farmer in Sichuan, to take an extreme example, was no better off than during the war-torn ravages of the 1930s.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;After 1978, incomes rose steeply when farmers were allowed to manage their own plots and sell produce on the open market. But although the economy was transformed in most of rural China, local political structures struggled to catch up. Chen Jinluo, from the China Council of Law, a government body, <ul><font size=1>Local leaders were all appointed by higher authorities. In theory, they were responsive to the peasants. In practice, they were not. After the 'family responsibility system' was adopted, which gave peasants their own land to farm, a political structure imposed from above became irrelevant.</font></ul>
The irrelevance of the old structures seems to have led to the spontaneous emergence of new village committees in southern China in the early 1980s. In 1987, a law was passed by the central government formally allowing villages to elect their own headmen and committees. The idea was that these new forms of government would be more responsive to local economic needs. The central authorities in Beijing remain quite blunt on this point. Zhan Chengfu, a civil servant who oversees village democratisation from Beijing, says: <ul><font size=1>Villagers have a much better notion of village talent than the higher authorities. If you allow the county government to choose a stupid idiot of a village chief, the whole economy will be ruined.</ul></font>The need for local talent to get the rural economy going has become still more urgent of late. The first flush of market-based reforms in rural China wore off in the late 1980s. Growth in farm incomes has been worryingly slow in recent years. Some official figures suggest that 95m Chinese still live below the poverty line; the World Bank recently put the figure at 350m, almost all of them in the countryside. "It is impossible for the central government to do much," says Mr Zhan, "and provincial and county governments are not going to be of much help either." Villages, in effect, are being asked to fend for themselves, and higher levels of government are being asked to keep out of the process. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So democratisation in the countryside, which began in piecemeal fashion, is now being pushed hard by the central authorities. Provinces which lag behind politically, such as Guangdong, Hainan and Guangxi in the south, are getting a tongue-lashing from Beijing. Local governments are being "educated" to surrender power. The central government insists that it does not vet candidates. And election procedures are said to be be increasingly safer and fairer. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But although new political structures have emerged, they often co-exist with the remnants of the old system. Although rural communes have died, their leaders live on. Every village still has a Communist Party secretary, often set in old ways. In Pingyuan, a dirt-poor village in the mountains outside Beijing that <i>The Economist</i> visited recently, the villagers were at a loss to say what the party secretary did, apart from attend endless conferences elsewhere. The village headman, however, was lauded as a natural leader, who would do something about Pingyuan's water shortage.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The central government, at least, is proud of the little victories scored by villagers over their overlords in nearby towns. In Hunan province this year, a township government thought that one village was too factionalised to deserve an elected chief. The villagers sued the local government in the provincial courts, the township leaders were sacked, and the villagers allowed to hold their election. Village committees from Hebei province regularly come to nearby Beijing to complain that their county government is taxing peasants too much. They are given a sympathetic ear: by law, the state may take no more than 5% of farmers' incomes. Village democracy, say officials in Beijing, will reinforce peasants' rights in future.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Officials are also upbeat about the economic consequences of democracy. The best-known example is an entrepreneur in Liaoning province, a yuan millionaire in a very poor village who ran his own transport company. While away on business three years ago, he was elected village chief. He has since brought several million dollars of business to the village, which now sports factories and processing plants.<br>
</p><p><b>From small seeds</b></b><br>
Many contenders for village chief campaign on the promise of bringing in investment. Du Xiaoshan, from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, the government's main think-tank, says that "the differences between two villages on the same plain can be striking. Good village heads spot commodities that are in demand." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The big question is whether this experiment with democracy will begin and end in China's villages. In urban areas, the Communist Party still guards power jealously, and promises to do so come what may. (Members of the Peoples' Congresses in small towns are elected--but the bodies they serve on are powerless and elections are closely controlled and often uncontested.) Some Communist Party cadres are prepared to suggest, quietly, that proper elections for real jobs, of the sort held in villages, may now be allowed to spread up to townships of around 10,000 people. Eventually, they suggest, democracy could spread onwards and upwards to counties, provinces and the central government. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet that would need a far greater willingness to risk Communist control than has been seen so far. Once proper elections spread beyond villages, it is hard to see how the crucial distinction between multi-candidate and multi-party elections could be preserved. And while some cadres are prepared to suggest that democracy in the villages may lead to bigger things, it is not at all clear that this is what the architects of village democratisation have in mind. On the contrary, the Communist Party leadership may feel that a limited, closely monitored local democracy may even win back some power for the party. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Their reasoning is that peasants who enjoy greater prosperity and autonomy may be less surly about central authority, and local leaders may be readier to carry out central policy. That is why the political thaw continued in the countryside after the Tiananmen Square killings of 1989 froze reform elsewhere. "Because peasants associate everything with the Communist Party," says Du Xiaoshan, "then if life is freer, the party gets the credit." The party, says one senior cadre, hopes that village democracy "can help safeguard central authority, particularly the one-child policy." In Pingyuan, villagers confirm that the new village chief and committee are even tougher on enforcing family planning than the Communist authorities.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some in the party insist, however, that senior party members are now actively considering allowing the democracy process to bubble up to the level of county government. Could it go further than that? "I can't give you a timetable," says a member on the party's liberal wing. "But one thing is clear: the democratic process in China largely hangs on the results of autonomous democracy in the countryside."<br>

<p align=center>
