<html><head><title>Cart before horse</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Betting</b></p>
<h1>Cart before horse</h1>

PLACE a winning wager in your local betting shop, and you will find a 9% deduction is made for tax. Place the same bet in a betting shop on a racecourse, and a deduction of only 6% is made. So what's the problem? The problem is that the exchequer does not charge tax on racecourse bets.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This scam was raised in the Commons on October 29th by Iain Duncan-Smith, Tory <font size=-1>MP</font> for Chingford. A cosy deal between the betting-shop owners and the racecourses is to blame. Punters want betting shop facilities on-course, but providing such facilities for just a few days' racing a year is expensive. So the punter is charged through the deduction, which is on top of the bookmakers' usual profits.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Punters rarely complain. Many think it is a government tax. In any case, they are better off than they were before such shops began to open in 1972. Until then, a punter wanting a bet on a race at another course had to resort to a so-called "away" bookmaker. As there were only a handful of them, they offered skimpy odds. Now, that racecourses have both "away" bookmakers and shops, the bookmakers are forced to be more generous. Any punter who does not want to pay the 6% can bet with them, and then retire to watch the race on television in the comfort of the betting shop.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Punters suffer more from another iniquitous scam. This concerns the bookmakers' arrangements for the allocation of the pitches from which they operate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The best pitches are near the stands where punters congregate. The worst are far away. Pitches are allocated by the National Association of Bookmakers (<font size=-1>NAB</font>), which operates a "dead man's shoes" rule. When a bookmaker dies, his pitch is first offered to his son or a near relative. If they do not take it, everyone moves up one. Outsiders may wait 25 years before they get a pitch at all.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No competition means a bad deal for consumers. The oldest, rudest bookmakers get the convenient pitches. They refuse smaller bets, and bets "each way" (to win, and to finish first, second or third). Inefficiency rules, with bookies employing a clerk to record bets in a big book and handing customers a cardboard receipt, instead of using computer technology.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Bookmaker conservatism upholds this absurd system. The <font size=-1>NAB</font> is meant to be negotiating with the Racecourse Association (<font size=-1>RCA</font>) for reform. However, Peter Watson, the chairman of <font size=-1>NAB</font>, has just been turfed out by his members for contemplating change.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Strangely, conservatism is reinforced by an equally absurd bit of law. Under the 1963 Betting, Gaming and Lotteries Act, racecourses cannot charge a bookmaker more than five times the standard entrance fee to take bets at their racecourse.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The House of Commons Home Affairs Committee argued in 1991 that this law should be scrapped. Racecourses could then charge what they wanted for pitches. They could ask more for the best, forcing inefficient bookmakers out of business. They could use the proceeds to improve the facilities offered to racegoers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, Tim Kirkhope, the Home Office minister responsible, says he will consider changing the law only when the <font size=-1>RCA-NAB</font> negotiations are complete. Since they could come to a sensible conclusion only if and when the law has been changed to free up charges, Mr Kirkhope is putting the cart before the horse.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846896400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7563.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

