</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Murdering the cathedral</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Roads</b></p>
<h1>Murdering the cathedral</h1>

FOR more than a decade, ministers have agonised over a by-pass for Salisbury which threatens one of the finest views in Britain, the view of the cathedral across the water meadows made famous by Constable. On October 29th they decided to dither some more. "Further detailed studies", the government decided, are required; which will, astonishingly, defer the decision until after the next election is due.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Salisbury by-pass saga is an example of the paralysis that now passes for transport policy. It was first mooted half a century ago. By 1984, the government included it in the roads programme. In April 1993, a year-long public inquiry began into the proposal for a dual carriageway by-pass. The inquiry's inspector, Sir Peter Buchanan, took another 18 months before he reported in its favour. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Similarly, last month the government decided to shelve a scheme to relieve traffic around Stonehenge. Britain's greatest prehistoric monument has a day-long traffic jam for a neighbour. Faced by opposition to expanding the road into a dual carriageway, ministers decided that the least unpopular option was to do nothing. The government acknowledges that a long tunnel by-passing the site is the only publicly acceptable solution but says that, at &#163;300m, it would be too expensive.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The stories of Salisbury and Stonehenge show that roads can no longer be built on the cheap. Too many people are willing to fight against the concreting of more of the countryside. But then the pressures on public expenditure, which have pushed roads way down the list of priorities, mean that the Treasury will no longer pay for expensive roads.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is, however, an alternative. If the taxpayer will not foot the bill for roads, the motorist can be made to. People are used to tolls on tunnels under estuaries: the Dartford Tunnel that forms part of the <font size=-1>M</font>25, for instance, and employs an automatic collection system, has proved so successful that it is expected to repay its &#163;215m construction costs well ahead of schedule.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is no reason why a long tunnel by-passing Stonehenge should not be financed in a similar way. Objectors worry that locals would suffer; but they could carry concessional residents' permits, as with parking. Another concern is that, in order to avoid the charge, drivers would instead use little roads through neighbouring villages; but traffic-management techniques (putting in lots of lights, for instance, or snail's-pace speed limits) can help solve that problem. The obstacle is not technology, but lack of political will. Privately, politicians say that tolling is the only solution. Sooner or later, they are going to have to admit it publicly.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
