<html><head><title>The new age of holistic policing</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Law and order</b></p>
<h1>The new age of holistic policing</h1>

<font size=1>MILTON KEYNES</font><p>
LAURA, a 13-year-old who has stolen some pens from the John Lewis department store, sits facing a police officer in Milton Keynes police station. Her face is a painful blush, her eyes red and downcast. Her parents, on either side of her, are angry: her father in a needs-a-good-hiding spirit, her mother confused. The police officer is nice. All adults have stolen something in their lives, he says, and don't believe those who tell you otherwise. However, some kids who shoplift go on to do worse things, and he intends to see that Laura does not.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Laura will get a talking to from a manager at the shopping centre she stole from. He will explain to her that shoplifting is not a victimless crime; she may be persuaded to apologise. She will get a sensible chat from a police officer about what is called "protective behaviour"--how not to get yourself into the sort of situation where you may shoplift.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other agencies are on hand. Laura could (though the officer does not think it necessary in her case) be given a session with the Prison Service about how that is not a nice place to end up. If there were bad problems at home, the social services could be brought in. If she had no friends, the youth service could help. If there were no responsible adult in her life, "Befrienders", a local service which matches adult volunteers with needy children, might step in.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rather an elaborate reaction, perhaps, to a few pens. But "Caution Plus", a programme aimed at first-time shoplifters which was designed by Caroline Nicholl, chief superintendent of Milton Keynes, two-and-a-half years ago, aims to nip criminal behaviour in the bud. Its effect is impressive. According to a study by the Home Office, the reoffending rate for first-timers in nearby Peterborough, where they will receive a police caution and then be sent home, is 35%; for those who have been through the Milton Keynes programme, it is 3%.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Behind what is going on in Milton Keynes is a set of ideas known in the management-speak that has taken over the police as "problem-oriented policing". The ideas, which come from North America, are seeping through British police forces as they grapple with the problems of fast-increasing demands and slowly-increasing resources. Leicestershire, for instance, has had an increase in emergency calls of 136% in the past eight years, and a real increase in resources of 3.5% over the same period.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Problem-oriented policing aims not just to react to calls from the public, but to find out why those demands are being made and to solve problems at their source. Charles Pollard, chief constable of Thames Valley Police, and one of its principal advocates, calls it "holistic" policing, as opposed to the "sticking-plaster" variety.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To some extent, implementing these ideas means teaching policemen to go about their work in a different way. But administrative changes are also making a difference. "Sector policing", for instance, means dividing up beats and putting policemen in charge of small slices. The smaller the area, the idea is, the better a policeman can get to know it. According to David Morgan in Milton Keynes--who, as a beat officer, is likely to be sceptical about management theory--it works. "Before, if you got a 'domestic', you'd get different shifts coming fresh to it. Now, if you see the same thing happening again and again, you can do something about it." And the more you know about a neighbourhood, the more likely you are to be able to identify the culprit in a burglary or a murder.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Working with other agencies, something the police have not been good at, is central to these new ideas. Social services can help with domestic violence, which is behind most murders. Rehousing could be the solution to a long battle between warring neighbours, one of the sources of endless work for the police. Alcoholics--much crime is alcohol-related--can be pushed towards getting treatment.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;David Coleman, assistant chief constable of Leicestershire, cites the case of an old man who, one policewoman discovered, had called the police 20 times in four months. She went to see him, and found that he was bored. She contacted the British Legion, who helped him to buy a television. In the following three months he made just one call.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Problem-oriented policing has been taken up enthusiastically by some forces-- Thames Valley, Leicestershire and Surrey in particular--and more patchily by others. Although top policemen seem convinced, this approach to policing runs against the government's determined push for better crime figures.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Problem-oriented policing does not pay much attention to immediate trends in crime figures. It sees success in the longer term. Crime figures, as Mr Pollard points out, are too easily manipulated--as they were, he says, when he first joined the force and senior officers would discourage junior officers from recording crimes in order to keep the figures down. Policing by numbers, of the sort required by the Home Office's emphasis on performance targets, may thus be untrustworthy.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anyway, by its nature, problem-oriented policing is likely to push the crime figures up. Some British police officers point out the contrast between this approach and that of the world's most-trumpeted policing success story, New York city. New York's police have achieved their results by making life tough for likely suspects (black teenagers, mainly) and have thereby generated hostility in black neighbourhoods as well as relief at the falling crime figures. If, by contrast, a policeman gets to know locals, and they trust him, the crime rate is likely to go up because they will report more crimes to him. The officer may be solving the problems of locals more effectively, and actually reducing the real level of crime, but the reported crime figures will make it look as if the opposite is happening.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Accordingly, it does not make much sense to look at what these new ideas are doing to the reported crime figures. They are new, they have been patchily implemented, they may take some time to bear fruit. But their supporters claim that they can, in the long run, have considerable effect: they point to cities such as Edmonton, in Canada, which has been pursuing this approach for years: emergency calls fell by 36% in four years, and crime by 40% in ten years. Maybe policing had something to do with it; and maybe the same will, eventually, happen in Milton Keynes too.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
