<html><head><title>Yon bonny banks and yon bonny bribes</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Yon bonny banks and yon bonny bribes</h1>

<font size=1>INVERNESS</font><p>
CUT-PRICE sales of state-owned assets are usually roundly condemned by opposition parties. Yet when Michael Forsyth, the Scottish secretary, introduced a bill in the House of Lords on October 25th for a bargain-basement sale of government-owned land in the Highlands, his opponents raised a pious cheer.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Forsyth wants to sell 259,000 acres of the Highlands to the 1,400 crofters who live on them. They are the last remnants and descendants of 4,500 soldiers and sailors demobilised after the first world war who were persuaded to settle in Scotland on land bought by the government with the grand aim of producing "a fit and healthy race", and a nation self-sufficient in food production.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the Highlands, this land came under 19th-century crofting law which was passed to protect poor tenants from being evicted by rich landlords. The law on crofts is so peculiar that Highland wits define them as small pieces of land entirely surrounded by legislation.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Forsyth could ask his tenants to stump up &#163;1.5m. But he says he will hand the land over for nothing if need be, and may even give the crofters some money to band together in community trusts. These have been set up by the few crofters who have managed to buy land from private estate-owners; and the government hopes its tenants will do the same. Labour and the Scottish Nationalists, who have long sided with crofters as the victims of oppression, can hardly complain.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the government gets about &#163;150,000 a year in rent, it spends &#163;370,000 in administering and maintaining the crofts. Saving money, however, is not Mr Forsyth's main motive.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Politically, the Highlands divide between landlords and tenants. Landlords are rich, aristocratic and Tory-voting; tenants (including crofters) vote anything but Tory. The Tories lost their last seat in northern Scotland--Ross, Cromarty & Skye--in 1983.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the last election threw up a political oddity. Inverness, Nairn & Lochaber became Britain's only four-way marginal seat. Sir Russell Johnston, a Liberal Democrat, held on to his seat with just 26% of the vote, with Labour (25%), the Scottish Nationalists (25%) and the Tories (23%) hard on his heels. Since Sir Russell is retiring at the next election and boundary changes have moved a few thousand Labour voters into a different seat, the Tories think they have as good a chance as anybody else of winning it. <br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


