<table border=0><tr><td><hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><img src="ameb.gif" width="230" height="178" alt="Election graph"><br><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Trends of the week</h2><p>
<b>Divide and vote: </b>A majority of Americans (55%) think it is good for the country to have a president of one party and Congress controlled by another, reports a Harris poll. Ticket-splitting has become the norm: 62% say they will vote for candidates from both parties.<center>***</center><br>
<b>Travels: </b>In the last stretch of the campaign, Mr Dole finds it necessary to visit Florida, Texas and Arizona, states that should have been safely Republican. Mr Clinton, trawling for ethnic votes in the mid-west, eats pirogies (stuffed pastries) and recommends <font size=-1>NATO</font> membership for Central European countries by 1999.<center>***</center><br>
<b>Travails:</b> Mr Dole's attacks on Mr Clinton's ethics backfire. Most polls show Mr Clinton's lead widening. Mr Dole takes to referring to the Truman-Dewey upset of 1948 to show that the unexpected can happen. <center>***</center><br>
<b>Defeatism:</b> Rife among top Republicans. Defeatists reportedly include Jack Kemp (says privately the race is over, according to <i>Newsweek</i>) and Republican governors such as Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin ("I thought George Bush's campaign was probably the poorest-run . . . and I think this is a close second.").<center></center><br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Ethics: </b>As part of his offensive over foreign contributions to the Democratic Party, Mr Dole proposes campaign-finance reform. The Clinton camp mocks this "political deathbed conversion"-- and releases an ad accusing Republicans of tapping foreign money too.<center>***</center><br>
<b>Objection: </b>Nancy Reagan writes to Mr Clinton asking him "as a matter of decency" to stop airing replays of the assassination attempt on her husband. The footage is included in a Clinton campaign ad in which Jim Brady, Mr Reagan's former press secretary who was crippled in the incident, endorses Mr Clinton's gun-control efforts. The Clinton campaign says it will consider Mrs Reagan's views, but does not apologise.<center>***</center><br>
<b>Motor-doper: </b>Under attack for the rise in teenage drug use during his presidency, Mr Clinton proposes drug-testing for teenagers applying for a driving licence. Civil libertarians in turn attack Mr Clinton for pandering for votes with policies that intrude on freedom. <center>***</center><br>
<b>Prop: </b>"The Clean Sweep Truck", spotted at rallies in North Carolina. A pick-up truck with two tall brooms sticking into the air, it displays stickers for Democratic candidates from Clinton/Gore to Jim Long for insurance commissioner.<center>***</center><br>
<b>Music: </b>The high-school band in Chelsea, Michigan, welcomes Mr Dole with the theme from "Mission Impossible".<center>***</center><br>
<b>Symbolism: </b>Oxygen masks come down in the Dole campaign aircraft as it makes a particularly bumpy landing.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>
</td></tr></table>


