<html><head><title>Moving ma'am</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>The Queen's Speech</b></p>
<h1>Moving ma'am</h1>

JOHN MAJOR is a constitutional conservative. You would think, therefore, that when the prime minister did propose a change, it would be remembered. Not so: on October 23rd, the Queen's Speech, setting out the government's legislative programme, went by without mention of Mr Major's proposal earlier this year that it be shifted from the autumn to May.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The autumn Queen's Speech is an anachronism. The budget used to take place in the spring. In those days it made sense to spread parliamentary business through the year by starting on the non budget legislation in the autumn. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, since 1993, the unified budget, which brings together the government's spending and taxing plans, has taken place in November. The result: an autumn logjam with the budget and new laws competing for time in the Commons. Come spring, there is a hiatus for <font size=-1>MP</font>s while those laws are considered by the House of Lords. Hence Mr Major's sensible proposal.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Next year will offer a great opportunity to make the change. Most people now expect the general election to be on May 1st 1997. A new government could announce its legislative plans for a normal one-year session of Parliament in the Queen's Speech just after that election. Otherwise there will be a tiresomely long session of Parliament, running until autumn 1998. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Surprisingly, however, the prime minister's proposal has got nowhere. The usual process of consultation between the parties which precedes such changes has not even been started. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tony Newton, the leader of the Commons, is said to be concentrating on the general election--a suspicion borne out by the fact that this year's Queen's Speech mostly contained bills designed to emphasise the gap between the main parties rather than any common ground. Ann Taylor, his Labour shadow, has failed to push for change. A good idea could easily be lost.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another reform proposed by Mr Major is, however, taking root. He wants bills to be published in draft before debate to allow expert scrutiny. The queen told the Commons that two bills--on care of the elderly and on national identity cards--will now get that treatment. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour is urging one further reform. It wants to abolish the ludicrous rule by which government bills are deemed lost if they fail to be carried in a single parliamentary session. Instead, unfinished bills could be picked up again in a new session at the stage they had reached when the old session ended--as is already the case with private legislation on behalf of particular companies and interests. Taken together, these proposals, Mr Major's and Labour's, could transform the effectiveness of Parliament in scrutinising legislation, which makes it all the sadder that they are subject to so much foot-dragging.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
