<html><head><title>Dialling Tone</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Dialling Tone</h1>

LABOUR'S telephone campaign to persuade its members to vote on Tony Blair's "New Labour, New Life for Britain" policy document is being ridiculed by the Conservatives. But all the main parties now realise how effective telephone marketing can be, either to get supporters into the polling booths or to solicit donations. Especially after the 1992 general election, in which some say the phone was the secret weapon behind the Tories' surprise win.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Simon Pell, a Labour official who was behind his party's adoption of telephone marketing, later left to form Pell & Bales, a firm which is now being paid &#163;1.10 a call to ring thousands of party members to urge them to vote on the policy document. Although the document was approved by the party's conference, Mr Blair wants a direct vote of support from at least half of the 370,000 members.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour claims that just under 40% have voted so far, not all of whom will have backed Mr Blair's vision of a new Britain. Pell & Bales, with Labour's in house telephone canvassers, aim to reach 40,000 households containing, in all, 100,000 party members by October 31st, the closing date for the vote.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;During the 1992 election, Labour and the Liberal Democrats were lulled into false optimism because the Tories did hardly any traditional doorstep canvassing. In fact, local Tory constituency parties had switched tactics, realising that as voters were increasingly reluctant to open their doors to strangers it made more sense to canvass support by phone. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since then, Labour has invested heavily in setting up telephone canvassing operations, both at party headquarters and locally. Michael Cunnington, Labour's head of fund-raising, reckons that donations gathered by phone are worth about &#163;1.7m a year. The Lib Dems are also doing more phone-politicking, but mostly at a local level.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Tories seem to have lost the lead they built at the last election. Harvey Thomas, a publicity chief for the Tories from 1985 to 1991, says that after seeing how much money America's Republicans were raising by telephone, he pleaded in vain with his party bosses to set up a similar operation at Conservative Central Office. But local constituency parties refused to let go of their membership lists. Even now, Tory headquarters has no comprehensive list of party members. If it wanted to launch a nationwide telephone campaign like Mr Blair's, it would not know whom to call.<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
