<html><head><title>Misty</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>The cost of Scotland</b></p>
<h1>Misty</h1>

<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font><p>
SCOTLAND is over-subsidised, think many right-wing Tories. A study published by the Scottish Office on October 21st seems to confirm this. It estimated that in the 1994-95 fiscal year the government spent &#163;30.3 billion in Scotland, whilst the Scots stumped up a mere &#163;22.1 billion in tax, leaving a whopping &#163;8.2 billion gap (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Michael Forsyth, the Scottish secretary, is oddly proud of this for a right-winger, boasting that he spends about 25% more per Scot on things such as education than is spent south of the border. He warns that this Tory generosity will come to an abrupt halt if Labour wins power and a devolved Scottish parliament takes over his budget. Scots would be even worse off were they ever to be governed by the Scottish National Party (<font size=-1>SNP</font>), he threatens.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the <font size=-1>SNP</font> complains that the Scottish Office figures are distorted. The party has a point. Britain as a whole had a huge public sector deficit in 1994-95. Part of the &#163;8.2 billion shortfall between Scotland's public spending and tax revenues--around &#163;4.2 billion of it--is its share of that overall British deficit, not a subsidy from the rest of Britain. Moreover, Scotland should be allocated a share of privatisation revenues-- around &#163;600m, assuming revenues are divided according to population. That would cut Scotland's subsidy from (fiscal deficit with) the rest of Britain to just &#163;3.4 billion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This might still embarrass Labour. Its devolution plans would make this cash transfer from the south crystal clear, leaving the party with some explaining to do. As for the independent Scotland favoured by the <font size=-1>SNP</font>, surely it would be a poorer country than now, as presumably such transfers would stop on independence? No, says the <font size=-1>SNP</font>, arguing that independence would give Scotland control of most tax revenue from Britain's North Sea oil. Maybe. But, as our chart shows, even with 90% of this revenue, Scotland would still be in hock to the rest of Britain to the tune of &#163;2 billion--not including its share of Britain's deficit, which it would have to find a way to pay for if independence arrived. Freedom would not come for free.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7548.html">Next article</a>
