<html><head><title>Jewish family values</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Same-sex marriages</b></p>
<h1>Jewish family values</h1>

BRITAIN'S politicians are currently gushing with professions of faith in religion and family values. Yet two of Britain's bigger religious groups are struggling to decide what sort of families to value. The Church of England has been in uproar since Anne Atkins, a conservative Anglican, used <font size=-1>BBC</font> radio's "Thought for the Day" slot earlier this month to accuse the church of taking too liberal a line on homosexuality. And similar stirrings are afoot within Britain's Jewish community.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reform Judaism is a branch of the religion that prides itself on its openness, especially in matters sexual. Unlike the various Orthodox strands, it has female rabbis, seats men and women together in synagogues and sees homosexuality as a legitimate form of love. But when one rabbi, Elizabeth Sarah, used a sermon on Yom Kippur, the holiest day in the Jewish year, to say that she was to officiate at a "commitment ceremony" between two lesbians, all hell broke loose. One rabbi threatened to quit the Reform umbrella organisation; some Orthodox Jews said that Reform had, in the words of one rabbi, shown its "farcical and ugly face". The couple cancelled the ceremony, Rabbi Sarah apologised for the fuss and Reform leaders were muzzled.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reform's peculiar position in Britain makes the mix of sex and religion more than usually combustible. In America, where Reform is the most popular branch of Judaism, Reform rabbis have been blessing same-sex unions for years. But in Britain Reform plays second fiddle to the Orthodox establishment; 13% of the country's 300,000 Jews belong to Reform synagogues while 40% belong to the United Synagogue, the main Orthodox grouping. Partly for that reason, British Reform is more conservative than its American variant. Its rabbis do not marry Jews to non-Jews; they do not acknowledge as Jews children of non-Jewish mothers unless they convert.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This cautious liberalism has served Reform Judaism well. Although synagogue membership is declining overall, Reform is adding members. It dreams of someday supplanting the United Synagogue as British Jewry's dominant religious group.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The uproar over homosexuality has exposed rifts between rabbis who think heterosexual marriage is the only kind Judaism can openly endorse and those who think gay couples deserve some kind of consecration. The controversy has also pitted clergy against laity. In what liberal rabbis regard as unprecedented meddling by a lay body in religious matters, the Council of Reform Synagogues ordered rabbis not to do same-sex ceremonies until the Reform movement decides on the matter.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That will not be easy. Unlike the United Synagogue, Reform has no chief rabbi to lay down the law. A committee of the rabbinical assembly, set up before the controversy broke, had hoped to include same-sex unions in a broader ruling on other sorts of family relationship, including unmarried heterosexual couples. Now it has been bounced into dealing with homosexual unions alone.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Reform Jews may yet agree to disagree. Rabbi Rodney Mariner, a member of the committee, says most members oppose letting rabbis officiate at gay unions but may nonetheless free dissenting rabbis to go their own way. Without a solution, Reform rabbis may find themselves presiding over a same-sect schism.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
