<html><head><title>Land of the free, home of the Braves</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26" alt="Finance and Economics" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Land of the free, home of the Braves</h1>

INVESTMENT bankers may not be able to hit a curve ball, but the average professional baseball player would feel at home on a trading floor: the foul language, the cut-throat competition, the outrageous salaries. Since 1977, when America's ball players gained the freedom to change teams without owners' permission, their salaries have soared: the average major-league player now makes more than $1m a year. Besides enriching the athletes at the owners' expense, however, "free agency" was also supposed to make professional players more mobile and thus make competition among clubs more even. Has it?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The return of the Atlanta Braves to this year's World Series--their fourth appearance in five seasons--suggests that the best teams can still find a way to stay on top. (As <i>The Economist</i> went to press, the series was in progress.) Yet many people contend that the game has become more competitive in recent years: new teams are making the post-season play-offs, divisional races are more exciting, and so forth. So to try to determine whether this is so, Craig Depken, an economist at the University of Texas in Arlington, has tried to marry baseball with economics.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Economists often gauge the competitiveness of an industry by measuring the extent to which its output is concentrated among a few companies. The most common such measure is a "Herfindahl Hirschman" (<font size=-1>HH</font>) index: to calculate it, take the market shares of all the firms, square them, and add them up. If there are 100 equal-sized firms, the index is 0.01; if there are four equal-sized firms, it will be 0.25. So the higher the number, the more market power is concentrated. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In applying this to baseball, one difficulty is defining what ball players produce. Mr Depken uses two rough measures: strike-outs and home runs. After calculating <font size=-1>HH</font> indices for 1920-93, he found that both home runs and strike outs have indeed been growing less concentrated over time: that is, there is less disparity between the number of home runs hit by good teams and those hit by bad ones.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If free agency has indeed spread the best players more evenly around the league, this trend should have become more marked after 1977. However, this does not appear to be the case. Instead, the fall in concentration can be explained by other factors, such as adding more teams to the league, breaking teams into more divisions and so on.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This makes sense. Most owners of small-city teams complain that their big city rivals have more money than they do, and can therefore afford to buy the best players. Free agency appears simply to have bid up the players' salaries at their employers' expense, without changing the balance of power in the league. A lesson for investment banks?<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846288000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a>
</p>
