<html><head><title> Why the Net should grow up</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><h1 align=center> Why the Net should grow up</h1>THE growth of the Internet has been the most astonishing technological phenomenon of the last decade of this century. In 1990 only a few academics had heard of it; now, anything up to 50m people use it. In a year's time, that figure could be 100m--so far, the network's only constant has been that the number of people tapping into it has doubled every 12 months. But up to now, only a handful of companies have made much money from the Internet. If it is to become a commercial success, rather than merely a <i>succ&egrave;s d'estime</i>, it has to change. Otherwise many of the qualities that brought it popularity will become liabilities.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Increasingly, the Internet is coming under attack, and from many quarters. The telephone companies, whose networks carry much of its traffic, grumble noisily that Internet users clog their wires and bypass their long-distance rates with cheap Internet telephone calls. Frustrated regulators wail that the Internet has become a way to dodge national laws. Users are driven to distraction by the delays, the muddle and the brainless rubbish. Breakdowns of bits of the Net are hardly new, but when they happen these days a lot more people notice--as when America Online crashed in August, leaving 6m subscribers to twiddle their thumbs. Last week a group of American universities, fed up with the Net's sluggish ways, decided to set up Internet II, a new network that will allow its members to swap data more smoothly.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Faced with pile-ups and pollution on the prototype information superhighway, governments will be increasingly tempted to intervene. The Net's early colonisers reply that regulation will slow its growth. But is there any alternative?<br></p><p><b>Did somebody say market?</b><br>The first and most pressing need is for a better way to price the use of the Internet (see <a href="sf0774.html">page</a>). At present, many users pay less than the true cost of carrying their messages over the network. Most pay a one-off monthly fee to the firm that offers them a Net connection; and then home users typically have the additional cost of the local telephone call every time that they log on. This system is an invitation to use the network as intensively as possible, even if it causes problems for others. Thanks to the wonders of the World Wide Web, the multimedia part of the Net, people are using the network to transmit telephone calls, film clips and other capacity-guzzling applications. The upshot is that the Net still resembles a congested city street: because users pay only for their car and its fuel, rather than for the inconvenience their presence on the road imposes on others, they have no incentive to limit the use of their car in order to avoid traffic jams.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Congestion is made worse by the absence of a satisfactory way for firms running the Net to charge for carrying each other's traffic. Sticking to the informal style that was characteristic of the Net's early days, they have tended to use a rough-and-ready barter system. That worked when there were just a handful of firms whose own networks formed the Net, but today there are thousands. Some admit that they now carry as much traffic from freeloaders as from their own customers. When they cannot afford to spend enough to keep up with this demand, they become bottlenecks.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To some extent, the market will develop answers for itself. Indeed, to the dismay of the most ardent Internet enthusiasts, companies are increasingly building private Internets either to connect their internal users, or to ensure fast communications with other firms. These private networks will solve other Internet problems: they offer quality-of-service guarantees, and better security against hackers. Geeks will grumble that they risk causing the balkanisation of the Net. Customers will be delighted by the absence of delays.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The subsidy from the telephone network is a different matter, and usually reflects political pressures: governments, keen to see competition when it benefits customers, do not much like measures that drive up the cost of a local call. One of the welcome effects of the Internet will be to make political meddling in telephone prices harder to sustain, because inexpensive telephone calls over the Internet will help to undermine excessive margins on long-distance telephone tariffs. Indeed, the interests of surfers and telephone callers are ultimately identical: where competition thrives and regulation does not suppress it, people will communicate through whichever channel is best for their particular needs.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Governments can leave the market to sort out the way transmission over the Net is priced. Their proper role is to decide how far to try to regulate the material that passes through it. Many people dislike the way the Net is used by law-breakers to bypass national laws on decency, libel, racism, intellectual property, and so on. Because the Internet whisks content around the world, it is harder to police than a national television channel or a newspaper.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Policing, mind you, is not impossible. The government of Myanmar has outlawed the unauthorised possession of networked computers on pain of 15 years in prison. For governments that care a jot for liberty (let alone for the health of their communications-based economies), matters are more complicated. None of the abuses complained of can be stamped out without gross invasion of privacy, any more than people can be prevented from sending racist letters to each other in the ordinary mail or making obscene telephone calls or from pirating home videos. But all can be discouraged more vigorously than most countries have yet done. Governments need to force Internet service providers, many of which will in future be big telephone companies, to take responsibility for what they knowingly carry on their sites. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Internet will always allow the really determined user access to unpleasant or illegal material. The telephone does the same. The important thing is that governments should not treat the Internet differently from other communications media, merely because it is new. The faster the Net grows up, the easier it will be to follow that rule.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845683200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="ld4398.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
