<html><head><title>Election Billboard</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><center><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><p align=center><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0></p></center><p align=center><img src="../images/eb.gif" width="360" height="22" alt="Election Billboard" border=0></p><p align=center><font size=-1></font></p></center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><center><img src="ameb.gif" width="232" height="152" alt="Election graph"><br><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Trends of the week</h2><p><b>Attack: </b>Bob Dole puts in an aggressive performance in the second and final presidential debate in San Diego, questioning the administration's ethics at every turn, while Bill Clinton avoids confrontation and talks about issues. In instant polls, some 57% call Mr Clinton the winner; 27% go for Mr Dole.<br><br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Defence: </b>Mr Clinton's effort to blunt Mr Dole's assaults: "No attack ever created a job or educated a child, or helped a family make ends meet. No insult ever cleaned up a toxic waste dump or helped an elderly person."<br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Celebrityendorsement: </b>Mr Clinton mentions <i>The Economist</i> in the middle of berating Mr Dole for his tax-cut proposal. <br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Toys:</b> Little plastic spinning tops, carried by Clinton/Gore spinmeisters in San Diego.<br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Money: </b>The Dole campaign claims it has as much as one-third more money left in its coffers than the Clinton campaign to spend on advertising in the three weeks before the election. <br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Travel: </b>As of October 15th, Bob Dole had visited 24 states and Bill Clinton 25. Mr Dole had been to California eight times, Ohio seven times, and Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>, six times. Both men were still ignoring the toss-up states of Montana (three electoral college votes) Nevada (4), Alabama (9) and Indiana (12). Mr Dole decides to visit Texas (32 electoral-college votes, and not quite in his pocket) only after the San Diego debate and a wake-up call from George Bush.<br></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><b>Tactics:</b> Hints from the Dole campaign, as well as mentions of affirmative action and defence cuts in the debate, confirm that Mr Dole is going flat-out for a win in California (54 votes), diverting resources from other key states. A Field poll immediately shows the gap in California more than halving, to ten points. Joe Lockhart, the Clinton/Gore campaign spokesman, in San Diego: "If the Dole campaign wants to make this state the battleground, I can't think of a single thing that's better for us." <br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>NAFTAthought:</b> Mindful of Florida's 25 electoral-college votes, the Clinton administration responds to complaints from Florida tomato growers by fixing a deal with Mexican growers that sets a floor price for their vine-ripened tomatoes. So much for free trade (not to mention consumers).<br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Boast:</b> Bigger government. To counter his opponent's Mediscare tactics, Mr Dole's campaign ads point out that under the Dole plan government spending to 2002 would grow by 14%. <br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Sign: </b>Spotted on Interstate 70 at Mr Dole's home town of Russell, Kansas, a big sign advertising: "Olde Tower Antique & Craft Gallery. Dole Collectables <br>c". Investigation reveals that the shop recently went out of business.<br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Portent: </b><i>TV Guide</i> runs cover pictures of Mr Dole and Mr Clinton on its Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font> edition. The rest of the country gets Brooke Shields. <br><p align=center><center>***</center></p><b>Tip: </b>Watch the signs in the front yards. Yardsignologists detect a trend towards ticket-splitting. More than usual, it seems, voters are mixing signs of candidates from different parties for various races. <br><br></td></tr></table></center><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845683200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="am3091.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
