<html><head><title>Cheap</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Broadcasting</b></p>
<h1>Cheap</h1>

THERE is a good case to be made for privatising Channel 4 television. It is, some say, absurd and illiberal that the state should own three out of four terrestrial television channels. Others maintain that the state should not own television channels at all. Against the privatisers, supporters of Channel 4's current status maintain that its rich diversity would not survive in the commercial world.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, there is also a bad case for privatising Channel 4, and that is the one that the government is currently considering: that the sale could raise money for electoral bribes. Behind that lies an even worse argument: that, by offsetting the proceeds of the proposed sale against its public-spending plans to be published next month, the Tories could plant a time-bomb for a Labour government, which would not sell the channel. John Major is considering the proposal, which is backed by Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, but opposed by Virginia Bottomley, the heritage secretary. Mr Major should have no truck with such specious economic reasoning.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Channel 4 is not subsidised, but estimates of how much it would fetch vary hugely. If, at one extreme, it was given a remit to produce the unpopular minority-interest programmes that constitute much of its present output, it might raise only &#163;200m. Remit-free it might be worth as much as &#163;2 billion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if the government decided now to sell it, this could not pay for tax cuts next year because of the legislative timetable. Some Tory backbenchers, including Nicholas Winterton and Sir Tim Renton, are passionately opposed to a sale on cultural grounds. Even if they were persuaded, the government would find it hard to push through an act of parliament before the general election, which cannot be delayed beyond May. Privatisation is thus unlikely to figure in the Queen's speech on October 23rd which will set out this Parliament's legislative programme. And even if it were legislated straight after the election, the bill would not become law in time to allow a sale in 1997-98.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, Mr Clarke could announce the government's intention to legislate next year as part of his spending plans in his budget on November 26th, with the actual sale scheduled for 1998-99. Under existing public spending rules he would then be entitled to score the proceeds in his plans for 1998-99, allowing him to project lower borrowing in that year--and perhaps lower taxes as a result.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That would pose a problem for Labour, whose heritage spokesman, Jack Cunningham, is passionately against a sale. If Labour won, and the sale was ditched, a Labour government would have to find more revenue or spend less elsewhere. With the outlook for public finances already tight, neither option is attractive.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, it is bad economics to use financial receipts from the sale of state assets to pay for current spending or tax cuts. Such receipts do reduce the public sector borrowing requirement but they do not reduce the state's long-term claim on national resources. As for the politics, Mr Clarke's device is transparently sleazy. The government's proper course, if it decides that privatisation is right, would be to leave the sale out of its budget spending plans; to put a proposal for selling Channel 4 in its manifesto; and only if it is re-elected to take account of the proceeds in drawing up its future budgetary plans.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
