<html><head><title>Sterling efforts</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Sterling efforts</h1>

THE pound rose this week to its highest level since 1994. Its trade-weighted exchange-rate (its exchange rate with the currencies of its trading partners, weighted by Britain's trade in each currency) is 6.1% up so far this year. It fell by a similar amount during 1995 (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>). Arguably, sterling's strength is now the only excuse that Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, has left for not raising interest rates--but it is not a good excuse.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recent economic data have confirmed that the economy is growing fast and inflationary pressures increasing. An interest-rate rise is needed. The underlying rate of inflation (which excludes mortgage-interest payments) edged up to an annual rate of 2.9% in September. The government's target is 2.5% or less. The jobless total fell by an unexpectedly large 35,600 in September, to 7.4% of the workforce. Vacancies soared by 16,600, the biggest monthly increase in 16 years. The labour market is as tight as in 1988, a fact reflected in rising wage inflation: underlying average earnings grew by 4% in the year to August.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But sterling's recent strength complicates matters. As the pound rises, the cost of imports falls. In the year to August 1995, when sterling's trade-weighted value was low, import prices rose by 11%. They fell by 0.8% in the 12 months to July of this year. Exchange-rate movements take time to work through. According to Martin Brookes, an economist at Goldman Sachs, an investment bank, sterling's fall during 1995 added one percentage point to the inflation rate in the middle of this year. This year's stronger pound should ease inflationary pressures over the coming months.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although it may not do so by enough to overcome the building inflationary pressure elsewhere in the economy, might Mr Clarke use the possibility of a sterling boost to delay an interest-rate rise? It would be a gamble. The likeliest reason for sterling's recent rise is that the financial markets think that British interest rates will soon rise. If they do not, sterling might tumble again, adding to inflation instead of curbing it.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


