<html><head><title> After he's gone </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><h1 align=center>After he's gone</h1>HE IS, in some ways, quite an ordinary man. He is neither great intellect, nor rousing orator. He can be impetuous and sometimes quick of temper. He has failed, twice, to make marriage work. Yet few can doubt that much of the credit for the negotiated collapse of apartheid, and for the building of a new, non-triumphalist nation through racial reconciliation, belongs to Nelson Rolihlahla Mandela. In this sense he is far from ordinary, and it is understandable that he should be so revered. The trouble for South Africans now, as they peer anxiously around them at their gathering problems and further, into a post-Mandela future, is that the more both they and the outside world cling to the saint-like figure, the harder they will find it when he goes.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That day is not yet at hand. God willing, Mr Mandela will remain in office till 1999, when he will be 80 and deserving, surely, of a peaceful retirement. But the aura of sainthood is now deflecting attention from some of South Africa's problems (see <a href="sf0760.html">pages</a>). It has also placed Mr Mandela out of reach of criticism, though he is not infallible. He has stood by incompetent lieutenants out of stubborn loyalty, while dismissing another (not incompetent) merely for challenging his authority. He has taken cash for his party from a casino tycoon, who had previously admitted paying the head of an apartheid homeland to secure gambling rights. In any event, fallible or not, Mr Mandela increasingly leaves the day-to-day running of government to others. He must take responsibility for their mistakes.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fortunately, his detachment is not total. He is fit and, as long as he is in ultimate charge, South Africans can be pretty confident that things will not go badly wrong: he has the authority to enforce his will, and on the large issues his will is dependably rooted in honesty and reconciliation. The immediate worry is that a number of apparently minor problems will get worse, and that in time they will add up to something serious. The longer-term worry is that, when the saint departs, he will be followed by someone much less saintlike.<br><b> <br></p><p><b>No easy walk</b></b><br>For those inclined to take a dark view, there is plenty to be concerned about. South Africa is a poor country, with a history of division and violence. Millions of people live in abject poverty with little immediate prospect of a better life: one in three is without even an informal job. Ethnic strains persist. Robbery, murder and every other kind of crime are rife.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To make matters worse, political stability is uncertain. Two of the main parties represent racial groups. The National Party, anchored in Afrikanerdom, has won some mixed-race adherents but little black support. The Inkatha Freedom Party speaks mainly for rural Zulus. They, and the other opposition parties, are hugely outnumbered in Parliament by Mr Mandela's African National Congress, which took 63% of the vote in the 1994 general election. It is hard to envisage the <font size=-1>ANC</font> out of government. Electorally, it has no need to listen to its critics. And it may already be showing, albeit in small ways, the arrogance of unfettered power: an apparent readiness here to tolerate incompetence, an apparent reluctance there to pursue corruption.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Africa, this scene is familiar. It usually turns to intolerance and impoverishment, sometimes to tyranny and bloodshed. Is this to be South Africa's fate?<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It need not be. But South Africa's ability to get beyond its first few years of post-apartheid transition, and thereby to secure its post-Mandela democracy, will be made infinitely harder if action is not taken now to strengthen both the spirit of reconciliation and the institutions that must underpin it.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One such is the constitution. The <font size=-1>ANC</font> takes this document seriously; the effort that has already gone into it--and in many ways it is a model of protected freedoms--suggests that this is not a piece of paper to be swept aside lightly, as so many others have been in Africa. That should be reassuring for all minorities, as should the tradition of an independent judiciary. But the new constitution, due to be adopted by Parliament on October 11th, is not accepted by all parties, as, ideally, it should be. In particular, Inkatha wants stronger powers for the provinces and the chiefs. Its readiness to live with the new constitution may have to be bought either by promising to redraft the provincial constitution of KwaZulu-Natal, where the party's power is concentrated, or even by offering a deputy presidency (one of the two is vacant) to Inkatha's leader, Chief Mangosuthu Buthelezi.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Inkatha's Zulus are one group who need to be accommodated if democracy is to be consolidated. The whites are another. Not all blacks are as forgiving as Mr Mandela. Some still seek vengeance for the crimes of apartheid, others merely want to press harder for black advancement. And no wonder: much power, especially in business, the civil service, the press and the universities, remains in white hands. It needs to be spread. Mr Mandela knows that that cannot happen instantly if peace and prosperity are to be secured. Others in the <font size=-1>ANC</font> need to make it plain that they realise this too.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That applies in particular to Thabo Mbeki, deputy president and Mr Mandela's anointed heir. He is a shrewd politician, and has shown himself ready to compromise with the <font size=-1>ANC</font>'s Zulu critics. But he lacks Mr Mandela's charm and personality, as well as, inevitably, his self-assurance and moral authority. The temptation for him will be to pick a path that does less to calm white fears and more to meet black demands than the route his boss has taken. That would be full of dangers. Plenty of old ghosts still haunt South Africa, as has been shown by the trial of Magnus Malan, a former defence minister, whose trial on charges of murder in the name of apartheid was due to end this week. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whites should, however, be clear that their privileges cannot endure. The aim must be a fair society for all, created by sweeping away the legacies of apartheid as fast as is compatible with nurturing stability and economic growth. Mr Mandela has given the new South Africa a famous start. Honour him for that. Criticise him, if need be, for his errors. But remember, above all, that what he has put in place must be fortified and extended by others if it is not soon to fall apart.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845078400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="sf0760.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
