<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Pump action</h2>Three oil giants are considering a liaison. America's <b>Texaco</b>, its joint venture with Saudi Aramco,<b> Star Enterprise</b>, and <b>Shell Oil</b>, the American unit of Royal Dutch/Shell, want to merge their American refining and marketing operations to create America's biggest oil retailer. <font size=-1>BP</font> and Mobil reached a similar deal involving their European downstream operations earlier this year.<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br> Shares in <b>Eurotunnel </b>fell heavily when trading in them resumed after details emerged of a plan to restructure its &#163;9.1 billion ($14.2 billion) debt. The complex plan would almost halve the company's annual debt-servicing costs, to about &#163;430m, partly through a &#163;1 billion debt-for equity swap that would give its 225 creditor banks a 45.5% stake in the Chunnel operator. The company's bankers and its shareholders must approve the scheme.</p><p>The <b>Dow </b>reached 6,000 in intra-day trading before falling again, pulling other bourses down with it. But Frankfurt hit another high.</p><p><h2>Change of cast</p></h2><b>Sony</b> had another go at tackling the problems of its troubled Sony Pictures Entertainment unit. The Japanese electronics giant named a new team to run its Hollywood business, led by John Calley, currently president of United Artists. To ease transpacific communications, Sony is appointing a Japanese executive to the team for the first time.<p>South Korea's <b>Hyundai Electronics</b> is setting up a &#163;1 billion ($1.6 billion) semiconductor plant in Scotland and creating 1,000 jobs initially, with the prospect of a further &#163;1.4 billion investment in a second chip plant. The two-phase deal would be one of the largest-ever inward investments in Europe.</p><p>After a year-long slump, demand for <b>semiconductors</b> is recovering. A ratio that measures the value of orders booked by North American chip makers to the value of their shipments reached its highest level this year in September.</p><p><h2>Taking credit</p></h2>Britain scrapped tax credits linked to <b>share buybacks </b> and special dividends just in time to scupper a plan by <b>Reuters</b>, a British information and media giant, to repurchase &#163;613m ($959m) of its shares. The government believes closing this tax loophole will add &#163;80m to its coffers in this fiscal year, rising to &#163;400m a year by 1998-99.<p>The <b>Nobel prize for economics</b> was shared by James Mirrlees of Cambridge University, a Scot, and William Vickrey of Columbia University in New York, who becomes the first Canadian to win the prize. They were rewarded for their work on "asymmetric information"--a situation in which two parties to a decision do not have the same facts.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p>American and European credit-rating agencies gave <b>Russia's debt</b> its first rating since the Russian Revolution. The higher-than-expected grading puts it on a par with American junk bonds.</p><p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br> Helped by its huge foreign-exchange reserves, <b>China's holdings </b>of American Treasury securities soared to $12 billion in the first half of this year, putting it behind only Britain ($19.7 billion) and Japan ($16 billion).</p><p><h2>Numbers games</p></h2>German utilities and international telecoms companies are preparing for the deregulation of <b>Germany's telecoms market</b>. <font size=-1>RWE</font>, an energy firm, pulled out of an alliance with British Telecom and Germany's Viag. Instead, it is joining Veba, another German firm, and Cable & Wireless, a British one. <font size=-1>BT</font> and Viag said they would seek other partners and press ahead with a joint application for Germany's <font size=-1>E2</font> mobile telephone network.<p>America's <b>ComputerAssociates</b>, a software giant, agreed to buy <b>Cheyenne Software</b>, which produces software for business computers and networks, for a hefty $1.2 billion or so.</p><p><b>American Brands</b>, which shed its American tobacco business in 1994, is abandoning tobacco altogether with the spin-off of <b>Gallaghers</b>, Britain's biggest cigarette maker. American is changing its name to Fortune Brands and will stick mainly to making whisky and golf clubs.</p><p><h2>Buying Europe</p></h2>European <b>state-owned giants</b> are up for sale. Italy set the second stage of its flotation of Eni, an energy and chemicals company: a maximum of 10% of its shares will be sold to raise over 5 trillion lire ($3.3 billion). Germany's offering was Deutsche Telekom, which plans to issue 500m new shares in a DM15 billion ($9.8 billion) initial offering. A fifth of France Telecom will be sold next year, for around FFr35 billion ($6.8 billion). And a 1% stake in Gazprom, Russia's huge gas monopoly, went on sale to foreigners for up to $380m.<p>The European Commission opened an inquiry into a proposal by the Italian government to inject 1.5 trillion lire ($980m) into <b>Alitalia</b>, the country's floundering state owned airline.</p><p>One of America's largest makers of heavy lorries, <b>Paccar</b>, ventured into Europe with an agreement to buy small-but efficient <b>DAF Trucks</b> of the Netherlands for 933m guilders ($544m). The Dutch government has a 39% stake in <b>DAF</b>, which has about 9% of the European truck market.</p></td></tr></table></center><p align=center><a href="ww0224.html">POLITICS THIS WEEK</a></p><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845078400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="ld4392.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
