<html><head><title> How wrong is it going?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" alt="Special feature"><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table><h1>How wrong is it going? </h1><p><b>South Africa's breezy post-apartheid self-confidence has crumbled</b></p>JUST over a year ago, the world was marvelling at South Africans' ability to bury the past, and reach across the racial divide to share the triumph of the rugby world cup. A jubilant President Nelson Mandela, dressed in the once-detested Springbok rugby jersey, seemed to embody the country's new, non-racial spirit. A year later the Springboks have now lost to New Zealand for the first time on South African soil--and the waving of the national flag of the apartheid era at the matches has revived the country's introspective fears over unhealed racial wounds. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Is sporting disenchantment the symbol of a wider malaise, and a worrying future? Perhaps so. Take one fortnight in August. Cape Town vigilantes burned a drug baron to death, in full view of television cameras and the police; the justice minister, Dullah Omar, had to move his family out of their Cape Town house in fear of their lives; the German company-secretary of <font size=-1>AEG </font>in South Africa was shot dead in his front drive in Johannesburg by car-hijackers; and the president of the Constitutional Court, Arthur Chaskalson, was held at gun point in his house.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lawlessness is not the only cause of the spreading gloom. Since mid-February, the currency, the  rand, has collapsed (see <a href="sf1.gif">chart</A>), losing 23% of its value against the dollar and falling below the level at which it might have been expected to settle after the overvaluation caused by the strong inflows of capital in 1994 and 1995. Had the rand stabilised, regardless of level, its depreciation might have been regarded as an opportunity to boost exports. Instead, the downward slide fosters the worry that the world's currency markets are giving a vote of no confidence in South African economic stability. The finance minister, Trevor Manuel, thanks to inexperience, and the central bank, thanks to low foreign reserves, were able to stem the fall only briefly.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To make matters worse, the African National Congress-led government seems to stumble from one blunder into another. In May, for example, a deputy minister, Bantu Holomisa, alleged that a cabinet member had received a bribe in apartheid days, and that the <font size=-1>ANC</font> had accepted 2m rand (at the time some $600,000) from a casino magnate in return for favours. "Blatant lies," declared the <font size=-1>ANC</font>, only to hear Mr Mandela later admit to having taken the money without telling anyone--though not in exchange for granting any favours. For his pains, the <font size=-1>ANC</font> expelled Mr Holomisa.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Do these dramas amount to a blip, the spasm of a country undergoing a wrenching transition from the tight controls of apartheid to a society of freedom and democracy? Or do they represent the first skid down the slippery African slope, one which has oiled the failure of so many other countries to build a prosperous democracy after winning political liberation? The questions are no longer the products of the old worries--the threat from the white far-right; the risk of Zulu-inspired secession; the danger of reckless public-spending. Certainly those worries remain, but no longer at the forefront of people's concerns. Today, three new anxieties stand out: lawlessness, unemployment and political accountability.<br></p><p><b>New--and uncomfortable</b><br>Behind smoked glass windows, an alien phenomenon has arrived in South Africa's cities: the sex shop. American accessories nestle alongside local ones "made in sizes for the African man". <i>Hustler</i> and <i>Penthouse </i>are on newsagents' shelves. There is even a soft-porn magazine, <i>Loslyf </i>(loose body), in Afrikaans. The end of apartheid ended a system of racial injustice--and lifted the repressive lid of Calvinist culture.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For many whites, the lifting of the old social controls is disconcerting. A decade ago, whites dressed up to go to the theatre or dine out in central Johannesburg; blacks stepped off the pavement for them, and conveniently disappeared home at night. Today, Johannesburg has become a heaving African city, its pavements crowded with hawkers of boiled sweets and witch medicine, from which white businessmen scurry home at the end of the day. Once, both Africa and decadent America could be kept at bay; now the fantasy is over.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As in Russia, the collapse of the authoritarian state in South Africa has unleashed social and political freedoms--and with them controversy and criminality. The reasons are the same: the end of the old order dramatically increased the number of new commercial opportunities but did so at a time when the criminal-justice system (designed for the old regime) had changed comparatively little. Organised crime has filled the resulting gap.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The police at present have records on 481 crime syndicates operating in the country. The opening of post-apartheid South Africa has turned the country into a trans-shipment point for drugs from Latin America and Asia, heading for the European market. Johannesburg's sophisticated banks have become a target for money-launderers. Much of the car-hijacking in Johannesburg is linked to syndicates that run luxury cars north to nearby countries such as Zambia.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not crime <i>per se </i>that grips the imagination but its random and violent nature. The murdered are no longer mainly the victims of political revenge, nor are they mafia-linked. Instead, violent crime touches all. Fully 58% of whites and 41% of blacks named crime as the country's most serious problem in a recent study sponsored by Nedcor, a South African bank. South Africa's murder rate is perhaps six times that of America, maybe five times that of Russia. Last year 19,000 people were murdered--52 each day. This was 4% more than in 1994. Car-hijackings around Johannesburg jumped 12%, to 8,524.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The study also exposed the weakness of the criminal-justice system. For every 450 crimes reported, there are 100 prosecutions, 77 convictions and a mere 36 imprisonments. Such is popular dissatisfaction that when the vigilante gangs burned to death the Cape Town drug baron, they won widespread public support. "I and several friends watched with undisguised admiration," wrote Thami Mazwai, a black writer. Weeks later, an opinion poll suggested 71% of South Africans want to bring back hanging, which was abolished only last year.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By itself, crime probably does not deter foreign investors much: if there is money to be made or a market to conquer, businessmen will go there. But crime puts off tourists. The number of foreign tourists visiting South Africa between January and May grew by only 2% over the same period in 1995, compared with year-on-year growth of 38% over the same period the previous year. Meanwhile, lawlessness feeds the feeling that the government is not in control.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What feeds it still more is the impression that some members of the police are in league with the criminals. In August, the commander of the vehicle-theft branch in Rustenburg, 100 kilometres from Johannesburg, and three other policemen, were charged in court with--guess what?--running a vehicle-theft syndicate. The problem compounds itself: poorly paid policemen who accept bribes to drop charges; excessive bureaucracy; public mistrust; ineffective prosecutors; loose conditions for bail; and overcrowded prisons. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of these problems, however, would be insurmountable if the government were determined enough to grasp them. Part of the solution must be political will. It is a measure of some progress that, for the first time, President Mandela has admitted that crime is "out of control", sending 500 soldiers to help the police in Johannesburg. The government has finally worked out a crime-prevention plan. Some road-blocks are said to have been spotted around Johannesburg. One police station, in the suburb of Rosebank, has even recruited street beggars as informal, unpaid assistants and issued them with fluorescent vests and identity cards. Another has obtained four horses so that policemen can peer over residents' high-perimeter walls.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To improve efficiency, McKinsey & Co, a consulting firm, has helped nine police stations reorganise themselves. At one, it found that only 7% of policemen spent time on "pro-active" (ie, preventive) policing; at another, less than half the vehicles were in service at any time. Reorganisation has now freed twice as many policemen to go on the beat at one station; at another, it cut the backlog in clearing dockets by 10% in the first month. By next May, McKinsey will be working in 100 stations across the country. Perhaps, therefore, South Africa's greatest enemy in its war against crime is its belief that little can be done about it.<br></p><p><b><b>Finding work . . . </b><br></b>Dawn, outside a Johannesburg metal-casting factory in January this year. Two thousand black South Africans are queuing in the street outside, drawn by rumours that the factory has 200 job vacancies. In the scuffle for a place in line, gunshots are fired. Eight people are shot dead. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of all the menaces to South Africa's stability, the most troubling is jobless growth. After a long recession, which ended in 1993, the economy is now growing robustly. Last year, <font size=-1>GDP</font> grew by 3.5% (see <a href="sf2.gif">chart</A>); but the number of recorded jobs inched up by just 0.6%. In the formal (ie, taxpaying) sector, the unemployment rate is 20%; add those who scratch a living informally by, say, hawking brushes or weeding gardens, and perhaps a third of the labour force is without work. Unlike in West Africa, where land has not historically been parcelled into a few large commercial farms, the jobless city-dwellers cannot fall back into the safety net of the family's subsistence-farming.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;South Africa's unresponsive labour market is not the result only of strong unions and labour protection. True, there are government-imposed non-wage costs, and it is costly to hire and difficult to fire. So companies look for capital-intensive, not labour-intensive, ways to grow. But the market's stickiness is also a product of apartheid's inferior education for blacks: unskilled black labour is cheap but unproductive; skilled labour is scarce, but costly. In addition, high tariff walls have sheltered manufacturers from competition, allowing skilled wages to rise and isolating South Africa's hierarchical companies from modern management practices. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result is a conundrum the government has yet to resolve. How can it maintain the rights that unions won for workers operating in miserable apartheid conditions, without jeopardising the economy's ability to create new jobs?<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the short-run, joblessness will probably worsen. The government promises to bring its budget deficit down from 5.4% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>in 1995-1996, to 4% by 1998. This will mean less spending and the loss of jobs in state firms and organisations. Meanwhile, as import tariffs are loweredto meet international obligations, firms will have to lay off workers to compete.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even foreign investment will not help much. In the two years to May 1996, foreign direct investment amounted to 18 billion rand, according to BusinessMap, a research group. But most has been to buy stakes in existing South African companies, often by firms which divested because of international sanctions in the apartheid days; they are not in greenfield investments creating immediate jobs.</p><p><b> . . . will not be easy</b><br>South Africa is a country of 41m people, fringed by African poverty, with a rigid labour market, an oligopolistic economy and high real interest-rates. Even gold output is declining, as mining the reserves becomes more difficult. Fast growth will not be easy.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet jobless growth is growth nonetheless. Two huge capital projects, to make stainless steel and smelt aluminium, are up and running; exports of coal and high-tech defence products are booming; luxury hotels are rising across the skyline in Johannesburg and Cape Town. Real domestic fixed investment grew by a year-on-year 5.5% in the second quarter of 1996. Privatisation could attract foreign cash and expertise, if the government would only get a move on.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, South Africans are, on average, no longer getting poorer. With annual population growth of just 2.1% and <font size=-1>GDP</font> growing by around 3.5%, <font size=-1>GDP</font> per head is on the rise. Indeed, the economy is in its best shape for years. The government inherited an economy emerging from over three years of recession and 20 years of double digit inflation. Now it has published a fiscally prudent macro-economic policy. Inflation, thoughrising, was still only 7.1% in July. The widening current-account deficit, of 2.3 billion rand in the first quarter of 1996, amounted to just 2% of <font size=-1>GDP</font>; Mexico's, before its currency crisis, was 7%.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike the rest of Africa, South Africa also has a diversified and sophisticated private sector and several home grown multinationals--with enough assets at home to keep a watchful eye on economic housekeeping. The Brenthurst group, an elite from South Africa's old business families, regularly visits Mr Mandela's home.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For all the fears that resentful <font size=-1>ANC</font> socialists would confiscate wealth, the new breed shares the same capitalist aspirations as the old. Though black incomes are barely a sixth of white ones, a black elite is rising on the back of government jobs and the promotion of black business. It is moving into the leafy avenues of formerly white Johannesburg suburbs, such as Kelvin and Sandton, and adopting the outward symbols of prestige--the <font size=-1>BMW</font>, swimming pool, golf handicap and black maid--that so mesmerise status-conscious whites. Most intriguing of all, the unions are becoming capitalists: dozens of them have become part-owners of a stake in Johnnic, an industrial holding company, sold by Anglo American in August to a black consortium.<br></p><p><b>Future imperfect</b><br>When South Africans are at their most despondent, they mutter about Zimbabwe. "Look north," says one black investment banker when asked to imagine South Africa in five years' time, "and temper it a bit." Without the unifying figure and moral integrity of Mr Mandela, who retires in 1999, what is to stop South Africa slipping the way of Zimbabwe: a supposed multiparty democracy ruled as a de facto one-party state, with a government that rides in limousines, periodically clamps down on the press, and blames white ownership of the economy for the country's ills? <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>ANC</font>, which won a handsome 63% of the vote at the 1994 general election, looks unassailable. Though their leaders deny it, political opposition remains ethnically divided: the Inkatha Freedom Party represents chiefly Zulus, the Democratic Party chiefly whites, the Freedom Front chiefly Afrikaners. Even the National Party--once all-white, now vigorously courting the non-white vote--won only 20% of the 1994 vote. At national level, disgruntlement with the <font size=-1>ANC</font> is more likely to translate into apathy than electoral protest. The worry is that the political elite, unburdened by electoral worries, will grow increasingly distant from those who elected it, and arrogant in its use of power.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Problems are appearing. In June, the public protector investigated how the health department had spent 14m rand ($3.2m) on a single musical play designed to promote "<font size=-1>AIDS-</font>awareness". He found that the health minister, Nkosazana Zuma, had misled parliament over the matter. She did not resign. Dr Zuma then declared that a business donor would foot part of the bill--but would not name him. When pressure grew to do so, she announced that the mystery donor had withdrawn his offer. In an uncharacteristic racial swipe, President Mandela accused the "white-owned media" of victimising her.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>ANC</font> might claim in its own defence that it is victim to its own determination to prise open the once-murky workings of government. The National Party, in apartheid days, scarcely felt accountable to anybody; patronage and corruption went on behind impenetrable walls. But the <font size=-1>ANC</font> can hardly be judged by the miserable standards of those who went before when it has declared itself the champion of accountable and open government. Contempt for parliament, suspicion of the press, intolerance of criticism: there is enough to breed disquiet. What will check South Africa's rulers from heading Zimbabwe's way?<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the shortrun, the answer probably lies not in opposition parties (though noisy minority parties--and a resentful black constituency, fed up with President Mandela's failure to punish whites--could one day be mobilised from the left). <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead, the safeguard may rest in the new constitution, which protects individuals from abuse by government. Or in the fact that two of the nine provinces--the Western Cape (run by the National Party) and KwaZulu-Natal (run by Inkatha)--are not controlled by the <font size=-1>ANC</font>. Or in the informal organisations--the women's groups, church groups, street committees, parents' associations-- that rail against the government on behalf of ordinary South Africans. Lastly, it rests in a vigilant press, learning fast how to act as a check on government, and in a political leadership which worries about what outsiders think.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"President Mandela's visit to London in July represented the end of a chapter," says Jack Spence, director of studies at Britain's Royal Institute of International Affairs. There was something of a rite of passage in the extraordinary welcome given to him by the British state, a big congratulatory hug for coming of age, and a farewell wave of good luck as South Africa begins a new era. Now, however, the country has to face reality--and start delivering. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;South Africa suffers from schizophrenic foreign perceptions and turbulent domestic mood-swings. The euphoria of the political transition in 1994 inflated expectations. South Africa was hailed as the continent's saviour, a tiger economy for Africa. As sentiment now swings the other way, South Africa is being smudged with the brush of African failure. "If South Africa, with all its problems and opportunities, were geographically located in Latin America or Asia, observers would be far more optimistic about its prospects," says Robert Schrire, of the University of Cape Town. "However unfair and inaccurate, South Africa is viewed through the prisms of the African experiences."<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Asia-like economic success, or stagnant African disappointment? Mundane reality will surely lie in between.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845078400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="am3077.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
