<html><head><title> Raining on Dole's parade </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Raining on Dole's parade</h1>

<font size=1>HARTFORD, CONNECTICUT, AND LYNDHURST, NEW JERSEY</font><p>
"WEEEE'VE got the momentum," Bob Dole told New Jersey this week. He arrived there fresh from Sunday's televised debate with Bill Clinton, in buoyant mood for a two-day bus tour. His campaign manager predicted the gap in the polls would shrink to single digits by week's end. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But by Tuesday, the second day of the bus tour, this was what the Dole momentum looked like. The polls had declared Mr Clinton the winner of the debate in Hartford, Connecticut, and the president's lead had even edged up a tad. As Mr Dole's bus-- called Asphalt I, "American Dream Machine"--arrived at Riverside Park in Lyndhurst, north of Newark in New Jersey, the skies were darkening ominously. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The crowd for the morning rally was thin, perhaps 300 people (including a few holding "Keep Abortion Legal" signs), leaving embarrassingly large patches of green grass between the television cameras and the podium. The musical introduction for Mr Dole was bungled, the candidate's speech was lacklustre. Dick Zimmer, the Republican senatorial candidate, who might be expected to attach himself like glue to Mr Dole if he reckoned it would help his own chances, was notable by his absence. Worse, a <font size=-1>TV</font> appearance the next day on "Oprah", an ideal forum for appealing to women voters, had fallen through.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By the time the "American Dream Machine" arrived at its next stop, Morristown, rain was falling. Although the crowd was bigger and Mr Dole did a brave job of speaking in the wet (proposing a "tax credit for rain"), it was no fun. The two open-air rallies and a fundraising meeting scheduled for the rest of the day were cancelled, and Mr Dole retreated to the "Citizen's Ship" to fly back to Washington.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dole momentum is proving hard to achieve. It was supposed to happen when he left the Senate, then at the Republican convention, and now with the two presidential debates. With less than a month to polling day, time is running out. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fairness, Mr Dole seemed genuinely pleased with his performance in Sunday's debate. He had held his own with the man his campaign had dubbed the greatest debater since Demosthenes. In New Jersey, he was greeted on his first day by blissful sunshine and respectable if not overflowing crowds. He told them Mr Clinton was a "stealth liberal" and assured them they could trust Bob Dole to keep his word, including his promise of a 15% tax cut--indeed, as president he would come to New Jersey to sign the tax-cutting legislation. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New Jersey is one of the "battleground" states Mr Dole must carry to win the election. He trails there by 7-14 points in the latest polls, but is heartened by the example of New Jersey's governor, Christine Whitman, who accompanied him on the bus tour. Three years ago Mrs Whitman, who also campaigned on a platform of tax cuts, was 22 points behind at this stage of the race for governor, and went on to win.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Mr Dole is to pull off a similar feat, he needs to change the dynamics of the contest. He failed to do that in the 90-minute Hartford debate. True, he succeeded in being warm and witty, a far cry from the uncaring extremist portrayed in Democratic advertisements. Most people watching liked him more at the end of the debate than at the beginning.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But that is not enough. Mr Dole was not terribly good at conveying his ideas for the future. And in order to avoid appearing mean, he passed up the opportunity-- served up on a platter by the debate's moderator, Jim Lehrer--to attack Mr Clinton's character. Mr Dole reckoned this was "an invitation to nowhere", and stuck to policy issues. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is, policy issues suit Mr Clinton fine. The president could reel off his achievements over the past four years, especially the impressive figures on jobs, growth and deficit-reduction. He could list umpteen policy ideas designed to relate to voters' everyday concerns, from more cops on the streets to <font size=-1>V</font>-chips in televisions and tax credits for education. And of course he could repeat his favourite campaign metaphor of bridge-building to the 21st century.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It was not exactly a glittering performance, but it was sufficient to keep the race looking much as it did beforehand, which is to say handsomely favouring Mr Clinton. Hence the almost taunting confidence with which Mr Clinton set off from Hartford to pick up endorsements from corporate America and to travel into what used to be the staunch Republican territory of New Hampshire, where he has a 21-point lead in the polls. If there was any change in momentum, it was not evident by mid-week.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What does Mr Dole try next? Another bus tour would take him this week to another battleground state, Ohio. He was due to be joined there by Colin Powell, amid speculation that he might announce some of the names voters could expect to see in a Dole administration. Then he heads for California in preparation for the second (and last) presidential debate, in San Diego on October 16th.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tough decisions are crowding in. How should he allocate its resources in the final weeks of the campaign? Should he abandon expensive California in order to concentrate on states where he has a more plausible chance of winning? Above all, if everything else fails to produce the magical momentum, should he change tactics and get personal?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Dole campaign this week launched a new advertisement, airing on Christian radio stations, which talks of a "moral crisis" in the White House. In Lyndhurst on Tuesday Mr Dole was preceded on the podium by Michael Chertoff, the former Senate Whitewater counsel. "Get aggressive, Mr Dole, in the next debate," was the advice shouted by one supporter at the end of the rally. "Less foreign policy, more character." America's eyes will now turn to San Diego to see if he takes that advice. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
