<html><head><title> Kemp gored </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Kemp gored</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
AMERICAN life is plagued by electronic voices on the telephone, which forward calls and recite timetables in a relentlessly efficient and tedious way. Al Gore is one of those voices with a pretty face. At the vice-presidential debate on October 9th, he methodically defeated Jack Kemp, his Republican opponent. He was better briefed, stuck more closely to the questions, and attacked deftly. He was also dull beyond belief.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Defeating Mr Kemp, mind you, was not especially difficult. Mr Kemp made a fool of himself on foreign policy, waffling on Haiti, and eccentrically blaming the Clinton administration for causing the devaluation of Mexico's peso in 1994-95. Mr Kemp was also embarrassing on his supposed speciality, the economy. At one point he blurted out that the current long-run growth rate of 2.5% could be doubled, an outrageous claim. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kemp was better at pleading the cause of inner cities. But Mr Gore can also do that (with statistics). Mr Kemp called for enterprise zones for poor urban areas. Mr Gore boasted about the empowerment zones that the Clinton administration has set up. Your correspondent had begun watching the debate with three eager friends. At about this point, all three wandered off.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However boring, the debate did reveal something about the last weeks of this campaign. Mr Kemp was invited by the moderator to attack President Clinton's character. He refused to do so, suggesting that the Dole team remains unwilling to exploit its greatest potential advantage. Instead, Mr Kemp offered a mix of nutty criticisms (as on Mexico) and artificial disagreements (as on inner-city policy). It is hard to see how either can dent the Clinton-Gore lead. Ghetto dwellers are not about to vote Republican, no matter what Mr Kemp may say.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The debate also shed some light on the next presidential campaign, in 2000. Mr Gore was already the front-runner for the Democratic nomination; he is even more so now. Unless a man of equal competence but greater passion emerges, it will be hard to topple him. But Mr Kemp has seen his stock slip a bit.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ed Rollins, who chaired Mr Kemp's disastrous presidential bid in 1988, says of his friend: "He was impossible to discipline and simply wouldn't listen." The lack of discipline came out on Wednesday. Kemp 2000 is a poor bet.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
