<html><head><title> Campaign issues: Opinion polls </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Campaign issues: Opinion polls</b></p>
<h1>Some margin for error</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
IMAGINE the impossible: an American presidential election without opinion polls. It would be much more fun. There would be real tension about the outcome. As it is, polls have been the driving force of this campaign, shaping the candidates' messages and determining the dynamics of the race. Thanks to the polls, Bill Clinton has been able to cultivate an aura of inevitability. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet polls can mislead. A salutory lesson comes from Britain's experience in 1992. The major eve-of-election polls showed Labour just ahead, but John Major's Conservatives confounded everyone, winning by eight points. This was the British pollsters' most spectacular error ever, and it sent them into a painful post-election analysis to work out what went wrong. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They concluded that it was a mixture of things. There was a last-minute swing. There were problems with the method used to obtain a representative sample of the electorate. And there was a so-called "spiral of silence": many people, too embarrassed to admit that they would vote Conservative, claimed to be undecided or refused to answer questions.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Could distortions similar to those in Britain be affecting American polls this time? Some of the polls certainly raise eyebrows. In the space of five days late last month, the <font size=-1>CNN</font>/<i>USA Today</i>/Gallup tracking poll (a rolling sample taken over three nights) showed Mr Clinton's lead over Bob Dole moving from ten points to 25. It is hard to believe that voter opinion is really that volatile.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The odd rogue result is not on its own terribly significant. More to the point, the American practice of using computerised telephone banks to select a random sample of voters avoids the British pollsters' problematic quest for sociologically representative "quotas". But it raises other worries. John Zogby, whose tracking polls, in contrast to others, now show Mr Clinton's lead in single digits, and who uses a slightly different sampling method, reckons other polls "are talking to too many Democrats". The list of potential pitfalls suggests that the polls' margin of error may be greater than is generally acknowledged.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;First, there is the question of the non response rate--"the dirty little secret of the profession", says Karlyn Bowman, a poll watcher at the American Enterprise Institute, a Washington think-tank. In face-to face interviews, some 20% of people may refuse to answer questions. But in telephone polls, when people are often either not at home or choose to hang up, the non response rate is much higher (typically at least 50%). Diligent pollsters will repeatedly try to call back; but the non-response problem may be getting worse, as Americans lead ever-busier lives and do not hesitate to slam the phone down on what they assume are just more telemarketing calls.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pollsters rarely reveal the non-response rate. Yet it could be that Dole supporters are hanging up in greater numbers than Clinton-backers. If it is uncool to admit to being a Dole voter, a "spiral of silence" could be depressing Mr Dole's score in the polls.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The treatment of "undecided" respondents--say, 7%--probably also exaggerates Mr Dole's troubles. Two-thirds of the undecideds typically break for the challenger. This is not reflected in most polls, nor do published polls usually reveal the intensity of a candidate's support. Many respondents say they are leaning towards one side or the other, but may still change their minds. Add together the undecideds and the leaners in the presidential contest, and as much as 40% of the vote may still be up for grabs.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then there is the matter of turnout, a bigger complication for American pollsters than for British ones. The poor and members of ethnic minorities are most likely to support Mr Clinton, but they are least likely to vote. That explains why Mr Clinton's lead is greater among registered voters (16 points in a recent Pew poll) than among "likely voters" (12 points). The better pollsters ask a series of careful questions in an effort to establish whether a respondent is likely to vote, but this is not an exact science, and this year interest in the election seems to be low. In any case, not all pollsters are as scrupulous as they should be about their methods.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So is there hope yet for Mr Dole, who tells every audience not to believe the polls? Any systematic bias in the polls so far might open the possibility of a bigger-than-usual late swing, even of an upset victory. More than the presidency is at stake. If the presidential race is in fact closer than the polls suggest, then the Republicans' chances of retaining control of Congress are that much greater.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The size and persistence of Mr Clinton's lead argues against a surprise on November 5th. Moreover, the surveys of the major polling organisations that are not corner cutters all show essentially the same thing: a solid Clinton lead, larger than anything that has been reversed at this late stage since polling began. "Our track record is pretty good," notes Frank Newport of Gallup. True, but so was that of the British pollsters before 1992. <br>
<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
