<html><head><title>Election Billboard</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><center><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><p align=center><img src="../images/am.gif" alt="American Survey" border=0></p></center><p align=center><img src="../images/eb.gif" alt="Election Billboard" border=0></p><p align=center><font size=-1></font></p></center><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><center><p align=center><img src="am1.gif" width="227" height="166" alt="Election graph"></p><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Trends of the week</h2><b>Show: </b>About 31m households tune in to the first presidential debate. This is some 14% fewer than watched the first debate in 1992, according to Nielsen ratings. <center>***</center><b>Scorecard: </b>Instant post-debate polls show some 50% judging Mr Clinton the winner, 30% Mr Dole. But three out of four people also say Mr Dole did better than they expected.<br><center>***</center><b>Superhighway:</b> "Spin Alley", the packed area in the basement of Hartford's Civic Centre set aside for campaign spin doctors to meet spin-craving journalists. <br><center>***</center><b>Surrealism: </b>Presidential spokesman Michael McCurry being interrupted while in full flow in Spin Alley: "Mike, could you say hello to some parliamentarians from Mongolia?" Mr McCurry tells them they are witnessing a great exercise in democracy.<br><center>***</center><b>Sideshow:</b> Ross Perot, the Reform Party's candidate, has to make do with a brief post-debate interview with <font size=-1>CNN</font>'s Larry King, alongside other third-party candidates. He admits his exclusion from the debate and difficulties in buying air-time have "melted down" his election strategy.<br></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><b>Sideswipe:</b> Mr Clinton picks up the endorsement of more than 2,500 corporate bosses, including the <font size=-1>CEO</font> of Sprint, one of the biggest employers in Mr Dole's native Kansas.<br><center>***</center><b>Dolebites: </b>To a rally in Toms River, New Jersey: "This is not rocket science, this is a tax cut." Pointing to children in Red Bank, New Jersey: "I see a lot of $500 credits running around here." Over his bus loudspeaker to a group of protesters in Milltown, New Jersey: "Thanks for coming anyways. You'll still get the tax cut." <br><center>***</center><b>Bozobite:</b> Man in the crowd Mr Dole was greeting in Lyndhurst, New Jersey: "Please get Bozo out of the White House." Mr Dole (who, during the debate, had chided Mr Clinton for disrespect to presidents): "Bozo's on his way out."<br><center>***</center><b>Entrepreneurs: </b>During the Dole campaign stop in Red Bank, New Jersey, the owner of the Dublin House pub advertises 15% off beer. "If you can do it, Mr Dole, so can we."<br></td></tr></table></center><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845078400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="br7526.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
