<html><head><title> Nursery lessons </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Nursery lessons</h1>

A SPATE of press reports has claimed that the government's pilot scheme for nursery vouchers is in deep trouble. But these partly reflect the wishful thinking of the opponents of vouchers. When Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, sang the praises of vouchers at the Tory conference on October 10th, she seemed to have overcome her earlier doubts about them. Evidence from three of the four councils piloting vouchers contradicts a leaked memo from Westminster council, the fourth, which says they are a bureaucratic nightmare and are unlikely to create new nursery places.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Admittedly there have been some hitches. Kensington and Chelsea council says the system for distributing the vouchers, worth &#163;1,100 a year for each four-year-old, needs to be simplified, and that more effort must be made to explain the scheme to parents. It is also worried about the variation in standards between some private nursery providers. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But these problems are far from insurmountable, and Kensington also says there is "little doubt that the private sector will be interested in developing nursery provision, in part at least as a result of the voucher scheme." The other two pilot schemes--in London's Wandsworth and in Norfolk--have experienced no serious administrative problems, and both seem to have encouraged private and voluntary groups to create new places.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However they fare, the voucher experiments will be terminated prematurely next spring. If the Tories win the next election, they have promised to introduce vouchers nationwide whether or not their faults have been ironed out. More likely, Labour will win and scrap the voucher experiments without bothering to find out whether or not vouchers can create extra nursery places, at little extra public expense.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
