<html><head><title>Can Israel rekindle peace</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>Can Israel rekindle peace?</h1>


WITH Israel and the Palestinians sliding into war, a restraining hand was vital. Bill Clinton offered it, and for that the world should be glad. But the relief may be short lived. Though the summons to Washington got Binyamin Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat talking to each other, nothing was resolved. The two will meet again, to talk again (see <a href="ir5984.html">page</a>). But it will be no more than a brief truce unless Israel's new government can be persuaded to acknowledge the underlying deal done by its predecessor: the return of occupied land in exchange for peace.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both Israelis and Palestinians were responsible for the violence that cost 58 Palestinians and 15 Israelis their lives last week. Yet outsiders-- friendly countries in Europe and Asia straightaway, America probably not until the bonds of the presidential election are loosened--need to concentrate their persuasion on the Israelis because it is they, since their change of government in May, who have virtually blown out the flame of peace. And it is they alone who can now relight it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Netanyahu rejects this. He went into the Washington talks in a bluster of indignation, demanding an assurance that Palestinian security forces would never again fire at their Israeli counterparts. It was terrible, indeed, that the distrust should have come to that. Law and order in the territories depend on the Israeli and Palestinian forces co-operating, not shooting at each other. Tensions snapped as Israeli soldiers fired at stone-throwing protesters across the checkpoints that divide Israel from autonomous Palestinian zones. The Palestinian police joined in. It should not have happened. It should not happen again. But frustration often begets violence. After nearly four months of Mr Netanyahu's prime ministership, many Palestinians had come to believe that the prospects for peace were so poor that they had little to lose by breaking the rules. They probably still do.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With difficulty, the immediate crisis is being sorted out, including the wretched tunnel whose opening set off the Palestinian protests--a trivial issue that has developed into a symbol of Israeli arrogance toward Muslim and Palestinian rights in East Jerusalem. But Israel still has to make up its mind on a much more fundamental matter. What should it do about the Oslo peace process, signed to general acclaim three years ago, but virtually halted by Mr Netanyahu?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Israel has four broad choices, of which one is probably untenable. That is its current policy of paying lip service to the peace process, expecting peace on the ground but acting provocatively. Mr Netanyahu's belief, repeated before and after his election, that the Palestinians are realists who will adjust to new firmness and to new limits is simply not true. Or rather it is not true that they will adjust peaceably--especially when they see changes to the status quo that are designed to destroy for ever their grander aspirations.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A second choice would be to seek to impose peace through force. Mr Netanyahu has threatened as much: he has declared himself ready to disarm the Palestinian police, thus enabling his government to continue on its current path without armed resistance. But that could not be attempted without entering Palestinian cities with maximum force, or without putting all the territories, Gaza included, back under military occupation. The bloodshed would be horrific, and the future black, without a trace of the security that Mr Netanyahu has promised his people.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A third, less bloody, choice would be to try to redefine the peace process by agreement. Mr Netanyahu hates the course set at Oslo. His interpretation of a permanent settlement for the Palestinians--including their status, the future of Jerusalem, the position of Jewish settlers--has nothing in common with Mr Arafat's. Maybe it makes no sense to embark, merely for the sake of talking, on the final negotiations that were officially launched in May, when Israel was still ruled by the Labour government of Shimon Peres. They would get nowhere. Better perhaps for Israel to reach a tacit understanding with the Palestinians to implement the interim accords but put longer-term matters on hold. The Palestinians would consolidate what they have--and go back to waiting.<br>
<b><br>
</p><p><b>Best to be bold</b></b><br>
One difficulty is that the Palestinians' patience might not prove infinite. Another is that, for this option to work, Mr Netanyahu would have to honour his promise to carry out the commitments made by Mr Peres. That does not mean, as he suggests, renegotiating terms that have already been laboriously negotiated; it means implementing them with minor modifications. It also means, and this is even harder for Mr Netanyahu's men, that Israel should not pre-empt a final settlement by turning the West Bank into a network of roads and the outskirts of East Jerusalem into vast Jewish suburbs. To do that would merely turn this option into a variant of the untenable present course.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fourth and boldest choice for Mr Netanyahu would be to confound both his friends and his enemies. He could avoid the obstacles of an interim accord, all of them immensely difficult for a rightist-religious coalition, by leaping swiftly ahead to the big one: a final settlement. In doing this, he would be following a line of precedents. Hardline governments, from time to time, have pulled off coups that had eluded their more liberal predecessors: Menachem Begin made peace with Egypt, Richard Nixon opened the road to China. Now, if he is up to it, it could be Mr Netanyahu's turn.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the aim would not, with the taste of violence still on the tongue, be to seek some sort of cosy peace. The key word, these days, is "separation". This is an admission of defeat, perhaps. Yet, for the security of both, the Israeli and Palestinian peoples may need to hold themselves separate. This has been done, often enough, on a temporary basis by not allowing Palestinians into Israel. A permanent way of achieving much the same result would be to allow the Palestinians their own state, and draw a firm frontier between it and Israel.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Without ever publicly saying so, Israel's Labour government was coming to see a separate Palestinian state as the most feasible answer to the problem of co-existence. A map had been secretly drawn, clustering most of the Jewish settlements in the West Bank in a new, safely Israeli, bulge of the old green line--an adjustment that would cause endurable pain to both sides. It was a good compromise, but Yitzhak Rabin and Mr Peres were both too cautious to back it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A chance for Mr Netanyahu to show up his predecessors' lack of courage? Why not? If the candle of peace is not soon relit, the next spark will set off a conflagration, perhaps extending far into the Arab world. None of the ways forward is safe--and standing still could be the most dangerous of all. Given the choices, the boldest step could be the safest.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
