<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width="271" height="24" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>By Kabul ford</h2>
<p><b>Taliban forces </b>occupied Kabul, the Afghan capital, executed a former communist president, Najibullah, and imposed strict Islamic law. They prepared to attack the Panjshir valley, stronghold of Ahmad Shah Masoud, the military chief of the country's ousted government.</p>
<p>In response, Russia called for a summit of leaders of the Commonwealth of Independent States to discuss <b>Afghanistan</b>, amid fears that the taking of Kabul could strengthen the hand of Islamic rebels in neighbouring Tajikistan. Alexander Lebed, Russia's national security adviser, said Russia should help the Afghan government, driven out by the Taliban.</p>
<p><b>Kashmir</b>'s National Conference party, which wants the state to remain part of India, swept to victory in the first local elections since a separatist revolt broke out in 1990. </p>
<p>Myanmar's military government blockaded the home of <b>Aung San Suu Kyi </b>after she called a meeting of her National League for Democracy. Soldiers detained more than 500 of her supporters, later releasing 163.</p>
<p>New Zealand apologised to a <b>Maori tribe </b>for occupying its land 131 years ago and hanging its chief. The government agreed to pay NZ$40m ($27.6m) in compensation.</p>
<h2>Bleak talks</h2>
<p>After being summoned for two days of<b> crisis talks</b> on the Middle East as Bill Clinton's guests at the White House,<b> </b>Binyamin Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat could agree on nothing, except to continue negotiating when they returned home. Jordan's King Hussein was in attendance but Egypt's President Mubarak declined, reflecting the Arab belief that Mr Clinton was not prepared to exert real pressure on Israel to save the peace process.</p>
<p><b>Palestinians</b> in the West Bank and Gaza remained under strict "internal closure", unable to leave their neighbourhoods. Israeli tanks ringed their cities, and the army threatened to shoot anyone coming near checkpoints. A Palestinian demonstrator was killed near Hebron.</p>
<p>Commonwealth ministers abandoned talk of sanctions against <b>Nigeria</b>, agreeing to send a fact-finding mission-- and even that without guarantees, demanded earlier, that it would be able to meet opposition groups.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Petty cash</h2>
<p>Before Congress adjourned for <b>serious campaigning</b>, the Senate and the House of Representatives passed a $400 billion budget, ensuring that the American government could continue to operate while its representatives were on the road.</p>
<p>Congress also sent Bill Clinton a bill to strengthen <b>the border patrol </b>and to increase criminal penalties against smuggling aliens and document fraud. The Republicans wanted much tougher legislation that would have prevented illegal aliens receiving benefits. </p>
<p>Governor Pete Wilson of California signed a bill, the first of its kind, barring the state government from buying goods made in <b>labour camps</b>.</p>
<p>The Supreme Court agreed to decide the constitutionality of state laws that stop doctors assisting terminally ill people to commit <b>suicide</b>.</p>
<p><b>Colombia</b> saw more clashes between guerrillas and army. Six government men died in one day.</p>
<h2>Converging</h2>
<p>Several members of the European Union presented budgets designed to make them fit for <b>economic and monetary union</b>. Italy shocked financial markets by doubling its planned savings for next year, giving the country an outside chance of qualifying for <font size=-1>EMU</font> in 1999. Spain and Belgium unveiled tough fiscal programmes as well.</p>
<p>France's prime minister, Alain Jupp<e-acute>, won a <b>vote of confidence</b> in parliament, despite recent sniping from members of his own party. Mr Jupp<e-acute> defended his austere 1997 budget plan and promised action to reduce rising unemployment. Teachers staged a 24-hour strike against the budget.</p>
<p>Annual <b>inflation</b> in the European Union fell to a record low of 2.3% in August. Sweden's inflation rate of 0.3% was Europe's lowest; Greece's 8.5% rate was the highest. In all, nine of the 15 members had inflation rates below 2%.</p>
<p>The <font size=-1>UN</font> Security Council voted formally to end economic sanctions against <b>Serbia </b>after western observers approved the results of Bosnia's election. But Serbia is still excluded from the <font size=-1>UN</font> and international financial institutions like the World Bank.</p>

</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="bw0754.html">BUSINESS THIS WEEK</a></p>
<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?844473600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
