</font></p></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><p align=center><img src="ameb.gif" width="227" height="166" alt="Election graph"></p><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Trends of the week</h2><b>Hotspot:</b> The Middle East. Mr Clinton convenes a Washington summit to salvage the peace process, to accusations of "photo-op foreign policy" from Bob Dole.<br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Sunspot: </b>Bal Harbour. Mr Dole retreats to his Florida condo to prepare for the presidential debate on October 6th. "Late Show" host David Letterman quips: "He wants to be tanned and well-rested for his concession speech."<br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Blind spots:</b> Barely half of those asked in one poll know that Mr Dole has a disability. Another poll reveals that one in four voters do not know that Ross Perot is running at all, and nearly four out of ten cannot name Jack Kemp as Mr Dole's running mate.<br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Ignored spots:</b> The 17 states where neither Mr Dole nor Mr Clinton delivered a major speech or advertised significantly in September, according to the Annenberg School for Communication. The states: Alabama, Alaska, the Carolinas, Hawaii, Idaho, Indiana, Kansas, Oklahoma, Maine, Maryland, Minnesota, Mississippi, Montana, New Hampshire, Vermont and Wyoming.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>

<b>Verdict: </b>A federal judge rejects Mr Perot's effort to force his way into the presidential debates, but gives the right to appeal against the verdict before the first debate, in Hartford on Sunday.<br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Promise: </b>Campaigning in California, Mr Kemp pledges not merely to halve capital gains tax, as promised in the Dole plan, but to eliminate it by the end of the century.<br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Barb: </b>The Clinton camp refers to Mr Dole's "Midnight in America campaign".<br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Counter-barb:</b> Mr Dole on Mr Clinton in Kirtland, Ohio: "Would you buy a used election promise from this man?"<br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Rush: </b>To leave Washington. The 104th Congress wraps up its (less-than-revolutionary) business, and lawmakers dash home to campaign to be in the 105th. <br>
<p align=center>***</p>
<b>Tip: </b>Watch how the New York Yankees perform in the baseball play-offs. Since 1945, they have appeared in five election year World Series. When they lose (1960, 1964, 1976), a Democrat wins the White House; when they win (1952, 1956), the Republican triumphs.<br>
<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

