<html><head><title>Israelis divided</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width="224" height="26" alt="International" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Israelis divided</h1>

<font size=1>JERUSALEM </font><p>
LAST week's bloodshed has hardened Israelis in their polarised beliefs. Peace Now, a grassroots movement, staged a large anti-government demonstration in Tel Aviv on October 1st. But pro-government demonstrators too were filling the streets. Their red and blue banners, "Be Strong and of Good Courage", greet motorists driving from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Early polls show a we-told-you-so reaction from both sides of the divide. The right, whose slogan two years ago was, "Don't give them  guns", feel vindicated. On the left, politicians and demonstrators are demanding an inquiry into Mr Netanyahu's decision to open the tunnel--a demand fuelled by the continuing efforts of the defence minister, the army senior command and the Shin Bet security service to distance themselves from the timing of that decision.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In Washington, Mr Netanyahu confounded the politicians plotting his downfall. At the height of last week's violence, he blustered in public, but seemed at a loss for what to do. Mutterings began to be heard even within his own camp about his fitness for the job. Some Likud old-timers have always regarded the 46-year-old, American educated Mr Netanyahu as an<i> arriviste</i> lightweight and (with hindsight) see his decision to open the tunnel as a product of inexperience and brashness.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In former times, a groundswell would have developed to replace Mr Netanyahu with another Likud figure. But under the reformed Israeli constitution, a prime minister is directly elected and hard to shift. And Mr Netanyahu's firmness in Washington has, at least for now, silenced his critics. The jubilant right, across its spectrum, has hailed him as a hero.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The left is close to despair, its one hope for peace being that a re-elected Mr Clinton will apply the pressure he dare not apply now. The crisis had ignited the Labour opposition's hope of being invited to join a government of national unity. With that in mind, diehard supporters of Shimon Peres gathered on October 2nd to demand that he stay on indefinitely as leader of the Labour Party. Under its rules, the party must vote for a new leader within 14 months of an electoral defeat. Mr Peres, 73, has said he will not stand again, and half-a-dozen candidates, headed by Ehud Barak, a former foreign minister and army chief of staff, would be happy to succeed him. But with the peace process on the verge of dying, said his supporters, Labour must not jettison the man who largely brought it into being and may yet be called on to revive it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One man could force Mr Netanyahu to broaden his government: Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, spiritual mentor of the Sephardic-religious party, Shas, which, with ten seats, is a pivotal coalition ally. On September 29th, both Mr Peres and Mr Netanyahu made (separate) Feast of Tabernacles calls on him. He merely requested the rivals to "consult", which they dutifully did.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; In the occupied territories, the settlers are now rejoicing. And the army is poised to deal the Palestinians devastating punishment. Senior officers say they have been ordered to use all the firepower they need to crush any renewed assaults on military checkpoints or other targets by Palestinian civilians or policemen. The army is smarting, particularly, over an episode on September 26th, when six soldiers were killed in a fight at a Jewish holy site in Nablus. Next time, says the army, we go in with tanks, barrels blazing if necessary. The tanks are already in position.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
