<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/05-10-96/ir5980.html 199.173.162.110 19970215024543 text/html 5848
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 02:41:40 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 03-Oct-96 19:49:31 GMT
Content-length: 5661
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Under threat</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width="224" height="26" alt="International" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Under threat</h1>

<font size=1>RAMALLAH </font><p>
IT WAS the worst violence in the occupied territories since 1967: 73 people killed, 58 of them Palestinian, and 1,500 injured. Palestinians hope that last week's fighting will convince everybody that the Oslo peace process cannot endure under the terms dictated by Israel's hardline prime minister. But they fear the worst, and the news from Washington confirmed their gloom: the peace process is "on the verge of collapse", said the mayor of Hebron. In Jerusalem Faisal Husseini, the <font size=-1>PLO</font>'s top man there, said he "was never as pessimistic as today".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Israelis, in their fashion, seem to agree. After last week's fighting, they slapped an "internal closure" on the West Bank and Gaza. Some 2m Palestinians are immobilised, within their local "autonomous areas", with Israeli tanks ringing the main cities and helicopter gunships at the ready. Even the sick are barred from moving from their homes in one area to hospitals in another. Under orders from Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian police are keeping people away from Israeli army checkpoints. Wisely: the army has said it will shoot on sight any Palestinian who comes near its soldiers. Already, on October 2nd, one demonstrator near Hebron was shot dead and others wounded.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ominously, the army has suspended all joint patrols with the Palestinian police, pending a "thorough investigation" into the breakdown of security co-ordination which led to gun battles between the two forces. Palestinians can guess what this means. The Oslo process is predicated on co-operation between the two forces. If this is abandoned, so too is Oslo. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Were the gun battles the result of a calculated gamble by Mr Arafat to force Mr Netanyahu's hand and get the process moving again? So the Israeli government says. Palestinians believe that once their demonstrations were met by Israeli army gunfire--and that was the sequence of events in Ramallah and Gaza last week--the Palestinian police were bound to fire back.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Mr Arafat certainly decided to raise the stakes, after Mr Netanyahu authorised a new exit from the tunnel in Jerusalem's Old City. A month earlier he had a poor response when he called on Palestinians to converge on Jerusalem in protest at Israel's decision to demolish a centre for disabled Palestinians and build 900 new homes for Jewish settlers. His people muttered darkly that Mr Arafat was losing support.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The tunnel business gave him a chance to regain it. He called on Palestinians to resist Israel's "Judaisation of Jerusalem". He did not spell out how they should resist. But after nearly 30 years of occupation, and seven of <i>intifada</i>--the popular uprising that began in 1987--he did not need to.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The difference now is the presence of some 40,000 Palestinian policemen, with weapons, albeit only light ones. In East Jerusalem--from where they are excluded-- the protests were all-civilian, though even so three Palestinians were killed after demonstrations outside al-Aqsa mosque. But in the Palestinian areas of the West Bank and Gaza,<i> intifada</i> rules no longer apply. Last week the incendiary mix of the Israeli army, the Palestinian police and stone-throwing civilians exploded. The policemen's controllers in the Palestinian Authority (<font size=-1>PA</font>) admit that they lost control. So, therefore, did Mr Arafat.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He did, however, recover it. By the weekend, Gaza was quiet, and Bethlehem and Ramallah under control. In Nablus, where the Israeli army lost six soldiers after trying to protect the besieged, Israeli-controlled, religious site known as Joseph's Tomb, the Palestinian police imposed a curfew on their own people.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Israeli government is demanding that the <font size=-1>PA</font> dismiss and prosecute those policemen--some 200 of them, says the Israeli army--who shot at Israeli soldiers. This will not happen. In Washington, Mr Arafat committed himself to a general end to violence. But he is not going to condemn members of his security forces for defending their own people. To do so would further undermine his leadership. It would also risk fracturing his security forces, on which he depends.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And Oslo? "The peace process is already dead, and has been since Mr Netanyahu was elected," says Marwan Barghouti, Fatah's leader in the West Bank. "Our protests are aimed at restoring it to life." Should the resuscitation fail, Mr Barghouti is clear what comes next. "War," he says.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
