<html><head><title>A right lot </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Conservative Party 2</b></p>
<h1>A right lot </h1>

WIN or lose, the Conservative Party seems sure to lurch to the right after the general election, a special <i>Economist </i> survey of prospective parliamentary candidates suggests. Moreover, supposing the party is defeated and John Major resigns, the survey also indicates that the intake of new <font size=-1>MP</font>s will boost John Redwood's chances of becoming the Tory leader.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The survey was conducted between July and September among prospective Tory candidates in 75 seats where the present Tory <font size=-1>MP</font> had indicated an intention to stand down--ie, seats where prospective Tory candidates have the best chance of entering Parliament. Of these candidates, 46, or 61% of the total, sent usable replies. We also surveyed all the retiring Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>s in the same constituencies, asking them the same set of questions. Of these, 40% replied.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;We tested opinion in three spheres of policy. Naturally, one was Europe, where we sought to measure Euroscepticism and attitudes towards a single European currency. Another was social liberalism, where our chosen indicator was their attitude to the death penalty. Another was economic wetness or dryness, where we asked whether they would favour tax cuts even if they meant spending less on health, education and social benefits. We also asked how they would vote in a post-election leadership contest.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The prospective candidates turn out to be a formidably right-wing lot. On Europe first, we asked them to rank themselves on a scale of one to five, one being the most pro European and five the most anti-European. Their score averaged 4.1: strongly sceptical. By comparison, among the retiring <font size=-1>MP</font>s, the average answer was 3.2. Not a single prospective candidate gave a pro-European answer of one or two. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Again, among the 46 Conservative candidates who replied, not one favoured a single currency. Indeed most of them were very hostile to the idea. By contrast, although some retiring <font size=-1>MP</font>s who replied were for a single currency and others against it, they fall on average roughly in the middle of the five-point scale.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although there is no chance of Parliament restoring the death penalty, the prospective candidates favour it, by a three-to one majority. By contrast, retiring Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>s are evenly divided. Moreover, two-thirds of candidates want tax cuts even at the expense of spending cuts. Only a quarter of retiring <font size=-1>MP</font>s felt that way.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for a future leadership contest, most of our respondents, among both retiring <font size=-1>MP</font>s and new candidates, kept their counsel. In both groups a dozen or so possible candidates have some support. But among the prospective candidates, the name of John Redwood is the most often cited (by eight), while several others back the alternative right-wing contenders, Michael Howard and Michael Portillo. Four retiring <font size=-1>MP</font>s cited Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, as their preferred candidate for leader. He was not mentioned by a single prospective candidate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A few warnings should be attached to these findings. First, the sample among retiring <font size=-1>MP</font>s was small, and may have a left wing bias since <font size=-1>MP</font>s who are fed up with the rightward drift of the Conservative Party may have been the most likely to take the opportunity of our survey to register their protest. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second, we do not know how many of these candidates will actually make it into Parliament. If there is a strong anti-Tory swing at the next general election, many may lose the seats they are fighting. Finally, Westminster has a famously cooling effect on firebrands. Once they get there, many candidates may moderate their views. Labour's ranks in the Commons are full of <font size=-1>MP</font>s who today follow Tony Blair but who once followed Tony Benn.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, on the eve of the Tory party conference, our survey will give valuable ammunition to the Labour Party. The Tories have campaigned on the slogan: "New Labour, New Danger." On this evidence, Labour could respond "New Tory, New Danger" with more justification.<br>

<p align=center>
