<html><head><title>A forgiving lot </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Conservative Party 3</b></p>
<h1>A forgiving lot </h1>

SHOULD John Major lose the general election, the favourite choice of Tory voters for the next leader is . . . John Major. More than a quarter of Tory voters want him to stay (see <a href="br1.gif">table</a>). He leads Michael Heseltine, preferred by 16%, with Margaret Thatcher the surprising third choice.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ostensibly, the Tory party conference, which opens in Bournemouth on October 8th, is about winning the election. But the succession to Mr Major is top of the real agenda. <i>The Economist</i> commissioned <font size=-1>MORI</font> to conduct an opinion poll to see whom voters wanted for the job. The firm interviewed 1,800 voters between September 20th and September 23rd.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arguably, although Mr Major came top of the poll among Tory voters, after a defeat the party should be looking for the candidate with most appeal to voters generally. Here Mr Heseltine came top, though with only 16% of the vote. Mr Major was the second choice, with Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and John Redwood, the leading Eurosceptic, next.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Conservatives are famously loyal to their leaders--at least until they decide to ditch them. This is borne out not only by Mr Major's strongish showing, but by that of Lady Thatcher, six years after she was deposed by her own <font size=-1>MP</font>s. But the poll also shows that candidates on the left of the party, such as Mr Heseltine and Mr Clarke, run strongest. This is partly because they have held senior government jobs for longer than their rivals, and are therefore better known.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the two most right-wing and Eurosceptical of the candidates are also favoured by many voters. Mr Redwood, in particular, features remarkably well for a man whose highest office was Welsh secretary. In contrast, the most regularly cited compromise candidates do badly. Messrs Dorrell, Lang and Rifkind manage between them the support of only 3% of Tory voters and 4% of the general public. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, the next leader is not chosen by the public but by Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>s. The compromise candidates remain relatively unknown by the public, although clearly this would change rapidly for any one of them who got the job. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, voters in general and Tory voters in particular seem to want any new leader to come from candidates on the extremes of the Tory party rather than those at its centre. After a defeat, therefore, and on current showings, Conservative <font size=-1>MP</font>s might have to choose between a candidate with voter appeal and a candidate able to reunite their party. Perhaps the idea of keeping Mr Major on is not such a bad one after all.<br>

<p align=center>
