<html><head><title>Learning to earn </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Oxbridge</b></p>
<h1>Learning to earn </h1>

THE squeeze in government funding is beginning to hurt even Britain's richest universities. On October 1st, when Alec Broers became Cambridge's new vice-chancellor, he said his university would be in deficit within four years unless it found new sources of income. Some old fogeys may grumble at having to "dirty their hands with commerce", but Cambridge and its arch-rival Oxford are realising that the only way to pay for world-class laboratories and researchers is to exploit the fruits of their work more energetically.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The appointment of Mr Broers is a sign of such changing attitudes. Unlike his predecessors, he has spent much of his career in industry: for 20 years, he worked for <font size=-1>IBM</font>, an American computer giant. He promises that in seeking to boost the university's private income, he will consider "any reasonable proposal", such as letting firms set up their own laboratories within the university, or creating joint ventures in which the university holds a stake.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Cambridge has already had a fair amount of success in fostering a cluster of growing high-tech firms in its science parks, Mr Broers wants his researchers to think big, and to model themselves on Hewlett-Packard--once a small firm sheltering in the shadow of California's Stanford University, now a giant multinational with annual sales of $30 billion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Oxford has lagged behind Cambridge in creating spin-off companies. Now it is starting to catch up. Oxford Science Park is expanding rapidly, and Brian Richards, an entrepreneur who has founded a string of biotechnology firms, has been recruited to oversee a more ambitious strategy at Isis Innovation, a company set up to market the university's intellectual-property rights.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last month Sharp, a Japanese electronics firm, opened a &#163;5m extension to its laboratory in the science park. A second building was also opened, to provide larger premises for five of the park's other fast growing firms. Further building work is about to start. The park now has a waiting list of would-be technology entrepreneurs queueing to get in.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Paul Drayson, managing director of Oxford BioSciences, a firm spun out of the university's medical-engineering unit, is convinced that Oxford is about to witness an explosion of innovation in disciplines such as his. He is urging the science park's managers to accelerate the park's expansion so that the university's keen young researchers do not take their ideas elsewhere.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Encouraging such entrepreneurship, while making sure that the university gets its share of the proceeds, is Isis Innovation's primary task. Up to now, it has tried to sell most of the university's good ideas to big firms. Mr Richards is planning a more adventurous strategy: he wants researchers to set up more companies to exploit their own ideas commercially, with the university as a shareholder. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Isis Innovation has been hampered by hostility from a few academics who see it as a sort of Frankenstein's monster in their midst and who abhor the very idea of the university getting into bed with industry. Mr Richards admits that overcoming such opposition is one of his main challenges, and that this will limit the amount of money that the university will allow him to spend on fostering high-tech spin-offs. But fortunately, claims Mr Richards, such old fashioned attitudes are waning. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It will be years before Oxford and Cambridge earn anything like as much from their private-sector spin-offs as the &#163;180m a year of government research funding they now share. But the potential exists: Oxford Science Park's star performer is Oxford Molecular, which makes software for drug design and now has a stockmarket value of &#163;196m--which means that the university's 6% shareholding is worth almost &#163;12m.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
