<html><head><title>Reaching for the stars</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Satellite television in Japan</b></p>
<h1>Reaching for the stars</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font><p>
<p><b>Digital satellite television has been a huge hit in the United States, but a disappointment in its brief life in Germany. Which will it be in Japan?</b></p>
WITHIN 18 months of its launch in America, digital satellite <font size=-1>TV</font> had scooped up 3m subscribers. In Germany, by contrast, subscriptions to the Kirch group's new service appear to be well below expectations (see <a href="wb8375.html">page</a>). Now it is the turn of Japan. The country's first digital television service, Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>! (<i>sic</i>, in more ways than one), started commercial broadcasting on October 1st. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The good news for the companies betting that the Japanese are willing to pay well for more television is that the Japanese are ardent televiewers, spending an average of 4.25 hours a day glued to the box. On the other hand, they appear to have little taste for foreign programmes, and already have more channels to choose between than most Europeans. They also have, in <font size=-1>NHK</font>, a politically powerful public broadcaster which has usually topped the ratings. And past experience with commercial satellite broadcasting has been bleak: the main analogue venture, <font size=-1>WOWOW</font>, racked up debts faster than subscribers at first. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nonetheless, a few moments' channel surfing suggests plenty of scope for improvement. Japanese broadcasters and cable companies have grown fat by serving up a mushy diet of chat shows, panel games and soap operas. Since Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>! began its free trial period on June 30th, Japan's media bosses have begun to fear that they may not be calling the shots for much longer. Industry watchers believe the parents of Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>!--four Japanese trading houses (Itochu, Nissho Iwai, Mitsui and Sumitomo) and Japan Satellite Systems (<font size=-1>JSAT</font>), a satellite operator--will easily sign up the 300,000 subscribers they want by next March, and may have 2m within five years.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even as it starts to charge, Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>! may strike subscribers as a bargain. For around &#165;2,900 ($26) a month, viewers get 57 channels of pin-sharp television and 103 channels of radio with <font size=-1>CD</font>-like sound. The snag is that subscribers will also have to pay &#165;50,000 or more for yet another set-top box and satellite dish to receive Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>!'s compressed signal. At present, the 9.4m subscribers to Japan's three competing analogue satellite services need a different brand of set-top box and costly antennae for each one. Will they invest in a fourth?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason they may is that, to the dismay of Japanese television executives, the digital newcomers have begun to rally around a single standard. Come next summer, viewers who have bought receiving equipment for Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>! will also be able to tune in to <font size=-1>J</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, a 100-channel digital satellite-television service being developed jointly by Rupert Murdoch's News Corporation and Softbank, a Japanese software and media conglomerate. Mr Murdoch has shrewdly chosen to use the big new <font size=-1>JCSAT-3</font> satellite owned by <font size=-1>JSAT</font>, one of Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>!'s parents. As a result, subscribers to both satellite services will be able to use the same set-top box and miniature dish.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other digital broadcasters are expected to follow suit--or, at least, to make their services as compatible as possible. Direc<font size=-1>TV</font>, a digital satellite-<font size=-1>TV</font> operator owned by General Motors' Hughes Electronics in Los Angeles, is planning to launch a 100-channel service in Japan later next year. The American aerospace firm has teamed up with Culture Convenience Club, Japan's largest video-rental chain. Direc<font size=-1>TV</font>--like <font size=-1>J</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>--may decide to use the same family of Hughes-built satellites adopted by Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>!. With one small dish on the roof, one decoder box on the television set and one remote control in the hand, the Japanese could be surfing hundreds of television channels within a year or two. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To flourish, the new satellite broadcasters need to see off competition from the cable industry. With typically no more than 150,000 subscribers apiece, most of Japan's cable systems operators are more threatened than threatening, and ripe for consolidation. A greater threat may be the handful of big operators. Jupiter Telecommunications, the biggest, is a joint venture between Sumitomo and Tele-Communications Inc, America's largest cable operator. Set up in March 1995, Jupiter already has the franchise for accessing some 2.5m homes in western Tokyo, Osaka and Fukuoka. Its state-of-the-art networks will carry telephone messages as well as data and television programmes. It is developing four new television channels--movies, golf, shopping and documentaries--for this year and six more for 1997. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Japan's commercial networks--<font size=-1>TBS</font>, <font size=-1>NTV</font>, Fuji and <font size=-1>TV</font> Asahi--are in a much stronger position. Their audiences remain vast; and they still have an arm-lock on national advertising revenues. But they now face the prospect of having to invest heavily in digital broadcasting. In 1994 some government officials wanted to bring forward the date at which all the country's <font size=-1>TV</font> would be broadcast digitally from 2010 to 1999-- only to have their plan shredded by <font size=-1>NHK</font>, which had sunk billions in developing an analogue form of high-definition <font size=-1>TV</font>. Now even <font size=-1>NHK</font> is expected to go digital soon.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The question is: what will viewers pay for? Although American soaps, baseball and golf shows will be plentiful, the Japanese will mainly want home-grown fare. That gives tremendous power to the companies that produce programmes, such as Japan Image Corporation, a consortium of 50 small production companies that has been signed up by Perfec<font size=-1>TV</font>! to provide shows for four of its forthcoming 70 channels. By 2000 <font size=-1>JIC</font> expects to supply a dozen channels-worth of content. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With up to 500 Japanese-language channels to feed, such production houses will bring Japan's most talented young producers streaming out of the television studios to seek their fortune. But only if the programmes they provide for the digital satellite services are at least as good as those from analogue broadcasters will digital television in Japan copy America's blast off, rather than Germany's sluggish start.<br>
<br>

<p align=center>
