<html><head><title>TECHNOLOGY BRIEF</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>TECHNOLOGY BRIEF</h1>

<h2> </h2>
A word is worth 1,000 pictures<br>
 
<p><b>The second in our series of articles on why some new technologies fly and others flop looks at the wretched saga of the videophone, and asks whether the personal computer will come to its rescue</b></p><br>
HOW can you improve on the telephone? Since Alexander Graham Bell first ordered his assistant to "come here" 120 years ago, calls have become clearer, automatic switches have brought direct dialling, and digital ones have delivered nifty features such as conference calls and voice mail. Telephones have proliferated (the International Telecommunications Union estimates there are over 800m of them); and most recently they have become portable.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But time and again, one enhancement has been rejected: the addition of pictures, either still or moving. Videophones, as they are known, were such techno-turkeys that telephone companies have at last stopped selling them altogether. One sign of their failure is that few consumers ever realised that they were on offer.<br>
Adding pictures to voice calls seems an obvious step--adding images to radio signals created television, and with it a huge new industry. But telephones have so far remained stubbornly photo-free. "Picturephone", developed at <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s Bell Labs, now part of Lucent Technologies, was first demonstrated in 1964. At the time, other telephone companies talked of public videophone booths in major cities. Three decades later, videophones are still a rarity.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first consumer devices to sell in any number appeared in Japan in 1988. They were a fiasco. Rather than adding an extra dimension to conversations, the gadgets detracted. Whenever callers wanted to send an image of themselves, they had to interrupt their telephone calls for six seconds for a blotchy, black-and white picture to be transmitted. Only 250,000 of the phones were sold, mostly in pairs to men who worked away from their families.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These gizmos were followed four years later by <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s VideoPhone 2500. Instead of still, black-and-white images, VideoPhone 2500 could send colour images that were updated a few times a second, although the screen, at five square inches, was hardly lavish. Like the Japanese device, VideoPhone 2500 flopped. Sales did not even reach 100,000 before the prices were slashed (they started off at $1,500). In the end, <font size=-1>AT&T</font> started to give the phones away.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Unwanted</b></b><br>

Certainly, videophones have been too expensive and their pictures too poor; cheaper phones and better images would undoubtedly have helped. But ultimately, they may have failed for a more basic reason: people just do not seem to want them. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Experience suggests that consumers will put up with high prices and low quality if they want the service on offer. There was great demand for crackly international phone calls (featuring bellowed exchanges of "Can you hear me?") even when they were ferociously expensive. The earliest mobile phones won fans despite their bulk and poor voice quality because people wanted to make telephone calls on the move. Because the demand was there, the technology improved rapidly: the price and quality of long-distance calls and mobile phones have improved as the market has expanded. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Videophones have never benefited from this virtuous circle. According to Tim Midwinter of <font size=-1>BT</font>'s Martlesham Heath research laboratories, the trouble is that when people make calls, they mostly want to talk. Ordinary telephones have been allowing this adequately for more than a century. Adding video, particularly when it is a jerky picture on a small screen, matters much less. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Videophones seem also to have suffered from another drawback. People make phone calls in any state of dress, or undress; while dirty or clean; and, perhaps most importantly, argues David Farber, a telephone expert at the University of Pennsylvania, while they are doing other things at the same time. Anecdotal evidence suggests that for many conversations, videophones would be more curse than blessing. Even <font size=-1>AT&T</font> executives were not immune: testing videophones in the 1960s, some would claim their systems were broken to avoid having to smarten up for each call.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A final defect of the videophone, compared, say, to the mobile one, is that it requires two to tango. If you are the only person you know who has one, who will you call? The same logic applied to the fax in its infancy--but lots of people saw they could benefit from having one. This has not been so for videophones. The model user became the grandmother who missed her grandchildren and had enough money to buy a pair. This market turned out to be tiny: <font size=-1>BT</font> sold only 10,000 of its domestic videophones between 1993 and 1995. Worse, if you bought a videophone from <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, but your granny in Scotland had one from <font size=-1>BT</font>, you would not be able to swap images with her.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So will the videophone always flop? Maybe not. Prearranged video conferences are becoming increasingly popular within companies, especially if they are seen as a way to cut down on overseas travel. A one hour video call between London and New York costs less than $150, and Dataquest, a research firm, estimates that more than 1m videoconferencing units will have been shipped by 1999. But these are usually large bits of specialist equipment that sit in the boardroom--hardly the omnipresent, friendly telephone handset.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The technology for one-to one video calls is, however, starting to show other promising signs of life. International standards for video telephony have been developed, ensuring that devices bought from one maker will work with those from another. And the complex gadgetry needed to squeeze and transmit video images down a telephone line is becoming ubiquitous. In the early 1990s, videophone makers had to cram clever chips and tiny screens into handsets. Today, the modern personal computer can become a videophone of sorts merely by adding a $200 digital camera and software (now standard) to compress and transmit the images. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may turn out to be a vital change. The <font size=-1>PC</font> is not yet as compact as a telephone but it has become as familiar and unexceptional as one. And sales of multimedia <font size=-1>PC</font>s, almost perfect for video calls, will reach around 35m this year. In addition, <font size=-1>PC</font>s become cheaper and more powerful every year, so the quality of picture calls goes up as the price of the equipment comes down.<br>
<b> </b> Better still, Intel, the world's leading supplier of <font size=-1>PC</font> chips, is showing new interest in video telephony. From this Christmas, adding a special camera to an Intel-based <font size=-1>PC</font> will be enough to turn it into a videophone that can work over telephone networks and the Internet alike. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There will still be limitations. Ordinary phone lines are not best suited to carrying video images and the high-capacity connections of the future are still, well, in the future for most telephone subscribers. The <font size=-1>PC</font> with camera attached is anyway a far cry from the compact, dedicated videophone the telephone companies once hoped to turn into a mass-market product.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?844473600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
