<html><head><title>How Labour could lose</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<p align=center><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1>How Labour could lose</h1>

NOTHING is ever certain in politics. But few things in British politics now look more likely than that Tony Blair's "New Labour" will win the next election. Labour will begin its party conference on September 30th further ahead in the opinion polls than any British opposition party has ever been at this stage. Indeed, Labour's poll lead has remained so large for so long that pollsters are questioning their own methods, and trying to adjust for the fact that people seem ashamed to admit to supporting the Tories (see <a href="br7495.html">page</a>). But even after adjustments--and a dose of scepticism born of the polls' failure to predict the Tory victory in 1992--Labour seems far ahead. Local elections, by-elections and what voters tell canvassers of every party all point to the same conclusion as the polls: after 17 years of Conservative government, the mood favours a change. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, Labour could still lose--and it could do so without a scandal or Mr Blair falling under the proverbial bus. If you find this difficult to swallow, suspend your disbelief for a moment, and come along on an imaginary journey.<br>
</p><p><b>Tony Blair's worst nightmare</b><br>
Imagine first that the economy continues to grow, that inflation remains low and that rising house prices, more cash in consumers' pockets and declining unemployment produce the "feel-good" factor for which the Tories have been praying for so long. And then imagine that the Tories manage to stop squabbling and rally round Mr Major's "wait and see" policy on <font size=-1>EMU</font>--which is, by the way, also Labour's policy. Finally, imagine that, with its poll lead shrinking, its policies subjected to withering scrutiny month after month and with many in its ranks deeply unhappy about Mr Blair's junking of so much of "old" Labour, the party begins to stumble. Internal squabbles escalate. Labour's leaders, fearing that their victory is slipping away, begin to flounder. By next spring, the race is close. And, in a repeat of 1992, floating voters reluctantly decide that they would be safer with the sorry lot of devils they know than the sorry lot of devils they don't. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, some elements of this future are more likely than others. It is quite probable that economic growth and low inflation will finally produce the long-awaited "feel good" factor and that voters will at last begin to give the Tories some of the credit for this. It is less probable that the Tories will stop fighting over <font size=-1>EMU</font>, especially after their most recent outburst of hostilities over the past two weeks. But a truce on <font size=-1>EMU</font> cannot be ruled out. Facing an election, the Tories could yet come to their senses.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The final ingredient in this scenario--Labour blundering and squabbling its way to defeat--may at first appear the least likely. Mr Blair, after all, has shown himself to be the strongest leader in the party's history. Who can deny with what zeal, and skill, he has set about smashing left-wing shibboleths or squashing internal opposition Would his party opponents really rock the boat if they faced the political armageddon of a fifth straight defeat? <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Believe it or not, they might. Mr Blair's party opponents have already made it abundantly clear that they are unhappy with his leadership. More damaging are rumblings of discontent from Mr Blair's own front bench. John Prescott, the party's deputy leader, relishes every opportunity to describe himself as a "socialist", in implicit but oh-so-obvious contrast with you know-who. Robin Cook, the shadow foreign secretary, can barely disguise his impatience with the enthusiasm for <font size=-1>EMU</font>, low taxes and fiscal prudence of Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor and Mr Blair's closest ally. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If internal discontent not only grows, but is accompanied by signs of incompetence from Labour's leaders, the threat to the party's electoral prospects could become genuine. And incompetence is what, surprisingly, Labour's leaders have begun to display as the party's policies come under closer scrutiny. Over the past month they have made unforced bungles on two of the trickiest issues facing the party: Scottish devolution, and relations with the trade unions, putting forward and then abruptly withdrawing proposals on both topics.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the months of campaigning pass, such scrutiny will grow, and it could provoke more blunders. The reason is simple. Mr Blair has been sending two messages to the electorate which fit together awkwardly: that a change of government is urgently needed, but that electing New Labour will not involve so much change as to be risky. This is best summed up by that delicious oxymoron which Mr Blair uses to describe New Labour: "a party of the radical centre". <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour's policies betray this contradiction. With the important exception of constitutional reform--the details of which Labour still seems confused about--the party's policies sound bold, but on closer examination are either so vague as to mean little, or are basically the Tories' policies with the sharpest (and thus, arguably, the most effective) edges shaved off. Despite all Mr Blair's rhetoric of radicalism, such policy conservatism sums up rather well what he is offering the voters: continuity, but with a set of fresh, vigorous new faces at the helm, speaking in softer tones.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may appeal to enough uncommitted voters to give Labour its expected victory, even if the economy is growing and the Tories unite. But this means that the competence of Labour's leaders and the unity of their party are likely to become the key issues in many voters' minds. Voters may not expect an opposition party's policies to be worked out in complete detail. They may accept that Labour, like the Tories, will always have dissidents. But if voters come to believe that Labour's untested leadership is not united or skilful enough to take tough decisions in government, or that Mr Blair is in fact an isolated figure leading a disgruntled party (see <a href="br7505.html">page</a>), then his pitch from the "radical centre" will fail. The next election looks like being the first in living memory which is the opposition's, not the government's, to lose. But lose it Labour still could.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
