</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The jam-and-Perrier budget</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The jam-and-Perrier budget</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
IN A strange and marvellous way, the hypocrisy of this election season is unlike any that has come before it. In the past, politicians swore to run the economy responsibly, while at the same time promising programmes that would explode the deficit and multiply red tape. This time the opposite is happening: both President Clinton and the Republicans in Congress trumpet government handouts, while at the same time pursuing policies that will protect the budget and curb regulation. The old kind of hypocrisy was like that of an upright, war era American, who denounced all vice and sinfulness while committing adultery on the quiet. The new kind of hypocrisy is like that of a casual, computer-era American, who pretends to love drugs and sexual licence while drinking mineral water and working round the clock.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over the past week, congressional Republicans have been caving in to Bill Clinton's spending demands, apparently jeopardising their promise to balance the budget by 2002. They have bowed to the president's zeal for regulation, barely criticising his decree that a huge swathe of Utah be designated a national monument, and acceding to pressure for new health rules. Meanwhile, out on the campaign trail, both presidential candidates are promising tax cuts. Not surprisingly, many have concluded that runaway government has returned, and that fiscal responsibility lies in ruins. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With one big exception, however, there are scant grounds for these fears. The exception is Bob Dole, whose promise to balance the budget and still cut taxes falls into the old category of hypocrisy: he is claiming to be responsible, while offering policies that would wreak fiscal chaos. For the moment, however, Mr Dole appears likely to lose the election. Assuming that Bill Clinton beats him, America will remain roughly on track for a balanced budget six years from now. Mr Clinton's election promises--Longer hospital stays for new mothers! Extra education programmes!--sound profligate but are in truth mercifully modest. The same goes for the Republicans in Congress, who are making much of their new willingness to pay for "commonsense" programmes, but who still retain much of their old budget-balancing zeal.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Consider, first, the recent expansions in government regulation. Posing in front of the Grand Canyon (actually in Arizona) on September 18th, Mr Clinton declared 1.7m acres of Utah a national monument, so protecting it from mining. Critics called this the biggest land grab in recent memory. But the truth is that nearly all the land involved in the Utah "grab" was already owned by the federal government. Besides, it does not add vastly to the more than 100m acres of America already designated a national park or a national monument. Compared with Jimmy Carter, who turned 50m acres of Alaska into a national monument, Mr Clinton's grab looks pretty trifling. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same goes for the new health regulations. The day after the president's trip to the Grand Canyon, Congress agreed that new mothers should be allowed to stay in hospital at least 48 hours after giving birth. It also laid down that the maximum allowable cost of treatment for mental illness, which under most insurance policies is meagre, should henceforth be raised to the same level as the spending cap for physical illnesses. In principle (though not in compassionate practice), both new regulations are misguided: they will push up the cost of health insurance, so reducing the number of Americans who can afford it. Fortunately, however, both changes are modest. The new childbirth rule will raise insurance premiums by a barely noticeable 0.06%, according to the Congressional Budget Office; the mental-health clause will raise them by 0.4%. A much more sweeping attempt to put mental and physical illness on the same footing, which died in congruous earlier this year, would have increased premiums by a far heftier 4%.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In general, the president is insisting that non-defence discretionary spending be increased, which is a big symbolic defeat for the cause of budget balancing. Last year, for the first time in 25 years, this category of spending fell. To build on that success, Congress laid out a plan to balance the budget by 2002, which was based on tightening the discretionary-spending belt in each intervening year. Now the belt is to be loosened.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile the House Republicans are also doing violence to the principle of fiscal responsibility. They are proposing to pay for next year's extra spending partly by auctioning radio frequencies. But their estimates for the potential receipts from this source are probably too high, and part of the expected auction revenue had already been pledged to cut the deficit. The Republicans also propose to raise the deposit-insurance premiums collected from banks and thrifts. But higher premiums next year will probably mean lower premiums later, so contributing nothing to the medium-term goal of balancing the budget. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In sum, both president and Congress sound as irresponsible as the average laid back baby-boomer. The good news, however, is that they sin only in small ways. At mid-week, the president was holding out for $237 billion in non-defence discretionary spending, a rise in real terms of only 3% on last year. Meanwhile the dodgy money raising wheezes proposed by Congress were unwise in principle but insignificant in size: they would raise a mere $5.5 billion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same goes for Mr Clinton's proposed tax cuts. In principle, these are rakish. Half the deficit reduction of recent years has come about because of the tax increases of 1990 and 1993, according to Robert Reischauer of the Brookings Institution. A proposal to cut taxes threatens to expand the deficit again. But the saving grace of Mr Clinton's tax cuts is that they are so small. Whereas Mr Dole proposes $550 billion worth of cuts, Mr Clinton promises a mere $20 billion or so. On the stump, the president boasts of tax credits and tax deductions with the devil-may-care panache of a champion budget-wrecker. The truth is that these flourishes have been carefully costed by mineral-water types with spreadsheets. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even when it comes to entitlements, the vast chunk of the budget not affected by this week's appropriations bills, Mr Clinton's irresponsibility is an affectation. He has spent much of the year attacking Republicans for their proposed cuts in Medicare, the health programme for the elderly. But the truth is that the president has proposed cuts too: $124 billion over six years, compared with Mr Dole's $158 billion. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For an election season, all this is quite remarkable. It does not guarantee that America will return to the budget-balancing path next year--the tax-slashing Mr Dole may beat Mr Clinton after all, or second-term Clinton may prove profligate. But there is at least a chance that the goal of balancing the budget by 2002 can be achieved. It had better be: in the 20 or so years after that, the retirement of America's rakish-workaholic baby-boomers will heap pressure on the public finances far more severe than any faced at present.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
