<html><head><title>Trends of the week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Trends of the week</h1>


<p><b>Word: </b>"Liberal"--the label Bob Dole tries to attach to Bill Clinton. Mr Clinton says it doesn't stick.<br>
<p><b>Inexactitude: </b>Mr Clinton, appearing on "NewsHour": "There still has not been a single solitary shred of evidence of anything dishonest that I have done in my public life."<br>
<p><b>Fall guy: </b>The best quips on Mr Dole's embarrassing tumble after a railing collapsed in California come from Mr Dole himself. Example: "The first person to call me was a trial lawyer."<br>
<p><b>Complaint: </b>By the Nike Corporation ("Just Do It"), after Mr Dole unveiled his "Just Don't Do It" anti-drugs slogan. <br>
<p><b>Stealth: </b>Mr Clinton signs anti-gay-marriage legislation at 12.50am.<br>
<p><b>Prediction: </b>The election forecasts of seven political scientists, all with their own forecasting models, are published in the October issue of <i>American Politics Quarterly</i>. All predict a Clinton win. So does a <font size=-1>WEFA</font> Group model based on a state-by-state analysis: it says Mr Clinton will win with 406 electoral-college votes to Mr Dole's 132.<br>
<p><b>Surprise: </b>Although 23 points behind just three weeks before, Woody Jenkins, a Republican, wins Louisiana's open primary and will face Mary Landrieu, a Democrat, in the run-off. Hope for Mr Dole yet?<br>
<p><b>Company: </b>Asked in a <i>Wall Street Journal</i>/<font size=-1>NBC</font> poll which couple they would rather sit next to on an aeroplane, 35% of respondents said the Clintons, 23% preferred the Doles, 13% chose the Gores, 11% the Kemps and 7% the Perots.<br>
<p><b>Button: </b>"Hungarians for Dole".<br>

