<html><head><title>Nico Colchester</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width="105" height="26" alt="Europe" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Nico Colchester</h1>

ON SEPTEMBER 25th, on a visit to New York, Nico Colchester died of a heart attack while out on his early morning run. Nico was deputy editor of <i>The Economist</i> from 1989 to 1993, since when he had been editorial director of the Economist Intelligence Unit, our sister company. He was 49, and was one of Britain's finest writers on foreign affairs and business.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Nico's writing ranged far and wide, he was probably best known for his work on the European Union, first as Bonn correspondent and then as foreign editor of the <i>Financial Times</i>, and from 1986 at <i>The Economist</i>. He wrote two surveys for this newspaper on the <font size=-1>EU</font>, and then in 1990 a book, jointly with his friend David Buchan of the <i>Financial Times</i>, called "Europe Relaunched: Truths and Illusions on the Way to 1992".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The book's sub-title sums up Nico's journalism admirably. He was pro-European, but as a result of hard thought, not dreamy sentiment, and was always fast to criticise the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s methods and muddles when he thought it necessary. A cover-leader of his, "Half Maastricht" (September 26th 1992), was typical in its punchy criticism of Europe's Maastricht treaty, and its prescient advice that a two-speed Europe was both desirable and inevitable. He was awarded France's Order of Merit in 1990 and Britain's Order of the British Empire in 1993.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of Nico's particular talents was in the use of humour to cast light upon serious matters. At the <i>Financial Times</i>, where he spent the first 18 years of his career, one of his trademarks was his use of the Mars bar as a commodity standard with which to analyse inflation. At <i>The Economist</i>, a splendid leader in mid-1988 brought bank collapses and the Falklands war together to caution readers of "the dangers of sogginess" and the merits of "crunchiness". And rare indeed, it sometimes seemed, was a piece from Nico without a quote from "The Wind in the Willows". "Poop, poop", went Mr Toad, whenever appropriate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nico was as energetic in life as in his writing. A regular runner for more than a decade, next month he was due to run a marathon in Greece, along Pheidippides's original course, for charity. When writing on knotty subjects, he was fond of inviting readers "to engage their mental four-wheel drives". Nico's was never disengaged.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843868800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7495.html">Next article</a>
</p>
