<html><head><title>Deregulation</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Deregulation</b></p>
<h1>Something must be done</h1>

IT IS against the law to charge for dancing on Sunday, either in a disco or at a decorous tea-dance. It is legal to charge for drinking, horse-racing and other Sunday activities but not, according to the Sunday Observance Act of 1780, for dancing. Despite the efforts of the government's deregulation task force, and the passing of the 1994 Deregulation and Contracting Out Act, which made it easier to get rid of unnecessary regulations, charging for dancing on Sunday remains illegal.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Deregulation", said Michael Heseltine, the deputy prime minister, on September 23rd when presenting the second report of the task force that he set up on deregulation, "remains one of the government's top priorities." This does not leave much hope for things lower down the government's list. In 1995, according to the government's own figures, 1,404 new regulations were added, and 420 were thrown out. But this is not necessarily the fault of evil bureaucrats. At least some of the blame lies with the politicians and the public.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To be fair, those figures are crude. Some of them relate to such unobjectionable measures as road closures. But anti-red tape activists insist that they are a massive underestimate: <font size=-1>MP</font>s supporting a parliamentary motion earlier this year to promote deregulation maintain that the real figure from April 1995 to July 1996 is 3,000 new regulations. The task force, too, is clearly not content: its report focused not on achievements, but on the vast amount still to be done.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why are regulations being created faster than they are being abolished? Europe must take some of the blame. Single market legislation means that products must be acceptable throughout the <font size=-1>EU</font>, which regulates to harmonise. Hence, apparently, the need for ten pages of Euro regulations related to the sale of cut flowers. If Europe's Council of Ministers passes new regulations in areas where national rules already exist, the result is too often two sets of regulation on the same subject.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet more of the blame, say the deregulators, lies at home. As Maurice Denyer, managing director of a small building company and a member of the task force, points out, efforts to make life easier for businesses sometimes fall foul of the regulators' passion for regulating.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government has, for instance, moved towards goals-based regulation: telling businesses what to aim for, but not how to do it. The idea is to give firms freedom in how to comply with the rules. Yet, says Mr Denyer, inspectors have responded by making "accepted codes of practice" appended to the regulations increasingly rigid, so the effect is much the same as the old, prescriptive, regulations.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then there is the problem of vested interests created by the existing set of regulations. The almighty row about the deregulation of Sunday shopping hours was created not just by the trade unions and the religious few, but also by small shopkeepers who feared that their profit margins would be eroded by supermarkets. The result was partial deregulation.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But a wider problem is attitudes to regulation among the public and in the press. Although people are against "red tape" in general, any particular health problem or accident inevitably leads to calls that "something must be done". The sharpest current example is a network of regulations and inspectors currently being set up for youth activity centres, as a result of an accident at such a centre in Lyme Regis in 1993, in which four teenagers were killed. The accident was a freak. The cost of setting up the system will be around &#163;5.5m if only the 3,000-odd profit-making centres are included, or &#163;100m if 80,000-odd voluntary sector ones are also included.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843868800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7502.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT09-B16-209</DOCNO>
