<html><head><title>Labour's awkward one-man band</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Labour's awkward one-man band</h1>

IT WAS as wooer to shy virgin that Tony Blair gave his speech to a City of London audience this month. This was not the tough Mr Blair who will be paraded before voters at next week's Labour Party conference in Blackpool, but Tony Blair as Hugh Grant-- self-deprecating, charming and seductive. And so it took a certain nerve on the part of one member of the audience, George Cox of the London International Financial Futures and Options Exchange, to ask the $64,000 question.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Mr Blair, like many here, I greatly enjoyed your talk and I applaud much of the sentiment in it," began Mr Cox. "My question is this: that if, sadly, at the last minute you had been incapacitated . . . could we have expected the same speech to have been given with the same insights, the same passion, the same conviction from any other member of your shadow cabinet, or perhaps of more importance, from any Labour candidate whom you will be putting forward to us to elect next year?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair replied with practised fluency. After the largest democratic exercise any party has undertaken, he had been elected on a modernisation ticket. There was "no real intellectual argument against modernisation". New Labour candidates and young Labour members were enthusiastic Blairites. His party was much less extreme and more united than were the Tories. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the one-man-band question is still the one the leader's intimates fear the most. It might cost them the election. Worse, if New Labour does prove a one-man band, it will fail in government. It is too easy to imagine circumstances in which a Labour government, elected with high hopes, dissolves into division and disarray. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The party's immediate priority is to try to stop the electorate imagining any such thing. At Blackpool the leadership will therefore seek to repeat last year's feat of winning every single tricky vote. They do not want a conference, but a rally.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet they may not get it. Imagine, if you will, the moment when the 85-year-old Barbara Castle, the personal embodiment of sentimental old Labour, totters to the rostrum to call for higher universal pensions. The argument against her is being conducted by Harriet Harman, who speaks for Labour on social security and who, for half the hall, is the traitor who sent her son to a selective grammar school. Ms Harman will win the argument. Lady Castle's proposal would clobber the taxpayer while doing nothing for poor pensioners who would lose in means tested benefits what they gain from higher universal pensions. But minds are not hearts, and Lady Castle may yet render her party one last disservice by winning the vote.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Defeat for Mr Blair would not matter much in substance. Labour leaders have frequently ignored unpalatable conference decisions in the past. But it would be an uncomfortable omen for a Blair-led government. Two-thirds of Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s in the next Parliament will be retreads from this one. Many are not Blairites, but voted for him in a Faustian bargain: they give him silence, he gives them victory. But once he has won, they may not prove so tractable. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Evidence of the potential cussedness of Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s in the next Parliament is contained in a fascinating paper, "Blair's Bastards", by Philip Cowley and Philip Norton of Hull University. Even now, their analysis shows, Labour rebels are both more numerous and more persistent than their Tory counterparts. Almost 70% of the party have rebelled against the party line since 1992; 35% have cast more than ten votes against the party line compared with 27% of Tories. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True, a few of the serial dissenters are to leave the Commons at the next general election--notably Peter Shore, a distinguished Eurosceptic. But, of the top 38 rebels, just five will definitely be gone from the next Parliament.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of course, Mr Blair will have potent weapons to wield against rebels: the power of patronage and the threat of expulsion or deselection. And he will be immeasurably helped by the fact that not one of the rebels proposes any serious alternative to Blairism.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, you can have rebels without a cause; which means that Mr Blair would be wise to contemplate an insurance policy. Even if Labour has a clear overall majority, he would be sensible to seek a working arrangement with Paddy Ashdown's Liberal Democrats.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, it may be easier for Mr Blair to do the deal if he has a majority than if the next Parliament is hung. In a hung Parliament, the Lib Dems will be <i>demandeurs</i>, with the power to pull the rug. Their price might prove too high. If, however, Mr Blair courts them when he has no need to, they should come cheaper. A cabinet job for Mr Ashdown; lesser ministries for Mr Ashdown's lesser colleagues; a modest reform of the voting system--although Lib Dem purists will huff and puff, these in reality might seal a deal.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The advantages to Mr Blair would be substantial. The Lib Dems expect to win at least 30 seats. If they side with Labour, therefore, Mr Blair's majority will be 60 higher than if they are against him--a comfortable cushion against rebellion and the almost inevitable losses at by-elections. Such an alliance would also make it easier, if it endured, for him to win a second term. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Seen in this light, the conference that is of most significance for a future Labour government may not be the party's own in Blackpool, but the one the Lib Dems have just held in Brighton. Some Lib Dems were outspokenly in favour of dealing with Labour. Some were outspokenly against. But most, including the leader himself, spoke about it not at all. As a result, come the day after polling, Mr Ashdown has a pretty free hand. If Mr Blair has any sense, he will firmly grasp it.<br>

<p align=center>
