<html><head><title>Campaigning for a cause</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Campaigning for a cause</h1>

WHY did 550 British marketeers, a habitually well-fed bunch, receive a Red Cross food parcel on September 24th? The Red Cross, one of the world's largest humanitarian organisations, is less concerned with their eating the loaf of bread it contained than their digesting the message on its wrapper. For Hovis, the baker of the bread, is one of the first companies to sign up with HelpAd, a company owned by the charity.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;HelpAd persuades makers of consumer goods to leave room for an advertisement on the outside of their packaging, and then sells this advertising space to another manufacturer, who makes something which goes well with the first product. Thus the loaf in the parcel carried an ad for Anchor butter; in another example Tabasco pepper sauce has bought spaces on the side of bottles of Del Monte tomato juice. The advertisements all include a little HelpAd logo explaining that the money from selling the space goes to the Red Cross. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;HelpAd charges commercially competitive rates for the space it sells. The aim is to secure a sustainable source of money for the Red Cross by tapping into companies' advertising budgets, rather than the discretionary funds usually set aside for charitable donations. The Red Cross spends around $24 billion a year-- around a tenth of the sum companies spend on advertising. HelpAd's goal is to be selling &#163;10m ($16m) of advertisements a year in Britain within two years. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far the makers of some 500 products have made inquiries. However, persuading protective brand managers to take the plunge has been laborious. A frequent obstacle to an apparently promising product marriage is that a parent company that makes a brand of cream cheese, say, which might potentially be advertised on another company's crackers in fact has its own rival brand of cracker under another label. So far HelpAds have appeared on seven products, and three more product pairings have been firmly promised to appear by February 1997. Many interested companies are holding off from commitment to see how these ten fare. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If they go well, HelpAd intends to expand overseas. Plans are already afoot in another seven European countries and in South Africa. Other kinds of advertising are on the cards, too. Robert Doyle, a Northern Irish construction surveyor who thought up the idea of HelpAd and who is now a consultant to the Red Cross, is encouraging sports stars to "give their right arms to the Red Cross", by using the right sleeve of their playing shirts as a location for a HelpAd. And HelpAd may function as a broker for charities other than the Red Cross, offering its service for a small percentage of the money paid for the advertisement.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
