<html><head><title>Bulgaria</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26" alt="Finance and Economics" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Bulgaria</b></p>
<h1>Into the hole</h1>

FORTUNES are mixed among former communists. While frothy stockmarkets fuel recovery in Central Europe, Bulgaria is fighting to avert meltdown. On September 24th, the central bank raised its main interest rate almost threefold, to 300%, and placed nine banks under "special supervision". The move was a last-ditch attempt to restore public confidence in the banking system, to stave off default on the country's $11.9 billion foreign debt, and to halt the steep slide of the Bulgarian currency, the lev. The central bank's governor, Lyubomir Filipov, staked his job on the new reforms working: a brave bet indeed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Earlier stabs at reform were far too timid. In the spring, the central bank closed five troubled banks and raised interest rates several times, while the government launched a plan to shut loss-making industrial behemoths and kick-start privatisation. But this has proved inadequate. Inflation, brought under control last year, is now an annualised 110% and may soon hit 150%. The lev has collapsed from 71 to the dollar at start of the year to 230 (see <a href="fn1.gif">chart</a>). In recent weeks, depositors have lost all faith in the insolvent banking system, withdrawing local currency and switching it into dollars.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the government wants to avert disaster, it must move quickly on three fronts. First, it will have to close more dodgy banks, while toughening supervision and raising capital requirements for the survivors. Most banks are shoddily managed and have far too many dud loans. It must also stop state-run industry's losses. Of the 64 state-owned companies that the government promised to close earlier this year, only five have been wound up so far.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third aim should be quicker privatisation. Asset sales brought in a piffling 9 billion lev ($135m) last year. Only by speeding up the process can Bulgaria raise enough cash to see it through the coming months. On September 22nd, it announced plans to sell 15 of the largest state firms by the year's end. The sales should raise between $500m and $1 billion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But more than this is needed. Repairing a battered economy is expensive: raising the biggest Bulgarian banks' solvency ratios to international levels could cost $3 billion alone. On top of this, Bulgaria has its foreign debt to service. This month alone, it must find $130m to repay both principal and interest; next year it is expected to repay a total of $1.25 billion. If privatisation flags, the country may have to default for the second time since 1990.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whether it does or not may depend on the World Bank and the <font size=-1>IMF</font>. Next week their representatives are due to meet government officials to discuss progress. If the Bulgarians impress the <font size=-1>IMF</font>, the Fund will release a $115m loan that it delayed last month; the World Bank may then follow with $200m of its own. If, however, the Fund holds on to its money, the lev--and Bulgaria's economic prospects--are sure to take another dive.<br>

<p align=center>
