<html><head><title>Leadership by Stealth</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>Leadership by Stealth</center></h1>

VICTORIANS enforced their diplomacy by gunboat. At the end of the 20th century, the preferred instrument is the Stealth bomber. The Stealth is technically amazing, powerfully effective--and also bizarrely-shaped and difficult to trace. Is it not, in fact, rather like America's foreign policy?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As America goes nose-to-nose with Iraq's Saddam Hussein in the closing weeks of an election campaign, the familiar chorus can be heard. The United States is unpredictable; unreliable; too easily excited; too easily distracted; too fond of throwing its weight around. While Americans wonder which candidate will be better for their living standards over the next four years, America's friends have a wish-list of their own for foreign-policy improvements, irrespective of who wins or loses in November. And it is not short.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But is it fair? The main indictment, of inconsistency abroad, was current even before Mr Clinton began his unnerving odyssey through the perils of international affairs. Yet the verdict is not cut and dried. In many spheres, America has stood firm. It has persisted in trying to bring peace to the Middle East. It has remained committed to security in Europe, through <font size=-1>NATO</font>, and in Asia, through <font size=-1>APEC</font> and the security treaty with Japan. Most bases abroad have been retained. America continues to understand--indeed, to take pride in--its role as sole superpower, military colossus and chief knocker-together-of-heads on the world stage. It preened itself over the Rabin-Arafat handshake and, more justifiably, over Bosnia's Dayton accords--although they followed four damaging years of shall-we-shan't-we muddle towards the war.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America is also, however, consistent in less palatable ways. Since the end of the cold war, it has been in search of an enemy: and has found him in despots hither and yon, from Saddam Hussein to Cuba's Fidel Castro to Muhammad Farrah Aideed in Somalia. The personal vendetta, sometimes pursued by aged congressmen rather than the president, has become a regular event. So too has a manifest public reluctance to involve America in the sort of activities abroad that may be required of a superpower, especially the spending of money and the sending of troops.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Here lies the nub of the matter. The real complaint about American foreign policy is not waywardness, but reluctance to engage. To begin with, it is often hard to get America's attention. The problem is not isolationism, which, some firebrands apart, has no constituency these days. It is the natural self-centredness of a vast continent that faces no immediate external threats. No president since Nixon has seen his main job as devising foreign policy. Mr Clinton's attention-deficit on the subject (recently reduced) is not, alas, an aberration. But a president can be helped by good advisers in both the State Department and the Pentagon; and, however the election turns out, a more authoritative secretary of state in a happier department would be useful.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For nowadays the main point of foreign policy ought not to be the elimination of immediate external threats, but the avoidance of future ones. On that score, recent policy looks misdirected. During his tenure so far, Warren Christopher has been 27 times to Damascus and only once to China. Indeed, from sheer energy and verbiage alone, it may well appear that little Cuba is as much a threat as an expansionary China. America has not hesitated to offend most of its allies in Europe and in its own hemisphere in the cause of bashing a neighbouring island which represents no threat to it at all. Meanwhile, the signals sent to China, which may be a huge threat in future, have been distinctly mixed: now tough on human rights, now fawning on trade; now oblivious to China's menacing noises in the South China Sea, now gunships in the Taiwan Strait.
</p><p><b>More clarity, less crusading</b>
<br>This choice of priorities has been unfortunate. Even more so, however, has been America's confusion between economics and politics, and its treatment of its biggest allies. Starting under George Bush, and continuing enthusiastically under Mr Clinton, America embarked on the idea that economics, not politics, should now take the lead in foreign affairs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is a mistake in principle, for governments are no better at selling exports or levering open foreign markets than they are at domestic industrial policy. But it is a disaster in practice, because it leads inevitably to confrontation with America's rich-world allies, which are its main exporting rivals and offer the juiciest markets. Squabbles with Europe over trade, and divisive competition with it over exports to China, have been regular bugbears. Even worse was America's eagerness to take Japan to the brink of a trade war over cars in June 1995. America is not the only guilty party in this regard. But it is the world's leader, and it needs to keep in mind the temptation that a divided alliance offers to rogue dictators such as Saddam as well as to budding powers such as China.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These strains have been worsened by America's distrust of multilateralism. True, it can have its drawbacks, notably the confusion of lines of command; unilateral action must remain an option. But America needs to get over its awkwardness in tactical alliances, its hit-or-miss communication with allies, and, in particular, its niggling attitude towards the United Nations. For all its failings, the <font size=-1>UN</font> is a useful resource, not least in long-term peacekeeping. America's rudeness towards it, and refusal to help pay for it, are foolish.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The business of prioritising has also been confused by the conviction that America should have a set of moral rules for foreign policy. Several presidents this century have tried to formulate a doctrine that laid down when America would intervene, in defence of which principles. To uphold human rights or democracy is an admirable aim, but desperately uneven in application. Lack of democracy does not inspire America to put pressure on Saudi Arabia, for example. As a guiding rule for foreign policy, it is more honest for America to admit (as James Baker, then secretary of state, did during the Gulf war, and as Mr Clinton did over Rwanda), that it intervenes when an essential resource such as oil is at risk, or when the threat to world stability cannot be ignored.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;America's friends may feel that this is not good enough. But they should examine their own consciences. They frequently go crying to America over problems, such as Bosnia, in which it has no obvious interest. They are the first to complain if America does nothing. Yet if it intervenes, or adopts a policy of constant covert meddling, they may well complain even more. A little consistency in the world's attitude is overdue; a little more gratitude, when earned, might even encourage the American public.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All these improvements are devoutly to be wished as the next four years unfold. Would one candidate in the election ensure them more than the other? That is uncertain. Mr Clinton's grasp of foreign policy has improved markedly in the past two years; but his attention is still less focused than it might be, and his team is tired. Bob Dole has hinted that he might act more from principle, and his foreign-policy advisers have much to say about consistency and clarity. But he seems barely interested, and they are untried. Between the Clinton muddle and the Dole vacuum, the world may well go on asking whether America's foreign policy is a bird or a plane. And if that is an unfair question, the remedy is still largely--though not entirely--in America's hands.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
