<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><h2>Tribal splits</h2></p>
<p><p>The first <b>Bosnian elections</b>, intended to create national institutions in the aftermath of a 43-month civil war, passed off peacefully, with most voters favouring tribal parties. Alija Izetbegovic, Bosnia's Muslim president, who favours a unified country, narrowly defeated Momcilo Krajisnik, a Serb separatist, for the chairmanship of a three-man presidency. Few Muslims dared to exercise their right to vote in their former homes, now ethnically cleansed by Bosnian Serbs.
<p>Umberto Bossi, leader of the separatist Northern League, proclaimed northern Italy an "independent and sovereign" republic called <b>Padania</b>. But fewer people than the League expected turned up to hear the announcement in Venice, after three days of secession rallies along the River Po.
<p>Russia's president, <b>Boris Yeltsin</b>, entered hospital in preparation for a heart operation. His stay is to be extended by several days, raising fears that he is sicker than the Kremlin admits.
<p>The European Union rejected a British proposal to scale back or eliminate a cull of up to 147,000 cattle thought to carry <font size=-1>BSE</font>, or <b>mad-cow disease</b>. Britain threatened to go ahead anyway, risking the collapse of an agreement designed to lead to the lifting of the <font size=-1>EU</font> ban on exports of British beef. Switzerland said it would kill one in eight of its herd to eradicate the disease.
<p>European governments tightened their belts to prepare for <b>economic and monetary union</b> in 1999. France announced a budget that it claims will cut its public-sector deficit to the Maastricht treaty target of 3% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> next year and its debt to 58%. Germany's parliament passed a series of cuts to social-welfare programmes.
<p>Eurostat, the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s statistical arm, said traditional <b>families</b> are in decline. Although 72% of men and women are married, the share is shrinking and 8% of children in 12 countries live with only one parent. Danes are the loneliest Europeans: 22% of them live alone; only 4% of Spaniards do so. Ireland has the biggest families, with half the population living in families of five or more.</p>
<p><h2>Korean conundrum</h2></p>
<p><p>A <b>North Korean submarine </b>ran aground in South Korean waters; 11 North Korean soldiers were later found shot dead on a mountain, in what the South Korean authorities said was a mass suicide. Another seven were found and killed by the South Koreans; others were thought still to be at large.
<p>The Japanese prime minister convened a special session of parliament for September 27th. This is widely expected to set the stage for a <b>snap election</b> in October.
<p>Indian police <b>arrested Sukh Ram</b>, a former communications minister, a month after police found over $1m in cash hidden in his house. Mr Ram was arrested on his return from abroad.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>The Afghan rebel militia, the <b>Taliban</b>, captured the strategic city of Jalalabad. They now control two-thirds of the country.</p>
<p><h2>Iraqi lull</h2></p>
<p><p>To general relief, <b>Iraq and America</b> both drew back from full battle, though America's military build-up in the Gulf continued. Massoud Barzani who, with Iraqi help, had defeated his Kurdish rival in northern Iraq, hedged his bets by renewing his previously warm contacts with America.
<p>Syria gave Israel, on the eve of Yom Kippur, a<b> bad case of nerves</b> by redeploying some 12,000 of its troops in Lebanon. The completion of Lebanon's general election showed Syrian-backed politicians firmly in control.
<p>Israel's Likud government approved plans to build 1,800 <b>new housing units</b> in Matityahu, a West Bank settlement where about 2,400 ultra-orthodox Jews live. Talks with the Palestinians on Israeli troop redeployment in occupied Hebron got nowhere.
<p>At the end of a "national understanding conference", <b>Algeria's</b> President Liamine Zeroual said a general election would be held early next year. Several secular opposition parties boycotted the conference. The Islamic party, the <font size=-1>FIS</font>, was barred. The <font size=-1>FIS</font>'s armed wing further distanced itself from what it called "suspicious terrorist operations" by its rival, the <font size=-1>GIA</font>.
<p>Eugene de Kock, a former policeman in <b>South Africa</b> convicted of murder and pleading for leniency, said that two former presidents, F.W. de Klerk and P.W. Botha, knew of covert attacks on anti-apartheid activists.</p>
<p><h2>America in camera</h2></p>
<p><p>A civil action against <b>O.J. Simpson</b>, the football star acquitted last year of killing his ex-wife and her lover, opened in Santa Monica without television cameras. It also lacked a jury, as lawyers scrambled to find 12 people uninfluenced by the criminal trial.
<p><b>Guatemala's</b> government and rebel guerrillas reached an agreement on the future role of the armed forces that should open the way to a full peace deal soon. The 45,000-strong army, notoriously as brutal as the rebels in the 1970s and 1980s, will be cut by a third.
<p>In Colombia, a <b>kidnapped </b>Briton and a Dane were released after months--against payment of a ransom, complained Colombian officials. The kidnapping of a new-born baby aroused public outrage. A Dutch couple kidnapped in Costa Rica by former Contra guerrillas from Nicaragua were freed, also for ransom. In Mexico, Marxist guerrillas threatened to hit big business, method unspecified.
<p>The five-country Andean Pact said it expected to sign a preliminary deal on free trade with the <b>Mercosur</b> customs union by year-end. Venezuela and Peru hope for full deals with Mercosur by then.
<p>
<p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="wtw2.html">BUSINESS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
