<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><h2>Ciao, Caio</h2>
<p><p>Barely three months into the job and two weeks after Carlo De Benedetti resigned as chairman, <b>Olivetti</b>'s chief executive, Francesco Caio, quit in the wake of an investigation into alleged false corporate reporting at the high-technology group. Mr Caio's replacement is Roberto Colaninno, boss of Sogefi, a car-parts firm.
<p><b>Italian prosecutors </b>ordered a new round of arrests, beginning with one of the country's most prominent businessmen, Lorenzo Necci, who is head of Italy's state railway. Among others detained as part of the same investigation into corruption were the head of a state-owned arms company, two magistrates and a former politician.
<p>In a serious blow for Britain's Serious Fraud Office, a judge ruled out any further legal action against four former executives of the <b>Maxwell group</b> of companies, including Kevin Maxwell, son of its founder, the late Robert Maxwell. Mr Maxwell, who had been cleared of conspiring to defraud the group's pension funds in an earlier trial, had argued that the <font size=-1>SFO</font>'s decision to seek another one was "oppressive". The judge agreed.
<p>Grappling with a <b>Czech banking crisis</b>, authorities took control of Agrobanka, the country's fifth-largest bank and its largest privately owned one. Agrobanka's links with Kreditni, a bust bank, were beginning to cause liquidity problems.
<p>The European Commission was expected to open a formal inquiry into the price paid by <b>Cr&eacute;dit Lyonnais</b> for a former subsidiary. The state-owned French bank, undergoing a massive restructuring and about to ask the government to assume yet more costs, pushed Soci&eacute;t&eacute; de Banque Occidentale into a state-owned holding company last year before buying it back in June.</p>
<p><h2>Beat that</h2></p>
<p><p><b>Ford</b> struck a three-year pay deal with its unions, setting a pace that General Motors, its bigger rival, might be forced to keep. America's number-two car maker promised to guarantee the survival of 95% of union jobs (now that it has slimmed down).
<p><b>Alcatel Alsthom</b> submitted a bid to buy <b>Thomson</b>, a defence group, from the French government, and said it would seek an Asian partner for the group's loss-making consumer-electronics business. The French government has received a rival bid from the <b>Lagard&egrave;re/Matra </b>group, another French conglomerate.
<p><b>Sony's Hollywood problems </b>returned with the ejection of Mark Canton from his job as chairman of Columbia TriStar Pictures and the refusal by Arnold Rifkin of the William Morris talent agency to take the job. Lucy Fisher, vice-chairman, didn't want the job either, but she is temporarily running the studios.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Scott Sassa quit as head of <b>Turner Broadcasting System's</b> entertainment division as the acquisition of <font size=-1>TBS</font> by <b>Time Warner</b>, newly equipped with federal approval, neared completion. Ted Turner, founder of <font size=-1>TBS</font>, takes on responsibility for the new group's cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> networks and will also become vice-chairman of Time Warner.
<p><b>Deutsche Telekom</b>, with a view to its partial privatisation in November, forecast a DM1.5 billion ($1 billion) dividend for 1996 despite a 96% plunge in first-half net profits from last year's DM3.5 billion to DM129m, caused mainly by the cost of redundancies. Telekom also said it was pulling out of a digital pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> consortium, intending to cash in on its cable-network monopoly. A prospective competitor, Vebacom, announced a deal with Ruhrgas to build a fibre-optic network alongside the country's gas pipelines.
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>) <br> Forecasts for international <b>air travel </b>are being revised upwards by the airlines. The International Air Transport Association (<font size=-1>IATA</font>) now expects average annual growth of 7.1% in 1996-2000, up from earlier forecasts of 6.6%. Domestic traffic will grow by 6%. By 2000 the total number of airline passengers is expected to have risen to almost 1.7 billion from 1.3 billion last year.</p>
<p><h2>Peaks and troughs</h2></p>
<p><p>American, British and German <b>stockmarkets </b>reached record highs and in Japan two days of trading on the Nikkei brought gains of more than 4%. But America said that July had seen a trade deficit of $11.7 billion, the biggest for five years.
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>) <br> Mexico's remarkable return to health continued with the launch of a $1 billion global bond issue aimed at redeeming another chunk of existing high-interest <b>Brady bonds</b>. Mexico has raised more than $14 billion this year to pay off more expensive debt.
<p>As Switzerland's recession deepened--its <font size=-1>GDP</font> growth declined for the sixth quarter in a row--the country's third-largest bank, <b>Swiss Bank Corp</b> said that it would make a loss in 1996. It also plans a restructuring that will result in more central control, a loss of about a quarter of its branches and 1,700 jobs over the next three years.
<p>In the wake of "irregularities" discovered at some of its investments funds, <b>Deutsche</b> <b>Morgan Grenfell</b> sacked the funds' manager, Peter Young, for "gross misconduct" .
<p><p><b>Sumitomo Corporation</b> announced that its losses from apparently unauthorised copper trading by Yasuo Hamanaka were $2.6 billion, not the $1.8 billion it estimated in June. It has also decided to prosecute Mr Hamanaka.
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
