<html><head><title>On the road</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>On the road</h1>


<font size=1>CINCINNATI, HARTFORD AND WILMINGTON</font><p>

IT WAS drizzling in Cincinnati last Monday, so Bill Clinton's campaign event could not take place outdoors, but had to move across the street to the old Music Hall building. This, it so happens, was the site of the 1880 Democratic convention, which nominated Winfield Hancock, a Civil War hero but a lousy campaigner. Hancock went on to lose to the handsome if scandal-tainted James Garfield, who just loved meeting voters. "The World Almanac of Presidential Campaigns" refers to the 1880 election as "one of the most boring and inconsequential of all time." In 1996, a day with each of the major candidates suggests strong similarities, albeit with parties reversed, with 1880.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Clinton campaign oozes energy and seems to do everything right. The stop in Cincinnati was part of a tireless week of campaigning covering places as far afield as North Carolina, Iowa and Arizona. Ohio, with its 21 electoral-college votes, is a key state--no Republican has ever won without carrying Ohio--and was the one most often visited by both sides in 1992. This year is no exception. In Cincinnati, presidential politics is as finely balanced as views on whether the city's famous chili is best "three ways" (without onions) or "five ways" (with beans and onions): Cincinnati's vote went both ways in 1992, with 43% for Mr Clinton and 43% for George Bush.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So Mr Clinton was in the right place, and at the right time. On the day his opponent was setting out his policies on crime, the president was standing before rows of police officers to accept the cherished endorsement of the 270,000-member Fraternal Order of Police. It was the first time the <font size=-1>FOP</font> had endorsed a Democrat for national office.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Partly by dint of being president, wherever Mr Clinton goes it is a Big Event. In Cincinnati, the crowds were large, the surrounding security operation was imposing, the vendors of badges and other campaign memorabilia were out in force. There was "Hail to the Chief" to greet Mr Clinton's arrival at the Music Hall, plus an enthusiastic chant orchestrated by the local state representative. "Where's the president?" he asked three times. "Whoop, there he is!", the crowd roared thrice in response.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"That's the most unusual welcome I've ever had," Mr Clinton told his audience, "but I like it." Indeed, he likes everything about campaigning. He relishes the stump speeches, despite the hoarseness of voice they are causing. More than anything, he loves the adulation he gets when he plunges into a crowd. In the Music Hall, with a glowing, ruddy-faced smile, he lingered among his supporters, reluctant to leave, pausing for photographs, stretching out his hands to people desperate for a touch of the visiting superstar.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The contrast with the Dole campaign could hardly be greater. Bob Dole has been concentrating on Small Events, informal "Listening to America" sessions with sympathetic hand-picked audiences. Quizzical faces stare at the motorcade from the airports to the venues, where there often seem to be more Clinton/Gore demonstrators than Dole/Kemp supporters. Whereas with Mr Clinton you notice the prowess of the campaigning, with Mr Dole you puzzle over the point of it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why, for example, did Mr Dole spend precious time on September 18th "Listening to America" in Hartford, Connecticut, where a poll published that day showed him 26 points behind Mr Clinton? (Mr Dole was "listening" to a few women entrepreneurs, invited by the state Republican Party and outnumbered by the media squeezed into a meeting room on the 22nd floor of the Hartford Group insurance company.) And why did he then proceed to "Listen to America" in Wilmington, Delaware, a bellwether state but one with a grand total of three electoral-college votes? "Dole and Delaware. The Road to Victory Begins Here", proclaimed the banner in the hall of the Catholic girls' school.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The moderator of the Wilmington session was Steve Forbes, winner of the Delaware primary. Judging by the way he took charge of the question-and-answer session, he still rather fancies himself as the Republican candidate. He himself answered the questions from the invited panelists. As the proceedings dragged on, with Mr Dole shuffling in his seat, Mr Forbes began yet another reply by saying, "Bob will be responding later." Mr Dole looked at his watch and mumbled, "Not much later." When, at long last, Mr Forbes introduced Mr Dole, he praised him as "a man of few words".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole gave a 35-minute monologue, without notes. He brandished a nickel--the amount he says would have to be saved out of every dollar of cuttable spending under his economic plan--to illustrate how easy it would be to cut taxes and balance the budget as he proposes. He presented the election as a choice between "trust" (in him) and "fear" (being spread by the Clinton campaign). It was a competent performance, but not one destined to resonate far beyond the Delaware media market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The journalists who follow Mr Dole aboard his "Citizen's Ship" despair of the scarcity of real news generated by his campaign. Just a tiny nugget a day would keep them happy. The candidate, fearful of the off-the-cuff gaffes which caused him problems earlier in the year, now rarely wanders back to the press section of the aircraft. At least one daily newspaper is thinking of taking a break because it is "so dull". The greatest excitement during a Dole day comes from the bumps that invariably seem to happen in mid-air: if there is a bad-weather front lurking somewhere in the country, that is where the "Citizen's Ship" is likely to be.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet a day with the two candidates also leaves a nagging feeling that, despite all the outward appearances, Mr Clinton is not quite as strong as he seems, and Mr Dole not quite as weak. Mr Dole plays a good underdog, emphasising the point that he has been prematurely given up for dead before by showing a letter to his father from the hospital where he lay wounded in December 1945: "At the present time it would appear that his recovery is somewhat questionable," the letter said.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There may be no wild excitement at Dole events, but there is a palpable sense of respect. Boring as it is for reporters, Mr Dole is sticking relentlessly to his message, and the conversation of the campaign is turning to issues--crime, the economy, foreign policy--that work well for him. A few other things have also started to go right. Ross Perot will not be in the televised presidential debates. Some national polls show the race tightening.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ohio, where he is about nine points behind, is still very much in play. In Cincinnati, not all the police officers assembled behind the president were in fact Clinton supporters. Outside the Music Hall, which sits in a run-down part of town, protesters from the local homeless centre predicted that the welfare bill Mr Clinton signed would result in more people living in cardboard boxes in the neighbourhood. Peter Ritchy from the Homeless Hotline of Greater Cincinnati handed out leaflets complaining that Mr Clinton listened to his rich Hollywood backers while ignoring the poor. "The Democrats have gotten complacent that all the poor people are going to vote for them," said Mr Ritchy, who would like to vote for Ralph Nader himself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is still possible that this election could resemble that of 1880 in another respect besides tedium and the character of the candidates. It was one of the closest ever.




