<html><head><title>Trends of the week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Trends of the week</h1>


<p><b>Faith: </b>Pat Robertson tells his flock at a Christian Coalition conference that, given the gap between Bob Dole and Bill Clinton in the polls: "There has to be a miracle from Almighty God to pull it out. And that could happen."
<p><b>Miracle: </b>The gap halves, to only eight points, says an <font size=-1>ABC</font> poll of likely voters.
<p><b>Lone star: </b>A new poll gives Mr Dole an 11-point lead in Texas. In August, polls showing the candidates neck-and-neck there brought talk of a Democratic landslide.
<p><b>Song: </b>Anything but "Dole Man", an adaptation of the 1967 song "Soul Man", which was the Dole campaign's anthem until a lawsuit by one of the song's owners silenced the fun. Time to turn now to rock 'n' Dole, or beBob?
<p><b>Omen: </b>Miss Kansas wins the Miss America beauty pageant.
<p><b>Book: </b>"Trusting the People", by Bob Dole and Jack Kemp (HarperCollins, $15). Mr Dole's plug for the 164-page <i>chef d'oeuvre</i>: "Doesn't take long to read."
<p><b>Good news: </b>The White House reveals that Mr Clinton tested negative for <font size=-1>HIV</font> in 1990 (in a routine test for an insurance policy). The bad news: Republicans, suspecting the president is hiding something, still press for release of his full medical records.
<p><b>Lollywood:</b> Even before last week's glitzy presidential fund-raiser starring Barbra Streisand, federal election reports show that residents of the 90210 zip code, covering Beverly Hills, had given five times as much money to Mr Clinton as to Mr Dole.
<p><b>Ladbroke's odds:</b> Clinton 1-7 (as last week); Dole 9-2 (last week, 4-1).
<p><b>Word-association: </b>The word voters most commonly associate with Vice-President Al Gore is "intelligent", according to a Pew survey. For Jack Kemp, Republican would-be vice-president, it is "football".
<p><b>Bumper-sticker:</b> Spotted in Louisville, Kentucky: "Cut Waste and Taxes. Re-Elect No One!"
<p><b>Free</b> <b>air: </b>Rupert Murdoch's Fox television network begins broadcasting ten free, one-minute spots by each candidate. The Dole campaign objected, however, that Mr Clinton would have an unfair advantage answering the set questions from the pomp of the Oval Office. Compromise: he sits at his Oval Office desk, but with curtains behind him and not a presidential seal in sight.
<p><b>Hot air: </b>According to a study by the Centre for Media and Public Affairs, candidate soundbites at the party conventions averaged 10.4 seconds in length, led by 15 seconds for loquacious Mr Kemp, 11 for Mr Gore, 10 for Mr Clinton and eight for plain-spoken Bob Dole.
<p><b>Fresh air: </b>A non-partisan commission recommended that the televised presidential debates should feature only Messrs Clinton and Dole. Ross Perot is excluded on the ground that he has no serious chance of winning the election.





