<html><head><title>Trainspotting</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Rail privatisation</b></p>
<h1>Trainspotting</h1>


<p>DESPITE opposition predictions that it would be "a poll tax on wheels", Britain's newly privatised rail network seems about to deliver significant improvements for its passengers. Roger Salmon, the rail franchising director, will invite bids next month for a new high-speed route to be operated by 160mph Italian-designed tilting trains on the west-coast main line. The journey time from London to Manchester will be cut by 25%, to less than two hours. A bullish message of increased investment and improving performance will also be given by Bob Horton, the chairman of Railtrack, at the newly privatised company's first annual meeting on September 25th.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True, little on the railways has changed just yet. Decades of under-investment have bequeathed a legacy of too much bumpy track and antiquated rolling stock. Punctuality and reliability remain as patchy as ever. Finding out when trains run and reserving seats is still often absurdly difficult. Media comment is invariably bilious. Passenger complaints are at record levels, rising by 14.5% in the year to the end of March, the 13th consecutive year in which complaints have increased (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). The sour public mood is unlikely to be sweetened by a series of one-day strikes called by the <font size=-1>RMT</font> transport union beginning on September 20th and 23rd, which threatens to cause widespread disruption across the country.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, those who said that splitting the nationalised British Rail (<font size=-1>BR</font>) into 60 separate private companies would prove a political disaster have fallen silent. Labour is busy backtracking on its commitment to restore "a publicly owned, publicly accountable railway". It is easy to see why. The announcement on September 17th that two more passenger services in the west of England have been successfully franchised means that more than half the network is now operated by private firms. Contrary to many forecasts (including by <i>The Economist</i>), competition for the passenger franchises has been so intense that subsidies required to maintain the privatised services are significantly less than they were under <font size=-1>BR</font>. Sir George Young, the transport secretary, claims that annual government grants to support the first seven franchises will, by 2003, be a third of the amount needed by <font size=-1>BR</font> to run them in its last year of operation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the private train operators have been in business for only a few months, their determination to improve service and attract more passengers is already beginning to show results. Later this month, Great Western, which operates services throughout the West Country, will unveil the first of its newly liveried and refurbished trains. The company has already reduced journey times on its long-distance routes by up to 20 minutes and is planning to introduce new motorail services. Great Western's passenger traffic is up by nearly 7% since privatisation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other operators are also trying to lure passengers back to the railways with better service. Chiltern Railways, a firm run by former <font size=-1>BR</font> managers, announced earlier this month that it had ordered 12 diesel-powered 100mph express trains to reduce its journey times between London and Birmingham by a third, in order to compete with InterCity services. Sea Containers, a freight company which took over the east-coast main line six months ago, is also planning to order two Italian or Swedish high-speed tilting trains to reduce the journey time between Edinburgh and London from 4.75 to 3.75 hours.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Train companies operating less glamorous routes are also keen to boast of their improvements. Prism Rail, which operates the so-called "misery commuter line" from Fenchurch Street in London to Tilbury and Southend, is spending &#163;14m on modernising stations. The company, run by former bus executives, has promised to replace two-thirds of its existing 40-year-old rolling stock with new trains by 1999.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until the new investment in track, stations and rolling stock comes onstream, passengers will understandably be sceptical about privatisation. So far improvements have been largely cosmetic. Midland Main Line, which operates services between London and Sheffield, offers all passengers free tea and coffee, for example. Great Western has introduced a business carriage where complimentary newspapers can supposedly be read in peace: mobile phones and tape players are discouraged. South West Trains, operated by Stagecoach, an aggressive bus company, maintains a spare train at Waterloo for peak-time emergencies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A lively price war is a more potent sign of the benefits of the new regime. Chiltern is promoting a &#163;20 day-return fare between London and Birmingham. This undercuts the peak fare on InterCity West Coast's line (which is 40 minutes faster) by &#163;35. Ferocious competition marked by knocking copy is also taking place over the London to Gatwick services operated by Gatwick Express and Network South Central. Both the west-coast and east-coast InterCity companies are fighting a price war with EasyJet, a budget airline, which offers a &#163;29 single fare on the London-Glasgow and London-Edinburgh routes. The rail companies responded with an identical fare and complained to the Advertising Standards Authority that EasyJet failed to tell passengers about the &#163;5 in airport tax.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The train operating companies have been slower to respond to long-standing complaints about the inadequacy of train-inquiry bureaus. A national system with a single phone number is under development, but industry sources acknowledge that the speed, quality and accuracy of information provided is still "a very thorny problem". The performance regime under which Railtrack and the train operators are penalised for late-running also causes problems for delayed passengers catching connecting trains. Companies are less and less willing to hold trains, for fear of financial penalties.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such transitional problems should soon be resolved. Better management aside, the fact that the new privatised railway has been given guaranteed levels of subsidy, a stable fare structure and the freedom to invest long term unhindered by the vagaries of the government's annual expenditure round should deliver better services eventually. Unfortunately for the Tories, they may not be in power to get the credit. Politics is so unfair.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
