<html><head><title>Profit taking</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Profit taking</h1>

<p>WITH only two months to go until the budget, anyone lucky enough to benefit from a tax break is starting to get nervous. Easily the most worried this year should be anyone who receives government-approved profit-related pay (<font size=-1>PRP</font>). The Treasury has spotted that the tax perk granted to <font size=-1>PRP</font> schemes is costing it a fortune (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>), and that an increasing number of such schemes are nothing more than tax-avoidance ploys. Thus, <font size=-1>PRP</font> is ripe for deperking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Profit-related pay was given favourable tax treatment in the 1987 budget as a temporary measure intended to encourage firms to tie their employees' salaries more closely to company profits. This was supposed to help wages to fall during bad times and to encourage more entrepreneurialism among ordinary workers. High hopes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At first, the number of <font size=-1>PRP</font> schemes grew at a snail's pace: by 1991-92, they cost the exchequer only &#163;40m. But then firms, egged on by their accountants, found clever ways of using <font size=-1>PRP</font> without linking employees' pay any more closely to changes in their employer's profits. (Employees rarely want pay that is genuinely linked to their firm's profits--which is less certain than basic pay--unless it is on top of what they already get.) The cost of tax-rebates soared, to an estimated &#163;1.5 billion this financial year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>PRP</font> ploy appealed to firms because it enabled them either to increase their workers' after-tax pay without actually paying them any extra or to cut their own wage bill without cutting the after-tax pay of their employees. Thanks to such wheezes, says Chris Giles, an economist at the Institute for Fiscal Studies, an independent research group, people as unfamiliar with profits as charity workers and university lecturers are now able to receive <font size=-1>PRP</font>.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The case for scrapping the tax-break on <font size=-1>PRP</font> is overwhelming: even when it is not a scam, why should other workers subsidise it? But it may yet survive. Some 3m people get <font size=-1>PRP</font>; to a top-rate taxpayer on maximum <font size=-1>PRP</font>, the tax-break is worth &#163;1,600 a year. How many votes are there for the Tories in grabbing that?



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
