<html><head><title>Grim for Tories</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>



<p><b>Voting reform</b></p>
<h1>Grim for Tories</h1>

<p>TONY BLAIR is against introducing full proportional representation in Britain. But the Labour leader is privately more sympathetic to a half-way sort of electoral reform, the alternative vote (<font size=-1>AV</font>), which takes account of voters' second preferences. The Liberal Democrats, meanwhile, although traditionally in favour of full <font size=-1>PR</font>, are now deliberately vague about other options for change. A resolution to be debated on September 24th at their annual conference in Brighton calls only for a "fair system of voting". Only the Tories adamantly resist even <font size=-1>AV</font>--unsurprisingly, since a new study of <font size=-1>AV</font> for <i>The Economist</i> suggests that it would probably mean many more Labour and Liberal Democrat <font size=-1>MP</font>s and far fewer Tories (see <a href="br3.gif">table</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The study, carried out by John Curtice, a psephologist, for the Centre for Research into Elections and Social Trends (<font size=-1>CREST</font>), makes use of newly available data from the 1996 edition of <font size=-1>CREST</font>'s British Election Panel Study, which regularly interviews the same group of voters. The study shows that 51% of Liberal Democrat voters now prefer Labour as their second choice compared with only 29% who prefer the Tories. Similarly, Labour voters prefer the Lib Dems to the Tories by about eight to one, up from four to one at the time of the last election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under the alternative vote, the candidate who comes bottom of the poll is eliminated and his vote redistributed among the other candidates according to the second preferences of his supporters until one candidate obtains 51% of the vote. As far more Lib Dems currently say they prefer Labour to the Tories, in the many seats where the Lib Dems are in third place their votes would switch to Labour under <font size=-1>AV</font>, knocking out the Tory candidate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The results are dramatic. Look at the second section of the table, which shows the results of a hypothetical election in which Labour and the Tories are level pegging with 39% of the vote each. Under the present system, Labour would still win more seats than the Tories, partly because of tactical voting. But under <font size=-1>AV</font>, Labour would win 105 more seats than the Tories, giving it a comfortable overall majority. If Labour wins the election by as much as recent polls suggest, it would get 451 seats, compared with 426 under the present electoral system (third section of table).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour is not the only gainer. True, the Lib Dems would still get less seats under <font size=-1>AV</font> than they would under proportional representation. However, they would get nearly twice as many seats as under the current system of "first past the post" in an election where the two big parties were neck and neck, and nearly three times as many in a Labour landslide.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Conservatives could argue that this shows that <font size=-1>AV</font> is unfair to them. Those who complain about the existing voting system say that it unjustly gave the Tories an overall Commons majority at four successive general elections, even though they fell well short of half the vote in each of them. <font size=-1>AV</font>, our study suggests, could have the same effect, although this time benefiting Labour, not the Tories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In practice, however, <font size=-1>AV</font> would probably not be as hard on the Tories as our crude numbers suggest. Most Lib Dems in the study have Labour as their second choice because of the Tories' current unpopularity. But this will not always be so. Indeed, at the time of the 1992 general election, the same <font size=-1>CREST</font> panel showed that Lib Dems were more likely to say that the Tories were their second choice than Labour. As the gap between Labour and the Tories narrows nearer the election, as it surely will, the gap in Lib Dem second preferences is also likely to narrow. If Lib Dem second preferences returned to what they were in 1992, then Labour would still be the biggest party in a level-pegging election, but would fall short of an overall majority. <font size=-1>AV</font> may seem an attractive half-way house for Labour, but it could still give the Lib Dems the balance of power in a hung Parliament.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
