These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Max factor</b> &nbsp;The High Court decided that Kevin Maxwell, acquitted in a fraud trial in January, would not face a second trial on charges relating to the collapse of companies once owned by his father, Robert Maxwell, as to do so would be "unfair".</p>
<p><b>Too nice</b> &nbsp;The Secondary Heads Association criticised school inspectors for failing to name incompetent teachers, making it harder for school heads to sack them or to insist that they retrain.</p>
<p><b>Letter bombshell</b> &nbsp;With no end in sight to the postal dispute, <font size=-1>TNT</font>, a courier firm, said it wanted to set up a rival postal service in the Midlands, eventually extending it nationwide.</p>
<p><b>Plunder</b> &nbsp;The government said it may return four tonnes of gold, which has been in the Bank of England's vaults since it was recovered from Germany after the second world war, to the families of the Jewish victims of the Holocaust, from whom it was stolen.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Double indemnity</b> &nbsp;Labour proposed a scheme to insure home owners' mortgage payments against the threat of unemployment, to be run jointly by the government and private firms. The Joseph Rowntree Foundation, an independent research body, proposed a compulsory insurance scheme which would provide finance for long-term care for the elderly.</p>
<p><b>Antisocial</b> &nbsp;Kim Howells, Labour's trade and industry spokesman, called for the party to abandon the word "socialism" . Left-wingers condemned the suggestion, but Mr Howells was supported by Tony Blair, the party's leader.</p>
<p><b>No sex, please...</b> &nbsp;Cardinal Hume, the leader of Britain's Roman Catholics, attacked society's "endless obsession" with sex. Roderick Wright, the Catholic bishop of Argyll and the Isles, resigned after disappearing amid rumours linking him with a divorced woman.</p>
<p><b>Dognapped</b> &nbsp;Thieves who stole two monkeys from a zoo in Staffordshire also took a rottweiler which was supposed to be acting as a guard dog.

</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
