<DOCNO>WT09-B16-234</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA096-001031-B036-180</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.europe.economist.com:80/issue/21-09-96/wb2.html 199.173.162.110 19970215025755 text/html 7602
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 15-Feb-97 02:53:34 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 20-Sep-96 08:27:40 GMT
Content-length: 7417
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title></title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>



<h1>Of MiGs and microchips</h1><p><b>Is Larry Ellison's vision of the future of the computer industry really that different from Bill Gates's?</b><p>MICROSOFT'S job is to get Windows everywhere," said Larry Ellison on September 16th. "It's our job to stop them." The founder of Oracle, the world's second-largest software company, is taking pot-shots at the largest one, and loving every minute of it (see <a href="wb2.gif">chart</a>). To a thumping rock soundtrack, he has just mounted the stage of a computer conference in Paris, to take part in a much-hyped "battle of titans" between himself (worth a mere $5 billion) and Bill Gates ($18 billion) over whether the future of their industry will belong to the <font size=-1>PC</font> or to Mr Ellison's cheap and cheerful network computer, or <font size=-1>NC</font>, which should soon reach the shops.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a striking contrast of styles. Mr Gates is coyly self-effacing in his Paris speech ("We're just plumbers," he claims). Mr Ellison is bitingly sarcastic ("More like the only plumber"). Mr Gates stays behind the podium and talks about directories and file formats. Mr Ellison stalks around the stage in his trademark tailored double-breasted suit and shows a picture of the MiG-<font size=-1>29</font> he is buying himself as a new toy. Mr Gates gives warning against industry "bologna" and hype. Mr Ellison talks grandly about the converging of television and information.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A network computer gets its information from the Internet and stores it there, instead of using its own memory and disk drives. This, says Mr Ellison, will change the world, not just the computer industry. Since they are easier to use (turn them on and they are connected) and will cost a few hundred dollars at most, the <font size=-1>NC</font>, unlike the <font size=-1>PC</font>, will spread beyond the rich and the corporate user.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This argument has struck a chord with many, making this a heady time for Mr Ellison. Two years ago, practically nobody outside the computer industry had heard of him or could say what Oracle did (it makes fairly arcane database software). Now Mr Ellison is stopped on the street by people who have seen him on <font size=-1>TV</font>, and is invited into the presidential limo to explain the <font size=-1>NC</font> to Bill Clinton. Better still, the unruly children of the computing world, always looking for a new prophet, now think that Mr Ellison and the <font size=-1>NC</font> might lead them out of the valley that has for the past 15 years been ruled by Mr Gates, the pharaoh of the <font size=-1>PC</font>. (The previous would-be Moses, Marc Andreessen of Netscape, was last seen being chased by Mr Gates's chariots.)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But how real is the difference between Mr Gates and Mr Ellison? In terms of personality it could not be much larger. Despite recently becoming both a husband and a father, Mr Gates remains intently focused on technology and his business. He never talks of his private life in public, and starting a family has made no apparent difference to his famously long work hours. Even his $30m house is portrayed more as a showroom for Microsoft technology than a home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Ellison, by contrast, works out, sails his boats, flies his planes, dates a lot, and meditates in the replica of a Japanese monastery he built near his company's California headquarters. "I don't dedicate my life to Oracle," he says. Ask him why, and something very unGateslike happens. He talks for nearly an hour about his feelings. He describes the need of a lower-middle-class kid growing up in Chicago to prove himself (his sister now complains that their early family life gets poorer with each telling) and muses about his reasons for pushing <font size=-1>NC</font>s ("Am I doing this for the greed of self-esteem or for the benefit of mankind? I don't know"). As for the MiG-<font size=-1>29</font>, it could fill several psychoanalysts' notebooks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Put in these terms, all the waffle about clashing titans seems justified. Yet it ignores two things. First, as Mr Ellison admits, his conversion to the <font size=-1>NC</font> was a little accidental. In 1993, Oracle looked at the idea of building databases to deliver digital movies, and worked with Apple to develop simple set-top boxes to display them. Two years later, when the Internet thundered past the stumbling interactive <font size=-1>TV</font> trials, Mr Ellison got his idea of retailoring them as <font size=-1>NC</font>s, still fed by Oracle databases. He first blurted out his "vision" at a meeting with Mr Clinton and a number of software executives, then floated it at the Paris conference last year. The press latched on to the idea and Oracle raced to come up with prototypes to match the rhetoric.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second hitch is that over the past year, the differences between his vision and Mr Gates's have blurred. The Microsoft boss also talks of simple, cheap devices that draw many of their programs from the network to which they are connected (indeed, the firm introduced its operating system for such machines, Windows <font size=-1>CE</font>, this week). Both think that the new devices will get many of their parts from the <font size=-1>PC</font>, which benefits from great economies of scale. Whether to call the boxes <font size=-1>PC</font>s or not is really a matter of semantics. The disagreement is really over how much of the market will go to each type of machine. Mr Gates, who has made his billions on the premise that people always want more power on their desktop, not less, thinks that some variant of the traditional <font size=-1>PC</font> will dominate. Mr Ellison thinks that most people will prefer <font size=-1>NC</font>s.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given the fact that the technical gap between their two visions is so small, the struggle for leadership in the software industry may become a matter of personal will. Here, Mr Ellison does not have as much to lose or gain as Mr Gates: whether it is a <font size=-1>PC</font> age or an <font size=-1>NC</font> one, Oracle's databases will feed any networked device. But if Mr Gates yields the <font size=-1>PC</font>, then he loses the core of his business. That may explain why he seems to care so much more about the outcome than Mr Ellison. And so far in this industry, obsession has proved more rewarding than reflection.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
</DOC>
