<html><head><title>Trends of the week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Trends of the week</h1>


<b>Statistic: </b>Bill Clinton paid the 27th visit of his presidency to California (more than California's own Ronald Reagan made in his two terms). Judging by the polls, Mr Clinton looks set to win the reward for his frequent flying: California's 54 electoral college votes.
<P><b>Damning statistic: </b>According to a briefing from the Media Studies Centre, the 1996 race is likely to be the least-covered presidential campaign in recent memory. From January to the end of July, network coverage was down 43% compared with 1992, and down 51% compared with the stunningly soporific campaign of 1988.
<P><b>Reshuffle: </b>Mr Dole replaced his media team. A sign of trouble--and a portent of more aggressive ads?
<b>Non-events: </b>Mr Dole's "Listening to America" sessions, at which hand-picked friendly audiences praise the candidate.
<P><b>Sticker:</b> "Bob Dole Listens".
<P><b>Optimist: </b>Jack Kemp, campaigning in Harlem.
<P><b>Doppelg&auml;ngers: </b>To help candidates prepare for the presidential debates, ex-Senator George Mitchell plays the part of Mr Dole for Mr Clinton; Senator Fred Thompson, an ex-actor, plays Mr Clinton for Mr Dole.
<P><b>Least-wanted job: </b>Ross Perot's running mate, turned down by more than one recognisable name. The poisoned chalice was at last accepted by Pat Choate, an economist and fellow anti-<font size=-1>NAFTA</font> crusader. Mr Choate played Al Gore in rehearsals for Mr Perot's disastrous televised <font size=-1>NAFTA</font> debate with the vice-president in 1993.
<P><b>Ladbroke's odds: </b>Clinton 1-7; Dole 4-1; Perot (50-1 last week) no longer listed.
<P><b>Quote: </b>Dick Morris, former Clinton strategist-in-chief, now a writer with a $2.5m contract, on the White House collection of <font size=-1>FBI</font> files, as recorded in the diary of prostitute Sherry Rowlands and printed in the tabloid <i>Star</i>: "It was Hillary, in 1993. She ordered them. She's a paranoid lady--she did it." 
<P><b>Denial</b>: Mr Morris tells a congressional committee that Miss Rowlands got the wrong end of the stick.
<P><b>Morbid speculation: </b>Mr Dole's musing on what he would want on his tombstone: "The people trusted him".
