<html><head><title>NetNanny states</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width=67 height=26  alt="Asia">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>NetNanny states</h1>

<font size=1>SINGAPORE</font>
<p>ASIA'S authoritarians are continuing their unequal struggle against the Internet. In China last week some users noticed that access had been blocked to over 100 sites on the World Wide Web, the multimedia part of the Internet. The ban seems to cover, among others, American newspapers, Tibetan exiles, the Taiwanese government, <i>Playboy</i> and <i>The Economist</i>. The Chinese government has said nothing about what is going on--although it did promise a clampdown against pornography last February. The ban still seems patchy. International wire-services that provide Internet access seem to be unaffected--which may have something to do with the fact that they are compelled to pay fat fees to the official Chinese news agency.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New controls are also on their way in Singapore, where three local Internet "service providers" have more than 150,000 subscribers--5% of the population. In March the government began a drive to curb unwholesome activity in cyberspace, such as pornography and "material sowing social and religious discord."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until now, regulation in Singapore has relied largely on self-policing. Access providers were urged to install filtering software, such as Surfwatch, CyberPatrol or NetNanny. Some content providers, including political parties and religious groups, have to register with the authorities. But for those who managed to dodge the barricades to ogle hard-core porn or incite revolution, the chief constraint was the fear of being caught.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From September 15th, a new phase of regulation begins. Internet providers will introduce technology that enables them automatically to block access to sites banned by the regulator, the Singapore Broadcasting Authority (<font size=-1>SBA</font>). As might be expected, some Internet users are up in arms at censorship. Others, however, have more practical worries. Technology designed to censor material has hitherto been used on a much smaller scale, by companies. It tends to slow down connections to less-frequented Internet sites. The more banned sites there are, the slower it will be.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Optimists think the <font size=-1>SBA</font> list will be short. After all, Singapore is enthralled by the commercial possibilities of the Internet and cherishes its position as a regional communications hub. Others fear the worst. Already, big businesses, which have their own leased lines for Internet access, have secured an exemption from the new requirements. That only heightens the fear of some individual users that their access will be sharply curtailed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor has the government disguised its wish to censor objectionable political material as well as pornography. Internet "newsgroups" have provided perhaps the freest forums for political discussion Singapore has known. The question of re-merger with Malaysia, for example, has provoked a debate that has at times become overtly racist. The government is particularly worried by the fact that people can post their views anonymously, or under false names. Subscribers to a news group discussing Singapore were amused to find anonymous postings purporting to be from Lee Kuan Yew, the former Singaporean prime minister, hurling criticism--and sarcastic praise--at the regime. The real author of these messages has not yet been found.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In early September, Singapore and the six other members of the Association of South-East Asian Nations met in Singapore to discuss the promotion and policing of the Internet. Singapore is far ahead in the business and even administrative uses of the Internet (which can be used, for example, to apply for some government permits). But agreement on a common approach to regulation was difficult. There, too, Singapore is streets ahead.
</td></tr></table>
