<html><head><title>Sega's sonic hedge</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Sega's sonic hedge</h1>
<p>
SEGA ENTERPRISES, the Japanese firm that created Sonic the Hedgehog, is feeling prickly. The home video-games market, which turned Sega and its charmless mascot into household names, has been in the doldrums for three years, with sinking demand and a nasty price war. Worse, Sega appears to be on the losing side: revenues from its consumer sales are expected to be only &#165;114 billion ($1.05 billion) this year, down from &#165;301 billion in 1993, according to Morgan Stanley, an investment bank.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sega's attempts to revive its fortunes in the home rested on the Saturn, a fancy video-games machine it released last year. Unfortunately the PlayStation, a machine made by Sony, has proved much more popular in Europe and the United States. Now Sega's old rival, Nintendo, has launched an even fancier machine, the Nintendo 64. It looks set to knock Saturn for six in Japan.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Game over? Not quite. More than half of Sega's &#165;384 billion in total revenues come from two other markets: coin-operated arcade games and amusement centres. The first is doing well enough--Sega has about half the market--and Morgan Stanley reckons it will bring in &#165;114 billion this year. But it is the amusement centres that currently excite Sega executives.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On September 7th the firm launched Segaworld, a joint venture with Trocadero, owners of the eponymous building in London's touristy Leicester Square. Sega grandly calls Segaworld a "theme park for the 21st century" , but in reality it is a vast (110,000 sqare feet or 10,220 square metres) video-game arcade.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At around &#163;50m ($78m), Segaworld cost far more than the average games centre. But it charges far more, too. Segaworld expects 1.75m people, each paying an admission charge of between &#163;9 and &#163;12, to pass through its doors in the first year. When inside, Segaworld's six flagship interactive rides are free, but the coin-operated machines are not. The company reckons that each visitor will spend &#163;15 (including admission), bringing in a handy &#163;26m in the first year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While this will hardly make up for Sega's losses in the game-machines business in the immediate future, the firm thinks it might do so in the long run. It plans to launch dozens of these mega-arcade centres, the next in Sydney later this year. It already runs two similar centres, revoltingly called Joypolises, in Japan. Yasuo Tazoe, Sega's head of amusement theme parks, reckons that the company's parks might ultimately bring in &#165;200 billion annually in the Japanese market alone. Rather than earning just a series of one-off revenues from selling coin-operating machines, Sega should earn a steady cash stream, from per-use fees on the machines as well as admission fees.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Elsewhere, the spoils could be even bigger: in America alone the theme-park business was worth $12 billion in 1994. A lone hedgehog may not look like much next to Disney's beloved menagerie, but Mickey doesn't surf.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
