<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><h2>Ciao, Carlo</h2>
<p><p>After 18 years in control, <b>Carlo De Benedetti</b> quit as chairman of Olivetti after pressure from Francesco Caio, the new chief executive, and foreign shareholders underwhelmed by his efforts to turn round the Italian electronics group. Its shares leapt before being suspended after another departing executive said that first half pre-tax losses of 440.2 billion lire ($270.2m) understated the company's true financial plight.
<p>Britain's <b>General Electric</b> pacified angry institutional investors by agreeing to raise the performance targets in a &#163;1.5m ($2.3m) incentive package for George Simpson, its new managing director. <b>Procter &amp; Gamble</b> in America gave John Pepper, its chairman and chief executive for the past (very profitable) year, a package that rose 18% in fiscal 1996 to $2.12m.
<p>Potash Corp of Saskatchewan, a top producer of potash and potassium, agreed to pay $1.2 billion for Arcadian Corp, a big nitrogen producer, beating an offer by Freeport-McMoRan, a New Orleans-based mining company. The deal gives Potash the three ingredients it needs to become the world's biggest integrated producer of <b>fertilisers</b>.
<p>Alcatel Alsthom of France and General Electric of Britain are pondering a merger of their <font size=-1>GEC</font> Alsthom train-making and power-plant joint venture with Framatome, already the world's biggest maker of nuclear-power plants. A merger would create an <b>engineering giant </b>second only to <font size=-1>ABB</font> Asea Brown Boveri, and, through a share swap, take Framatome out of the hands of the French state and into private ownership.</p>
<p><h2>Shored up</h2></p>
<p><p>Deutsche Bank stepped in with &#163;200m ($311m) in cash to restore trading in three investment funds managed by its <b>Morgan Grenfell </b>subsidiary in London. Dealing in the &#163;1.4 billion funds had been halted and a fund manager suspended when Morgan Grenfell found "possible irregularities". Investigators began an inquiry. The revelation came only days after <b>Flemings</b>, an investment banking group, was fined &#163;700,000 by regulators in London and Hong Kong and ordered to pay $19.3m in compensation to investors after one of its fund managers diverted profitable trades to his personal account.
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">table</a>)<br>European <b>business students </b>prefer to work for consultancies, preferably American ones, and preferably multinational.
<p>The British government approved the &#163;3.2 billion ($5 billion) recovery plan by <b>Lloyd's of London</b> in the wake of overwhelming acceptance of it by names, the insurance market's investors, to complete one of the biggest turnarounds in corporate history.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Consolidation among American banks continued apace with the third largest such deal. <b>NationsBank</b> agreed to pay $9.5 billion for <b>Boatmen's Bancshares</b> in a takeover that will create America's fourth-largest banking group. The combine would have
<p>assets of $230 billion and a presence in 16 states, ranging from North Carolina to the mid-west.</p>
<p><h2>Turbulent</h2></p>
<p><p>The Farnborough air show in Britain set the scene for another dash by <b>Boeing and Airbus </b>in the race to develop a super-huge commercial jet. Boeing, which plans to stretch its existing 747 to accommodate 550 or more seats at a cost of $5 billion, reckons developing a new superjet could cost $15 billion; Airbus insists its <font size=-1>A3XX</font> fly for $8 billion. New orders claimed by Boeing at the show amounted to $6.3 billion, by Airbus $3 billion.
<p><b>A&eacute;rospatiale</b> of France became the first of the four Airbus Industrie partners to declare its results from the consortium, which is planning at last to turn itself into a limited company. The French firm made an operating profit from Airbus of FFr1.08 billion ($216m) in 1995, up from FFr734m the year before. A&eacute;rospatiale itself, which declared a big loss in its other businesses in 1995, said it would be well back in profit in 1996, a year ahead of schedule.</p>
<p><h2>The Saddam effect</h2></p>
<p><p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>The <b>price of oil</b> jumped after the United Nations suspended the "oil for food" deal, in which Iraq was to be allowed to sell $2 billion-worth of oil to buy food and other necessities, in the wake of Iraq's attack on the Kurds.
<p>August was Russia's first
<p><b>inflation-free</b> month since the start of economic reforms in 1992. The State Statistics Committee said consumer prices fell 0.2%, mainly because of seasonally cheaper food. Monthly inflation has been falling steadily since January 1995, when it stood at 17.8%.
<p>The European Union may block imports of <b>genetically engineered corn </b>from America over worries about it damaging human and animal health. The maize is designed to be resistant to a crop pest in Europe but contains another gene which some fear could increase resistance to antibiotics in animals that eat it unprocessed.
<p>Moody's Investors Service <b>downgraded Thailand</b> because of the country's reliance on short-term foreign borrowing. Its sovereign short-term debt rating was shaved from Prime-1 to Prime-2.
<p><p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
