<html><head><title>Monopolies in cyberspace</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>


<h1><center>Monopolies in cyberspace</center></h1>
<p><b>Hands off Microsoft--for now</b></p>

BILL GATES'S Microsoft is one of the world's most innovative companies, his position as the world's richest man well deserved. But any firm that dominates its market as thoroughly as Microsoft dominates software rightly arouses the suspicion of regulators. There has been hardly a week in the past five years when antitrust investigators have not been scrutinising Microsoft. Is it now time for them to act?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason for posing the question anew arises from the difficulties of Netscape. This firm, quicker than Mr Gates to spot the potential of the Internet, has captured about 80% of the market for the "browsers" that guide users through cyberspace. Until recently its success suggested that the software industry was too fast-changing for regulators to understand, or for any one firm to dominate for long. It had once been argued that since Microsoft's Windows operating system (the program that lies between all other software and the computer itself) is installed on most of the world's <font size=-1>PC</font>s, Microsoft would enjoy an unfair advantage in selling its own application programs. But then along came the Internet, and the rules seemed to change. Now there was plenty of room--or so it seemed--for nimble upstarts such as Netscape to catch the giant of software napping.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that the giant has woken up. Netscape achieved its early domination by distributing its browser for free. Though the program now costs $50, its technical superiority and brand name have kept it on top. But the latest version of Microsoft's browser matches Netscape's, feature for feature. Moreover, Microsoft gives its browser away, and has promised that it will always be free: indeed, it plans to eliminate it as a stand-alone product entirely, by making it part of Windows. It is distributing the browser over the Internet, and Mr Gates has arranged deals with most big on-line services and Internet providers to use it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft will probably win this battle, even though it has less than 20% of the market today. The combination of its technical excellence, marketing deals and free distribution will probably be too much for Netscape. If the young software firm cannot find another hit-product its fortunes could plummet as quickly as they rose. So it is hardly surprising that Netscape has now cried "foul", prompting yet another antitrust investigation by America's justice department.

</p><p><b>Microsoft is to be admired, not trusted</b>
<br>Should the trustbusters clamp down? Unless Microsoft is indeed guilty of some of the outright dirty tricks Netscape has accused it of, the answer on balance is no.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It will be a shame to see an innovator such as Netscape go under, if that is what happens, but the job of a trustbuster is not to keep alive plucky firms. It is to protect consumers by ensuring that a market remains competitive enough to spur innovation and keep prices in check.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For now, the software market still passes these tests. It remains relatively easy for new firms to barge into the market, as Netscape itself proved when it grabbed almost all the browser market within a year of its founding. Keen programmers are still coming from nowhere with world-beating programs and growing rich on them. And although a company such as Microsoft possesses huge advantages in marketing and distribution, the Internet has probably made the job of new entrants easier. Word on hot new products spreads quickly in cyberspace, and, if they wish to, technically proficient consumers can download software directly from the Internet into their computers. Another reason for confidence is that Microsoft keeps its operating system "open", making public the codes that enable competitors' applications to run smoothly on Windows.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What, though, if Microsoft chose to abandon this policy? And what about the complaint that Microsoft is, in effect, "dumping" its browser to put its competitor out of business? These are scarier questions. With $7 billion in the bank and ownership of the operating system, Microsoft could probably conquer practically any market if it wanted to badly enough. The justice department needs to intervene the moment it seems that Microsoft's formidable market power is threatening the interests of consumers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is, of course, easier to preach vigilance than to tell regulators how to recognise that moment when it comes. In the browser war, it is market power that threatens to clinch things for Microsoft: the deadliness of its product is not that it is better than Netscape's but that it is free. On the other hand, Microsoft is not yet in a position to foist an inferior or pricier product on consumers without a competitor popping up.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The worry is that this could swiftly change once more of Mr Gates's rivals have disappeared. Microsoft has already picked off rival after rival by making previously stand-alone software products into part-and-parcel of its operating system. Until now, the consumer has not visibly suffered. Just possibly, the simplicity of buying a seamless do-everything operating system from a monopolist is anyway worth more to consumers than they would gain if regulators were, say, to split Microsoft into a maker of operating systems and a maker of applications. But that sort of monopoly would need to be regulated on price. Those who thought the moral of Netscape's rise was that innovation can beat Microsoft can scarcely ignore the moral of the smaller firm's present peril.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
