<html><head><title>Smashing the lock</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Smashing the lock</h1>


<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><P>

FEW Americans can hate Saddam Hussein more than poor Bob Dole. By inviting American air strikes, Iraq's dictator gave President Clinton a chance to look resolute, and to dispel the idea that a Democrat cannot be trusted with military affairs. On the evening of September 3rd, after Mr Clinton had unleashed the first mini-storm of missiles on Iraq's air defences, an <font size=-1>ABC</font> News poll found that nearly eight in ten Americans approved of the president's action; and that, if it came to full-scale war with Iraq, a majority would choose Mr Clinton to lead it in preference to Mr Dole.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This capped a run of awful news for the Republicans. After their convention in San Diego, the Dole team had been buoyed by polls showing that the gap between their candidate and the president had halved to ten points. Their spirits held up through the Democratic convention. On the last day Mr Clinton gave a disappointing, laundry-list speech; and a sex scandal forced the president's Svengali, Dick Morris, to resign. But, on September 3rd, two new polls put the president's lead back at 21 points (see <a href="am1.gif">map</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The more closely Mr Dole examines his predicament, the more hopeless he must feel. A candidate's usual strategy is to focus attention on issues that put him in a better light than his opponent. In Mr Dole's case there are precious few of these. On education and family values, on Medicare and the economy, and even on traditionally Republican strongpoints like crime, taxes and the budget deficit, voters trust Mr Clinton more than Mr Dole, according to polls conducted by Gallup. The Iraqi crisis seems to have robbed Mr Dole of the defence issue, as also of the charge that Mr Clinton tends to avoid a fight. Each new set of encouraging economic figures blunts the appeal of Mr Dole's promise of tax cuts and regulatory reform.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The president's only point of vulnerability is "character". Asked which of the candidates has a higher moral character, voters prefer Mr Dole by a margin of 26 points. But it is peculiarly difficult for the Republicans to turn this fact to their advantage. If Mr Dole seeks to shift attention to Mr Clinton's personal failings, he will be accused of dirty campaigning; and this accusation may sully his own character in the public's eyes. Focus groups show that undecided voters--the ones who determine the outcome of elections--are especially turned off by <i>ad hominem </i>campaigning. It is as though Mr Dole holds a trump that he is not allowed to play.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are still two months to go, time enough for voters to change their minds several times. The televised debates are unlikely to help the tongue-tied Mr Dole. But other things may, notably a set-back for the president's foreign policy in Bosnia or Iraq, or progress (of which, inevitably, there are rumours) towards indicting Hillary Clinton for her alleged role in the Whitewater affair. Yet, barring calamity, the president's lead looks unassailable. He won the election in 1992 with 43% of the vote; this time round, polls predict he will get about 55%. Meanwhile polls give Mr Dole 35% or so; in this century, the lowest winning percentage of the popular vote was Woodrow Wilson's 42% in 1912.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Translated into electoral-college votes, Mr Clinton's lead looks devastating. The map below compiles the latest polls from each state. Some date from before the conventions, so should be treated cautiously; but, given Mr Clinton's continuing lead in national polls, they probably give a fair idea of the voters' mood. Taken together, the state polls (excluding Texas, West Virginia and Vermont) suggest that Mr Clinton would win 417 electoral college votes, compared with 81 for Mr Dole. This would represent more than a resounding victory. It would bury the Republican claim to a "lock" over the electoral college.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This lock is said to consist of the states listed in the tables that accompany the map. The 12 states in the first table have voted for the Republican candidate in all seven presidential contests since 1968. The 12 in the second have done so six out of seven times. Altogether, the 24 states in the lock are worth 238 electoral college votes--just 32 short of the total needed for victory. Given this powerful base, Republican candidates have been able to concentrate their time and advertising dollars on a few swing states: usually the industrial centres around the Great Lakes (Michigan, Illinois and Ohio) and in the north-east (New Jersey, Pennsylvania).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Dole team still talks as if the election will be decided on this traditional battle-ground. The truth is that Mr Dole may be pressed to hold the states in his own base. Of the 24 "lock" states, four are leaning strongly to Mr Clinton, and nine are leaning slightly towards him. And the biggest states are among the likeliest defectors. The 13 in which Mr Clinton now leads account for 176 electoral-college votes, a bit more than two-thirds of the total in the lock.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The biggest defector is California, where the latest poll gives Mr Clinton a lead of ten points (even though it was taken at the same time as the Republicans were holding their convention in San Diego). In 1992 a big Clinton lead in California persuaded George Bush to pull out of the state several weeks before the election. For the moment, Mr Dole vows not to do this, partly in order to force his rival to devote resources to California, and partly in order to help his party's congressional prospects there. He is betting that a part-Californian running mate, together with ruthless views on civil rights and immigration, will shake the president's lead. If it does not, Mr Dole may at some point decide that California is unwinnable, and concede the state's 54 electoral-college votes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole is also under threat in Florida, which is worth 25 electoral votes, and which narrowly tipped to Mr Bush in 1992. No poll has been taken in Florida since late June, when Mr Clinton had a lead of two points; another poll conducted a fortnight earlier had the president 13 points ahead. In his convention speech, Mr Clinton went out of his way to attract Florida voters, promising to conserve the precious Everglades, to stand up to Fidel Castro, and to protect the Medicare programme beloved of Florida's many pensioners. On September 5th-6th, hurricanes permitting, he was due to campaign in the state.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton will also have a go at North Carolina, part of the Republicans' supposed southern stronghold, and at Arizona, which has not voted Democratic since 1948. If Mr Clinton succeeds, and the Republican lock is smashed convincingly, you will see some acrobatic punditry. Just two years ago, after the Republican victory in the mid-term elections, there was talk of a historic realignment in the opposite direction: the Democrats' grip on both chambers of Congress had been broken for the first time in 42 years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What to make of this confusing mix of realignments? It may be that controlling Congress makes it harder to win the presidency. Americans dislike handing too much power to either party, so they tend to entrust each with Congress or the White House but not both. In 1994 they put Republicans in charge of Congress in order to check Mr Clinton's expansive view of government. In 1996 they seem set to put Mr Clinton in the White House in order to check the Republican government-cutters who run Congress.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Or, alternatively, it may be that all theories of realignment are empty--or that, in the expression used by Larry Sabato of the University of Virginia, "dealignment" is the real trend. He reckons that, in the 1960s, 75% of Americans felt some kind of party allegiance; today, as few as 60% do. As a result, voters are more fickle, and electoral "locks" are outdated. It is no longer just a belt of industrial America that determines elections. Most of the country can swing.


