<html><head><title>Trends of the week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Trends of the week</h1>

<p>
<b>Resilience: </b>Bill Clinton, boosted by a triumphant train trip, the Democratic convention and a quick bus tour with Al Gore, has restored his lead over Bob Dole to some 20-plus points.<p>
<b>September Surprise</b>: Saddam Hussein.<p>
<b>Word:</b> Bridge. Mr Clinton wants to build a bridge to the 21st century. Mr Dole calls it a toll bridge ("You gotta pay").<p>
<b>Coincidence: </b>The Clinton/Gore post-convention bus tour began in Cape Girardeau, Missouri, the birthplace of America's best-known Clinton-basher, talk-show host Rush Limbaugh.<p>
<b>Pain in the neck:</b> The White House disclosed that the presidential neck had a benign cyst, which was removed on September 4th. Mr Dole has cheekily been calling for full disclosure of Mr Clinton's medical records.<p>
<b>Local heroics: </b>Mr Dole wants to scrap the Energy Department to help pay for his proposed tax cut, but in Albuquerque he pledged to keep New Mexico's two national laboratories (10% of the department's budget). Mr Dole also campaigned hard in Utah, one of only three states that solidly support him.<p>
<b>Debate: </b>Whether Ross Perot should be included in the three planned presidential debates, starting on September 25th. It would suit Mr Clinton to have him in, and Mr Dole to have him out.<p>
<b>Ads:</b> Mr Perot began airing a half-hour <b>"</b>infomercial<b>"</b> called <b>"</b>Results, Not Free Candy<b>"</b> (paid for from the $30m in federal funds that the billionaire-candidate has decided to accept). The Clinton and Dole campaigns traded blows in ads on rising drug abuse.<p>
<b>Quote:</b> Mr Dole, in a <i>New York Times </i>interview: "We're going to compete for every vote...Jack Kemp is certainly reaching out to black communities. I've tried to over the years. Hispanics. So I'm very optimistic. I feel good. I'm confident. Sleep good. Work hard. I mean, I like to work. I like to campaign. I like people. I was out there the other night with flashlights..."<p>
<b>Ladbroke's odds:</b> Clinton 1-6; Dole 7-2; Perot 50-1.<p>
<b>Forbearance:</b> Eileen McGann, whose husband Dick Morris resigned as chief Clinton strategist because of a sex scandal: "I'm an adult. I accepted Dick's apology."<p>
<b>Sex fad: </b>Triangulation.



</td></tr></table>
