<html><head><title>Through the roof</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Through the roof</h1>


THERE is now no doubt that house prices are rising steadily. Unlike last year, the pick-up in prices during the spring has continued throughout the summer (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). According to figures published by the Halifax, a building society, on September 2nd, average house prices rose by 0.5% during August, to 5.7% higher than a year earlier. This is good for people wanting to sell their homes, particularly those who have been unable to do so because of "negative equity" (the value of their mortgage exceeding the value of their property). It is less good for buyers, although if higher prices tempt more people to consider selling their homes, there might be greater choice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now that prices are rising, how much further will they go? Partly this depends on supply. Anecdotal reports suggest that for many owners prices are still too low for them to sell and, in particular, that there is a shortage of high-quality properties. That suggests that, if demand increases strongly, so might prices.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some economists claim that demand is hard to predict because average incomes are no longer a good indicator: in the 1990s, average incomes have risen steadily while the housing market has slumped. But according to Nigel Pain and Peter Westaway, two economists at the National Institute of Economic and Social Research, housing demand reflects not current income but rather how confident people are about their future income. A good proxy for this is consumer spending, which is now soaring. Mortgage-interest rates are at their lowest for decades. Lenders are keen to lend--the average ratio of loan to house price for first-time buyers is 90%, higher even than in the 1980s. As a result, say Messrs Pain and Westaway, prices could rise by as much as 10% in 1997.


</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842050800,iss">Search</a>
