<html><head><title>The soul of Ulster</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Northern Ireland</b></p>
<h1>The soul of Ulster</h1>


<font size=1>BELFAST</font>

<p>WHEN Northern Ireland's political parties resume talks on September 9th, attention may no longer be focused on the exclusion of Sinn Fein, the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s political wing. Instead, the spectacle of unionists falling out with each other will be impossible to ignore.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the top of the agenda will be what to do about the fringe political parties--the Progressive Unionists and the Ulster Democrats--which speak for loyalist paramilitary groups. The ultimatum by the "Combined Loyalist Military Command" to leave Ulster or face "summary justice" delivered to Billy Wright and Alec Kerr, two hardline loyalists, has divided unionist politicians and left them in a quandary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Loyalist leaders are fed up with Mr Wright in particular, who they cannot control and who has made no secret of the fact that he wants the loyalists to call off their own ceasefire. Worse for the loyalist leadership, Mr Wright brushed aside their deadline--midnight of August 31st--and held a series of media interviews in which he declared his determination to stay. As <i>The Economist</i> went to press, Mr Wright was still alive, and still granting interviews.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has left unionist leaders in the awkward position of condemning a death threat against a man who wants to resume violence. Ian Paisley's Democratic Unionist Party has demanded the explusion of the two loyalist parties from the talks, on the obvious grounds that their refusal to repudiate the threat to Mr Wright and Mr Kerr violates their commitment to the exclusively democratic means enshrined in the "Mitchell principles" which are supposed to be the basis for participation (and for Sinn Fein's exclusion because of the absence of an <font size=-1>IRA</font> ceasefire).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists, has been more ambivalent. He held secret talks with Mr Wright during the stand-off between police and Orange Order marchers at Drumcree in June. Now he is offering to mediate between loyalist leaders and Mr Wright. Meanwhile none of the other parties at the talks, including the nationalist <font size=-1>SDLP</font>, wants the loyalist parties to be expelled. This is because they assume that this would lead directly to an ending of the loyalist ceasefire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps it is not surprising that a squabble between the killers in their midst has divided unionists. Nationalists have frequently been divided by the <font size=-1>IRA</font>'s violence, and a feud between warring factions of <font size=-1>INLA</font>, a republican splinter group, claimed a life this week. But unionist politicians are also about to face a rebellion from an unexpected quarter: Protestant businessmen.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In "Agenda", a <font size=-1>BBC</font> Radio Four documentary to be broadcast on September 7th, Bill Tosh, chairman of the Confederation of British Industry in Northern Ireland, says that business organisations will be asking for a place alongside the political parties when the talks convene next week. If that does not work, Mr Tosh says businessmen are ready to become even more directly involved in forging a political settlement and then making it work. "We want to get our hands on the problem and help with its resolution. And if it has to be through an appointed body to include ourselves, so be it."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This sounds like an outright challenge to unionist politicians. Many Protestant businessmen are keen to do more business with counterparts in the Irish Republic, which has the fastest growing economy in the European Union, and impatient with the lack of progress towards a political settlement. To unionist politicians this smacks of putting profit before principle. To outsiders it might sound more like the pragmatism and willingness to compromise which Northern Irleand has sorely needed for so long.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842050800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br4.html">Next article</a>
</p>
