<html><head><title>Not bothered</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Traffic</b></p>
<h1>Not bothered</h1>


<p>TWO years ago the Royal Commission on Environmental Pollution published a 300-page report arguing that traffic growth was unsustainable and that vehicle exhausts were causing 10,000 deaths annually. Since then its detailed recommendations for restraining car use have not elicited any kind of formal response from the government--an unprecedented snub for a Royal Commission. Ministers have not even bothered to reject its recommendations publicly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has so angered the commission's members, who include some of the nation's top scientists, that they have decided to try again, determined this time that what they say will not be ignored by the next government. Sir John Houghton, the commission's chairman and a former chief executive of the Meteorological Office, will announce next week that the commission is to launch a further study into traffic growth. It is very unusual for a Royal Commission to revisit a subject on which it has just reported. But sources close to the commission stress that, if difficult decisions on restraining car use are not made, the consequences for the environment and the nation's health could be terrible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new study, which is deliberately timed to be published after the general election, will be designed to force the next government, be it Labour, Conservative or coalition, to face these hard choices. The commission's first report recommended increasing duties on petrol and diesel twice as fast as the 5% rate adopted by the government, thus doubling the price of fuel by 2000; halving spending on new motorways and trunk roads; and setting ambitious targets for increasing the use of public transport and shifting heavy freight loads from road to rail.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;These recommendations proved anathema to Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, and Michael Heseltine, then president of the Board of Trade. They privately criticised the commission for having failed to quantify the cost of its proposals and their impact on business competitiveness. Brian Mawhinney, the then transport secretary, was predictably hostile: the commission alleged that his department was in the pocket of the road lobby. Even John Gummer, the environment secretary, distanced himself from the recommendations, claiming that increasing fuel duties would not have much impact on drivers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With few friends in the cabinet, the report had a cool reception in Whitehall. "It's all very difficult," one senior civil servant muttered. The only official response to the commission's recommendations was oblique references in the government's transport green paper, published earlier this year, which seemed to dismiss the commission's proposals for setting targets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the report has been officially cold-shouldered, its views have not been without influence, even within government. The building of new motorways and trunk roads has been severely reduced, rail fares have been pegged in real terms, and the call for a national strategy on air quality has been endorsed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not surprising, in the run-up to a general election, that ministers have shied away from more radical proposals. Yet the issues raised by the commission's first report will not go away. Despite attempts by the government to massage the numbers, traffic is forecast to more than double by 2025. The current road system cannot sustain anything like that growth without traffic, eventually, grinding to a halt.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842050800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br5.html">Next article</a>
</p>
