<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Supergrasses</b> &nbsp;Michael Howard, the home secretary, rejected criticism of his decision to release John Haase and Paul Bennett, two leaders of a drug gang, after they had served only 11 months of their 18-year jail sentences. Mr Howard said their trial judge had recommended early release because they had informed on other drug dealers.<p><b>Kids'</b> <b>stuff</b><br>
The government unveiled plans to test the reading, writing and arithmetic of all children as they begin their compulsory education at age five.</p>
<p><b>Soldiers' lament</b> &nbsp;Veterans of Japanese prisoner-of-war camps in the second world war protested after a consortium led by Nomura, a Japanese bank, won the bidding to buy the Ministry of Defence's 58,000 homes for married members of the armed forces.</p>
<p><b>Caught</b> &nbsp;Trevor Holland, a convicted paedophile, was recaptured after escaping while being taken around a children's theme-park by a nurse from the hospital where he was under detention.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>In or out?</b> &nbsp;The Bank of England said London's position as Europe's leading financial centre would not be affected by whether Britain did or did not join a European single currency. The Corporation of London, the local authority for the City, said there could be heavy job losses if Britain stayed out.</p>
<p><b>Stalled</b> &nbsp;The Williams Formula One motor-racing team said it would not renew the contract of Damon Hill at the end of this season, even though he is the favourite to win the world championship. Mr Hill will be replaced by Heinz-Harald Frentzen, a German driver.</p>
<p><b>Brave heart</b> &nbsp;A medieval casket thought to contain the heart of Robert the Bruce, the king of the Scots who won his country's freedom from the English at Bannockburn in 1314, was found at Melrose Abbey in the Borders.</p>
<p><b>Tagliatelle tale</b> &nbsp;Euromonitor, a market-research firm, reported that sales of pasta have hit an all-time high in Britain but are showing their first ever decline in Italy.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
