<html><head><title>Send in the marine</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width=360 height=26  alt="Finance And Economics">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>American banking</b></p>
<h1>Send in the marine</h1>

<p>WHAT ever happened to the urge to merge which characterised American banking last year? Hugh McColl, long the chairman of NationsBank, based in North Carolina, recently averred that big mergers were an "old paradigm". Banks should concentrate on the needs of their own customers. But Mr McColl, an ex-marine of aggressive mien and acquisitive habits, knows when to ignore his own advice. On August 30th NationsBank said that it would pay $9 billion for Boatmen's Bancshares, a smaller rival based in Missouri with assets of $41 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;NationsBank thus becomes America's fourth-largest bank. It now has operations in 16 states, 13m customers and a clear lead in the race to become the first national retail bank. The deal startled Wall Street, which had unwisely taken Mr McColl at his word. But it has greater significance: it highlights the ever more intense search for efficiency by America's banks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The deal--America's third-biggest banking merger ever--comes after a brief lull. According to Houlihan Lokey Howard &amp; Zukin, a Los Angeles investment bank, the volume of banking mergers in the first half of 1996 slipped to $9.7 billion from $21 billion in the same period last year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For both sides, the Boatmen's deal carries clear attractions. Boatmen's shareholders get a 40% premium on their shares. And NationsBank is happy to pay it, for several reasons. First, Boatmen's gives it a large and respected business in trust and investment management, previously an area of weakness. Moreover, it is acquiring a unique franchise: a string of small acquisitions by Boatmen's has already turned it into the largest bank in five mid-western states. Third, NationsBank reckons it can squeeze $335m of annual costs out of Boatmen's flab within three years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some argue that the Boatmen's deal is the first portent of a new wave of banking mergers. Certainly, more are likely, if only because the market is still divided among almost 10,000 banks. Regional banks, taking advantage of the liberalisation of interstate banking laws, will drive consolidation. The largest of them--known as "super-regionals" --such as Norwest, Banc One, First Union and First Bank System, are evolving into diversified banks covering several regions. They hope eventually to become truly national retail banks. None can yet boast a national brand.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Several super-regionals have bagged big game recently. Last year First Union bought First Fidelity for $5.6 billion and Wells Fargo swallowed First Interstate after an $11 billion hostile takeover. These banks may now pause to digest their prey. Others, such as Norwest and Banc One, have been stalking banks in the mid-west and south-east.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But acquiring has become expensive. So keen was NationsBank that it paid 2.7 times Boatmen's book value in a market where paying twice book value is considered generous. If, as seems likely, other would-be sellers demand such prices, buyers will be deterred.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead, they will focus on improving their own efficiency. Although mergers help banks to rationalise branch networks and computer systems, there are other ways to do so. Several are closing expensive old branches and replacing them with lower-cost outlets in supermarkets and shopping malls. Wells Fargo has even begun renting space in its own branches to retailers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With an average cost-to-income ratio of 59%, American banks are now among the world's most efficient (see <a href="fn1.gif">chart</a>). Still, this conceals a huge disparity among them. Michael Mayo, an analyst with Lehman Brothers, an investment bank, reckons that over the next five years the average cost-to-income ratio may fall below 55%. Only the fittest, and those with marine training, are likely to survive.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842050800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
