<html><head><title>Just when you thought it was safe...</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width=360 height=26  alt="Finance And Economics">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Just when you thought it was safe...</h1>

ROME<p>DESCRIBING banks as Shylocks is now rather more than just colourful hyperbole in Italy. With about 3% of bank loans thought to exceed new legal limits for usury, imposed earlier this year, bankers are beginning to worry about their pound of flesh. This month the treasury ministry will begin implementing the law by dividing loans into different categories, grouping them by their riskiness. By March next year, it will announce the average interest rate for each category, and any loan on which interest is more than 50% above average will be deemed usurious, and thus illegal.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the new law is aimed at banks, they are only small-time players in a booming loan-sharking business. According to the Bank of Italy, more than 300,000 families fell into the clutches of loan sharks--known as <i>cravattari</i>, or stranglers--in 1993, the latest year for its figures. They borrowed almost 4 trillion lire ($2.6 billion) and paid nearly 3.5 trillion lire in interest. Confesercenti, a retail traders' association, says that the business has grown ten-fold since then.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The authorities are barely scratching the surface in tackling the problem. Earlier this week, the <i>Guardia di Finanza</i>, Italy's financial police force, announced that they had uncovered 140 cases of loan sharking during the first seven months of the year and brought charges against 371 people. Despite a well-publicised effort to crack down, these figures are virtually unchanged from a year earlier.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The loan sharks were helped by Italy's recession in the early 1990s, which hurt many small firms. The Bank of Italy reckons that 90% of the money borrowed from <i>cravattari</i> during that period was used for financing businesses. Rather than blaming the business cycle, or the <i>cravattari </i>themselves, many people accuse the banks of extending too little credit to help small firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is no doubt misleading to place banks in the same category as the <i>cravattari</i>. The interest rates that they charge are around 18% on personal loans, compared with the 150% to 200% annual rates charged by the <i>cravattari</i>. And by forcing the banks to swim with the sharks, Italy's authorities may foster a perverse outcome. The new law will probably force many banks to ration credit more tightly, leaving even more victims within reach of the ever-circling predators.<fly><br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Italy's banks deny these claims vehemently. They argue that families and small firms are among the riskiest borrowers, with default rates that are 50% higher than those on large loans. Moreover, they say, default risks differ enormously across regions and borrowers, and so interest rates must vary widely to reflect these risks.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842050800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
