<html><head><title>Fit to rule?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>Fit to rule?</center></h1>

ANIMAL, vegetable or mineral? It is a question the people of several large countries may reasonably be asking of their political leaders these days. Deng Xiaoping, China's untitled but paramount leader, is 92 years old, never seen in public and, it seems, scarcely able to talk. At 65, Boris Yeltsin is much younger than Mr Deng, but he has already lived seven years longer than the average Russian male and looks far from well on the increasingly rare occasions when he makes an appearance. President Suharto of Indonesia is 75, spent several days in July having tests in a German hospital and, it is said, has grown seriously remote from his 190m people. For the citizens of these three countries, which together account for over a quarter of the world's population, a sickly gerontocrat means perpetual speculation and uncertainty. Is it also worrying for everyone else?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The worries may seem overblown. China is not notably worse governed now than it was a few years ago, when Mr Deng was a bit more sprightly. Certainly, the old man's decrepitude does not seem to have led directly either to chaos or to aggression. Such chaos as exists--and it is largely the benign anarchy of economic growth--probably derives from decisions he took when he had some command of his faculties: his last act of known significance, on a tour of southern China in 1992, was to call for uninhibited economic expansion, which has led to much boisterous prosperity (as well as some much less welcome inflation). As for aggression, China exhibits all too much of it, but it is far from clear that it would exhibit less either if Mr Deng were more effectively in charge or if he were unambiguously dead. Even the implications of Mr Yeltsin's parlous health may be exaggerated. Better, certainly, that Russia should be erratically governed by a sick democrat than consistently misgoverned by a healthy communist or a clear-eyed nationalist.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet to say all this is only to say that things might be worse, as indeed they might. They might also be better. The Chinese, and their neighbours, would be far better served by a leader who was able to take considered decisions and overrule, if necessary, colleagues who wanted to stand in the way of political reform and good relations with other countries. The Russians would be better served by a president who would end the war in Chechnya and attend to the creation of a sense of civic decency in their country. And the Indonesians would be better served by a president who would stop corruption and liberalise their country's political system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Age alone does not disqualify politicians from getting things done. If Mr Deng is one day remembered more as a great reformer than as a brutal autocrat, and he may be, it will be because of the changes he wrought after his ascent of the greasy pole in 1978--at the age of 74. Old men, from Gladstone to de Gaulle to Nelson Mandela (75 when he became president of South Africa), have shown that great things can be achieved in old age. Bob Dole must certainly hope so. If elected in November, at 73 he would become the oldest man ever to assume the American presidency.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;History, however, suggests that old politicians do not usually make up in wisdom what they lack in youthful vigour and sharpness of mind. Almost all Ronald Reagan's accomplishments came at the outset of his term of office. Even then he was culpably hard to educate about the economic consequences of cutting taxes but not spending, and towards the end he was so detached as to be almost dangerous: at the Reykjavik summit in 1986, when he was 75, he was nearly beguiled by Mikhail Gorbachev into signing America up for a nuclear-free future.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Old men are, inevitably, also more prone to illness than younger ones, and illness undoubtedly impairs judgment. Roosevelt might well have driven a harder bargain with Stalin at Yalta had he not been dying. Eden might not have mismanaged Suez had he not been ill. Churchill and Mitterrand might have presided over more than stagnation in their final administrations had they not been beset by infirmity.
</p><p><b>In God, and democracy, we trust</b>
<br>Still, America, Britain and France all survived the experience of frail old leaders with relatively little upheaval. One reason is that in these countries power is not entirely concentrated in the hands of one person, sane or gaga. Another is that, when a mistake is made, the institutions and mechanisms exist to repair the damage and restore some kind of continuity. Democracies offer orderly procedures for choosing successors. That, no doubt, is why voters may be ready to elect elderly politicians to office, especially nowadays when they have reasonable grounds for believing they will be told about the onset of any serious affliction. Mitterrand disguised the extent of his cancer for a while, but it is unthinkable that the American press would today fail to report the degree of paralysis of a president, as it did in Roosevelt's day.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although established democracies may be able to weather the rule of the distempered or the disabled, two other kinds of country may not. One is the new democracies, of which there are many, where the succession mechanism may be untested, the institutions fragile. This is true of South Africa, whose reputation for relative political tranquillity rests largely on Mr Mandela, who, fit though he is for a man of 78, is hardly in charge of day-to-day events. Trouble may already be brewing there. Russia is even more worrying, if only because it is a nuclear power with an expansionist history and an uncertain commitment to democratic rules. Mr Yeltsin's second term has started badly, with all the characteristics of a coma interrupted by fits. If it continues thus, it may be hard to bring it to a decent end, and meanwhile the power struggle to succeed will intensify.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Outright autocracies, however, are far more dangerous, since they generally prescribe no procedure for the handover of power. True, China has an heir-apparent in the shape of President Jiang Zemin, but his succession is far from assured. In any event, the prickly, uncertain nature of Chinese politics is likely to continue after Mr Deng's death, at least for a while, even if Mr Jiang does take over. In Indonesia, no heir of any kind is in sight and speculation about who it will be is now rivalled by how and when the changeover will come.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, the problem of the aged leader does not stop there. Zaire boasts one of the world's longest-running despots in Mobutu Sese Seko (65). Jordan's King Hussein is younger (60) and much less wicked, but perhaps less physically robust. King Hassan of Morocco is 67. President Assad of Syria is 65. None of these men runs a model democracy, or even a model monarchy. None can be sure of bequeathing a trouble-free succession. If you are worried about your own health, worry also about the health of every antique autocrat.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
