<html><head><title>Saving children from sex</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>



<h1><center>Saving children from sex</center></h1>
<p><b>Rich countries' laws won't stop poor countries' paedophiles</b></p>

EVEN in a world grown hardened to man's inhumanity to man, cruelty to children, and especially the sexual exploitation of the young, still has the power to shock. This week the first World Congress Against the Commercial Exploitation of Children met in Stockholm, bringing together government and non-governmental organisations (see <a href="eu1.html">page</a>). The figures it rehearsed were hideous: more than 1m children a year are added to the miserable total of youngsters used for commercial sexual purposes around the world; child prostitutes are visited by 10m-12m men a week; one-third of child prostitutes in Asia are <font size=-1>HIV</font>-positive. The emotion aroused by such numbers, and indeed by cases such as the abduction and murder of several young girls in Belgium, can easily lead governments into measures that mollify public outrage but do nothing to help potential victims.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Preventing the sexual abuse of children is difficult enough when it takes place within the borders of a rich country with adequate laws. But good communications have been kind to paedophiles. Thanks to inexpensive international air travel, they can easily reach pornographic materials and young victims beyond the scope of their country's disapproving courts. Wherever children live in poverty, they are at risk of commercial sexual exploitation. Their exploiters often include visitors from rich countries. Guided by word of mouth or by information on the Internet, sex tourists may behave abroad as they would never dare to behave in their own countries.
</p><p><b>Small beginnings</b>
<br>In frustration a dozen or so countries, mostly rich and western, have passed laws prohibiting their citizens from behaving abroad in ways that would be illegal at home. More such laws are on the way. Some countries insist, as a general legal principle, that their citizens can be prosecuted for breaking national laws abroad. Others are increasingly using the principle to deal with issues such as football hooliganism or hijacking. But the main drive to extend the reach of a country's courts beyond its borders is horror at the sexual exploitation of foreign children.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One problem with such measures is that they are particularly difficult to enforce. Courts in developed countries may set different standards for the collection of evidence from those set in the country where the offence took place, and some require witnesses to testify in person. Some sketchy evidence also suggests that courts may deal more lightly with an offence committed abroad than at home.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the bigger problem is that, by proposing to prosecute their own citizens for misbehaving abroad, rich countries may inadvertently give the impression that the commercial exploitation of children is mainly an offence committed by foreigners. In fact, by far the main customers of child prostitutes are locals. The first requirement for ending child prostitution is for countries, poor and rich, to pass appropriate laws. Indeed, one of the justifications for extra-territorial laws is often the inadequacy of poor-country laws. In some countries, for instance, the age of consent is low; in others, commercial sex with girls is outlawed, but not with boys.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even more important than passing laws is enforcing them fairly and vigorously. Too many countries have turned a blind eye to the excesses of the sex trade in the hope of luring tourists. The best way for richer countries to help is by giving aid and training: to the police, who may be in league with brothel owners, and to children at risk. Only when poor countries care more about protecting their children than their tourist revenues will this nasty global trade start to die.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?841446000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
