<html><head><title>Pity the children</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Pity the children</h1>

<p>ONE of man's nastiest vices, the sexual exploitation of children, has become an international business. An international conference has therefore gathered to ponder ways to prevent it: the World Congress on the Commercial Sexual Exploitation of Children, which met in Stockholm this week. Like most such conferences, it was long on "global partnership" and "stronger co-operation" . But its main outcome was to expose the powerlessness of rich-country governments to root out a practice for which there is great demand.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In any given year, 1m or more children (90% of them girls) join the sex trade, some as prostitutes, some in pornography. Child prostitution is mainly but not exclusively a problem in poor countries, and the conference rightly deplored rich tourists who travel to poor countries to have sex with children. Many rich countries are making an effort to scare--or shame--their citizens into behaving decently abroad. Some airlines show videos urging vistors not to have sex with children; signs in Taiwanese hotels warn guests not to bring children to their rooms. More than a dozen countries have passed legislation allowing citizens to be prosecuted at home for crimes committed abroad.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the child-sex market is predominantly domestic: Filipino child prostitutes have more customers from the Philippines than from Japan or the West. Child prostitutes generally cater for the lower end of the market, where tourists are unlikely to trawl. International efforts to stamp out child sex must therefore take a back seat to local ones. Laws passed recently in Thailand, the Philippines, Sri Lanka and Brazil show that governments are getting more serious about restricting the child-sex trade, but enforcement is sporadic. It is still not unusual for child prostitutes to be arrested while their clients walk free.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?841446000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
