<html><head><title>Inflated expectations</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Inflated expectations</h1>

FEARS that inflation will be higher in two years' time should be taken seriously--which is why the Bank of England continues to urge Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, to consider raising interest rates soon. But it would not be astonishing if Mr Clarke's interest-rate policy were guided less by the inflation prospect for 1998 than by the predicted rate for the year to May 1997--by which time a general election will have to be held. The short-term picture may prove far rosier than the longer-term one, giving Mr Clarke all the excuse he needs not to raise interest rates.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clarke has promised to bring underlying inflation (which excludes mortgage-interest payments) to an annual rate of less than 2.5% by the end of this Parliament. This measure is expected to fall in August, from 2.8% in July. Last year's jump in seasonal food prices, due to hot weather, is unlikely to be repeated. Inflation will probably be unchanged during the autumn, and then start to fall steadily from December until well after an election has been held. So reckons Michael Saunders, an economist at Salomon Brothers, an investment bank.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He points out that output-price inflation--inflation in the prices charged to retailers by producers--has slowed abruptly, after an even sharper fall in input-price inflation (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). Output-price inflation is now almost three percentage points lower than it was a year ago. According to Mr Saunders, on each of the seven occasions over the past 30 years when it has fallen by that much in a year, retail-price inflation has fallen over the subsequent six-months by at least 0.3 percentage points. If history repeats itself, Mr Clarke should hit his inflation target.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is not certain. Although input and output prices have soared and plunged over the past few years, underlying inflation has been remarkably stable. Partly that was due to fortuitously timed changes in indirect tax, but it also reflected retailers' varying of profit margins to smooth the impact of output-price changes. With consumer spending likely to grow strongly over the next few months, retailers may try to raise their margins. If they succeed, Mr Clarke can kiss his inflation target goodbye.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?841446000,iss">Search</a>
