<html><head><title>Beware Geeks bearing gifts</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Beware Geeks bearing gifts</h1>

<p>THE Internet is well known as a pioneer when it comes to technology. Less noticed is its role on the cutting edge of management fashion. Nowadays, it is fashionable for firms to "outsource" product development to just about everybody. Leading Internet firms have developed this method a stage further: they have found an outside supplier so keen to tender his services that he is sometimes willing to pay for the privilege. The name of this fool? The consumer.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The ruse is based on a Greek letter. Add "beta" to the name of any software package, and your product need no longer work as it should--or at all. It can be full of bugs, crashing constantly, sometimes taking the rest of your computer with it. If it does, too bad. Expect no refund. Rather than compensate users, the software maker asks them to spend hours documenting the faults--for free.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Beta software is work in progress, released provisionally. Over the past year, Microsoft and Netscape have managed to get millions of Internet surfers to download beta versions of their Web browsers and document the flaws. Netscape offered users a <font size=-1>T</font>-shirt for each serious bug they found; Microsoft offered nothing but the thrill of helping Bill Gates conquer the world.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a new twist, Microsoft even charged users $32 for the privilege of testing Windows 95 last year. Most other beta programs are free--but then so are most programs available on-line. And, unlike other free programs, beta software usually carries a time-bomb that disables it after a month or two.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why accept it? Partly for fun. Partly because it is often the only way to keep up with the Internet. Since April, both Microsoft and Netscape have released two big upgrades of their browsers, with several beta versions in between. Web publishers adopted features from the newest beta versions to make their sites look better than the competition. Viewers with "old" versions of the browsers cannot see these innovations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Internet software firms argue that the beta system helps to speed up innovation (although many users would love to take a break from the frantic upgrade cycles). It also lets them rush out unfinished work and claim that they have developed new features ahead of their competitors. If it doesn't work, you were warned--and could you help us fix it?



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?841446000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="wb2.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
