<html><head><title>Two Davids join</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>



<p><b>Telecoms mergers</b></p>
<h1>Two Davids join</h1>
<p><b>America's latest huge telecoms merger may lead the way to full-scale competition in its local-call market</b></p>

<p>SINCE America opened its local-telephone markets earlier this year, the mighty firms that formerly monopolised the business--the so-called Baby Bells--have been jumping into bed together with an athleticism that belies their bulk. So far, the two biggest deals have been the mergers of Bell Atlantic with Nynex (whose combined market capitalisation is $44 billion) and Pacific Telesis with <font size=-1>SBC</font> Communications ($43 billion). By this standard, the $23 billion deal that was announced on August 26th is something of a tiddler. But the merger of WorldCom, a 13-year-old long-distance carrier from Mississippi, and <font size=-1>MFS</font>, a nine-year-old Nebraskan telecoms firm, is more significant than it looks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;WorldCom and <font size=-1>MFS</font> are two of America's new breed of telecoms companies. WorldCom is the country's fourth-largest long-distance carrier, and owns thousands of miles of fibre-optic circuits. <font size=-1>MFS</font> has local fibre-optic networks in 50 American cities. Thanks to its recent acquisition of <font size=-1>UUN</font>et Technologies for $2 billion, it is also the world's largest Internet access-provider. This will make the new firm, <font size=-1>MFS</font> WorldCom, the first American telephone company since <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s break-up in 1984 to offer customers every sort of telephony: local, long-distance and (since this is 1996) Internet access.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One-stop shops are said to represent the future of the telecoms business. In the international market, firms have fallen over themselves to provide them through alliances such as Concert (which brings together Britain's <font size=-1>BT</font> and America's <font size=-1>MCI</font>), and Global One (America's Sprint, France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom). Why is <font size=-1>MFS</font> WorldCom the first company to take the leap in America?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it the answer is that, until this year's Telecommunications Act, none of the big companies was allowed to offer both local and long-distance service. But although they are now free to do so, none has rushed in. The reason is that the law treats full entry into the local market by any company that is not a Baby Bell as a trigger that allows the Bells to invade the long-distance carriers' turf. None of the long-distance companies has wanted to face this unprepared. Hence their interest in less-than-full entry into local-call markets.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under the new law, a potential competitor has three ways to enter the local-telephone market. It can buy the Baby Bells' local service at rates guaranteed to be 17-25% less than the price the Baby Bells charge their customers, and then resell it to its own customers. It can lease parts of the local network &#224; la carte, for instance by hiring the local Bell's wires but providing its own switches; the Federal Communications Commission then says how much the Bells can charge. Or it can try to build its own rival network.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first of these--resale--is easy but hardly profitable. A long-distance firm hoping to win local-calling business would probably have to offer customers at least a 15% discount to switch. Take out marketing and other costs, and that leaves little or no profit. A would-be competitor might use such cheap local calling as a loss-leader to sell customers an all-in-one telecoms package, including other more profitable services such as long-distance calling. But every time customers called for repairs and found a worker from the local Baby Bell at their door, one-stop-shopping would seem a bit of a sham.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The &#224; la carte option offers a competitor the opportunity of fat margins on the parts of the job it does itself. But it leaves the newcomer dangerously dependent on its main competitor for other services. Even if the Baby Bells try to be scrupulously honest in their dealings with such intruders, they may not be very good at it. As Dan Reingold, a telecoms analyst for Merrill Lynch, an investment bank, puts it: "You go into a restuarant that has always served a set meal that never varies and now you want to pick <font size=-1>A</font> from this menu and <font size=-1>B</font> from that. You wouldn't be surprised if they delivered the wrong dish to the wrong table."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third option--for a competitor to build its own network--is the surest but also the most expensive. It is relatively cheap to lay a few long-distance lines, but wiring every home costs a fortune. Moreover, this is where the trigger comes in. The new law says that if a Baby Bell faces a significant "facilities-based" competitor (ie, one with large networks of its own) it is allowed to enter the long-distance market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, Sprint and <font size=-1>MCI</font>, the big three long-distance companies, this has, until recently, seemed a reason for caution. Their basic plan has been to experiment with the &#224; la carte and resale options first. However, as the limits of these two approaches have become clearer, the advantages of building networks from scratch have increased.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With its new merger, WorldCom has a head start. <font size=-1>MFS</font> has already built more local telephone networks than any firm except the Baby Bells (and <font size=-1>GTE</font>, which acts like a Bell). Even so, the new firm's local-telephone networks will still be well short of the level needed to trigger the Bells' entry into the long-distance market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By using <font size=-1>MFS</font>'s local networks, WorldCom will be able to bypass the local-access charges it pays to local-telephone companies in those regions, saving it as much as $400m a year. Likewise, among <font size=-1>MFS</font>'s highest costs are the charges it racks up sending calls long-distance between the cities in which it operates. After the merger, it will be able to transmit these on WorldCom's lines, saving up to $40m a year. And <font size=-1>UUN</font>et, <font size=-1>MFS</font>'s Internet subsidiary, will be able to shave up to 50% from its running costs by using WorldCom's lines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now attention is turning to Teleport, an Oregon-based telecoms firm, which has put $1.2 billion worth of local networks in the ground--just 10% less than <font size=-1>MFS</font>. Teleport's share price has risen 50% in the past month. The question is not whether it will be snapped up, but which long-distance firm will be the one to do it.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?841446000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
