<html><head><title>Which Bill Clinton?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>Which Bill Clinton?</center></h1>

HE NOW has more yesterdays, he says, than tomorrows. Given that the speaker was one William Jefferson Clinton, election-campaigner <i>extraordinaire</i>, it can safely be assumed that such melancholy was intended only as a reflection on the passing of his 50th birthday and not also on his prospects for a second four-year term in the White House. His opinion-poll lead over the Republican challenger, Bob Dole, may have narrowed appreciably during the Republican Party's convention in San Diego, but next week President Clinton has the chance to widen it again with his own party's spell in the camera lens, at the Democrats' convention in Chicago. Mr Clinton's position remains strong. But he has some weaknesses to overcome.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Chief among them is his own lack of consistency. The joke made by a senior adviser to Mr Dole, that the much-touted differences between Bob Dole and Jack Kemp, his running-mate, are less than those between Bill Clinton and Bill Clinton, rings uncomfortably true. For sure, Mr Dole is also vulnerable to the charge of inconsistency, for a man once contemptuous of tax-cutting "supply-side" economics is now running on exactly that platform. Mr Clinton can, and should, exploit this, and point to the fact that if Mr Dole really intends to cut taxes and balance the budget at the same time he will need to trim back public-spending programmes which he claims will be preserved. Yet the trouble is that Mr Dole's underlying image, of experience, humility, even staidness, is likely to reassure. The abiding impression produced by Mr Clinton's inconsistency does not.
</p><p><b>His biggest weakness</b>
<br>It is that you never know what you are getting with Bill Clinton. In political terms he has posed as a New Democrat, an Old Democrat and now, in effect, a moderate Republican. His style has swung even more violently: at times he has been a clever, energetic activist; an undisciplined, sometimes disloyal leader; a man of principle; a man of pragmatism; an idealist determined to set a moral course for foreign policy; a realist intent on defending American interests; a man who talks to terrorists; a man who condemns them. A guessing game is under way to divine how a second-term Clinton might behave (see <a href="sf1.html">page</a>); revealingly, the clues lie more in the constraints surrounding him than in the man himself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This, rather than scandals about sex or money, is likely to become the real "character" issue in this election campaign. Mr Clinton is a likeable man, good at empathising with ordinary people, excellent at waxing presidential at times of national tragedy. But can you trust a man who has changed his stance so often? Do you even know what you are voting for?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton's task, beginning with his speech formally accepting his party's nomination, will be to challenge these doubts, to re-interpret them, even to redefine this weakness as a strength. This he must do by stressing that there is no shame in learning from your mistakes, that the whole point about experience is that it makes you change your ways. In that cause his half-century, with its associated implications of maturity and greyer hair, has proved uncannily timely.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nevertheless, voters will still have to be convinced that the change is for real. Fortunately, the two areas in which the Republicans are likely to focus their attacks are also areas in which experience can usefully be displayed. The first is economic policy. Mr Dole's claim, typical for a challenger, is that America's economy is growing too slowly, that wages are stagnant, and that he has a magic bullet with which to improve things. The Old Clinton would not only respond by rubbishing Mr Dole's bullet; he would also try to find one of his own. The Experienced Clinton should react differently: the economy can and must grow faster, he can say, but there is no painless way to make this happen overnight. Taxes must be reformed to boost incentives and encourage savings; regulatory thickets must be hacked away; a president must stimulate, and co-operate with, state and local governments to improve education. Fiscal stability is an essential backdrop for this task--and would be threatened by the Dole plan.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second opportunity for Mr Clinton to try to prove that he has matured lies in foreign affairs. This poses a harder task, for a strong, clear position in matters of defence and foreign policy has of late been more naturally associated with Republican presidents (Nixon, Reagan, Bush) than with Democrats (Carter, Clinton). And it is traditionally assumed that elections are won more on domestic issues than by foreign entanglements; indeed, Mr Clinton ran and won on exactly that proposition in 1992. Yet foreign policy is where presidential character counts for most: not character as saintliness, but character as decisiveness, as clarity of thought and deed, as an ability to set priorities, as calm leadership at times of crisis.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Experienced Clinton will not be wishing for a crisis in which to prove himself. But he must nevertheless show that he has learned his foreign lessons, by defining the challenges America faces, and defining his priorities--such as security in Asia rather than human rights in China--to show that he now knows when not to intervene as well as when to act. For what is needed above all in foreign policy is consistency: needed by foreigners, so that they know what to expect; needed by Americans, so that they know why American money is being spent, or lives lost. And needed, more than anyone, by Bill Clinton.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
